<P>
   CONVENTION - A decade ago it was unthinkable that thousands of
Black journalists would ever visit Arizona. But the fact that more
than 2,000 members of the National Association of Black Journalists
will be downtown this week for the group's 25th anniversary
convention is evidence that the state is overcoming the damage done
in 1987, when then-Gov. Evan Mecham rescinded a paid state holiday
honoring the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. By DANIEL GONZALEZ and
PETER CORBETT. Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Prescott, Ariz.) {ndash} He may have been away from his
central Texas ranch, but George W. Bush had a real Lone Star
weekend planned. Go eat barbecue at Sen. John McCain's place. Hang
out by the creek. And talk politics in front of the same courthouse
36 years before where Sen. Barry Goldwater had extolled the rights
of sovereign citizens and the evils of communism. By MARK SHAFFER.
Story will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS - Democrats gather Monday for their national
convention as a party eagerly embracing the political center. As
they prepare to anoint Al Gore as their presidential candidate, the
Democrats hope for a convention that is exciting but not raucous,
innovative but not threatening, progressive but not radical. In
other words, middle of the road. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in
the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS - After nights in shelters, run-down motels and even
old cars, kids come to Thomas J. Pappas School, an Arizona success
story for more than a decade and the sweetheart charity of the
state's largest donors. But now a powerful national advocacy group,
one with the ear of federal lawmakers, wants to shut it down,
saying the children are unfairly segregated. By KARINA BLAND. Story
will move in the ``A'' category.
</P>
<P>
   MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) -This week the Democrats officially
scratch Babe Ruth from their starting line-up, leaving the team
without a heavy-hitter and establishing themselves as the Red Sox
of the 21st Century. Without Bill Clinton, the Backwoods Bambino,
politics is a dull game and the Democrats have no chance of winning
the pennant. By E.J. Montini. Story will move in the ``A'' and
``K'' categories.
</P>
<P>
   TV-GOODY13 (Undated) {ndash} Showtime's (beginitalic)The Thin
Blue Lie (enditalic)isn't a great movie, but it is convincing
enough to make any self-respecting reporter feel like a slug for
not finding corruption under every rock. By BILL GOODYKOONTZ. Story
will move in the ``E'' category.
</P>
