<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-SPRUCEUP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILLIONS SPENT TO IMPRESS THOUSANDS AT CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRENT HOPKINS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ In anticipation of the crush of national media
in town for the Democratic National Convention, Los Angeles has
received a multimillion-dollar face lift.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown streets have been resurfaced, sidewalks fixed and local
city attractions spruced up for the expected influx of more than
20,000 visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Though the improvements might benefit the city in the long run,
they've been a hassle for businesses in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had every public working project known to mankind here
in the last year,'' said Steve Auth, owner of Kaiser Brothers
Oldsmobile and Honda on Figueroa Street. ``I hope they're finally
finished. After it's all done, it should be nice, though.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the pieces are all in place, it should be smoother
sailing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city is looking beautiful and prepared for the DNC,''
Deputy Mayor Jennifer Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   One landmark benefiting from an extensive reworking is El Pueblo
National Historic Monument, home of Mexican-style marketplace
Olvera Street and several historic sites from L.A.'s 18th-century
beginnings. After a $20 million restoration, the city preserve's
old Plaza and Pico House are in top form for visitors, said
Director of Public Relations Pauline Cazares.
</P>
<P>
   ``It rivals anything Old Town Pasadena has right now,'' she
joked. ``We double-dare them to top this.''
</P>
<P>
   While the DNC has served as a catalyst for the improvements,
most would have been carried out anyway, said Greg Scott, director
of the city's Bureau of Street Services.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this work has been planned for quite a while,'' he
said. ``We took a look at all the major streets downtown that have
been in need of work for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Since late April, the Bureau of Street Services has resurfaced
8.21 miles of streets in the downtown area, in addition to making
improvements to sidewalks and trimming the city's trees. The bureau
has also installed more than a hundred flowerpots near Staples
Center on Figueroa and Flower streets.
</P>
<P>
   According to Scott, the price tag for those improvements is
$4.75 million, with $4.1 million reimbursed by Proposition C funds.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty sets of crosswalks downtown were targeted for
modifications to make them resemble old-fashioned brick walkways.
To achieve this effect, crews reheated the asphalt, imprinted a
brick design and colorized the surface.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that the streets maintain their nice new look, the
city has planned ahead, said Peter Hidalgo, spokesman for Mayor
Richard Riordan. Cleanup crews will be on hand around the clock to
keep trash off the streets, especially after parades and
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   According to Drew Sones, assistant director of sanitation, the
focus isn't limited to above ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made sure all the sewers and the catch basins in the areas
are clean,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While the city Sanitation Department was working to clean the
sewers, it also worked to keep things from getting in. In
coordination with the Secret Service, engineers have made sure to
keep below-ground waterways off-limits to any unauthorized
visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've secured any access to the storm drains so only water can
go in, and nothing else.'' Sones said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone found a need to make any changes. For both the
Public Library and Los Angeles Zoo, it's business as usual. Neither
organization has altered its maintenance or programming schedules
for the convention, but they said they are prepared for an increase
in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready for thousands of visitors, like always,'' said
Judy Shay, spokeswoman for the zoo.
</P>
<P>
   The city's agencies and organizations timed their architectural
improvements for visitors to Los Angeles during the convention, but
officials say the changes are meant to last far longer than through
the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The intention of the beautification efforts is that they'll
last long after the convention has wrapped up,'' Hidalgo said.
</P>
<P>
   The flowers might fade, but the rest of the renovations should
benefit the community for years, city officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the things that we've done will be relatively permanent,''
Scott said. ``They should last a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
