<HEADLINE>
SPARKS PUT ZONE TO GOOD USE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Defense is the Sparks' staple _ specifically man-to-man. But
coach Michael Cooper has been going to the zone defense more often
recently, with great results.
</P>
<P>
   But it was met with some resistance at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really pride ourselves on being a great man-on-man
defensive team, so when he first brought up the subject of zone
defense we were mad, we were like `No, we don't want to play
zone,''' DeLisha Milton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like that's a cop-out. But it's good to have
different-type weaponry in your arsenal. We've learned to like it,
but I think we fell in love with it because we have about three or
four zone offenses that we can go to. We like being able to keep
them on their toes.''
</P>
<P>
   Their 2-3 zone is hard to crack, especially when you're looking
at 6-foot-1 Milton and 6-5 Lisa Leslie on the wings and 6-5
Clarisse Machanguana guarding the paint. Machanguana normally comes
off the bench to give Leslie a rest, but she's been used more often
of late in this formation. The first time the Sparks used it was
against Minnesota on July 31. Cooper used it again Friday against
Phoenix, which has only one true post in Jennifer Gillom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just eased it in and now those are the little tricks that
we're trying to pull out to let people see us in a different
light,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us two good athletes that are big and mobile _ Lisa
and D on the wing, whereas Mach is like our enforcer in the middle.
We're able to get out and cover, yet it gives us good rebounding
advantage. When we work out of that and the team misses, most of
the time we're getting the rebound, we're getting out and going.
That's the key about that is that even though we're big, we're not
slow. D runs just as fast as any of our guards and Smooth (Leslie)
can run just as fast as any 4 or 5 in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   HOME SWEET HOME: The Sparks are returning home for the first
time since July 27. They played seven consecutive road games,
bringing back a 6-1 record that ended with the win at Phoenix on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   They are 15-1 at the Forum. Their only loss was to the Portland
Fire, which broke a 12-game winning streak July 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we can just come and do what we have all season at
home and give our fans a lot to cheer about,'' Ukari Figgs said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sparks don't take playing at home against Phoenix
lightly, especially against a team that needs a win today more than
they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this time of the season, playoffs, it doesn't matter that
you have home-court advantage,'' Machanguana said. ``This is the
playoffs _ just give everything or nothing. ... Just because we're
home it doesn't guarantee a win. You know that we kind of
embarrassed them, so I'm sure they're going to come in with an
attitude and just come in here ready to play. We just have to be
focused.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 0014EDT &QL; 
