<HEADER>
A0216 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-TV-GOODY-AZR &LR;      08-13 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-TV-GOODY-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    `TRUTH IS, ``BLUE LIE'' NOT LIKE REAL REPORTING(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By Bill Goodykoontz(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - See the dogged reporter ticking off his good-old-boy
colleagues as he tirelessly and bravely fights to expose big-city
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   See the powers-that-be brought to justice after trying in vain
to repel him.
</P>
<P>
   See the reporter's won-over colleagues help him celebrate his
Pulitzer Prize.
</P>
<P>
   See the TV critic cringe at his relative sloth and ineptitude.
</P>
<P>
   You can see all that if you see The Thin Blue Lie, a Showtime
original movie. (Except for the TV critic part, which is a matter
best kept private.) The movie follows Jonathan Neumann's efforts to
write a 1976 series for the Philadelphia Inquirer that exposed
police corruption reaching all the way to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The Thin Blue Lie isn't great, by any means, not in the same
league with such journalism films as All the President's Men (it in
fact often comes off as a sort of Some of the Mayor's Men). But
Paul Sorvino turns in a great, if too short, performance as
Hizzoner, Mayor Frank Rizzo. And it is a serviceable thriller based
on a true story.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also another example of a movie or television show
portraying an often routine job as a constantly thrilling,
life-or-death adventure. Certainly, the grunt work of reporting -
conducting interviews, checking records, that kind of thing - is
kept to a minimum; mostly Rob Morrow, who plays Neumann, runs
around yelling, eating like a pig, fleeing from sadistic cops,
scoring the big source that makes the whole incredible story fall
into place and puking when his editor doesn't want to run his
story.
</P>
<P>
   This is somewhat different from, say, my job, which consists
mostly of sitting in a chair watching hours of television while
taking notes; sitting in a chair in front of a computer screen
writing about it; and, OK, eating like a pig.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why you don't see a lot of movies about TV critics.
</P>
<P>
   Big Brother notwithstanding, television isn't overflowing with
shows about people simply going about their business (yet, anyway).
No matter how popular ``reality'' TV becomes, we'll still crave
entertainment. And what's that, if not a heightened version of real
life? (All you Star Trek freaks, feel free not to answer that.) TV
has to ratchet things up a notch or two to get our attention.
</P>
<P>
   Most lawyers toil quietly while they prepare for cases, for
instance, instead of talking to dead ex-boyfriends. Hardly any FBI
agents get abducted by aliens (so far as we know).
</P>
<P>
   And regular friendships are usually based on conversations about
things people have in common, instead of contests to see who can go
the longest without {hellip} well, you remember Seinfeld.
</P>
<P>
   So how real is The Thin Blue Lie? Neumann told critics last
month that all of the police-brutality aspects - and some are
shocking - are absolute truth, no garnish anywhere. The character
based on him, on the other hand, isn't quite so literal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But most of it is pretty realistic, and based on the way that
I was at that time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wow. That seems almost hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Which is, after all, why they made a movie about it.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Goodykoontz at bill.goodykoontz(a)arizonarepublic.
</P>
<P>
   com or (602) 444-8974.
</P>
</TEXT>
