<SLUG> BC-TEN-ESTYLE-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS LOOKING AHEAD TO U.S. OPEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Most of the top women's tennis players
will be in Toronto next week for the du Maurier Open, but their
thoughts are already two weeks down the road, to the start of the
U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   Tournaments such as the estyle.com Classic are considered
tune-ups, chances for players to work on their hard-court games
before the final Grand Slam event of the year, and most stars seem
to feel good about their chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going in the right direction,'' said the world's
top-ranked player, Martina Hingis, who lost to Serena Williams in
the semifinals in three sets Saturday. ``I just have to win matches
like this one, and not lose them. Maybe that's the next step.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only learn from this match and do better next week, and
definitely do better at the U.S. Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis said she is confident about her U.S. Open chances, but
realizes that no player can be considered a clear favorite. Hingis
maintains a big lead in the points standings, but her level of play
is much less dominating.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if she felt as though she had just beaten the best
player in the world with her victory over Hingis, Williams said,
``I don't know how to answer that. She's ranked No.1, and she's
been doing well, but at the same time, Venus is playing wonderful
tennis, and so is Lindsay (Davenport.)''
</P>
<P>
   HANDLING THE HEAT: Hingis and Williams played in the midday sun,
with little breeze and the temperature in the mid-80s, but both
players said the conditions were not a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I excel in the heat,'' Williams said. ``I train in Florida,
and one day, at 11:30 in the morning, it was 110 degrees, and I was
still out there practicing. I love the heat.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis admitted to tiring in the second set, but said her
fatigue was caused more by her two previous matches in the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a tough match with Chanda (Rubin), and then another
tough match with Amy (Frazier),'' Hingis said. ``I was just out
there for too long.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 0031EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
