<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0009 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0219 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS-LADN     08-13 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-TRIALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BENKO ANSWERS CALL IN 200 FREESTYLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Lindsay Benko knew she could make the U.S.
Olympic team. But after an unsettling summer, she was searching for
some kind of confirmation.
</P>
<P>
   It came while she was in her hotel room. The phone rang, she
answered it and to her astonishment John Wooden was on the other
end.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out Wooden had coached Benko's grandfather on the
basketball team at Indiana State, where he worked before moving to
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got good genes,'' Wooden told her.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden has good timing. Benko, buoyed by the phone call, went
out and won the 200-meter freestyle Saturday at the U.S. Olympic
Swimming Trials to secure the berth to Sydney that swimming
insiders had openly reserved for her after she won five medals at
the Pan Pacific Championships in Sydney last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Two other favorites _ Tom Malchow and Cristina Teuscher _ made
good on expectations with victories in the 200 butterfly and 200
individual medley, respectively. And 15-year-old Michael Phelps
finished second to Malchow to become the youngest U.S. male Olympic
swimmer since 1932.
</P>
<P>
   Benko's teammate, Lenny Krayzelburg, watched her race from the
IUPUI Natatorium stands. If he looked happier when she touched
first than he had the previous day in the 100 backstroke when he
did, there was a reason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a single person I want to make the
Olympic team more than Lindsay,'' Krayzelburg said before the
Trials began. ``Because I see day in and day out how hard she
works.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true: Krayzelburg and Benko are charter members of
Overtrainers Anonymous. They can't help it; they're addicted to
work. They spend almost as much time in the water as chlorine.
</P>
<P>
   The Odessa native and the Indiana native didn't get paid
time-and-a-half or anything, but obviously they both ended up with
something priceless for their trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such an overwhelming feeling,'' to look up on the
scoreboard and see an Olympic dream fulfilled,'' Benko said.
``There's so many things that go through your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the images that came to mind was the one of her sitting by
the same pool four years ago, inconsolable after finishing 10th in
the heats of the 200 freestyle and failing to advance to the final.
``It was the first time I ever cried after a race,'' Benko said.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the event brought more tears to her eyes. She
didn't try to stop them. Why contain joy?
</P>
<P>
   ``This year has been an emotional ride for me,'' said Benko,
whose times this summer were slower than usual. ``I was struggling
a little bit. There was a lot of pressure on me when I wasn't
swimming the way I wanted to. It was nerve-wracking.''
</P>
<P>
   Benko, who grew up three hours away in Elkhart, Ind., had more
than three dozen supporters in the stands that she knew of and
another 4,000 who got behind her simply because she was a
home-grown gal.
</P>
<P>
   She passed the fading frontrunner, Samantha Arsenault, and held
off a fast-finishing Rada Owen. Her winning time of 2:00.45 was
almost two seconds slower than her personal best. But on this
night, plenty fast enough. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0010 </DOCNO>
