<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0221 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-TEN-ESTYLE-CLASSIC-LA     08-13 0593
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ESTYLE-CLASSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS OUTMUSCLES NO. 1 HINGIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ All week long, Serena Williams
expressed disappointment in herself and harped on the seemingly
endless number of improvements she feels must be made to her game.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday afternoon, even the perfectionist Williams couldn't
hide her joy after a victory over the world's top-ranked player.
Williams survived a dreadful start and defeated Martina Hingis 4-6,
6-2, 6-3 in the semifinals of the estyle.com Classic at Manhattan
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Except for the Grand Slams, this is probably my favorite
event,'' said Williams, the fifth seed and defending champion, who
advanced to face second-seeded Lindsay Davenport, a 6-4, 6-4
semifinal winner over Elena Dementieva, in today's final at 11 a.m.
PDT.
</P>
<P>
   Williams' victory denied the tournament a coveted match between
the two top-ranked players in the world, but set up an equally
compelling matchup of two women with similar styles. Williams has
won their past four meetings, all on hard courts, with her only
loss to Davenport coming in 1997, when she was 16 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to play Lindsay,'' Williams said. ``I know her game
pretty well. She plays that California game, most girls from
California play the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``She hits the ball hard and very flat, and she hits big
serves.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who grew up in Los Angeles, might as well have been
describing her performance against Hingis. She bombed three
consecutive aces and won the first game of the first set, then
quickly fell behind two service breaks at 4-1 as Hingis took
advantage of Williams' frequent unforced errors.
</P>
<P>
   Williams followed with two service breaks to tie the set at 4-4,
but Hingis broke back and held serve at love to win the set.
</P>
<P>
   From there, it was pretty much all Williams. The unforced errors
dropped in frequency, and Williams was able to power her way out of
any trouble she encountered. Williams started the second set with a
service break and was never seriously challenged after that.
</P>
<P>
   The players held serve in the third set until Williams broke to
go up 5-3 and then won on her third match point. Williams finished
with 37 winners _ the same number as her unforced errors _ and had
seven aces. Williams still found plenty to fault with her effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't serve that well at all,'' said Williams, who had six
double faults. ``Usually if my serve is down, I don't play well,
but I like that I wasn't serving well, and I was still able to do
well against a good player.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said of Dementieva, an 18-year-old Russian who
is ranked No.32 in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport easily defeated Dementieva in their three previous
meetings, but struggled to control her groundstrokes early.
Dementieva won three consecutive games to take a 3-2 lead, but
struggled with her serve.
</P>
<P>
   Dementieva was successful when she got her first serve in, but
Davenport consistently blistered her second serve and won the first
set largely because of her three service breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Dementieva held strong in the second set and trailed 4-3, but
Davenport held serve at love and won the match on her next service.
As a reward, she gets a shot at Williams, no easy task.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I'm ranked higher, I'm probably the underdog,''
Davenport said. ``It's important for me to get a break, hopefully
early in the match. I have to be aggressive when I return, even if
I miss a few.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 0047EDT &QL; 
