<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RED-SOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELLING, LEDEE SLAM RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ Gabe Kapler has wiped Mickey Rivers from the
Rangers' record book, sort of like how some of his teammates would
like to erase this season from their memory.
</P>
<P>
   Not Rick Helling. Unlike the Rangers in general, Helling shows
no sign of wearing down as this tedious season heads down the final
stretch, even if he does continue to carry a heavy burden.
</P>
<P>
   Helling held the Boston Red Sox to one run on four hits over
seven innings and Ricky Ledee smashed a fourth-inning grand slam
off of pitcher Tim Wakefield to give the Rangers a 6-3 victory at
The Ballpark in Arlington last night.
</P>
<P>
   Helling threw 129 pitches as he raised his record to 14-8 and
lowered his earned-run average to 4.61] despite pitching on a night
when the game-time temperature was 96 degrees. He has thrown 2,929
pitches this season, the most in the American League, but said he
still feels as strong as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pretty much,'' Helling said. ``That's one of the things I take
pride in, how hard I work in the off-season and how hard I work in
the season, so I can pitch as well in the second half as I do in
the first, if not better. The last thing I want to worry about is
if I worked hard enough to be in shape so I can be successful on
the mound.''
</P>
<P>
   Kapler went 3-for-3, including a second-inning double off the
left-field wall that extended his hitting streak to 25 games. That
breaks the club record of 24 set by Mickey Rivers in 1980 and is
the longest hitting streak in the majors this season.
</P>
<P>
   More important to him, though, was a run-scoring single in the
fifth against reliever Bryce Florie after the Red Sox intentionally
walked Rafael Palmeiro with a runner at second and two outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The streak is nice,'' Kapler said. ``It's definitely something
to remember. But the thing I feel good about is the RBI single. I
want to feel that if Raffy is being pitched around or walked
intentionally, I can go up there and do the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Red Sox manager Jimy Williams: ``I thought we would try to
keep the ball down and get a ground ball. Palmeiro has hurt us a
lot. Not that Kapler can't, because he showed he could, and he did
hurt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledee had the biggest hit of the night. Helling and Wakefield
battled to a scoreless tie through three innings before the Red Sox
knuckleballer lost total control in the fourth. He started that
inning by walking Rusty Greer, Palmeiro and Kapler, then fell
behind 2-0 to Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he might throw me a fastball,'' Ledee said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Wakefield threw him one more knuckler, but it stayed up
and Ledee crushed it into the right-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to be aggressive,'' Ledee said. ``I knew I had
the advantage, and he threw me a good one to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling got into immediate trouble in the fifth when he hit
Jason Varitek, gave up a double to Rico Brogna that put runners on
second and third and a run-scoring single to Manny Alexander that
put runners at first and third.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up the top of the Red Sox order, but Helling got
Trot Nixon and Mike Lansing to pop out and struck out Carl Everett
to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your team scores like that, you want to be able to put up
a zero and get back in the dugout,'' Helling said. ``I didn't do
that, but the good thing was a potentially big inning was minimized
to just one run.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise it could have been more disaster for a team that has
seen more than it's share lately. Helling hasn't been immune to
that, but, with 10 more starts to go, he still has a chance to put
together one of the best seasons ever by a Rangers pitcher. He
isn't ready to slow down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easiest thing in the world is to say the last 10 starts
don't mean anything, just get the year over with,'' Helling said.
``But my competitive nature is still my best asset. I still have a
job to do, and that's to give my team everything I've got every
fifth day.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
