<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0223 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COL-SWIM     08-13 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-COL-SWIMMING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWIMMING HUNK SEES TRUE BEAUTY IN HIS PARENTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Up here in Speedo-land, sure, they know Lenny
Krayzelburg. His name is on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   He's a hunk. A god. ``People'' magazine found him in the pool at
Southern California and named him one of its ``50 most beautiful
people'' of the year.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a story behind that ``beautiful'' face. Today at
the U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials, Krayzelburg will again try to
validate his golden perch as the best backstroke swimmer in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The free world. The only world, thanks to the sacrifice of Oleg
and Yelena Krayzelburg, that their son now knows.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny was already a promising age-group swimmer when his parents
moved him, at the age of 13, from the former Soviet Union to
America. As a Soviet Jew, Oleg Krayzelburg wanted his son to have
the opportunities that he and Yelena had only dreamed about.
</P>
<P>
   They settled in California, home of the gold rush. There may or
may not, Lenny smiled, be some significance in that.
</P>
<P>
   ``To move to this country, with no guarantees, without knowing
what was going to happen, to do it for the sake of their children
was a very courageous thing,'' Krayzelburg, now 24, said.
</P>
<P>
   The pool at the Indiana University Natatorium this past week has
echoed with emotion. In keeping with tradition, as each Olympian is
named to the team, his or her name is painted onto the broad, white
wall behind the diving platform _ sometimes within minutes of the
end of their race.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing his name go up after his 100-meter backstroke victory on
Friday, Krayzelburg would only describe it as ``very emotional.''
None of the trials' more than 1,300 Olympic hopefuls have traveled
as far.
</P>
<P>
   Back in Odessa, in what is now Ukraine, young Lenny had
distinguished himself while swimming for the local version of the
YMCA, the town's Sports Army Club. The family left for Los Angeles
in 1989, settling in West Hollywood, and Oleg became a cook. There
was no extra money for any fancy swimming lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely was tough those first few years financially,''
Lenny said. ``That's why I had to work. Sure, I was 19, and I
wanted to go out sometimes. I just didn't feel comfortable asking
my parents for money, because they were struggling.''
</P>
<P>
   He found a place to swim _ and to work _ at the local community
center, which made him a lifeguard.
</P>
<P>
   His swim career had been flagging, but Lenny's father reminded
him of how the Soviet coaches had raved about his potential. His
father's persistence, Krayzelburg said, kept him returning to the
pool.
</P>
<P>
   He ended up after high school at Santa Monica City College, and
set a national junior college record in the backstroke. His coach
at Santa Monica contacted Southern Cal coach Mark Schubert (now the
Olympic men's coach), and painfully admitted that Krayzelburg had
outgrown his program.
</P>
<P>
   Krayzelburg officially became a U.S. citizen in 1995. A year
later at the U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials, held at this same IU
Natatorium, Krayzelburg finished fifth in the 200-meter backstroke
and failed to see his name go up on the wall of Olympians.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve months later, he was the best backstroker in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but the voice doesn't sound like a god's. Krayzelburg
speaks in soft, shy, disarming tones that still, if you listen
close enough, carry a whisper of his Ukrainian heritage. When he
says that he was ``kind of embarrassed'' about being named to
``People'''s most-beautiful list, Krayzelburg leaves no doubt that
he means it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a copy of the magazine,'' he said, almost blushing,
``but I was probably the last person to buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, after he qualifies for the 200-meter backstroke tomorrow _
he also will swim in the medley relay in Sydney _ Krayzelburg is
probably only three gold medals away from truly becoming one of
LA's beautiful people. Lakers games. Jay Leno's couch. The whole
thing.
</P>
<P>
   When he looked into the stands after the race Friday night,
Lenny saw his father crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a lot to them,'' he said. ``When I see how much joy
it brings to them, it makes me want to thank them for what they've
done. And, hopefully, that will come by winning three gold medals _
one for mom, one for dad, one for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Krayzelburg got to return to Odessa. When he saw
the pool that he had spent so many hours in as a youngster, it
brought tears to his eyes. No longer filled with water, it was
being used to collect garbage.
</P>
<P>
   This is home now, as Lenny Krayzelburg knows.
</P>
<P>
   You're going to be seeing a lot of his face.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
