A0224 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTEBOOK-LAD     08-13 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA WILL GIVE OPPONENTS DIFFERENT LOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA's football team may return 17 starters, but
the Bruins won't always look the same when they line up.
</P>
<P>
   They've added a couple of important wrinkles this season: they
won't move defensive end Kenyon Coleman inside on passing
situations and they'll use a two-tight end lineup more frequently
on offense.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, when the Bruins defense was in its nickel package,
Coleman was shifted to tackle and an outside linebacker _ either
Ali-Abdul Azziz or Santi Hall _ was brought in as a pass-rushing
end.
</P>
<P>
   The move constitutes much more than a few feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different world,'' said Coleman, who figures to improve
on last season's sack total of 3{. ``You've got double teams and
there's no space to work. It's lot more crowded in there.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive adjustments are in order to accommodate an
abundance of talent at tight end. Senior Gabe Crecion, junior Bryan
Fletcher and sophomore Mike Seidman (considered the top prep tight
end in the nation two years ago) are each listed as No.1 on the
depth chart.
</P>
<P>
   The extra tight end will often come at the expense of a
fullback, a position shallow in talent and experience. Junior Matt
Stanley, the projected starter, is a former walk-on and backups
Chris Jackson and Ed Ieremia-Stansbury were switched from
linebacker after last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins plan to use a fullback probably only a third of the
time, according to head coach Bob Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   Of the tight ends, Crecion is the most experienced and
fundamentally sound, tight ends coach Gary Bernardi said. Fletcher,
at 231 pounds, is the lightest and quickest; Seidman, at 251
pounds, is the most physical.
</P>
<P>
   The second tight end may line up in the backfield as a slot
receiver, an H-back or as another bookend on the line. But putting
a second tight end on the field won't change what the Bruins do as
much as how they look doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still do the same things,'' Toledo said. ``We're primarily
an I-formation team that'll run the football.''
</P>
<P>
   HALL QUITS: Hall, a reserve strong-side linebacker, quit the
team Saturday, a day after he was suspended for violating team
policy.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who started 10 games at outside linebacker as a redshirt
freshman in 1998, told Toledo after the morning practice that he
needed to attend to personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   Tony White will now be backed up by Asi Faoa, suspended for the
season opener, and freshman Brandon Chillar.
</P>
<P>
   It was a better day for another Hall. Senior John Hall, a
walk-on reserve safety, was awarded a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT I DID ON MY SUMMER VACATION: Outside linebacker Ryan Nece
went to Canton, Ohio, three weeks ago to watch his father, Ronnie
Lott, be enshrined at the NFL Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see your father get inducted is an amazing experience,''
said Nece, who was particularly thrilled to meet players like Joe
Namath, Willie Lanier and Joe Greene. ``I study the history of
football, so with all the all-time greats there, I was like a
little kid in a candy store.''
</P>
<P>
   INJURY REPORT: Jerry Lane, a UCLA assistant in the 1960s, was
treated by paramedics for dehydration after he felt faint during
the morning practice. He was resting at home by the end of the day,
said UCLA spokesman Marc Dellins. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 0112EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
