<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 01:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0226 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DNC-STREETS-LADN     08-13 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-STREETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTS LAUNCHED AS DELEGATES ARRIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Staff writers Heather MacDonald and Benjamin Parke contributed to
this story.) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER and BHAVNA MISTRY 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; LOS ANGELES _ A few hundred protesters took to the streets of
downtown Los Angeles Saturday as thousands of Democratic National
Convention delegates and the journalists covering them jammed
airports and hotel lobbies.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion rights, immigration rights and the wrongs of both
Democrats and Republicans were on the minds of the small groups of
protesters who were closely watched at a distance by cadres of Los
Angeles police officers.
</P>
<P>
   The only arrest reported was of a man who dumped a pickup
truckload of horse manure in front of the Wilshire Grand Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters did little to dampen the festive mood of
convention delegates who had survived long lines at Los Angeles
International Airport and Burbank Airport and even long lines at
hotel check-in desks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels fabulous,'' said delegate Kathleen McConnell, a
letter carrier from San Francisco checking in at the Westin
Bonaventure Hotel. ``It's a dream of mine, my first convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have so many invitations to parties I don't even know how to
begin to pick what I'm going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   McConnell and dozens of others checked in and picked up goody
bags filled with sunscreen, binoculars, water bottles, postcards
and candy then pored through the week's schedule of events.
</P>
<P>
   Print journalists finished their preconvention stories and
broadcast media members performed their umpteenth sound check, all
in time to get to a handful of evening parties thrown just for the
visiting media.
</P>
<P>
   And demonstrators protested at a handful of events around the
city, from government buildings to swank hotels downtown; a small
precursor to what should be massive demonstrations through
Thursday's nomination night.
</P>
<P>
   In one of the largest demonstrations Saturday, about 100 Latinos
gathered two blocks from Staples Center at The Original Pantry
Restaurant - owned by L.A. Mayor Richard Riordan - to demand more
Latino representation in the national parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democratic Party is the same two-headed monster as the
Republican Party,'' said Tezozo Moc Sandoval, 31, of Montebello,
who was among the demonstrators. ``They don't do anything for the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Representing about five organizations, the demonstrators blamed
Democrats and Republicans for the ongoing blockade against Cuba,
wars in Colombia and Mexico and efforts to install a military base
in El Salvador.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to protest against the Democrats' and the
Republicans' involvement in internal affairs of our nations,'' said
Francisco Martinez, who was born in El Salvador but now lives in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Following the initial rally, the group marched through downtown,
past Staples Center where the convention will start Monday and then
returned to the rally spot for a second rally in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the march were dancers dressed in colorful costumes
complete with feathered headdress. Marchers danced, drummed and
chanted while others held up several banners and signs.
</P>
<P>
   As the group filled the streets, the demonstrators were escorted
by about three dozen LAPD officers on bicycle, who along with
California Highway Patrol officers could be seen throughout the
downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   At Pershing Square, where many protesters are expected to gather
over the coming days, the action was low-key except for the arrival
at the Regal Biltmore Hotel of delegates from Vice President Al
Gore's home state, Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Saltkill, a United Steelworkers of America lobbyist from
Nashville, wore a red heart-shaped pin that said, ``Kiss me, I'm a
Democrat,'' and bragged about Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of him,'' he said. ``And we feel pretty fortunate
to be able to be here with him.''
</P>
<P>
   David Johnson, an electrician from Jackson, Tenn., said this was
his first visit to Los Angeles. He was supposed to come here once
before for a trade convention eight years ago but something
happened: the Northridge Earthquake of 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad to get here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile inside Staples Center, thousands of reporters,
technicians and camera crews tested equipment, while volunteers and
private security guards lined up for credentials and marching
orders.
</P>
<P>
   Security was the tightest it has been, with police, Secret
Service and bomb-sniffing dogs at each entrance. Officers searched
through the bags and purses of reporters and volunteers who had to
walk through metal detectors and flash credentials to enter the
building.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of groups held small events across the city to draw
attention to their cause. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   -- An activist dressed in a pink pig costume dumped four tons of
horse manure in front of the Wilshire Grand Hotel, police said, as
10 people from People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals watched
and cheered.
</P>
<P>
   The 5-by-10-foot spill was quickly cleaned up by hotel
employees. The unidentified protester was arrested and his truck
was impounded.
</P>
<P>
   -- Making their message as graphic as possible, anti-abortion
activists carried five-foot-tall posters of dead fetuses during a
protest Saturday outside a downtown health clinic that performs
abortions. They later drove around downtown L.A. with similar
posters placed on top of their cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore says that he's for family values but killing children
does not promote a family,'' said Jesse Slovenec, 19, of Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, abortion-rights activists carried signs and said they
came out to make sure that the clinic stays open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We anticipated that these other people were going to be out
here,'' said Mary Hood, 26, of Los Angeles. ``We wanted to be out
here to show our support. ... People have this right. Abortion is
supported.''
</P>
<P>
   -- At the First United Methodist Church at 1010 S. Flower St.,
activists erected 553 white crosses to commemorate those who have
died crossing the U.S.-Mexico border since the 1994 inception of
Operation Gatekeeper, a crackdown on illegal immigration that
pushed illegal traffic to more remote and treacherous areas.
</P>
<P>
   -- At Patriotic Hall - just down the street from the Staples
Center - about 250 people attended the Mothers' Convention on
Welfare.
</P>
<P>
   -- At St. James Episcopal Church, Women Against Gun
Violence/Silent March displayed scores of shoes that had belonged
to young gunshot victims. Among those present was LAPD Chief
Bernard C. Parks, whose granddaughter was recently shot to death.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's activities are just a warm-up for the massive
protests expected to begin with today's rally and march by the
Coalition to Stop the Execution of Mumia Abu-Jamal.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands are expected for the noontime event at Pershing Square
meant to draw attention to Abu-Jamal, an African-American
journalist on Death Row for the killing of a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 0127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0016 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 01:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0227 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r p BC-DNC-STREETS-LADN     08-13 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-STREETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTESTS LAUNCHED AS DELEGATES ARRIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Staff writers Heather MacDonald and Benjamin Parke contributed to
this story.) 
