<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0234 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-SOC-GALAXY-WIZARDS-LA     08-13 0528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-WIZARDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHMID SEETHING AFTER 1-1 DRAW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Upset with his team, the officials and
everything that went wrong Saturday night, Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid
finally lowered his pulse to a reasonable level shortly after his
team's 1-1 draw with Kansas City in front of 33,112 at the Rose
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   With a man advantage for the final 59 minutes and a chance to
move within a point of the Wizards in the Western Division
standings and stay in the race for the league's best record and
home-field advantage throughout the playoffs, all the Galaxy could
do was leave the way it had entered _ four points behind K.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you play a man up you need to play better and smarter,''
said Schmid. ``A tie for us is the same as losing. A tie doesn't do
us any good because we didn't make up any ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wizards (13-6-6, 45 points) _ more than happy to walk away
with a tie, especially after midfielder Matt Mckeon was ejected in
the 41st minute for taking a dangerous stab at Mauricio Cienfuegos'
knee _ maintains its comfortable lead over the Galaxy (11-7-8, 41
points) with a game in hand. K.C. has seven games remaining, the
Galaxy six.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extremely disappointing, it felt like we were a little
off,'' Galaxy defender Greg Vanney said. ``We have to regroup, we
still have a final run to make and we have to play much better than
this to have a shot at the division.''
</P>
<P>
   Referee Tim Weyland, whom Schmid has had problems with before,
failed to call what appeared to be a penalty kick for the Galaxy in
the first half. In the second half, two Galaxy goals were called
back after a questionable offsides and a penalty were whistled
against L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weyland's good for my heart, he gets my heart rate going,''
said Schmid, carefully choosing his words to avoid a fine. ``My
heart specialist says he's good for me because he gets my blood
flowing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy's lone goal of the night came in the opening moments.
Starting in place of Luis Hernandez, Haitian striker Sebastian
Vorbe notched his third goal of the season after some crafty work
by Cobi Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Along the right touchline, Jones juked K.C. defender Brandon
Prideaux and raced toward the endline. He sent a long cross before
Prideaux could catch up. Vorbe had an easy finish at the back of
the goal area, gently heading the ball to the near post for a 1-0
lead in the third minute.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy gave up a silly goal in the 29th minute, allowing
K.C. to even the match.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy defender Paul Caligiuri was dribbling toward goalkeeper
Matt Reis. Caligiuri turned to clear the ball away, but the ball
rolled in front of K.C. midfielder Chris Klein with Reis in a bad
spot near the top of the penalty area. All Klein had left was an
easy chip to an empty net for his sixth goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no need for Reis to come out (of his goal),'' said
Schmid. ``Then when he's there, either he (Reis) or Caligiuri need
to kick the freakin' ball into the stands. It's as simple as that.
You can't be indecisive on a play like that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 0140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
