<HEADER>
A0245 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-YANKEES-LA     08-13 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-YANKEES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCKER RETURNS, ANGELS WIN 9-6
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Kent Mercker made his emotional return to the
Angels on Saturday night against the New York Yankees at Edison
Field, his first appearance in a big-league game since suffering a
life-threatening cerebral hemorrhage pitching on the same mound
three months and one day earlier.
</P>
<P>
   His return was warmly welcomed by the sellout crowd of 43,394,
when he walked in from the left-field bullpen before the start of
the game and again when he went out to pitch the first inning ...
and, once more, when he walked off after being removed in the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very excited and happy I was able to pitch,'' he said
afterward, ``but I didn't pitch well. ... I had too much energy. I
let my emotions get to me. There was no excuse to be as wild as I
was.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to do well, I wanted to be perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, so he wasn't perfect. But he was certainly better than the
Yankees' starter, Denny Neagle, who didn't even make it past the
second inning. He was knocked out in the midst of a six-run
uprising by the Angels, who emerged with a 9-6 win, their third
victory in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Credit much of it to a deft maneuver by the Angels' manager,
Mike Scioscia.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia, looking for more punch against left-handed starters,
gave his lineup a good working over. The key move: shifting
power-hitting third baseman Troy Glaus from the sixth spot to No.2.
</P>
<P>
   A little unusual, perhaps, having a 30-plus home run hitter
batting second. But, as Scioscia explained afterward _ after Glaus
had driven in a career high five runs with two homers, his 33rd and
34th of the year, one of them the first grand slam of his career,
and a double _ ``he's really more like a No.3 hitter, because we've
got Benji Gil hitting ninth.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus' slam highlighted the six-run second inning. Mo Vaughn
also homered in the second. And Glaus homered again in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Garret Anderson had doubles in his first three at-bats,
giving him five so far in the series with the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The win kept the Angels within two games of first place in the
American League's ever-so-wild wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for all of it, it was Mercker's return that stood out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a guy ... what he went through, to pitch
into the fourth inning ... it gave us a big lift,'' Scioscia said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little fatigued, he didn't quite get to the range we
expected (which was about 90 pitches; he left after 74), but his
velocity was good, he threw some good change-ups, some good
sliders. Obviously, his command wasn't there, but he kept
battling.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker admitted he did some thinking, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had that long inning (the second), and I had a lot of time
to think,'' he said, smiling. ``I kind of pinched myself, asking,
`Am I really here?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great physically, even if it didn't look so great. Now
... I'm looking forward to my next start.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker, who was eventually charged with three runs on five hits
over 32/3 innings, pitched a 1-2-3 first inning and allowed
bases-empty homers to Glenallen Hill in the second and Scott
Brosius in the third. In the fourth, he turned a 6-2 lead over to
reliever Lou Pote. There were two outs, but the bases were loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter shot a single to right that scored one run. But
right fielder Tim Salmon cut down Hill at the plate for the third
out, Salmon's 11th assist of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was big,'' Scioscia said. ``It stopped them right
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels ballooned the lead to 9-3 with three runs in the
fourth, then had to hang on.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees got to Pote (1-0) for two runs in the seventh, then
one off of Mike Holtz in the eighth. Shigetoshi Hasegawa put out
the fire, allowing one hit the final 11/3 innings for his fifth
save, extending his scoreless streak to 181/3 innings over 11
appearances. He hasn't given up an earned run his last 251/3
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Mercker reflected on the moment, saying, ``I sat
around for three months. I was out a long time ... and it felt
great to be back.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
