<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-MCBUSH-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    TEXAS-SIZE HOWDY TO BUSH(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By MARK SHAFFER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Prescott, ARIZ.) - He may have been away from his central Texas
ranch, but George W. Bush had a real Lone Star weekend planned.
</P>
<P>
   Eat barbecue at Sen. John McCain's place. Hang out by the creek.
Talk politics.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing missing was Willie Nelson.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his once bitter foe for the Republican presidential
nomination jetted in Saturday afternoon 30 minutes ahead of
schedule for a weekend retreat at McCain's home on Oak Creek, about
halfway between Cottonwood and Sedona.
</P>
<P>
   But first, there was a campaign stop in front of the same
courthouse where, 36 years before, Sen. Barry Goldwater had
extolled the rights of sovereign citizens, the evils of communism
and the lack of law and order as he kicked off his losing
presidential campaign to Lyndon B. Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Bush talked about what a great patriot McCain is. McCain talked
about how cool it is that the next first lady won't be running for
the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and McCain had spent Saturday morning in photo
opportunities in front of aircraft carriers in Everett, Wash., and
had spent the past three days campaigning together in California,
Oregon and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   McCain enthusiastically predicted that Bush will carry all three
states in November, along with Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Bush didn't deviate from his normal spiel as about 5,000
supporters jockeyed for a good view on the courtyard grass,
dominated by a statue of Arizona frontier hero Bucky O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   We won't have to worry about interns in the Oval Office or what
``is'' means, Bush said. Honor and dignity are in. So is Social
Security, Medicare and the military. And, as has become his habit
on the stump, Bush threw in a sentence in Spanish to the decidedly
non-Latin American crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd started gathering more than three hours before as
venders hawked Bush/Cheney buttons for $4 and Prescott High School
cheerleaders led the crowd in Republican cheers.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was happy to see Bush come to town.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the campaign rally was held right in the middle of
the Mountain Artist Guild crafts festival, which had booked the
site a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Debora Geiger of Santa Fe, who makes crosses of spruce inlaid
with tiles, said business had been slow. And she blamed politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did really well over here on Mother's Day when all these
politicos weren't around,'' Geiger said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at mark.shaffer(a)arizonarepublic.com or
(602) 444-8057.
</P>
</TEXT>
