<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 08:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0249 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-HOMELESS-AZR &LR;      08-13 2251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-HOMELESS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    A SHINING SUCCESS, ILLEGAL NONETHELESS?(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By KARINA BLAND(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - After nights in shelters, run-down motels and even
old cars, kids come to Thomas J. Pappas School not only to learn
but for a good breakfast, a clean pair of underwear and a chance to
cool off.
</P>
<P>
   The school for homeless children has been an Arizona success
story for more than a decade and the sweetheart charity of the
state's largest donors.
</P>
<P>
   But now a powerful national advocacy group, one with the ear of
federal lawmakers, wants to shut it down, saying the children are
unfairly segregated.
</P>
<P>
   The fervor in Washington is so great that congressional hearings
will be held at the school on Sept. 5, so politicians can see the
place for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The debate began with a report by the National Law Center on
Homelessness and Poverty released in February. It charges that
segregating children because they are homeless deprives them of a
quality education and the chance to develop friendships with
children who aren't homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The report notes that Pappas is far different from the 40 other
schools for homeless children scattered across the country.
Typically, they are little more than a room in a shelter or church
basement, often without certified teachers or a real curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas is a $3.8million school with computers and a library.
Still, says Bret Boyce, the center's staff attorney, the concern is
the same: The separate schools are unequal, in much the same way
that schools that segregated children by color were.
</P>
<P>
   The homeless schools don't have the resources to offer advanced
math, science and computer classes, or theater, music and sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even absent all that,'' Boyce said, ``we are concerned about
the practice of segregating homeless students, simply based on
their status. That, in and of itself, isolates and stigmatizes
them.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's against the law.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Maricopa County Regional School District, which
runs the homeless school, are unapologetic: If it weren't for
Pappas, they contend, their students wouldn't even go to school.
</P>
<P>
   And while Washington considers Pappas' fate, Maricopa County
Schools Superintendent Sandra Dowling, who started the school 11
years ago, will open a second campus in the East Valley sometime in
the next year.
</P>
<P>
   She'll hear no talk of shutting down.
</P>
<P>
   MODEST BEGINNINGS
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 1.2 million children nationwide are homeless. Local
officials figure as many as 24,000 homeless children are in Arizona
public schools, a number that has doubled since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas started with eight children in a church 11 years ago. At
the end of last school year, it had 780 students, up from 450 the
year before.
</P>
<P>
   Boyce, of the National Law Center, says he doesn't question
whether Pappas is doing well by students academically and in
meeting their other needs. It's the principle he's concerned about.
Segregation of students, for any reason, can't be OK in one case
but not another, he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Stuart B. McKinney Homeless Assistance Act of 1987 backs him
up. Providing $30million nationwide for housing, health care and
education of the homeless, it also prohibits putting homeless kids
in separate schools.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona receives several million annually in McKinney funds,
with $444,000 of last year's allocation going to the state
Department of Education for homeless students. Pappas received
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Boyce wants Congress to prohibit the separate schools or at
least deny them, and the states that support them, McKinney
funding.
</P>
<P>
   He suggests sending homeless students to regular public schools
and turning Pappas into a resource center for all homeless
children.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence for and against segregating homeless students is
mostly anecdotal. The Law Center report is the first to look
closely at such schools, which operate quietly out of the public
eye.
</P>
<P>
   Many homeless students do just fine in regular public schools,
says Jennifer Henderson, the state Department of Education's
homeless education coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   After all, Pappas has only a fraction of the estimated 24,000
homeless kids in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   The rest blend in to regular classrooms, wearing discreetly
donated clothes and showering in the school nurse's office. The bus
picks them up down the street from the shelter, so the other kids
won't see where they live.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson likes Pappas, but says that because of its high
profile, ``people think we're taking care of all of our homeless
students, and we're not.''
</P>
<P>
   So while Pappas gets the donations and Christmas parties,
regular public schools limp by on what money they did get from the
McKinney Act, paying for tutoring, after-school programs and bus
transportation for their homeless students.
</P>
<P>
   But the federal funds Arizona gets doesn't go far. Only 10 of
Arizona's 400 school districts, including charters, got the federal
grants last year. So, school secretaries and teachers often use
their own money for new backpacks and shoes.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, not all kids, especially those in the toughest
circumstances, fare as well. And if you force them to go to regular
schools, they might not go at all, explained Ernalee Phelps, the
Pappas School's resource development director.
</P>
<P>
   Pappas students eat breakfast and lunch at school, the only
meals some of them get.
</P>
<P>
   Children with lice are soaped with medicated shampoo.
Counselors, doctors and dentists visit regularly.
</P>
<P>
   Dirty, torn or worn-out clothes warrant a stop at the school's
clothing room for a clean outfit, right down to new underwear and
socks.
</P>
<P>
   Little of this is available in regular public schools. And at
Pappas, no one makes fun of matted hair and dirty clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing you can do to a child is break their spirit,''
Phelps said. ``And a single comment - `Ew, you wore that
yesterday,' or, `Why are you so dirty?' - can break a homeless
child's spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Mangini, director of Arizona State University's Bureau
of Educational Research, says that despite the lack of sweeping
studies backing it up, Pappas' mission is ``the right thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is against the law to do this,'' she said, ``change the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   In an October visit to the school, George W. Bush says no way
should the school be closed. Arizona Gov. Jane Hull agrees with the
Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Rep. Matt Salmon, R-Phoenix, has introduced legislation
to exempt existing homeless schools from attempts to ban such
segregation and allow them to continue receiving McKinney funding.
It passed the House but stalled in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one forces these kids to be in this school. It's the
family's decision,'' said Salmon, a regular Pappas visitor and
longtime homeless advocate. ``They know what is best for their
children, not these federal stooges.''
</P>
<P>
   FEARS OF DUMPING
</P>
<P>
   Because of the hassles that come with homeless students, some
schools push them to Pappas, says Mary Michaelis, the school's
registrar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, the public schools would rather not deal with these
kids,'' she said. ``They tire of kids not showing up or moving all
of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Lisa Graham Keegan, state superintendent of public
instruction and a Pappas fan, is concerned that regular public
schools are dumping their homeless students at Pappas.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I have an issue with is the creation of a belief system
that these kids are Pappas' problem,'' Keegan said.
</P>
<P>
   State law requires students to show proof of a permanent
address, immunization and transcripts to enroll in public schools.
Homeless children are exempt.
</P>
<P>
   Crockett Elementary near the large United Methodist Outreach
Ministry shelter at 32nd and Van Buren streets would get the bulk
of Pappas' students if Pappas were to close.
</P>
<P>
   Already, a number of students from the ministry shelter attend,
says Principal Jeanne Sorci, although she is not sure just how
many.
</P>
<P>
   One child even enrolled using an address that turned out to be
an empty lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't care if they are homeless or not,'' Sorci said. ``Our
responsibility is to educate any child who comes through the
door.''
</P>
<P>
   But she says homeless families in crisis can get more help at
Pappas.
</P>
<P>
   At Crockett, homeless children get free meals and uniforms, as
any kid in need would. But, unlike at Pappas, school officials can
only refer them to other agencies for social services, not provide
them at the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are attempting to do as much as we can for these
families,'' Sorci said. ``But schools can't be everything to
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   SPECIAL CIRCUMSTANCES
</P>
<P>
   The students at Pappas score dismally on standardized tests,
ranking among the lowest in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But these children, Phelps explains, miss months, even years of
school as they are dragged from one place to another.
</P>
<P>
   For some, this is their sixth school in as many months.
</P>
<P>
   What's important, Phelps says, is that children who stay at
Pappas from year to year routinely improve their scores. And
they're in school, which is an accomplishment in itself,
considering that the buses from Pappas travel almost 400 miles a
day across Maricopa County to pick up students.
</P>
<P>
   In Lisa Hestand's first-grade summer-school class, Caroline
Rader cuts paper fish with blunted scissors after reading Dr.
Seuss' (beginitalic)Red Fish, Blue Fish.
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic) She lives in an apartment with her mother. Before
that, she says, they lived in a hotel and, before that, in
someone's garage. The 7-year-old has attended six schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it here,'' Caroline says, coloring one fish red and the
other blue. ``The lunch here is good. I really love the lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   The school, which opened in 1997, is getting cramped, though
many other Valley schools have the same problem. Some classes seat
up to 40 students.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Dowling is shopping for a second school site,
somewhere in the East Valley. Already, the county schools 100
children living at a shelter on what was Williams Air Force Base.
</P>
<P>
   Michaelis, the school's registrar, decides when students are
ready to leave Pappas for neighborhood schools, typically four
months after a family finds a place to live.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Morgan, who sits on the board of the Pappas Foundation,
complains Michaelis doesn't move children out soon enough and
admits students who technically aren't homeless to boost
enrollment. That way, he says, the school gets more state funding
and more money from donors and grants.
</P>
<P>
   Michaelis says that isn't true, pointing out that the school
already is cramped.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that whatever causes most families to become
homeless - poverty, domestic violence, substance abuse, health
problems - rarely disappears with a new address.
</P>
<P>
   Michaelis has a family now that has been in the same place for
more than four months. But, she says, looking at the kids' records,
it is their eighth move since December.
</P>
<P>
   If they transfer to a neighborhood school now, they'll be back
at Pappas with the next move, Michaelis says. Best just to keep the
children here.
</P>
<P>
   Michaelis estimates it takes 18 months before a family is stable
enough to pay the rent, buy groceries and keep everyone in shoes
and clothes. She says only one of every 100 of her families ever
makes it on its own.
</P>
<P>
   When Corrine Frank, a special-education teacher, started at
Pappas eight years ago, she delighted when a student left for a
regular public school. Now, she watches for their return.
</P>
<P>
   In the mornings before class, Frank's students come to her with
their problems:
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom got drunk last night, and she busted all the windows,
and now we have nowhere to go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting kicked out of the shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone stole my clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   And she still has to teach them about the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that is going to help them break the cycle is
education,'' Frank said. ``While we try to help them with
everything else, their education has to be our primary focus.''
</P>
<P>
   SUCCESS STORY
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Bacon had been to nine schools before he went to Pappas in
fifth grade. At the time, he was sleeping in an abandoned house
with his little brother, Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck's been on the street most of his life, begging on corners
and fending off lice.
</P>
<P>
   Now 19, he just graduated from Carl Hayden High with a ``B''
average and plans to start college this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck is one of seven Pappas alumni going to college, all on
scholarship through the school.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck talks of being a teacher, maybe at Pappas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for Pappas, I don't think I would have made
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So, Chuck is dismayed anyone would even think of shutting down
the school. His brother, 16, still goes there.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't see what's here,'' Chuck said, shaking his head.
``I wonder if any of them have ever been homeless, if they've ever
had to lay their head on a piece of cardboard and sleep in a field,
never knowing who's coming around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if they've ever been locked out of a hotel room with
all of their belongings inside because they couldn't pay the rent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder if any of them ever wanted to go to school but knew
if they did the other kids would make fun of them because they were
dirty and had holes in their shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know what's here at Pappas.''
</P>
<P>
   When politicians are here in September, he'll tell them:
``There's hope here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
