<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 08:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0250 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-CONVENTION-AZR &LR;      08-13 1411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONVENTION-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-CONVENTION-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    REAL ARIZONA TO GREET BLACK JOURNALIST(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By DANIEL GONZALEZ AND PETER CORBETT(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - A decade ago it was unthinkable that thousands of
Black journalists would ever visit Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that more than 2,000 members of the National
Association of Black Journalists will be downtown this week for the
group's 25th anniversary convention is evidence that the state is
overcoming the damage done in 1987, when then-Gov. Evan Mecham
rescinded a paid state holiday honoring the Rev. Martin Luther King
Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance to make over the image of Arizona through the
eyes of African-American journalists,'' said Venita James,
president of the Arizona Association of Black Journalists and
senior editor/bureaus for (beginitalic)The Arizona Republic.
</P>
<P>
   (enditalic)''Instead of lingering pictures of racism, we'll be
able to show that African-Americans can survive and thrive in
Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been an uphill climb to remove the stigma of Mecham's
decision to rescind the King holiday. Arizona lost the 1993 Super
Bowl and other groups, including the NABJ board of directors,
refused to book their conventions in the state or pulled out.
</P>
<P>
   Community leaders have worked for nearly five years to lure the
African-American journalists and other minority groups to town.
</P>
<P>
   NABJ is the largest African-American group to hit Phoenix since
the National Baptist Convention in 1995, which drew 30,000
delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The collaboration of more than 35 public and private entities on
the NABJ convention, far beyond what the average 2,000-delegate
group could expect, shows the growing importance of diversity
issues in competing for conventions, new businesses and even
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a large group of media coming in from all over
the country, it's important to put your best foot forward,'' said
Brian Kearney, executive director of the Downtown Phoenix
Partnership.
</P>
<P>
   SEEKING SIMILAR GROUPS
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the first major conferences involving an
influential minority group since the King holiday was approved, and
Arizona hopes to attract similar groups, according to James Jessie,
Greater Phoenix Convention &AMP; Visitors Bureau national convention
sales manager.
</P>
<P>
   The Native American Journalists of America came to Phoenix last
June, and the National Association of Hispanic Journalists will
meet in the Valley next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has celebrated King's birthday since 1992, after voters
finally approved a state holiday for the slain civil rights leader.
Arizona has the distinction of being the first and only state where
voters have approved a King holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is that they will hopefully write stories about the
changes (in Arizona),'' said Karen Mulzac-Frye, founder of the
Arizona Association of Black Journalists and co-chairwoman of the
committee organizing the convention.
</P>
<P>
   The event is a chance to reshape Arizona's image as a
progressive state where African-Americans enjoy a high quality of
life despite their relatively low numbers, said Denise Meridith,
Arizona director of the U.S. Bureau of Land Management and a
co-chairwoman of the organizing committee. Blacks make up just 5
percent of Phoenix's population of 1.28 million.
</P>
<P>
   Meridith, who is widely regarded as the highest ranking
African-American public official in the state, said organizers
promoted the Multi-Cultural Affairs Council, which was formed in
the early 1990s with support from the hospitality and tourism
industry, business and government, to show that the city was
welcoming to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The convention will showcase the state's many assets, from its
rich diversity of people and cultures, to its natural wonders like
the Grand Canyon and the red rocks of Sedona, Meridith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to sell here is culture,'' she said. ``We really
stressed what would be different here: the outdoors, experiencing
an outdoor fantasy. A lot of African-Americans, they've seen that
on TV, but they haven't had a chance to see it for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   They will have a chance to play golf, saddle up at a dude ranch
and tour the state from Kartchner Caverns to the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   The convention, held at the Phoenix Civic Plaza, runs Wednesday
through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A WARM WELCOME
</P>
<P>
   Skycaps at the airport will wear buttons welcoming the
journalists, banners will adorn downtown streetlights, merchants
will offer special discounts and the Arizona Center will host
entertainment and a film festival for the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Both major party presidential candidates could make an
appearance during the convention
</P>
<P>
   Symphony Hall will feature a Boyz II Men performance for the
NABJ attendees.
</P>
<P>
   NABJ is expected to generate 5,200 room-nights for downtown
hotels and have a direct economic impact of $5million, according to
the convention bureau.
</P>
<P>
   To win the convention, Phoenix beat out two attractive
convention cities, Orlando and New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   A long list of corporate and government agencies lined up to
support the cause, including the convention bureau, Arizona Office
of Tourism and the Downtown Phoenix Partnership. The local sports
teams, Bank One, Wells Fargo, Bank of America, American Express and
Salt River Project also joined the effort. (beginitalic)The Arizona
Republic (enditalic)is a major sponsor, and other local radio and
television stations are involved.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did local leaders have to overcome the racial storm
clouds hanging over the state, but also the fact that NABJ
typically holds its conventions east of the Mississippi. It heads
for cities with large African-American populations like Chicago;
Washington, D.C.; and Philadelphia, not perceived backwaters like
Phoenix. Plus, it's very hot in August. But hoteliers, eager to
fill up their empty rooms, cut room rates for August
conventioneers.
</P>
<P>
   The credit for luring the group goes primarily to the Arizona
Association of Black Journalists. With the help of high-level
community leaders, such as City Councilman Cody Williams, the local
chapter managed to convince NABJ's board of directors in 1997 that
Arizona wasn't the Third World country many within the organization
perceived it to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We generally don't like to go to places where there is
political divisiveness, where there is a sense that a community
doesn't want us,'' said William W. Sutton Jr., president of NABJ
and deputy managing editor at the (beginitalic)Raleigh News and
Observer (enditalic)in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   The NABJ board viewed coming to Arizona as a chance to support
the local chapter's goal of improving newsroom diversity and news
coverage in the state, Sutton said.
</P>
<P>
   SOME NOT HAPPY
</P>
<P>
   Still, the decision to celebrate NABJ's silver anniversary in
Arizona hasn't sat well with some NABJ members. The board of
directors twice considered pulling the convention from Phoenix
after some members raised objections. A few, like Sidmel
Estes-Sumpter, viewed Phoenix as too remote for such a high-profile
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I felt having a convention in the middle of the
desert wouldn't be that attractive to a lot of members,'' the
majority of whom live in the East, said Estes-Sumpter, an executive
producer at WAGA-TV in Atlanta and a former president of NABJ.
</P>
<P>
   Others had lingering concerns about the city's racial climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we won the business, there were a lot of journalists who
said, `How can we go to a state that doesn't celebrate the Martin
Luther King holiday,''' Mulzac-Frye said.
</P>
<P>
   Mecham, the man blamed for the King holiday controversy, was
unaware the Black journalists were coming to town.
</P>
<P>
   Retired and living in Glendale, Mecham said Arizona is as
colorblind a state as there is. He insists Arizona never had a
stigma as a racist state. Political enemies within the state used
the issue against him, he said, adding that his administration
``treated the Blacks very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Host committee co-chairwoman Mulzac-Frye said she focuses on
where Arizona is today, not where it was when the King holiday
issue was red hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has gone much deeper than Ev Mecham,'' she said. ``The
issue awakened the consciousness of all these ethnic groups in
Arizona, including Anglos.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporters at danielgonzalez(a)arizona republic.com or
(602) 444-8312 and peter.corbett(a)arizona republic.com or (602)
444-4815.
</P>
</TEXT>
