<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 08:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0251 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-DEMOCRATS-AZR &LR;      08-13 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-DEMOCRATS-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    IT'S THE DEMS' TURN(a) 
 &HT;    By JEFF BARKER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Los Angeles - Democrats gather Monday for their national
convention as a party eagerly embracing the political center.
</P>
<P>
   As they prepare to anoint Al Gore as their presidential
candidate, the Democrats hope for a convention that is exciting but
not raucous, innovative but not threatening, progressive but not
radical.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, middle of the road.
</P>
<P>
   It may not sound sexy, but that's OK with the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   When they convened four years ago, many of the party's liberals
still were simmering over a welfare-reform bill signed by President
Clinton. The left-leaning wing said that the bill abandoned the
poor and that Clinton was too intent on appealing to voters at the
center of the spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   With the four-day 2000 convention about to open, the Democrats'
march toward the middle is nearly complete. This year, there is
less controversy, at least so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton has moved our party to the center,'' said Mark
Fleisher, Arizona Democratic Party chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still want to protect opportunity for everybody, but we
also expect responsibility from everybody, and that's the
difference. A lot of the old (welfare) programs created in the '70s
and '80s were taken advantage of by some people to line their
pockets instead of using the programs as a steppingstone, the way
they were designed.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's selection of Connecticut Sen. Joe Lieberman as his
running mate offered a clear signal about the party's direction. In
1995, Lieberman became chairman of the Democratic Leadership
Council, a think tank that has worked to give the party a moderate
identity. Among other programs, the DLC pushed for the work-based
welfare reform that was attacked from the left in 1996 for ending
the federal guarantee of welfare for all eligible mothers and
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the parties this year have chosen two people who
understand the need for appeal to the political center,'' said Doug
Wilson, the DLC's former national political director who led the
Clinton-Gore Arizona campaign in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Lieberman) epitomizes this appeal to the center without
abandoning traditional Democratic values, and that's the key,''
Wilson said. ``You can't have one without the other, otherwise it's
Republicanism.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with both parties quieting their extremists, it's
sometimes hard to tell the difference between the two. Republicans
and Democrats alike have sought to claim credit for welfare reform,
and both parties stress ``compassion'' and ``responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, GOP nominee George W. Bush led a convention that
touted tolerance and inclusion. His speech was a radical departure
from Pat Buchanan's 1992 GOP convention address that suggested a
war for the ``soul'' of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess imitation is the sincerest form of flattery,'' said
Arizona Attorney General Janet Napolitano, who thinks Bush has been
borrowing this year from the Democratic playbook.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona state Rep. Ken Cheuvront agrees that Bush is co-opting
Democratic themes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is ``DLC-lite,'' Cheuvront said. ``I think he was using lot
of the rhetoric, but his record in Texas is still Old Guard
Republican right.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheuvront says the DLC's moderate themes fit well in Arizona, a
state in which the Legislature and congressional delegation are
dominated by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average Arizona voter is socially progressive but fiscally
conservative, which is very much in line with the DLC message,''
Cheuvront said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheuvront will join Napolitano as a delegate. Napolitano will
lead the state contingent, along with U.S. Rep. Ed Pastor, D-Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Cheuvront, who is openly gay, says many of the divisions of the
1996 Democratic convention have faded as the party has been
transformed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably the biggest struggle between some of the Old Guard
and the DLC is on free-trade issues,'' he said. Some in the party
have opposed Clinton administration-backed free-trade pacts, which
organized labor contends are sending American jobs overseas.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic convention won't be about highlighting
disagreement within the party. Rather, it will be about its
differences from the GOP, on everything from gun control to taxes.
Gore supports much broader gun control measures than does Bush, and
has said the GOP tax relief plan would threaten the future
viability of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last couple of months, it's the Democrats who have to
recapture ground that has been lost to the Republicans,'' Wilson
said.
</P>
<P>
   To do that, he said the party must define itself anew to the
American people.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at jeff.barker(a)arizonarepublic.com or
(202) 662-7264.
</P>
</TEXT>
