<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 08:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0252 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      08-13 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    BAMBINO'S STEPPING UP FOR LAST TIME(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By E.J. MONTINI(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - This week, the Democrats officially scratch Babe
Ruth from their starting lineup, leaving the team without a heavy
hitter and establishing themselves as the Red Sox of the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   For eight years, Bill Clinton, the Backwoods Bambino, has batted
cleanup for the Democrats, swatting tape-measure home runs and
taking to the pitcher's mound whenever the team needed someone to
toss a shutout.
</P>
<P>
   For eight years, Clinton has astonished the opposition with his
playing skills, particularly his ability to keep from being thrown
out. At the same time, he drew thousands of new fans to the
political ballgame through his off-the-field antics. He was a bad
boy, like Ruth. Flawed, vain, occasionally stupid, unexplainably
reckless but - (beginitalic)man (enditalic)- could he play.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, the Democrats will let Clinton step up to the
plate one last time at their convention in Los Angeles. For him,
it'll be like batting practice, a chance to hit a few long balls
for the home crowd.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Sultan of Political Swat gets shuffled off the
stage and replaced in the batting order by a couple of
minor-leaguers named Al Gore and Joe Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   For the Democratic Party, it'll be like Boston in 1920, when Red
Sox owner Harry Frazee sold Babe Ruth to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth was already the best hitter and one of the best pitchers in
baseball, as well as being what the (beginitalic)Boston Globe's
(enditalic)John J. Hallahan called ``the most colorful star in the
game today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox let Ruth go and haven't won a World Series since, a
record the Democrats will equal or exceed by offering up candidates
like Gore and Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   This must be why the Republicans figured they didn't need a
cleanup hitter like John McCain, the Reggie Jackson of their team.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is the Republicans' best slugger and provides the most
entertaining locker room interviews. Still, they shipped him back
to their Triple-A farm team in Phoenix, figuring they can beat the
Democrats with a couple of Bush-leaguers of their own. And why not?
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman have yet to turn a double play on the
opposition, even with George W. Bush and Dick Cheney lugging tons
of baggage around the bases.
</P>
<P>
   At their convention earlier this month, the Republicans tried to
resurrect the memory of their own Lou Gehrig - Ronald Reagan - and
instead only reminded people how interesting their team used to be.
The Democrats, not wanting to make the same mistake, are hoping to
get Clinton out of town before Gore even arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the political parties seem determined to take all the
color out of the election game, leaving fans to watch a dragged
out, dry-as-dust contest in which we can't tell (and don't care)
who's winning because all the players are wearing gray.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't happen with Clinton. His crazy eight years in office
will be remembered in a way the great Jimmy Cannon once wrote of
Ruth: ``He was a parade all by himself, a burst of dazzle and
jingle, Santa Claus drinking his whiskey straight and groaning with
a bellyache. {hellip} Babe Ruth made the music that his joyous
years danced to in a continuous party. ``
</P>
<P>
   For Democrats, for all of us, the party's over.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Montini at ed.montini(a)arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   republic.com or (602) 444-8978
</P>
</TEXT>
