<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0253 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-13 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ROUTINE ... FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    THE WHOOPS GORE GETS IN L.A. LIKELY WON'T COMPARE
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By JANE ELY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Surely it doesn't mean much politically, but, boy,
was Philadelphia a lot happier to see the Republicans than Los
Angeles appears to be to host the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when Al Gore arrives here mid-week to accept his party's
presidential nomination, his problem won't lie with the reception
he can expect from La La Land.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest hurdle he faces is the reception he will receive not
only in the convention hall here but with the Democratic base vote
all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he'll get lots of whoops and hollers when he comes before
the convention delegates here and he'll get many more along the
political road as he heads toward the November general election.
</P>
<P>
   But, there's your basically standard political whooping and
hollering and there's the truly passionate whooping and hollering.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the vice president has inspired a lot more of the
basically standard kind than the truly passionate kind that's been
such sweet music to the political ears of Republican nominee George
W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   One super-obvious reason for this difference, of course, is the
horrendous longing most GOPers have to take over the White House _
an emotion and drive quite similar to that felt by the Democrats
when they rallied to elect Bill Clinton and his running mate Al
Gore eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, whose selection of Gore to be his vice-presidential
candidate, now is giving the Dem who would succeed him political
grief coming and going.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, eliminate the going. Clinton may be technically a lame
duck, but he's giving every appearance he'll have to be dragged
kicking and screaming from office _ no matter who follows him into
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   And when you figure he and his wife, Hillary, are going to
dominate the opening day of the convention with their speeches
Monday and they each are having massive fund-raisers here _ he for
his presidential library, she for her New York Senate campaign _
Gore has every political right to be angry enough with Clinton to
denounce him.
</P>
<P>
   The veep, however, has designed his campaign in such a way he's
trying to make a political razor cut while walking a finer line
than any Clinton ever has.
</P>
<P>
   One slip, Gore obviously is convinced, and he'll cut his own
political throat, without scratching Clinton and never coming close
to nicking his GOP opponent Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Though not in very exact words, Gore essentially is telling
reporters in a series of pre-convention exclusive interviews that
he wants to campaign as part of a Clinton-Gore team that has
presided during eight years of a pretty swell economy while
severing any association with the president who admits an
inappropriate relationship with an 18-year-old White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of his own choice for a running mate, Connecticut Sen.
Joe Lieberman, Gore previewed his Thursday-night acceptance speech
for one newspaper by saying:
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic theme will be that we represent the new guard, in
sharp contrast to the efforts by the other side to take us back to
the old guard, whose approach did not allow the nation to flourish
and prosper when it was the guiding blueprint in the '80s and early
'90s.
</P>
<P>
   `` ... Our approach at our convention and in our platform and in
our plans for America's future is based not on the illusion of
inclusion, but the reality of diversity and harmony and the
commitment to one another.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Gore is not going to attack Clinton and has promised he
will avoid any personal attacks in his campaign against Bush, he
has honed himself an incredibly narrow political road to follow to
November.
</P>
<P>
   In this vein, he is going to have two opportunities to test his
balance this week.
</P>
<P>
   He is to appear with Clinton at an alleged passing of the
proverbial torch _ far from here, but still very much in the glare
of television lights and reporters' eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, comes his Thursday-night acceptance speech.
This will not be a good crowd to slip before. By and large,
delegates to this Democratic convention have been in the position
of defending Clinton for so long, they'll not welcome any hint of
disdain for and discomfort with the president.
</P>
<P>
   As for personal attacks on Bush, it's always tough to scorn an
opponent's positions without offering at least some derision of
him.
</P>
<P>
   There are indications Los Angeles, current home of heat and
smog, may get more enthusiastic about welcoming the Democrats as
the time for the arrival of droves of delegates nears.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how receptive La La Land winds up being to Gore,
he's still got two really tough crowds to crack if he wants to
smooth his road for the next couple of months. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ely is a Houston Chronicle columnist. (jane.elychron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
