<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0254 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-13 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROUTINE ... FOR SUNDAY &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    WHY TEXAS' TOP DEMOCRAT, PETE LANEY, WON'T BE SEEN IN L.A.
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Texas House Speaker Pete Laney is hardly a virgin
in the wiles of partisan politics.
</P>
<P>
   Before he was first elected to the Legislature 28 years ago, he
was Hale County Democratic chairman. He runs for office every two
years on a partisan ballot.
</P>
<P>
   And last year, when state Rep. Tom Craddick, R-Midland, seemed
too enthusiastic about hastening the day when Laney would be
replaced by a Republican speaker, Laney bumped him from his
longtime tenure as chairman of the House Ways and Means Committee _
and replaced him with a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Laney also is Texas' highest-ranking Democratic officeholder and
the only member of his party left in a statewide leadership role.
</P>
<P>
   So, why isn't he attending the Democratic National Convention?
</P>
<P>
   To some people, that may sound like a pretty good question, but
there is a better one.
</P>
<P>
   Why should he?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Laney is being consistent. Aides say he has never
attended a Democratic National Convention because he doesn't like
to get involved in presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   And this year the presidential race _ or at least being seen as
endorsing either major party candidate _ is near the top of Laney's
list of things to avoid, right under rabies and the bubonic plague.
</P>
<P>
   Laney is too much of a Democrat to openly endorse Gov. George W.
Bush for the White House, but not partisan enough to join the
Bush-bashing fest in Los Angeles. Laney and Bush have worked too
well together
</P>
<P>
   Laney is doubtlessly more conservative than many of Texas'
Democratic convention delegates. But as a lawmaker who has seen the
steady rise of Republican influence in Texas, he is probably more
pragmatic than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   Republican legislators helped elect him speaker over another
Democratic contender in 1993, and he has consistently rewarded
Republicans with House leadership positions.
</P>
<P>
   Although Laney gave Craddick the boot last year, he appointed
other Republicans to chair 11 of the House's 35 standing
committees.
</P>
<P>
   Right-wing Republican leaders, mostly outside the Legislature,
have attacked Laney for being partisan. But Laney has drawn nothing
but praise from Bush, and with good reason. Laney and the late Lt.
Gov. Bob Bullock were instrumental in helping Bush win the
legislative victories that Bush has been bragging about all over
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Civil justice changes, juvenile justice reform, education
improvements and changes in the welfare system _ all Bush
priorities _ were made possible by a bipartisan effort in the Texas
Legislature, the type of lawmaking that Bush says he wants to
export to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   If the truth be known, Laney probably dislikes the attacks that
Vice President Al Gore and other Democrats have waged on Texas'
record, which Laney and other Democratic legislators have had major
roles in compiling.
</P>
<P>
   Laney skated on the edge of the presidential race last month in
Chicago, where he gave Bush a strong, favorable introduction to the
National Conference of State Legislatures. Laney praised Bush for
his ability to work with legislators from both parties but stopped
short of endorsing him for president.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democratic legislators in Texas probably will vote for
Bush. State Rep. Rob Junell, D-San Angelo, Laney's hand-picked
chairman of the House Appropriations Committee, has endorsed and
campaigned for the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Laney's priority for this election year is protecting a thin,
78-72 Democratic majority in the Texas House, which is significant
for a couple of reasons.
</P>
<P>
   One, a Republican takeover could cost him his speakership. And,
two, partisan control of the House will be crucial in next year's
session, when legislators will reapportion legislative and
congressional districts to reflect population changes recorded in
the 2000 Census.
</P>
<P>
   Redistricting will affect elections and the partisan lineup in
the Texas Legislature and the U.S. Congress for the next 10 years.
It is the most partisan business that the Legislature conducts, and
if he is still speaker next year, Laney may need some of that
partisanship he is saving up this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Robison is chief of the Chronicle's Austin Bureau.
(clay.robisonchron.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
