<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0255 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-13 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    ROUTINE ... FOR SUNDAY
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    GO, PAT, GO! ... FAR AWAY AND QUICKLY
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ We interrupt the rush to the Democratic
National Convention to bring you a report from the netherworld of
American politics.
</P>
<P>
   In this funky oceanside metropolis due south of Los Angeles, Pat
Buchanan has been busy performing two praiseworthy tasks. He is
further marginalizing his own relevance to the current presidential
campaign (as well, one can only hope, to future ones), and he is
completing the drive of the Reform Party, that devil spawn of Ross
Perot, into the ditch.
</P>
<P>
   It's been the best day's work for a destructive force in these
parts since the Long Beach earthquake of 1933. And unlike that
event, no one has died _ although there has been pushing, shoving
and a hammerlock or two.
</P>
<P>
   To the delight of absurdists everywhere, the Reform mavens have
been assembled here for a national nominating convention amid other
quirky historic relics such as the immobilized liner Queen Mary.
It's been a co-production of P.T. Barnum and the Marquis de Sade.
</P>
<P>
   Actually make that sessions, plural, as the divide between the
Buchanan cadres and the anyone-but-Buchanan folks has riven the
party, sending the Perot (you should pardon the expression)
``regulars'' into rump session.
</P>
<P>
   High principles _ fairness, honesty, loyalty _ have been
invoked. But, not to be too cynical, it looks mostly like a fight
over the $12.6 million in federal funds (from the income tax
check-offs) that can be claimed by the ``real'' Reform nominee.
That person is in line for the cash because of Perot's 8 percent
showing in the 1996 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   With any luck, the Federal Election Commission will flip a coin,
it will land on its edge and the money will go back into the kitty.
More likely the two sides eventually are headed, where else, to
court. Unrecoverable, it seems, is the $2.5 the feds have already
forked over for the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is now at about 1 percent in national polling, and 5
percent is needed in the November election to trigger any federal
money in 2004. So our long national nightmare may soon be over.
</P>
<P>
   Arrayed against Buchanan is an unlikely confederation _ faithful
Perotistas who in their bid to thwart Pat have lined up with (you
better be sitting down) John Hagelin of the Natural Law Party
(whose motto could be: Levitators R Us). Hagelin is a physics
professor at the Maharishi University of Management (if you get my
drift).
</P>
<P>
   This all started last year when Perot made welcoming noises to
Buchanan who bolted the Republican Party as his third bid for its
presidential nomination was sinking quick. All who have watched
Perot toy with the desires of anyone seeking to take up his Reform
Party mantel (especially former Colorado Gov. Dick Lamm, a one-time
Democrat, in 1996) knew it wouldn't work.
</P>
<P>
   But Buchanan wasn't taking no for an answer. With the Perot
party moribund in many states, Buchanan roused just a handful of
folks from his old supporters lists and began to take over a number
of local Reform organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-Buchanan side accuses the erstwhile
columnist-commentator of what amounts to political necrophilia.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bunch of zombies, go follow Pat Buchanan,'' Florida Reform
Party activist Tony Hernandez hollered at one moment of hallway
drama. ``We built it, you stole it. We will not go quietly.''
</P>
<P>
   Whereupon, of course, they left, if not exactly quietly, to hold
their separate session.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The best thing that can be said of the meetings - and it was
argued to me seriously by partisans from both sides - is that these
sessions were not the scripted, sanitized offerings of the
Republicans in Philadelphia two weeks ago or what's on tap from the
Democrats in La-La-Land beginning Monday.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Under Perot, the Reform Party had a straightforward (if
misguided) message of economic nationalism: anti-NAFTA, anti-WTO,
anti-immigration. On those points, Buchanan was a decent fit. But
the Reform Party had said zilch about the social issues
(anti-abortion, anti-gay rights) that have always played a big role
in fueling whatever limited appeal Buchanan achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said he did not insist on making those views part of
the Reform Party platform, but then again, he didn't have to. He
put out a statement of his ``personal beliefs'' just in case anyone
had forgotten them.
</P>
<P>
   I'll give you one of the key lines (``Social and moral decline
and cultural decadence go hand in hand with the death of republics
and the end of empires.``) and you can probably fill in the rest.
Be sure to include, as Pat did, Rome and Weimar.
</P>
<P>
   It's so easy to make fun of these people, but just because it's
easy doesn't mean it's wrong. A national reporter following the
Reform Party saga, shook his head and said: ``I cover mutants,
misfits and the maladjusted.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Russell Verney, a Perot lieutenant in founding the party
eight years ago, could see the gallows humor in watching Buchanan
and the Reformers march off into the sunset together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only manning the Kool-Aid stand,'' Verney said.
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
