<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0292 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r k BC-DIAZ-DIAZ_SFCHRON &LR;      08-13 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIAZ-DIAZ </SLUG>
 _ SFCHRON  
AS THEY STRUGGLE TO SPEAK HIS NAME &HT;    BY JOHN DIAZ
 &HT;        CHRONICLE EDITORIAL PAGE EDITOR
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
LOS ANGELES _Which is most perilous to a politician: to embrace
President Clinton too enthusiastically or to attack him too
harshly?
<P>
   To judge from Campaign 2000, either option is, to borrow a
phrase, an unduly risky scheme.
</P>
<P>
   How else to explain the almost painstaking avoidance of the
words ``Bill Clinton'' by both Republicans and Democrats in the
spotlight these days.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, Republicans on the podium in Philadelphia made plenty
of references to the need for ``character'' and ``dignity'' in the
White House. The Democrats gathering at Staples Center this week
will not let Americans forget that the ``policies of the last eight
years'' have produced peace and prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Still, George W. Bush delivered an hourlong acceptance speech
without
once mentioning the president by name. Al Gore and his Democratic
running mate Joseph Lieberman spoke for a combined 50 minutes at
their Nashville, Tenn., announcement event last Tuesday. Their
C-word count: Zero.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost surreal, considering the passions generated during
the impeachment process just a year and a half ago. No one seems to
want to really run with or against the legacy of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Except, of course, Clinton himself. Clinton can always be
counted on to do what is best for Clinton. Compromise, apologize,
triangulate, lie under oath, retreat, apologize even harder _
whatever it takes. Follow him or try to block him at your peril.
Who is more frustrated today: Mike McCurry,
George Stephanopoulos, Gore and all the other Clinton insiders who
put their reputations and careers on the line to defend him? Or
Newt Gingrich, Bob Livingston, Tom DeLay, Henry Hyde and all the
Republicans who thought for sure they were about to finish him off
politically?
</P>
<P>
   No wonder both sides are keeping their distance.
</P>
<P>
   This week's convention is a perfect example of Clinton's self
absorption. One would think he might feel the pain of Gore and all
those Democratic members of Congress who trouped out to the White
House lawn on that dark December day to stand behind him after he
was impeached. The Democrats are now in serious danger of losing
control of the White House and both houses of Congress for the
first time since 1952. So what is the biggest fund-raising event of
all in Los Angeles, the one with the big
stars and big money?
</P>
<P>
   Why, it's a brunch at Barbara Streisand's Malibu compound to
raise $10 million for the Clinton Library, of course.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how Clinton will interpret history
in that Little Rock library. Will there be a replica of the Lincoln
Bedroom, with a kiosk explaining how the Clinton presidency
perfected the art of the soft-money deal? Will visitors in headsets
hear tapes of his evasive depositions as they view models of the
Oval Office?
</P>
<P>
   There will be plenty of positives to highlight in that library,
as Clinton himself surely will remind us in his prime-time speech
tonight. His timing was perfect, his instincts impressive, in
myriad ways. He came into office as the end of the Cold War
lightened the demand on defense spending, and created the climate
for a commitment to balanced budgets. He broke from party orthodoxy
to agree to welfare reform just as the economy was booming enough
to cushion its effects. He had a knack for knowing when to turn on
his interpersonal skills, and when to use the bully pulpit to
summon the pressure of public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   He continues to dominate the political scene, even when his name
is not spoken. Yet there is remarkably little afterglow for
Democrats, no percentage in hatred for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't like it, don't plan a vacation in Little Rock,
where the library will someday soon be the No. 1 destination. He
will be unrepentant and unindicted, but oddly unrevered, despite
his shopping list of accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current president embodied the potential of a
generation,'' Bush said in his Philadelphia acceptance speech. ``So
many talents. So much charm. Such great skill. But, in the end, to
what end?
</P>
<P>
   ``So much promise, to no great purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush is right about a president he cannot bring himself to
criticize without adding a concession of admiration.
</P>
<P>
   And many Democrats here must agree with those words _ albeit for
very different reasons _ about a president they cannot bring
themselves to praise without an obligatory expression of
condemnation about his personal failings.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they will not admit to their uneasiness.
</P>
<P>
   As they struggle to speak his name.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
