(Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LINUX _ SAN JOSE, Calif. - If there's any doubt that Linux isn't
legit, consider the lineup at this year's LinuxWorld conference
that starts Monday in San Jose. Michael Dell, until recently the
staunchest supporter of Linux rival Microsoft Corp., is one of the
keynoters. IBM, the world's biggest computer maker, is expected to
announce major new Linux-based products. And in perhaps the
ultimate sign that Linux is going mainstream, for the first time
this year the guy who invented it - Linus Torvalds - isn't even
speaking. More than 20,000 people are expected at the fourth annual
conference, and it's become such a hit that organizers are planning
to move it from working-class San Jose to cosmopolitan San
Francisco next year. (Keefe, Cox News Service)
</P>
