<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   STAR-DOC _ When Vladimir Chubinsky came to the U.S. in 1990, the
former Soviet wrestler turned physical therapist had no money,
spoke no English, and was supporting a wife and 4-month-old baby.
Now, he is a massage therapist to celebrities - including Jane
Fonda - and CEOs, and has developed a new fitness program called
``gravitational gymnastics'' that is part weightlifting, part
reflexology, and part energy healing. Chubinsky practices his
techniques with doctors, businesspeople, and celebrities in his
Sandy Springs Wellness Center. His clients claim amazing mental,
physical, and spiritual benefits, but scientists and conventional
physicians are skeptical. He is currently seeking a patent for the
system as well as validation from scientific researchers at GSU and
the Marcus Institute. Someday, Chubinsky hopes to bring his healing
methods to millions. (Kicklighter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   CLASSICAL-ONLINE _ ATLANTA _ Almost everything you read about
Napster, the embattled software program that allows users to trade
music over the Internet, concerns the vibrant, commerce-driven
world of pop music. Napster has grown into a national fad by
offering free tunes and a sense of community for a youthful,
computer-savvy crowd _ underscored by the rebellious thrill of
ripping off major corporations. This is not the profile of the
typical classical music fan. While a smattering of pieces by Bach
and Brahms, Stravinsky and Steve Reich are available on Napster,
downloaded music has thus far had a negligible effect on classical
recordings.(Ruhe, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TNT _ ATLANTA _ TNT rolls out its first series, Bull, with a
special airing at 8 p.m. Tuesday before it moves to a regular 10
p.m. telecast. A second series, Breaking News, is due early next
year. A look into what TNT has brewing in terms of series TV.
(Jubera, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
