u p BC-TAX-REFORM0814-COX     08-13 0403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-REFORM0814-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Modifications in tax law still in talking stage
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There's been much ado about tax reform this year. The
marriage tax bill has been vetoed. Estate tax repeal hasn't gotten
its veto yet.
</P>
<P>
   This election year has also produced legislation, still in
Congress, that would allow bigger retirement plan contributions and
cut taxes on Social Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot for taxpayers to think about. Or it will be if our
elected leaders ever get together enough to finally approve
something.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a lot of Americans not only want to understand any
new provisions but to begin updating their family's financial
plans.
</P>
<P>
   What can a conscientious taxpayer do now?
</P>
<P>
   The answer from experts is: Stay cool. ``I'm telling clients to
sit tight, to wait and see what becomes law,'' said Jeff Scroggin,
a Roswell attorney with experience in estate planning. ``If
something does, we'll deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The election could change the game considerably next year. If a
Republican is in the White House and Republicans dominate both
House and Senate, passage of extensive tax breaks would be more
likely.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say they will try to override President Clinton's
veto of the marriage tax bill this fall.
</P>
<P>
   If Democrats get a win in the House, Senate or White House, then
political compromises may be more likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing we don't want is for people to get complacent and
not do any estate planning because of all the talk,'' said James
Brennan, a manager in KPMG's personal financial planning group in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick look at the current legislation:
</P>
<P>
   _ Marriage penalty. The vetoed bill would give tax breaks to
married couples, with the stated aim of ending the ``marriage
penalty'' in current law.
</P>
<P>
   _ Estate tax. The bill would phase out taxes on large
inheritances over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Retirement accounts. Approved by the House of Representatives,
the bill would gradually increase the annual limit on IRA
contributions from $2,000 to $5,000. The limit on employee
contributions to 401(k) accounts would go up from $10,500 now to
$15,000 in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   _ Social Security. The House also has approved a bill that would
give tax relief to middle- and upper-income Social Security
recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
