<HEADER>
A0300 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-13 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUTCHMAN'S PIPE A ROOT-HARDY VINE 
(WITH PHOTO)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Have you ever heard of a plant called giant Dutchman's pipe?
It is a vine from Brazil with huge, dinner-plate-size flowers that
have a sweet smell that attracts flies, which the plant eats, much
as a pitcher plant catches its prey. The flowers are speckled red.
On TV, where I saw the plant, they said its scientific name was
something like Aristolochia gigantica, but I am unsure if I got it
down correctly. Do you know how I could get one? I am considering
planting the vine on a trellis all over my back fence at the new
house. _ T.L., Houston
</P>
<P>
   A: The extraordinary flower of the Dutchman's pipe vine
(Aristolochia giganea) begins as an odd, curled, C-shaped green
bud. As the bud enlarges, it begins to resemble a Dutchman's pipe.
A maroon/liver-brown saclike growth emerges and enlarges like a
balloon being gently filled with air. This soft pillow opens to
reveal a startling bloom, several inches deep and wide, with a
mottled face and a yellow mouth.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutchman's pipe is a root-hardy vine here, preferring life
on a fence or trellis with its heart-shaped foliage receiving sun
or part sun. A fertile, well-draining soil should help ensure
cycles of blooms spring to fall.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone would say the flowers' fragrance is sweet. The odor
does attract flies needed to pollinate the blooms. When a fly comes
to a flower, it is trapped in the oddly shaped bloom until
pollination occurs. Then the anthers and stigmas wither, and the
fly is released.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutchman's pipe is occasionally found in local nurseries.
Ask your nurseryman about supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am interested in starting new esperanza (Tecoma stans `Gold
Star') plants. I tried seeds, but nothing developed. _ D.C.,
Channelview, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Gardeners who want to encourage more flowering cycles are
encouraged to snip the long, narrow green pods that follow the
yellow esperanza blooms. However, you can leave a few pods on the
plant until they lose their green color, then harvest and separate
seeds from the pods. Sow the fresh seeds in containers of moist but
well-draining, light, loose soil. Press the seeds into the medium,
barely covering. Germination can occur in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Or take semi-hardwood cuttings now through fall. Take 4-inch
cuttings that are woody toward the base and about pencil-size in
diameter. Dip the cut end into rooting hormone and insert into the
growing medium. Protect from cold weather.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When we bought our home, we inherited several rain lilies in
our small garden. We have no idea how to care for them. They have
been blooming and appear to be healthy. Do we remove the tips from
the plants after they have bloomed? Do we cut the stem back or just
leave them alone? How much fertilizer do they require, and how long
will they bloom under normal conditions? _ F.G., Pearland, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: Rain lilies are small members of the amaryllis family that
naturalize easily in upper Gulf Coast area gardens. The crocuslike
blooms appear several times in mid- to late summer and fall,
especially after a rain. Some gardeners plant the bulbs, which will
grow 6- to 8-inch grasslike foliage, in liriope or monkey grass
borders or in sedum. Others mass them to create a small-scale
ground cover or plant them at the base of shrubs. Rain lilies come
in pink, white or yellow and are ideal in containers.
</P>
<P>
   Rain lilies prefer sun to part sun and a light, fertile soil.
They take little care. I just give ours a good drink every now and
then in an effort to jump-start a bloom or two. But nothing works,
of course, like the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   We grow rain lilies from the genera Zephyranthes and Habranthus.
Z. candida, a six-petaled white flower, is a roadside wildflower
that accepts most any kind of garden _ from sand to gumbo. Fall
rain makes this bulb shine. The foliage is upright and tapered. Z.
grandiflora has 3-inch rose-colored blooms and is at its best in
organically enriched soil. The smaller Z. rosea is a deep rose. Z.
citrina, a yellow rain lily, is often sold as Z. sulfurea.
</P>
<P>
   H. robustus is a lavender-pink rain lily on the same scale as Z.
grandiflora, but the flowers face outward like its relative, the
amaryllis.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperia rain lilies open their flowers as day fades to attract
pollinating night-flying moths. The familiar, small white Cooperia
drummondii (also known as Z. chlorosolen) is found throughout
Texas. The similar but more striking Z. drummondii (sometimes known
as C. pedunculata) is a white rain lily that ages to pink and is
commonly called the Hill Country rain lily.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a seeding species, you can remove spent blooms
before they go to seed; or you can allow seed pods to form, let
these ripen on the plant, then harvest and sow elsewhere. Water
rain lilies during long, dry spells. Occasionally improve the soil
with a little compost. Otherwise, I'd just let the little plants
be.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I was given an ``alligator plant'' and was assured I would
not be able to kill it with my brown thumb and that it would
proliferate. It is an interesting plant with serrated leaves that
have tiny pups on the tips of the leaves. The pups drop off and
easily root wherever they fall.
</P>
<P>
   I read somewhere that a plant called ``alligatorweed'' has been
choking some waterways and am concerned that this may be what I
have. I don't want to spread an invasive plant. Do you have any
idea what this plant is? _ S.D., Houston
</P>
<P>
   A: I believe you have Kalanchoe daigremontiana (syn. Bryophyllum
daigremontianum), a succulent with elongated triangular leaves that
are a shiny green on top and have purple splotches on the
undersides. The serrated leaves curl inward, and tiny plantlets
develop along the edges of the leaves. These, as you say, drop and
easily root. Another common name for this kalanchoe is devil's
backbone.
</P>
<P>
   Your plant is not the invasive alligatorweed (Alternanthera
philoxeroides) that is clogging waterways with dense mats with
long, branched and hollow stems. The stems have two leaves opposite
each other, and white flowers grow from the axils of the leaves.
Although alligatorweed grows in water, it also can grow on land. I
understand a biological control, the alligatorweed flea beetle, is
the primary source of control in Texas. This beetle apparently has
been effective across the country, because ``invaded'' acreage has
declined.
</P>
<P>
   (Kathy Huber is the Houston Chronicle's garden editor.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
