<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 14:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0301 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-NASALAB-2NDTAKE-HNS &LR;      08-13 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASALAB-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
X X X ... WADE SAYS.
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next best thing
</P>
<P>
   On land, Shannon Lucid is a national space icon.
</P>
<P>
   Underwater, she's just another astronaut trying to pass her
final exam.
</P>
<P>
   While Lucid has earned high marks in space for setting a world's
record for continuous space flight as a woman, she has never walked
in space.
</P>
<P>
   At age 57, she still hopes for a space walk. So on this day, she
is about to go underwater for six hours to prove she can master
generic EVA skills.
</P>
<P>
   Her partner for the day, astronaut Dan Tani, 39, hasn't made it
into space. But he has been underwater at the NBL close to 20
times, which only increases his anticipation for a space mission.
</P>
<P>
   He and Lucid will undergo a grueling test _ replacing broken
parts on a full-size model of a 300-foot-long section of the space
station's truss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to stay out of trouble and fix more than we break,''
Tani jokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``A six-hour run is tough,'' he admits. ``You're usually hungry
when you get out. But the best part for me is the people who help
you. It's like being king for a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Like royalty, the astronauts have dressers. The oversized
spacesuits weigh 250 pounds and are so bulky that it takes a team
of people to suit up the astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   All the pieces of the suit _ boots, lower torso assembly, hard
upper torso, arm assemblies, gloves, helmet _ are laid out near the
pool. With a lot of help and a little pulling and tugging, the
astronauts are outfitted piece by piece in the pressurized
spacesuits. At the end, each looks a bit like the Michelin man.
</P>
<P>
   The suits are similar to those worn in space, except they don't
last as long on Earth, says Louis Carfagno, spacesuit engineer for
United Space Alliance, a private contractor that makes and
maintains the spacesuits.
</P>
<P>
   He explains that suits are rebuilt for every 40 hours spent in
the water; the same suits last for 56 hours in space before needing
an overhaul.
</P>
<P>
   Before sending them under, workers strap a tool belt and a
tether onto each astronaut. The tether is used to latch onto the
mock-up. Without something to latch onto, it's virtually impossible
to work in a weightless environment.
</P>
<P>
   Divers also take two big tool boxes into the water. In all, more
than 300 tools will go down for the four astronauts. Lucid and Tana
will use 130; Wisoff and Lopez-Alegria will use more than 200.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the tools are made out of different materials
than those used in space, they are all very ``flight-like, '' tool
technician Ron Buckley says.
</P>
<P>
   Once underwater, spacesuits are adjusted to achieve ``neutral
buoyancy,'' the delicate balance between sinking and floating.
During the ``weigh out,'' which takes about five to 10 minutes,
music is piped in through the sound system.
</P>
<P>
   Lucid and Tani are ``weighed out'' to the sounds of steel drum
music. Wisoff and Lopez-Algeria _ who will go on a spacee mission
in October _ listen to the theme from the television show, ``Lost
in Space.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in the water, the work begins for both astronaut teams.
Maneuvering in such a weightless environment can be tricky. Even
tiny movements can be exhausting.
</P>
<P>
   During repairs, everything must be clamped in place _ including
the body _ before the job can start. All the while, the view
through the space helmet is distorted, like looking through a
fish-eye lens.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there's a sense of wonder and enchantment about being there
that's difficult to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to describe if you've never done it before,''
Lopez-Alegria says. ``The first time I did it, it was really a
magical feeling. It's like driving a car for the first time or
doing anything for the first time. It's like floating. It is
floating. It's pretty special.''
</P>
<P>
   There IS a difference
</P>
<P>
   Even though the underwater training mimics outer space, it's not
the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   Water offers resistance, and its viscosity creates drag. That
doesn't happen in space.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the difference between running through mud with
boots on versus ice skating,'' explains Michael Gernhardt, a
veteran of three missions who has logged nearly seven hours of
space walks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In space, you have to go lightly with the touch because
between you and the suit, there's 500 pounds. You get that mass
moving and it can be hard to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit also feels a little different. In space, the primary
life-support system is contained in a pack on the back of the
spacesuit. In the water, a long umbilical cord supplies cooling
water and specially blended oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   While being ``neutrally buoyant'' approximates zero gravity, it
doesn't achieve it. When an astronaut is upside down in the pool _
a lot of the training takes place that way because of the
configuration of the mock-up _ blood still rushes to the head.
</P>
<P>
   To get a better feel for what it is like in space, astronauts
fly in the KC-135 Weightless Flight Simulator, more commonly known
as the ``vomit comet.'' But they can experience weightlessness for
only about 20 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   They also train at the Virtual Reality Simulation Facility in
another NASA building.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing beats the hours spent in the NBL, Gernhardt says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, you can get all the geometry and choreography worked
out,'' he says. ``Quite frankly, we couldn't do the EVAs without
this kind of facility.''
</P>
<P>
   Uttley says the feeling is mutual among the divers, test
directors and other people who work there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody here is excited to be part of the program. Here, you
know you're having a direct impact or what takes place in space,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's our own little mission every day.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
