<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0302 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-NASALAB-2TAKES-HNS &LR;      08-13 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASALAB-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTER SPACE, UNDER WATER: TRAINING FOR WORK ON THE FINAL FRONTIER,
ASTRONAUTS SIMULATE SPACEWALKS UNDERWATER 
(TWO TAKES; WITH PHOTOS)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLIFFORD PUGH 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In less than two months, Jeff Wisoff and Michael
Lopez-Alegria will walk in space.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, they're doing the next best thing on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Outfitted in spacesuits and strapped onto a metal platform, the
astronauts are lowered into what seems like the largest swimming
pool ever constructed.
</P>
<P>
   Once submerged, they are released and ``weighed out'' by a team
of divers, who add and remove small weights from the suits until
the astronauts become ``neutrally buoyant'' or almost weightless.
</P>
<P>
   For the next six hours, they will remain underwater, where they
will remove a docking adapter and attach it to another part of a
mock-up of the international space station, near the bottom of a
pool more than two-thirds the size of a football field.
</P>
<P>
   Communicating with NASA's mission control throughout the
project, the astronauts follow the same timeline they will pursue
on their sixth day in space.
</P>
<P>
   Call it a dress rehearsal for the launch, which is scheduled for
early October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ready to go do it,'' Wisoff says. ``This is telling us
the clock is getting close.''
</P>
<P>
   It's just another day at the office for astronauts at the
Neutral Buoyancy Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   The mammoth pool, located in a converted aircraft building, is
ground zero for approximating zero gravity on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Known as the NBL, it's a prime training ground for every
astronaut who walks in space. It's also become a magnet for movie
makers.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Sutherland and Tommy Lee Jones are featured around the
pool in the new movie ``Space Cowboys.'' Ben Affleck and Bruce
Willis were among the first ``civilians'' allowed into the water
for a key scene in the hit movie ``Armageddon.``
</P>
<P>
   Willis and Affleck played offshore oil drillers whose expertise
is needed when NASA detects a Texas-sized asteroid on a collision
course with Earth. In interviews, the actors kidded each other
about the filming.
</P>
<P>
   Willis told reporters that Affleck had a nervous breakdown and
cried while filming scenes at the NBL. Affleck laughingly denied
Willis' allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Neither actor was in danger during the filming. They were
surrounded by safety divers and never left the metal platform,
known as the donning stand, that lowered them into the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know what you're looking for in the movie, you can spot
that they're actually still seat-belted and strapped onto the
donning stand,'' says NBL facility operations manager Tony Uttley.
</P>
<P>
   Every time astronauts go underwater for training, they are
surrounded by a team of divers who provide safety backup, keep the
cords that provide air and cooling out of the way, and film the
procedure from every angle imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   The footage is relayed to a bank of video screens in rooms above
the pool, where officials closely monitor the mission.
</P>
<P>
   The pool, which holds enough water to fill 60 Olympic-size
pools, is so enormous that underwater tests are conducted on either
end at the same time. During the ``Armageddon'' shoot in 1997,
while Willis and Affleck performed their scenes on one end,
astronauts underwent training involving large pieces of the space
station on the other end.
</P>
<P>
   Now, simultaneous tests take place all the time. With eight
space launches planned for next year, the NBL is a busy place. An
astronaut spends eight to 10 hours in the pool for every hour spent
in an EVA (``extravehicular activity'' _ that's NASA-speak for
spacewalking).
</P>
<P>
   A growing need
</P>
<P>
   Almost from the beginning of the space program, astronauts have
trained in water. In the early days, it was part of their
instruction because their tiny capsule landed in the ocean upon
re-entering the Earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   As spacewalks became incorporated into missions, astronauts went
underwater to get familiar with the weightless feeling of being in
space.
</P>
<P>
   The demand for underwater training skyrocketed in recent years
with the construction of the international space station.
</P>
<P>
   Astronauts are expected to spend about 1,100 hours in space to
assemble and maintain the sprawling orbital laboratory _ more than
twice the total EVA hours of all U.S. space missions to date.
</P>
<P>
   The old pool at the Johnson Space Center could barely hold a
portion of the space shuttle. Once the mock-up was in the pool,
there wasn't even enough room to open its bay doors.
</P>
<P>
   NASA proposed building a new underwater training facility from
scratch. But U.S. Rep. Tom DeLay, R-Sugar Land, pushed for
conversion of a building owned by McDonnell Douglas near NASA's
headquarters southeast of Houston as a cost-saving measure.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials agreed, and the $34 million facility opened in
late 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the huge building, workers constructed a pool which holds
6.2 million gallons of water. It is so big _ 202 feet long, 102
feet wide and 40 feet deep _ that nearly every cement truck in
Houston was commissioned for a 48-hour continuous pour, observers
recall.
</P>
<P>
   Even with all that concrete, so much metal rebar was used in the
construction that it is considered to be a metal pool, Uttley says.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson Engineering, the subsidiary of a company called Spacehab
that runs the facility under a contract with NASA, developed its
own underwater wireless communication system so astronauts could
talk with test control offices above the pool.
</P>
<P>
   The facility also makes its own oxygen-enriched breathing gas,
Nitrox, to allow for longer underwater training. A medical team is
on hand to monitor all divers, and a hyperbaric chamber is nearby
for emergency decompression treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Two overhead bridge cranes help a small army of workers move
full-scale working models of the shuttle station, robotic arms, and
the Hubble telescope into and out of the water.
</P>
<P>
   On the walls of the facility hang the flags of 17 nations
participating in the construction of the space station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it the biggest underwater space park in the world,''
senior test director Sherwin Wade says. ``It's one of a kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Wade has seen a lot of changes in underwater training since he
was hired as a diver apprentice in 1983. Back then, he was one of a
handful of divers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, around 80 divers rotate in teams every two hours. While
underwater, each astronaut is assigned two safety divers, one
utility diver (to help with tools), and a diver with a video camera
to photograph the scene.
</P>
<P>
   When Wade was hired, he couldn't even swim well. He learned by
``harassment training'' when others held him down in the water and
made him fight to get out. Now, all divers are certified before
they are hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to reminisce every once in a while, but I like where
we're headed now,'' Wade says.
</P>
<P>
   X X X MORE
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
