   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded i)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ U.S. officials are talking about
the possibility of reviving the Palestinian-Israeli talks, saying
the time is short, that Egypt appears ready to be helpful and that
they see some signs of willingness on both sides. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-FOX (Mexico City) _ An interview with Mexico's
president-elect. By Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN (Moscow) _ Since becoming president of Russia,
Vladimir Putin has capitalized on a voter mandate and high poll
ratings to begin putting Russia back in order after a decade of
wild economic and political swings. But along the way, he is
breaking a lot of china, indulging some of the anti-democratic
instincts, his critics say, that came with his KGB training. By
Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ The streets of Jakarta
were mostly quiet as parliament met this past week _ an indication,
perhaps, that despite its daunting problems and continuing disarray
there is hope in Indonesia for a more ordered and cohesive future.
``It's not over yet,'' cautioned a local journalist. But with
another week to go, this has been the first major political event
since former President Suharto was driven from office two and a
half years ago that has not been riven by chaos and bloodshed. By
Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-POLICE (Shanghai) _ Police activity has increased in
several parts of China as the country undergoes a tightening of
social controls ahead of the October 1st National Day holiday.
While the summer sweep of discos and karaoke bars and detentions of
people voicing political dissent is an annual event, the crackdown
appears unusually harsh this year. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CONCUBINES (Dongguan, China) _ Of all the ties that bind
Hong Kong and the Chinese mainland, few may be more pervasive than
sex. But it is not fueled by quick thrills and anonymous
encounters. It is based on a remarkably durable web of
relationships that have flowered between relatively poor Chinese
women and more affluent Hong Kong men, whose jobs require them to
spend days or weeks at a time in the mainland. Many of these
commuters support mistresses or de facto second wives, and
concubine villages have sprouted up across Guangdong Province. But
now the Chinese government is starting to view wholesale adultery
as a social menace, and it is cracking down. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded a)
</P>
<P>
   WELFARELESS-COUNTY (Rushville, Ill.) _ Welfare has completely
disappeared from Schuyler County, Ill. For more than a year, there
have been no new cases, no old cases, no one on the rolls. This
results not just from a strong economy, but also from hard work by
local welfare officials, who give lots of personal attention to
each case _ and have many lessons to teach the rest of the country.
By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-BEACH (Destin, Fla.) _ Destin, the Florida Panhandle village
that had long been regarded as one of the last, little jewels of
coastal old Florida, has been transformed into a coastal city of
condominiums. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
