<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 15:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0319 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-VIEWING14-COX     08-13 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-VIEWING14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'LOOK' MATTERS AS DEMOCRATS TRY TO UPSTAGE GOP
 &HT;    By TOM BAXTER
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Reflecting the party's desire to soften its image,
the polished wood stage of the Republican National Convention
looked like a set for one of the classier television talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   What viewers see when the Democratic National Convention wheels
into prime time Monday night may remind many of ``Who Wants to Be
Millionaire.''
</P>
<P>
   To be broadcast-precise, the futuristic set is colored in the
tones of Red 199, TV White (Cool Gray 3), Blue 300 and Metal
Effects platinum ME222. Designed by Rene Lagler, who has been doing
this for the Democrats since the 1988 convention in Atlanta, the
podium features an onstage chat room where speakers will go to
converse online, as well as the standard moving lectern and walls.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, the set is supposed to remind voters of the
Democrats' ``promise to look forward into the 21st century,''
according to a press release. But if a subliminal association with
the popular get-rich show reminds viewers how well they've done
over the past few years, that will fit with the party's message
also.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised to hear Democrats proclaim theirs to be a
real and authentic political gathering, in contrast to the
carefully staged GOP convention. That's another way of saying the
Democrats have no hope of keeping their delegates under the tight
discipline the Republicans were able to maintain in Philadelphia,
where rock-ribbed conservatives listened politely to doo-wop groups
and a gay congressman.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Democrats may hold up their disorganization as a
virtue _ as they have since at least the 1930s _ their convention
has been crafted with just as much attention to drawing the widest
possible voting audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking out from this stage, you will see a diverse audience
that truly represents all Americans,'' said Democratic official and
fund-raiser Terry McAuliffe. But the objectives of each night's
sessions will differ considerably from the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   _ Monday is Peace and Prosperity night, a time to showcase the
booming economy with a panel on the economy moderated by Labor
Secretary Alexis Herman.
</P>
<P>
   But it will also be Clinton and Clinton night, with the first
ladyspeaking among a group of female candidates and the
presidentbidding the party farewell. Because a major story line of
the week is whether Vice President Al Gore can step out from Bill
Clinton's shadow, expect pundits to drain every ounce of inference
from the president's speech.
</P>
<P>
   _ Republicans might want to skip the Clinton post-game and set
their VCRs for Tuesday. It's a night filled with speakers who often
raise the hackles of conservatives, including Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., the Rev. Jesse Jackson and Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y.,
moderating a panel on education.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday's program will be a liberal who may be more
worrisome to GOP strategists: former Sen. Bill Bradley, who appeals
to independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday is also the day Rep. Loretta Sanchez of California had
scheduled her fund-raiser at the Playboy Mansion, before Democratic
National Committee Chairman Joe Andrew took her off the convention
speakers list for holding it there. She was put back on after she
agreed to hold the fund-raiser elsewhere. _ Wednesday is a night
Democrats hope a broad audience _ from independents of two minds
about the Clinton legacy, to Jewish voters, to Democratic centrists
_ tunes in to see Gore's running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut. Lieberman has helped Gore in polls since he was
announced, and a successful prime-time speech could add to the
bounce.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers will also see a speech by Karenna Gore Schiff, who is
playing a big role in her father's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gore's acceptance speech will cap the convention Thursday
night. The vice president has to hope that Clinton's farewell, the
Sanchez flap and whatever protesters may do on the streets don't
divert too much attention from this, his best chance to make up
ground against George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
