<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALL IT WHAT YOU LIKE, BUT SNACKS ADD FLAVOR TO ANY OCCASION,
ANYWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there is still smoke coming out of my ears, it is probably
not a medical crisis. Call it ``a little whim.''
</P>
<P>
   The word for ``little whim'' in Guadalajara is antojito. That's
what the Mexicans call a pre-meal snack. The Hawaiians call them
pupus. In Greece the word is mezas, in Italy it's stuzzichino.
Visitors to Madrid with a weak grasp on the Spanish language might
be lured into a ``topless bar'' only to learn the actual word is
``tapas,'' another little whim.
</P>
<P>
   In India the word for snack food is chatt. That's what I thought
I was biting into during a visit to a vindaloo parlor in England
several years ago. It wasn't a snack; it was a chili pepper about
the size and voltage of a cherry bomb. It required two quick pints
of beer to reduce the fire to a smoldering ruin.
</P>
<P>
   In a city like Delhi, snack food is served up by a
khomcha-wallah. Indian food authority Madhur Jaffrey says she, and
most of her friends, learned to relish incendiary foods as
children. Her favorite chatt was fried, split-pea patties topped
with chilies, yogurt and tamarind chutney.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we ate them, the hot spices would bring tears to our eyes,
the yogurt would cool us down and the tamarind would perk up our
taste buds as nothing else could. This, to us, was heaven,'' she
reminisced
</P>
<P>
   That's not a little whim. That's a humongous hankering.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican cooking authority Diana Kennedy nominates the natives of
her adopted country as the most persistent noshers in the world.
</P>
<P>
   She points out that in Mexico the term ``little whim'' might
describe fresh roasted acorns or pumpkin seeds, quesadillas with
squash flowers, small tacos with shredded meat doused in green
tomato sauce or mango chunks skewered on a stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Ensenada it is the pismo clam that is the favorite of the
sidewalk carts,'' she wrote. ``In the La Paz market the tacos are
made of shredded fish and in Morelia they are made of brains
sprinkled with chopped coriander. At the back of the Oaxaca market
you can snack on toasted grasshoppers.''
</P>
<P>
   And of course the Mexicans brought us guacamole, chili con queso
and corn chips _ the staples of snack sessions on America's beach
blankets, picnic tables, patio platters and on saucers at ersatz
tapas (not topless) feasts.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent hot afternoon, Alice the Artist decided the only
appetizers served to guests should be cold ones. She also vetoed
the Scandinavian concept of creamed, pickled and smoked herring
with the merlot and dry martinis.
</P>
<P>
   So we served dishes like these.
</P>
<P>
   CURRY LAYERS
</P>
<P>
   SERVES SEVERAL
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cottage cheese
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons curry powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup Indian-style chutney
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup shredded coconut
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cooked chicken, diced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup salted peanuts, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Dump the cream cheese, cottage cheese and sour cream into a
mixing bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Add the curry powder and mix this mess until smooth. Spread the
glunk over bottom of an appetizer plate.
</P>
<P>
   Add layers of chutney, raisins, coconut, chicken and peanuts.
Cover, chill and serve with crackers.
</P>
<P>
   This is a variation on a recipe in the Honolulu cookbook
``Another Taste of Aloha.''
</P>
<P>
   SURIMI DIP
</P>
<P>
   SERVES SEVERAL
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound imitation crab sticks
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup medium-heat salsa
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup minced onion
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoon chopped cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   You could use a half-pound of bulk surimi, chopped. But the
imitation crab sticks are better.
</P>
<P>
   Thaw if necessary and slice the imitation crab sticks (surimi)
lengthwise, then cut each strip in half again. Line up the strips
and use a sharp knife to create quarter-inch cubes.
</P>
<P>
   Dump the cubes into a bowl. Mix in the other ingredients. If you
bought the chunky version, puree the salsa first.
</P>
<P>
   Serve chilled with crackers or crispy corn rounds.
</P>
<P>
   This is based on a recipe in Jane Brody's ``Good Seafood Book.''
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN BITES
</P>
<P>
   SERVES SEVERAL
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cooking oil
</P>
<P>
   2 whole chicken breasts, skinned and boned
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon powdered ginger
</P>
<P>
   toasted sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   Cut the chicken into three-quarter-inch hunks. Brown in oil,
along with the garlic.
</P>
<P>
   Moosh together the brown sugar, soy sauce and ginger. Mix this
into the pan, tossing the chicken pieces to coat, just until the
chicken is no longer pink in the middle. This means you have to cut
one of the pieces in half to test. It also means you get to eat
that piece, if it's cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Chill the chicken pieces, then coat with the sesame seeds and
serve with toothpicks.
</P>
<P>
   This simple but delicious recipe is from ``MONA Cooks,''
published by friends of the Museum of Northwest Art in La Conner,
Wash. If you buy a copy, you also get the recipe for the Mystic
Sons of Morris Graves' Famous Fishtown Zen Dip.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, the French call snack food hors d'oeuvre. And, no,
that does not translate as ``horse eggs.'' It means ``outside the
meal.''
</P>
<P>
   Pass the grasshoppers. And the zen dip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
