<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0327 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TOMCLANCY-MEDIA-ART-2     08-13 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOMCLANCY-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DIVORCE BY ANY OTHER NAME: TOM CLANCY'S EXIT
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV:  Photo NYT3  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On August 3, Robert Gottlieb, one of the most powerful agents in
the book business and the head of the William Morris agency's New
York literary group, received a letter from Tom Clancy, his old
friend and biggest client. His message: He was ending their 15
years of business together. From now on, his book deals would be
handled by Michael Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb was livid. Just a few years before, his relationship
with Clancy had been so close that Clancy occasionally referred to
``the two G's'' _ Gottlieb and God _ said Diana Patin, Clancy's
former longtime secretary. When both men had been divorced, Clancy
even established a pied-a-terre in Gottlieb's building on the Upper
West Side.
</P>
<P>
   Before the day was out, Gottlieb was on the phone to a New York
Times reporter, fuming that Ovitz had ``raided'' his client and
declaring ``open season'' on Ovitz. Clancy, Gottlieb insisted, had
been ``bamboozled.''
</P>
<P>
   The episode has turned Clancy's jump into a highly visible test
case for Ovitz's new business plan: representing writers and stars
as an adviser while simultaneously negotiating deals with them to
produce movies and television. And it has exacerbated already
strained relations between Gottlieb and William Morris' top
executives in Los Angeles, who prefer cordial relations with Ovitz.
William Morris is currently negotiating with Gottlieb to renew his
soon-to-expire contract, raising questions about his future at the
agency.
</P>
<P>
   But Clancy's defection is also an awkward chapter in a deep
friendship between two sharply drawn characters _ Gottlieb, the
streetwise dealmaker with a penchant for hardball, and Clancy, the
mercurial author who seals deals with handshakes and still harbors
fantasies about commanding a tank.
</P>
<P>
   Their relationship began in May 1984, when Gottlieb stumbled
across galleys of Clancy's first book, ``The Hunt for Red
October,'' at a booksellers' convention. Gottlieb cold-called him
at his home in Maryland near Chesapeake Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do I need an agent?'' Clancy replied at the time. Later,
he recalled, ``Rob came after me like a gigolo after an heiress.''.
</P>
<P>
   His military ambitions thwarted by vision problems, Clancy was
selling insurance while plotting thrillers at his dining room table
at night. He sold his debut novel on his own to the Naval Institute
Press for an advance of just $5,000, inadvertently signing away the
rights to use the story or its hero, Jack Ryan, in films.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1984, Clancy finally agreed to meet Gottlieb in New
York, over corned beef sandwiches at a midtown deli, and soon
signed on as client. Together they turned Clancy's name into one of
the most lucrative franchises in the book business. In all,
Gottlieb negotiated deals with Clancy's publisher, Penguin Putnam,
for 47 books, roughly 10 still to be published. Clancy has 10
best-selling hardcover novels to his credit, with another on the
way this fall. His career has spawned a cottage industry of other
projects _ military nonfiction, mass market paperbacks written with
a collaborator, and even his own video game company. Three of his
novels have become movies.
</P>
<P>
   According to executives at William Morris, Clancy earned more
than $300 million from its deals, although Clancy insists that he
made far less. A recent book contract fetched an advance of about
$19 million for each hardcover title. William Morris received a 10
percent commission on each deal. Gottlieb came to represent many
other best-selling clients, including Dean Koontz and Janet
Evanovich. But Clancy remained the foundation of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob is a good guy,'' Clancy, 53, said in an interview last
week. ``He made me a lot of money and I made him a lot of money. We
were pals, for crying out loud.'' Gottlieb, who is 46, attended not
only Clancy's wedding but the weddings of both of his daughters,
and Clancy attended Gottlieb's second wedding, too.
</P>
<P>
   But as time went on, Clancy said, he grew impatient that only
three of his highly cinematic thrillers had been turned into films,
the last one in 1994. ``Eight are out there hanging and flapping in
the wind, and I think they are damn good enough to be made into
movies,'' he said. ``I just wasn't terribly impressed with how the
movies and TV things had worked out.'' He also denied comparing
Gottlieb with God.
</P>
<P>
   People at the William Morris agency, however, point out that
Clancy's exacting standards did not help. He frequently sparred
with producers at Paramount Pictures &UR; ,  &LR; which had acquired the film
rights to his Jack Ryan character from his first publisher. ``I
just thought it was a bit of an exaggeration to say the movies were
based on the books by Tom Clancy _ they should have followed the
books a little more closely,'' he acknowledged last week. He has
also publicly deprecated the casting of Harrison Ford, who played
Jack Ryan in two films.
</P>
<P>
   Although already a millionaire, Clancy also complained about his
earnings from the films. ``The money matters, if you can make money
from it,'' he said. The Naval Institute's deal for ``The Hunt for
Red October'' earned Clancy a total of just over $251,000, he said.
He wasn't content with the two deals Gottlieb negotiated either.
After a multimillion-dollar signing fee, he said, he still hasn't
seen any royalties from ``Patriot Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Clancy met Ovitz about five years ago. Ovitz had resigned his
position as the head of Creative Artists Agency to become president
of the Walt Disney Co. He proposed a ``vertically integrated
partnership'' with Disney in books, television and movies, Clancy
recalled. The deal was never consummated. Ovitz's tenure at Disney
lasted just 14 months.
</P>
<P>
   But Clancy liked the way Ovitz was thinking, and they stayed in
touch. ``Friendship is important,'' Clancy said. ``He explains
Hollywood to me, and I explain the national security stuff to
him.'' When Clancy remarried, Ovitz, too, attended the wedding, and
chatted politely with Gottlieb.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz began informally offering Clancy advice, and about three
years ago signed on as his manager. Unlike agents, managers cannot
negotiate deals for clients, only advise. They usually collect 10
percent of their clients' revenue as a commission. As a result,
over the last few years, Clancy has been paying two commissions on
some deals, according to people at William Morris and associates of
Ovitz.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz began wooing Clancy more aggressively about 18 months ago,
when he founded his new firm, Artists Management Group. The new
firm is a talent management business that also seeks to produce its
own films and television programs on the side. The arrangement has
raised eyebrows in Hollywood because it puts Ovitz's firm in a
potential conflict of interest, advising clients as manager while
negotiating with them as producer. Agents are legally prohibited
from playing such dual roles with clients they represent. Mike
Burns, a spokesman for Artists Management, said that on its own
productions, the company does not take a commission and its clients
are represented by lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy, however, disputes that he ever paid two commissions, nor
does he know the difference between Ovitz's role as his manager and
Gottlieb's role as his agent.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz told Clancy that Artists Management could start generating
at least one movie or television program based on his novels each
year, partly by taking a role as a producer or co-producer. That
sounded good to Clancy. ``Ovitz knows Hollywood pretty well, or he
certainly seems to,'' he said, ``I decided to give him a chance to
show me if he is as good as he says he is.'' Artists Management's
television and movie units are now co-producing with Paramount at
several projects based on Clancy's books. In the next film, Ben
Affleck will replace Harrison Ford.
</P>
<P>
   About 18 months ago, Ovitz officially took over negotiations
from William Morris for all of Clancy's Hollywood dealings, and he
soon grew involved in Clancy's dealings with his publisher, too,
calling with suggestions about publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, opting for the formality of a letter, Clancy last week
cut Gottlieb out completely, explaining that from now on Ovitz
would manage his book deals, too. ``It was time to move on,''
Clancy said.
</P>
<P>
   To Gottlieb, the news was not unexpected, but it came at a
sensitive time within William Morris. The venerable agency last
year named a new co-chief executive, James A. Wiatt, a Hollywood
agent and former vice-chairman of International Creative
Management. His relations with Gottlieb quickly soured, according
to others at the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt rapidly consolidated his power, beginning with a shake-up
of the agency's East Coast film group that led to the departure of
10 agents last year. Wiatt told friends he intended to turn his
attention to the New York book group this summer. Then, over
strenuous objections from Gottlieb and others in New York, he
removed Dan Strone, a friend and ally of Gottlieb's, from his
position in charge of turning the New York literary group's books
into Hollywood films.
</P>
<P>
   Clancy's departure sparked a new confrontation. William Morris
executives in Los Angeles immediately called Ovitz, who was about
to leave for a two-week vacation in Italy and tried to mollify the
situation, saying that on his return he would try to keep William
Morris involved. Meanwhile, Gottlieb went public with his bitter
feelings _ accusing Ovitz of blurring the line between manager and
agent and poaching his client. (A spokesman for Artists Management
said many of its clients also have agents, noting their commissions
don't interfere with its own.)
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb's diatribe only underscored the tensions within the
firm: Don DeMesquita, an agency spokesman, took the extraordinary
step of disavowing Gottlieb's comments, explaining that Gottlieb
spoke only for himself and not for William Morris. The incident
quickly became the talk of the industry, fueling speculation about
Gottlieb's place at the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Through DeMesquita, Gottlieb declined to comment further. Asked
about Gottlieb's future at the firm, Wiatt issued a one-sentence
statement: ``William Morris is not cutting back its East Coast book
operations, and Robert Gottlieb remains in place as head of our New
York literary department.'' People at the firm say Gottlieb's
contract renewal remains under negotiation. Although he is one of
William Morris' biggest earners, the firm could retain the revenue
from his previous deals if he left.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clancy expressed a mixture of sympathy and chagrin
toward his old friend. ``I'm not a partridge; nobody poached me.
But sometimes people let their anger get in the way of their
brains, and that's what happened to Rob in this case. I just hope
Rob didn't shoot himself in the foot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
