<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 16:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0339 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-NYT     08-13 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNET IN JAPAN IS RIDING A WIRELESS WAVE
</HEADLINE>
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ To understand how different the development of the
Internet has been in Japan than in the United States, consider the
plight of Hiroaki Kobayashi.
</P>
<P>
   A veteran telecommunications entrepreneur who started one of the
first modem companies in Japan and then sold it to AT&AMP;T, Kobayashi
is now the president and founder of Tokyo Metallic, a struggling
Japanese provider of high-speed, or broadband, Internet access
lines.
</P>
<P>
   His company is trying to jump start the development of a type of
broadband telephone-line technology known as digital subscriber
loop, or DSL. But while Internet access through DSL is booming in
the United States, Kobayashi's business is barely sputtering. There
are fewer than 1,000 DSL customers in Japan, split between his
company and one lone competitor.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the incumbent Bell phone companies and
their start-up competitors, known as CLEC's, are now closing in on
a million DSL subscribers nationally, according to the Cahners
Instat market research group. And Internet access by high-speed
cable television lines is quickly reaching even higher numbers in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But in Japan, Tokyo Metallic's tiny band of entrepreneurs is
facing many obstacles, not the least of which is the giant Japanese
telephone company Nippon Telegraph and Telephone, which currently
has a competing strategy for wiring Japan with high-speed fiber
optic cables.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Japanese telephone industry invested heavily in an
early version of a digital technology known as ISDN _ a type of
phone service much slower than DSL and only slightly faster than
modem data sent over a standard, analog phone line that many people
in the United States still use for Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   Although NTT has recently made overtures to the American DSL
companies, industry executives said that the telecom giant was in
no rush to invest in DSL _ in part because it is still anxious to
retrieve its investment in ISDN.
</P>
<P>
   For all the landline forces working against him, though, the
biggest challenge to Kobayashi's vision of wiring Japan has nothing
to do with wires at all. Just the opposite, in fact. The Japanese
are heading onto the Internet in droves _ by wireless means.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, according to InfoCom Research, there are between 20
million and 27 million Internet users in Japan, or approximately
one of every five people in the nation. Of that number, nearly half
_ some 10 million _ are connecting to the Internet wirelessly. Of
these wireless customers, 7.5 million are using a service called
i-mode, offered by NTT DoCoMo, NTT's wireless division. For nearly
two of three i-mode users, this wireless link is their only method
of access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   InfoCom forecasts that the percent of Japanese population
connected wirelessly to the Internet will increase to more than 85
percent by 2003, compared with only about 60 percent connected by
fixed-line networks.
</P>
<P>
   That trend suggests that people here are likely to use and
experience the Internet much differently than they do in the United
States, where so far only a fraction of Internet users have
wireless access.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's wireless Internet explosion was set off last year by the
introduction of NTT DoCoMo's i-mode cellular phones, which are
capable of sending and receiving data. And now competing with the
i-modes are an increasingly popular type of cellular phone known as
PHS that supports data speeds of 64,000 bits a second _ as fast as
the wired, ISDN digital phone lines here.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Japan is now moving quickly to a second generation
of wireless Internet technology, which promises higher data speeds
and a variety of location-sensing commercial services that are
likely to be embraced by business customers.
</P>
<P>
   But this is far more than a business revolution. One has only to
sit in a Japanese subway car watching teen-agers communicating via
the Internet cell phones, or wander the stores of the Akihabara,
Tokyo's electronics district, where there are literally hundreds of
different voice, data and data-voice handset models on display, to
grasp the momentum of the wireless Net in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In advertisements and in interviews, Keiji Tachikawa, chief
executive and president of NTT DoCoMo, has been sketching out his
vision of a next-generation digital cellular network to be
initiated early next year, when DoCoMo plans to offer five types of
wireless Internet access devices that will further blur the line
between cell phones and computers.
</P>
<P>
   It is a prophecy that has led many observers of the Internet in
Japan to conclude that the wired world may increasingly become an
afterthought for most Internet users here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan is more mobile and less people are home,'' said Joichi
Ito, an Internet pioneer in Japan who now heads Neoteny, a
Tokyo-based Internet business incubator. ``Most people don't have
living rooms here, and wiring is very high-cost.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also other cultural factors that explain the wireless
versus wired split. Andrew Seybold, an American wireless expert who
visited here this summer to study the Japanese wireless market,
points to a variety of reasons that the wireless Internet has taken
faster, firmer root in Japan than in the United States: better
wireless coverage, pricing on a par with prices for wired service
and the fact that for many people, particularly teen-agers, the
wireless phone is their only phone.
</P>
<P>
   Seybold also noted the strong cultural factors that have driven
the success of the i-mode phone in Japan, particularly popular
``killer applications,'' like train schedules, wireless banking and
games.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese designers seem to have understood the user interface
issues in a way that American designers have not, Seybold said.
``In Japan you can get to the train schedule with two clicks,'' he
said. ``When I try to find a plane flight on a U.S. cell phone, I
have to go through seven menu levels before I can even enter the
flight number.''
</P>
<P>
   One likely consequence of the diverging approaches to the Web is
that Japan, and by extension Asia, may be reaching the next
generation of the Internet far sooner than the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that means that the next generation of technology
innovation and competitive advantage will follow the Web westward
across the Pacific Ocean remains to be seen. Meanwhile, Hiroaki
Kobayashi can only hope that Tokyo Metallic does not become
completely swamped by the wireless wave. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
