<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MUSIC-SATELLITES-ART-     08-13 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-SATELLITES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPACE DETOUR FOR STREAMING INTERNET TRAFFIC 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By THERESA FOLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Listening to NetRadio.com's Woodstock 69 music channel or
KBAC-FM, Santa Fe's jazz and eclectic radio station, or some other
music program over the Internet is gaining popularity among people
who spend lots of time online. But delivering simultaneous streams
of music to thousands or even millions of listeners over an
ever-more-clogged Internet has become increasingly frustrating. If
the audio stream hits too many traffic jams, the listener may find
his Internet radio program stuttering or stopping midway through a
song.
</P>
<P>
   One promising remedy involves sending the stream up to a
satellite, hopping over most of the jam ups on the ground and
landing the music stream at a network hub closer to the listener.
</P>
<P>
   That is how Viacom's MTV Networks is helping move the feed from
SonicNet.com _ one of 18 MTV Web sites _ to the ears of its
Internet audience. SonicNet beams its audio stream to the Loral
Skynet Telstar 7 satellite from a station in Tulsa, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   The satellite feeds SonicNet's programming to antennas around
the country, converting it back to an Internet signal that is
distributed to 135 network hubs operated by America Online,
Excite(AT)Home and other Internet service providers. Those
providers then pass it along through conventional cables or
telephone lines to people at their PC's.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't care if it's delivered by satellite, fiber or carrier
pigeon; we care about cost,'' said Nicholas Butterworth, president
and chief executive of the MTVi Group, MTV's Internet unit. He made
clear, though, that he was still monitoring the results. ``So far
the satellite service has proven valuable,'' Butterworth said,
``but over the long term, who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   MTVi is using competing ground-based distribution services from
companies like Akamai Technologies and Digital Island to improve
the reception of its Internet music and video programs.
</P>
<P>
   The iBeam Broadcasting Corp., which provides the satellite
service to MTVi, said it had signed up 250 Internet content
providers the last nine months, since it started operating its
network of satellites and fiber to bypass traffic jams on the
terrestrial Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment and news providers like MSNBC Cable News, another
iBeam customer, want to see their Web content delivered to users in
the fastest, most efficient way possible and are willing to pay for
such service. IBeam charges the companies monthly fees of $4,600 or
more.
</P>
<P>
   IBeam, which had a public stock offering in May, reported a loss
of $33.1 million for the second quarter on revenue of $3.4 million.
The company has several competitors that offer _ or plan to offer _
satellite service as a way for Internet content companies to rise
above the network fray.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, some overseas Internet service providers have
used satellite links as a way to connect to the United States'
Internet backbone. But the use of satellite distribution by
American Web content companies as a way to gain speed and
efficiency is still a new business, though it is an approach
similar to the way cable and broadcast TV networks have distributed
programming to cable operators and local stations for more than two
decades.
</P>
<P>
   IBeam and its rivals, including Cidera, InterPacket and NetSat
Express, contend that the Internet is a hostile network environment
for streaming media, the Internet term for video and audio that is
viewed or heard as it is transmitted, rather than being received
and stored on the user's PC before being played.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet was not designed to do what we're asking it to do
_ to distribute something that looks like TV or sounds like a CD,''
said Peter B. Desnoes, iBeam's chief executive. He notes that a
three-minute video stream requires a total data transfer of nearly
10 million bytes _ roughly 800 times more than a typical Web page.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way to solve it is to go around the Internet itself,''
Desnoes said. ``We have built a very complex private network that
includes satellite elements that sends content out to the edge.''
</P>
<P>
   The public Internet architecture is simply not designed to
handle large audiences of simultaneous users who, for example,
might tune into Internet Webcasts. Nor are the built-in backup
systems. If a few packets of data are lost in the transmission of
an e-mail message or a Web page, the Internet's software
automatically finds them and replaces them. But in the case of a
video transmission, resending packets to replace lost data can make
for a choppy picture.
</P>
<P>
   For video traveling from a single point to many, ``nothing beats
satellite,'' said Robert Fagin, Internet, infrastructure and
services analyst at Bear, Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Bear, Stearns forecasts a $48 billion market for streaming media
by 2010, up from $1.3 billion today, with perhaps 30 percent of the
flow being delivered by third-party service providers _ whether
satellite players or companies that offer land-based route-around
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Cidera, a satellite-delivery company based in Laurel, Md.,
predicts that audience demand for streaming media will be so strong
that content providers and Internet service companies alike will be
willing to pay companies like Cidera to ensure a smooth and steady
flow of streaming media.
</P>
<P>
   Ramachandran Viswanathan, Cidera's vice president for marketing,
said Internet service providers recognized that ``streaming media
is like a tsunami wave about to break on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even when people have high-speed Internet connections like the
DSL service available through telephone companies, they can find
that streaming media can be slowed or disrupted by bottlenecks on
the Internet, said Bill Collatos, a venture capitalist.
</P>
<P>
   Collatos is a founding managing general partner of Spectrum
Equity, a $3 billion firm in Boston that has invested in Orblynx
Inc. of Fairfax, Va., a company that, with the help of Intelsat,
has developed technology for distributing Internet content by
satellite.
</P>
<P>
   For the public, investment opportunities are still limited.
IBeam shares were offered at $10 in May, and reached nearly $28 in
early June, before falling back. They closed at $10.1875 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cidera, InterPacket and NetSat Express have all registered for
public offerings with the Securities and Exchange Commission, but
have not set dates for proceeding. Meanwhile, competition is on the
way from several big, established satellite companies, including
Intelsat and PanAmSat, which are putting their own Internet-content
delivery networks into service.
</P>
<P>
   IBeam appears to be ahead of the others in its service concept,
which goes beyond delivery and includes flourishes like adding
other material to the information stream. For MTVi, for example,
iBeam can insert advertising into the live streams, tailored to
individual subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a cat owner, you will get a cat commercial,''
Desnoes said. ``We provide those services.''
</P>
<P>
   The economics of the business models are still to be proved by
iBeam and the other start-ups, which lease satellite capacity
rather than operate their own spacecraft.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Stanyard, the principal consultant at the British firm DTT
Consulting, has studied the use of satellites with the Internet for
more than three years. He said that the most that a company like
Cidera could expect to charge an Internet service provider was $250
a month _ a figure that he said in some cases might not cover the
cost of providing the service. ``It becomes difficult to get your
money back,'' Stanyard said.
</P>
<P>
   But Collatos, the venture capitalist, remains guardedly
optimistic about the Internet satellite companies. ``All are early
stage and they will miss their plans; it's inevitable,'' he
acknowledged. ``But fundamentally, the concept they have is
sound.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
