<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TNT0814-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TNT original `Bull' looking marketable
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Money is the root of all TV, so it's a wonder TV and
Wall Street took so long to get together.
</P>
<P>
   But they're together now: ``Bull,'' the first original series
from Atlanta-based TNT (not counting wrestling), debuts Tuesday
night, and Fox counters in November with ``The $treet,'' an almost
note-for-note lifting of this year's market mayhem feature movie
``Boiler Room.''
</P>
<P>
   There's always been something congenitally chilly about Wall
Street's place in the popular culture: its DNA has had more in
common with bill changers than flesh and blood. But CNBC turned the
Street into a spectator sport, and now TNT turns it into a
melodrama, with worthy, if not quite bullish, results.
</P>
<P>
   Created with veteran know-how by Michael Chernuchin (``Law &AMP;
Order,'' ``Brooklyn South''), ``Bull'' begins as a Goliath v. Li'l
Goliath tale. Ditto (baby-faced George Newbern), grandson of the
firm's founder, is disillusioned with the creepy, calcified ways
Grandpa runs things, and so sets out with a band of young turks to
start his own company. It's risky: By striking out on his own,
Ditto might not be impossibly wealthy for the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well, life is risk. These young, cocky traders ditch the
shark's nest they know for the one they don't, and it doesn't take
long for seasoned shark eater Hunter Lasky (Stanley Tucci) to smell
their blood. But all ethics on the Street are situational, and
before you know it, the new firm wants to hire Lasky. Why? He can
show them the money.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto's grandfather, known as the Kaiser (Donald Moffat), is
this drama's most obvious immoral center. As with John Houseman in
that famous Merrill Lynch commercial, when the Kaiser speaks,
people listen. In fact, he's much like Houseman in every way but
one. He has the same jowly, scrubbed-pink face; the same flaring,
Pegasus-wing eyebrows; the same calibrated speech that commands as
it condescends.
</P>
<P>
   But where Houseman was inscrutable, the Kaiser is pure,
blue-blooded evil _ Gordon Gekko without the mousse. ``The one
reason God put us on this planet,'' he rallies the troops, ``is to
make money.'' Sort of makes Gekko's ``greed is good'' battle cry
sound like one of the Ten Commandments.
</P>
<P>
   It is in relation to the Kaiser _ and his
villainous-with-a-capital-V son-in-law (Larry Miller) _ that
everyone else's scruples are judged. They're illegal insider
trading tip isn't as bad as his insider trading tip; they're
sleeping with the enemy isn't as bad as his sleeping _ in the
back-stabbing sense _ with the enemy. Good and bad here can be a
messy distinction we hope the series is smart enough to explore.
</P>
<P>
   The troupe of renegades is more compelling than either the
Kaiser's too-blunt bad-guy role or Ditto's blandly indistinct
guerrilla leadership. There's a likeably smirky boyishness to the
boys _ cinched up in their suits with their hair slightly mussed,
they look the way we imagine they did when their mothers dressed
them up for their eighth-grade class photos.
</P>
<P>
   Carson (Christopher Wiehl) is a farm-boy newcomer; Corey (Malik
Yoba) the cool up-and-comer; Marty (Ian Kahn) not nearly as smart
as he thinks.
</P>
<P>
   The women are necessarily harder; this is a boy's club, after
all. Marissa (Alicia Coppola) is the up-from-nothing single mom;
Allison (Elisabeth Rohm) is Ditto's tough right hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bull'' is part of TNT's continuing strategy to reach a
broader, younger viewership, and it often seems so narrowly focused
on a wide audience that it fails to make the leap into something
memorable.
</P>
<P>
   But pretty good here is often good enough, and maybe, with time,
the network will trust enough in its audience to take it someplace
special.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
