<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0349 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-CHAIRMAN-PROFILE-     08-13 1088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-CHAIRMAN-PROFILE-ART-770&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC CHAIRMAN REMAINS CLOSE TO INDIANA ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republicans on MSNBC's ``Equal Time'' were
having a hard time depicting the smiling, smooth-faced guy in
glasses and a brown suit _ the one trying in vain to offer an
opinion _ as being in league with Al Gore's ``slaughterhouse
killers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, that nice Joe Andrew, the chairman of the Democratic
National Committee, who will bring the gavel down to start his
party's convention in Los Angeles on Monday, did manage to break
into the conversation a couple of times.
</P>
<P>
   When Oliver North asked, ``Is Joe Lieberman going to the Playboy
bunny club on the Feast of the Blessed Virgin,'' referring to a
convention-week fund-raiser unsanctioned by the party, Andrew
sighed and said no. ``I'd love to stop it but I can't,'' he said .
</P>
<P>
   Then he exchanged ideas on the issues with Jim Nicholson,
chairman of the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson: ``Is Joe Lieberman going to work in the
slaughterhouse?'' _ as Gore's wild-talking campaign manager, Donna
Brazile, recently called their headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew: ``It's called the kitchen'' _ the Gore campaign's name
for its ``war room.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson: ``No, it's killers in the kitchen.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew: ``The only killers in this process are Dick Cheney.''
</P>
<P>
   Not quite as tame as he looks, but not entirely comfortable with
the zingers, either. After the show, Andrew tried a little friendly
chitchat on Nicholson: ``Hey, they didn't even need us in there,
did they?''
</P>
<P>
   What he got back, though, was the tight smile of an airline
passenger engrossed in a really good book and hoping to discourage
instant intimacy without being totally rude.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew whispered, ``I'm always the one who asks about his kids''
_ not the other way around. He often sounds surprised by the
brusqueness of life in the capital, having arrived here with his
wife and two children just last year, ``plucked from the obscurity
of the cornfields of Indiana,'' as he puts it.
</P>
<P>
   But then Andrew did not get his job because he is an old
smoothie, or particularly good at acting bad. He got it in part
because the party's heaviest hitters were not begging to take over
at a time when the national committee was going broke, but also
because he had turned around the state operation in Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   He loves to tell the story of how, on his first day in the
Washington job, he took some union officials to lunch and handed
the waiter his brand-new corporate credit card: ``They came back to
the table and said, `I'm sorry, Andrew, but your card has been
rejected.' I didn't know we hadn't been able to pay Visa for six
months.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then he seems to have excelled at the unsexy business of
cutting costs, upgrading the party's online efforts and taking care
of Democrats around the country _ while the better-known general
party chairman, Ed Rendell, handles fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew's ``boring, difficult, unpopular'' cuts helped get the
operation back in the black last year, as one party operative put
it. And Andrew has emerged as a favorite of unions and state
parties, which like his regular-guyness and do not care if he fails
to dazzle on cable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Andrew has been a shot of adrenaline,'' said Judith Hope,
chairwoman of the New York State Democratic Party. ``It means a lot
to those of us in the trenches that he's been there himself.''
</P>
<P>
   The humble-Hoosier routine is no put-on. After an initial
meeting with a reporter, in which his behavior was correct in the
extreme, he asked an associate, ``Do you think I came on too
strong?'' But he is also better connected than his frequent
references to cornfields would suggest.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of those six-degrees-of-separation diagrams that
showed all Hollywood linked to Winona Ryder might work for Joe
Andrew in Washington. Gore's new running mate, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, had Andrew in class as a Yale undergraduate and
recommended him for his current job.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew once worked on a legal case with William M. Daley of
Chicago, who is running Gore's campaign. He is close to Jesse
Jackson, whom he got to know because Jackson regularly attended
Black Expo, an annual cultural festival in Indianapolis. He has
worked for Sen. Evan Bayh of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   That is how he got to know a bunch of people with ties to Gore _
including Bob Squier, Gore's longtime media consultant, who died
earlier this year, and Carter Eskew, Gore's top consultant. Ron
Klain, Gore's former chief of staff, is a fellow Hoosier whom
Andrew knows from Indianapolis _ a networking hot spot, it would
seem. And Klain also had a hand in bringing him into Goreworld.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In a long interview over dinner, Andrew, 40, said it was
politics that had gotten him interested in the wider world in his
hometown of Poe, Ind., population 87, where he was one of nine
children in a Republican family
</P>
<P>
   His father, a barber who went back to school and became a
doctor, moved the family to ``an actual corn-and-soybean farm,'' as
Andrew called it. ``His idea was to be a gentleman farmer,'' he
said of his father, ``but when they divorced, it became a real
farm.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a Newt Gingrich story,'' Andrew said, with a
partisan spin even on the story of how his father left the family.
</P>
<P>
   After that, his mother, a former teacher whom he described as
``a woman who likes a good glass of wine and a Shakespeare
festival'' had to learn how to farm. ``My entire adolescence was
spent mowing weeds,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His escape, his passion, his entertainment and probably his
rebellion were Democratic politics _ as inspired by Robert F.
Kennedy. At age 12, his idea of fun was to go to the mall and slap
bumper stickers for local Democratic candidates on the cars of
unsuspecting shoppers. The Allen County party headquarters became
his hangout.
</P>
<P>
   About that time, a ``very liberal'' teacher began encouraging
him to shoot for Yale University, mostly because a local man had
set up a scholarship to that school, Andrew said, and that is how
he went to college. He later graduated from Yale Law School.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, he met Lieberman. ``But for Lieberman,'' he
said, modestly, ``I would never had gotten involved in any of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
