<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-LIEBERMAN-MARGOLICK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR AMERICAN JEWS, HOPE AND UNCERTAINTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Saturday, Aug. 12, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By DAVID MARGOLICK    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Much has now been written about how the selection of Joseph
Lieberman as a vice presidential candidate breaks the last taboo
and shows how we Jews are now full members of the American
mainstream. To me, it has proved something quite different: just
how vulnerable and insecure we remain. And, depending on how things
play out in November, it may show how insecure and vigilant we
still should be.
</P>
<P>
   Take the initial reaction to the news. Jews everywhere were
instantly on their telephones, friends calling friends, parents
calling children, children calling parents, all prompted by the
same reactions: joy, yes, but also disbelief. We had been assuming
that Lieberman was, like another member of Gore's ``short list,''
Gov. Jean Shaheen of New Hampshire, mere window dressing to humor a
key Democratic constituency.
</P>
<P>
   Even younger Jews had accepted that a Jew on a national
political ticket was something they would never see. Our amazement
at finding we had been wrong was a reminder _ a surprising, telling
reminder _ that for all of our successes, we still felt like
outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   The first incredulity was quickly followed by two equally
revealing phenomena: an almost servile gratitude and a kind of
tribal, uncritical chauvinism. Many American Jews find Lieberman
vaguely discomfiting. We squirm at his conspicuous religiosity, his
constant references to God, which sound so, well, Christian to less
observant Jews. Besides, any friend of William Bennett and Jerry
Falwell is not a friend of ours (though of course the very public
piety we find so distasteful in them we are suddenly willing to
accept from Lieberman).
</P>
<P>
   But given our own deep-seated, atavistic insecurity, we are
willing to overlook these differences. Long ago, a much more
politically primitive and powerless Jewish community loudly
applauded when both the famously progressive Louis D. Brandeis and
the more conservative Felix Frankfurter joined the Supreme Court;
philosophy mattered less than raw ethnic identity and pride. The
reaction to Lieberman suggests that things have not really changed
that much.
</P>
<P>
   Along with what Jews think of themselves, there is the matter of
what others think of us.
</P>
<P>
   When Lieberman's wife, Hadassah, spoke of her mother's time in
Auschwitz and Dachau and her father's experiences in a Nazi labor
camp, a large part of me choked up with pride. In one generation,
we have emerged from unspeakable degradation and approached the
threshold of the White House. But the old fears die hard; at the
same time, I couldn't help but wonder whether other Americans
really wanted to hear what she was saying. How many were thinking,
``Enough already with the Holocaust,'' or even something worse?
</P>
<P>
   Tolerance is in; both parties talk endlessly of ``inclusion.''
But American tolerance is about to be put to a momentous political
test. I'm worried less about the white supremacists whose
anti-Semitic rhetoric now fills the chat rooms. They probably don't
vote in any case, or don't vote Democratic, or don't vote in the
crucial swing states. I'm thinking of the apparently reasonable,
upstanding, ostensibly open-minded and tolerant men and women who,
in the privacy of the voting booth might suddenly realize they
can't abide a Jew just a heartbeat away from the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   America has been good to the Jews. But more than ever before,
Jews are about to learn just how high America's beautiful and
spacious skies really reach, and we may not like what we learn. The
selection of Lieberman is not only a moment of triumph for American
Jews. It is also a moment of truth.
</P>
<P>
   (David Margolick is a contributing editor at Vanity Fair.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
