<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-JFK-BUSH-SORENSEN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TORCH DIDN'T PASS TO GEORGE W. BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Saturday, Aug. 12, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By THEODORE C. SORENSEN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The last Democratic Convention in Los Angeles nominated John F.
Kennedy in 1960. Some in George W. Bush's camp say this race is
Kennedy-Nixon all over again, but with Bush as the fresh face
challenging the two-term vice president. Bush even included footage
of Kennedy in the video that preceded his nomination speech.
</P>
<P>
   But another Jack Kennedy? Governor, let me say this ...
</P>
<P>
   Despite superficial similarities, JFK and George W. could hardly
be more different _ in preparation for global leadership, concern
for the least fortunate and devotion to public service.
</P>
<P>
   Both men came from influential, affluent political dynasties,
with ambitious fathers full of advice, and earned Ivy League
degrees. But Kennedy adopted neither his father's policies nor his
advisers, nor was he less than proud of own his intellectual
training.
</P>
<P>
   Both men delivered vigorous acceptance addresses in mostly
moderate tones, at ease on both television and the hustings. But
Kennedy, having never veered from the center during the primaries,
had no need to backpedal at the convention or to conceal his
party's record in Congress. He waged a campaign of ideas, not vague
applause lines, proposing a Peace Corps and an Alliance for
Progress with Latin America and calling for an end to racism and
the nuclear arms race. The New Frontier, Kennedy said, was ``not a
set of promises'' but ``a set of challenges ... not what I intend
to offer the American people, but what I intend to ask of them ...
appeal(ing) to their pride, not their pocketbooks.''
</P>
<P>
   Respectful of the presidency, Kennedy criticized the incumbent
administration only on policy grounds, never personal ones.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bush, Kennedy invoked compassion. But to Kennedy,
articulating what he called ``a choice between ... the public
interest and private comfort,'' compassion could never have
included a $1.3 trillion tax cut disproportionately favoring
wealthy families like his own, or a Supreme Court making decisions
unfriendly to the interests of women and minorities, or leaving
health coverage for seniors, children and the poor to the private
market.
</P>
<P>
   Both men had a religious upbringing. But Kennedy preferred not
to wear his religion on his sleeve, and he believed no clergyman
should instruct voters or public officials in their civic duties.
He believed taxpayer money should support only public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Both men emphasized strengthening our military. But Kennedy also
emphasized our alliances, our multilateral treaty obligations and
our participation in international organizations. Having
experienced the horrors of war, he sought a comprehensive nuclear
test ban.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, might have failed a surprise quiz on the names of four
relatively obscure foreign leaders. But he would have been able to
discuss in depth the political and economic situation in all four
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy in 1960, like Bush in 2000, represented the party then
in control of Congress, which had blocked the incumbent president's
initiatives and hurled invective at the vice president. But
Kennedy's years of experience in Washington matched those of his
opponent, and his views were already clear to most voters. He was
challenging an administration plunging into recession, not one
basking in prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy selected a running mate, Lyndon Johnson, residing
outside his own home state and with a congressional voting record
close to the center. Far from being anointed by the leaders in his
party, Kennedy came from behind, beholden to no one.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's handlers should reconsider inviting comparisons with
Kennedy. These differences make a difference.
</P>
<P>
   (Theodore C. Sorensen, who was counsel to President John
Kennedy, practices law in New York City.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
