<HEADER>
A0355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-FATHER-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     08-13 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FATHER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AN OBEDIENT FATHER': AN INDIAN STEW OF CORRUPTION, HUMAN AND
SOCIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Don't cry even though you cry such handsome tears.''
</P>
<P>
   The bitter words belong to Radha, the wife of Ram Karan. On a
holiday Ram had ignored her frantic telegrams about their first
baby's illness, finally returning to Delhi only to dissolve in
remorse when he finds that the child had died.
</P>
<P>
   Weeper of handsome tears: It perfectly sums up Akhil Sharma's
cunning, dismaying and beautifully conceived portrait of a corrupt
man in a corrupt society. For both, the corruption is double. On
the surface it is a matter of arrangements, reprehensible but with
a dose of comedy and forbearance.
</P>
<P>
   Ram is the uncomfortable but diligent bagman for a department
head in India's education ministry. He makes the rounds of school
principals, enjoying a good lunch with each and coming away with an
oblong packet wrapped in newspaper. Bribes nourish him and his
boss; they nourish the Congress Party that gave them their jobs and
whose long rule, in the telling of ``An Obedient Father,'' is
tightly woven into its intricate network of payoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so bad; but perhaps so human as well. After all, India
has avoided the extremes of dictatorship; and Ram is in many ways a
nice man.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the course of the 1947 partition, India and Pakistan saw
hundreds of thousands of Hindus and Muslims slaughtered in a mutual
massacre whose wounds _ Kashmir, extremist parties, two confronted
sets of nuclear weapons _ may prove lethal once more. As for Ram,
fat, tender and self-indulgent, he has committed the family
equivalent of civil war genocide: the repeated nightly rape of his
12-year-old daughter, Anita. This was also in the past (she is now
grown and keeps house for him) but, by the time the book ends, it
has proved lethal once more.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma's novel weaves the national into the personal without a
trace of the didactic. What is more astonishing is his success in
joining the amiably picaresque aspects of the corruption _ India's
and Ram's _ with the ghastly evil of its underside.
</P>
<P>
   There are the comically desultory dickerings and schemings among
the ministry officials, the ill-fated attempt of Ram's boss to
switch loyalty and bribes to the Congress Party's rivals, the
mournful intimacy that develops between a police spy and the man
whose telephone he is tapping. These are set among brief but
haunting glimpses of a larger India: street scenes, lovely circular
conversations, a bus ride from village to village. (The old men
squatting by the roadside stand up at the bus' approach, but turn
their backs to avoid humiliation in case it doesn't stop.)
</P>
<P>
   They are set, as well, among exhalations of charnel horror. A
politician casually mentions his partition role in loading a train
with thousands of dead Muslims and sending it north. A gang of
Hindu toughs prepares to massacre the Sikh owners of a store after
the assassination of Rajiv Gandhi. The wife emerges with two
children, washed and dressed for school. A rickshaw driver ignores
her terrified signal. It is a scene of sparse, tense anguish.
</P>
<P>
   Along comes Ram. He commandeers the rickshaw and sends off the
woman and her children. A brave and decent act. But why is he out
so early on streets all but deserted in the fear of rioting? To
fetch a holy man on the anniversary of the death of his wife,
Radha. Why the last-minute haste? To try to pacify Anita, whose
long-repressed rage ignites in a slow, multistaged explosion that
will destroy him.
</P>
<P>
   Years before, Radha had caught him with Anita. Screaming, she
beat him all night, then sent their daughter to live with
relatives, cautioning her to keep silent. Anita did, choking down
her hatred and returning silently home with Asha, her little
daughter, after her own husband's death. Then one night she finds
Ram, tipsy after a party at the house of his boss, Gupta, holding
Asha in an incipiently sexual embrace.
</P>
<P>
   Sharma's rendition of the confrontation is stunning
dramatically, psychologically and in terms of the social
constraints on Indian women. Anita is entirely dependent on Ram:
the reversal that will turn him into the obedient (destroyed, more
nearly) father of the title is like watching a building dynamited
in slow motion from within. Here is Anita's first piteous stammer:
``Mr. Gupta's party . . . You were drunk . . . I don't want . . . I
would kill Asha . . . I'm not joking . . . I would kill you . . . I
can't go anywhere . . . I have no other home.''
</P>
<P>
   Ram's first response is to apologize and console, as if he still
held that power. Over the days, as Anita grows into her fury, he
shrinks. There is rationalization: ``The crime against Anita was
decades old. Since then I had not repeated the crime with any other
child. Asha did not count because I was drunk and had been caught
before anything occurred.'' There is shame at what he did, but much
more at being found out. ``I did not actually believe that I would
ever be discovered, for I could not imagine the world after I had
been caught.''
</P>
<P>
   The world changes unimaginably. Ram curses himself in the
abasing words Anita requires; he pays her money and deeds her the
apartment. An oddly logical truce breaks down in new shame,
dramatized in a series of ghastly scenes that never lose their hold
on the novel's disorienting blend of irony, compassion and cold
moral gravity.
</P>
<P>
   ``An Obedient Father'' is hard, as well as rich and enthralling.
The initial rape scene is all but unbearable. (I think it was a
mistake to excerpt it in a recent issue of The New Yorker, lifted
from the novel's larger context.) Part of the hardness is a fix on
moral issues somewhat divergent from that in much of Western
literature (though the Greeks had it).
</P>
<P>
   Our tradition says, more or less: A person is evil and is or is
not punished, at some point internalizing the evil in the person.
Sharma's message is subtly different. Speaking with Andre Malraux
once, Nehru let drop the phrase ``An evil act has evil
consequences.'' It seems a tautology, but it is not. It steps back;
it is unsentimental and oddly liberating; it doesn't need to
forgive or condemn the person in order to lay the evil pitilessly
bare, and to punish it.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `AN OBEDIENT FATHER'
</P>
<P>
   By Akhil Sharma
</P>
<P>
   282 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 1724EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
