<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Aug. 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A broken area of showers will surround a slow-moving low
pressure area off the Middle Atlantic Coast. A few areas of locally
heavy rain will occur, especially in southern and central New
England, where Atlantic moisture is drawn inland. Meanwhile, a
mixture of clouds and sunshine will prevail over most of the
interior Northeast and Middle Atlantic States.
</P>
<P>
   Hot weather will cover most areas from the Plains to the
Southeastern States. Plentiful sunshine will boost afternoon
temperatures above 100 degrees in much of the central and southern
Plains. A few strong thunderstorms will develop at the periphery of
the hot air mass in the Dakotas and northern Mississippi Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, northern sections will be a bit cooler than in
recent days in the wake of a cool front. The Southwest will
continue to be hot with a few afternoon thunderstorms in the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: ANOTHER FLOOD
</P>
<P>
   Repeated heavy showers and thunderstorms brought as much as 14
inches of rain on Saturday, causing serious flooding in parts of
northwestern New Jersey. Throughout the nation, flooding rains are
more common than they used to be. A study done at the National
Climatic Data Center shows a steady upward trend in extreme
precipitation events since the beginning of the 20th century. The
cause of the long-term trend toward heavier rain storms is unclear,
but some climatologists believe it is related to the general
warming trend of the last 100 years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
