<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0078 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0361 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-WILDFIRES-MACLEA     08-13 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-WILDFIRES-MACLEAN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE THE SKIES ARE SMOKY ALL DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Sunday, Aug. 13, and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By JOHN N. MACLEAN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As air tankers loaded with fire retardant droned overhead, a
group of us gathered at the Teller Wildlife Refuge in Montana's
Bitterroot Valley to discuss the role of fire in the natural
ecosystem. A rash of fires in the valley has turned the Big Sky
into the Red Sky, a bloodshot whirl of smoke and fancy colors. The
main highway, U.S. 93, has become a runway for fire vehicles _
dilapidated school buses transporting 20-person crews, brush
buggies rigged with small fire hoses, heavy fire engines with
thousands of gallons of water, water tankers, and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   The audience at the symposium had come from near and far. There
were enough Forest Service personnel from the region for a reunion
of sorts. But we had a smattering of people from out of state as
well, both new residents of the Bitterroot Valley, the
fastest-growing region in Montana, and visitors to the Teller
refuge, a private sanctuary along the Bitterroot River.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, the Bitterroot Valley has become a magnet
for retirees, stock market millionaires and computer techies with
dreams of a ``cabin in the woods,'' even if the cabins cost upward
of $500,000.
</P>
<P>
   The conference became something of a forum for new-old
conflicts. Three of us _ Jack Ward Thomas, retired chief of the
Forest Service, Stephen J. Pyne, author of a dozen books on fire
history, and I _ tried to explain the basic fire problems of the
West, in particular the challenge of protecting the rising number
of homes and cabins built in once-unpopulated forests and
grasslands, the so-called urban-wildland interface.
</P>
<P>
   The dream home, a log structure with a shake roof nestled among
trees, is a firefighter's nightmare. A fire crew may well walk away
from such a place and let it burn _ a revelation to newly arrived
urbanites, used to city services.
</P>
<P>
   A federal crew chasing a fire beyond the public lands will
defend private homes. But these people should not be asked to risk
their lives if a homeowner has done nothing for wildfire
protection, we told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service vets nodded happily. Some homeowners looked glum.
One visitor piped up: ``Why can't you solve the problem with
zoning? In New York City we'd solve this problem in a minute. We'd
pass zoning so the houses would be built properly.'' Pretty tough
talk from a city that couldn't pick up its own garbage a few years
ago. But the problem is broader than regional resentments.
</P>
<P>
   As fire rages across the 11 Western states this summer, there is
no quick fix in sight. With the current fire season only half over,
more than 4 million acres have burned, already making this the
worst fire season in almost half a century. The previous record was
14 million acres in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   Today, huge amounts of dead wood are ready to burn.
</P>
<P>
   For the past century, the natural cycle of fires has been
interrupted. After fires destroyed early communities in the West _
the famed 1910 fire burned more than 3 million acres in Montana and
Idaho and killed more than 85 people _ the federal government
adopted the ``10 a.m. policy,'' meaning every fire was to be
controlled by 10 o'clock the morning after it was spotted. In
recent years, forest managers have allowed some fires to burn, if
they pose no threat to life and property.
</P>
<P>
   Logging and prescribed burning can help, but both have checkered
histories. Rapacious logging practices created a backlash that has
reduced the timber cut on federal lands to a quarter of what it
was.
</P>
<P>
   Prescribed burning, a godsend to land managers because it
creates breaks in the vegetation, lost some of its allure this
spring. A prescribed burn got out of hand and tore through Los
Alamos, N.M., and wiped out more than 200 homes. The General
Accounting Office estimates it would cost $12 billion to conduct
prescribed burning operations on the 40 million acres of land
needing treatment _ and that assumes no more expensive mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   The federal fire effort also suffers from government downsizing
and aging of the workforce. There are so few experienced
supervisors left that Australian fire managers have been called to
help out.
</P>
<P>
   Federal spending on fire runs close to $1 billion a year, but
budget numbers amount to a gamble, a yearly bet that nothing like
this summer will happen. Federal fire budgets are based on a
percentage of a 10-year average season, with emergency funds
available for heavy seasons. But this ensures inadequate funds for
staples like training and staffing.
</P>
<P>
   The threat fire poses to homes is a bigger problem than a local
zoning board can handle, we told the questioner from New York. For
one thing, home builders can hop from one jurisdiction to another,
avoiding restrictions. But those who buy the homes will expect
protection.
</P>
<P>
   The West has a split personality on government interference. A
Montana newspaper poll taken this summer as fires raged showed
almost even numbers favoring tighter restrictions and favoring
none.
</P>
<P>
   Attitudes may change with more bad fire seasons. At this stage,
no one has had the temerity to propose mandatory national
standards. The occasional insurance company provides a wake-up
call, denying coverage for a home that cannot be defended. Many
homeowners have installed metal roofs, moved woodpiles and taken
other steps.
</P>
<P>
   This season's fires will die out with the snows this fall. But
controversy and confusion over how to handle the fire crisis will
be with us for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   (John N. Maclean is the author of ``Fire on the Mountain,'' the
story of the 1994 fire on Storm King Mountain in Colorado that
killed 14 firefighters. He divides his time between Washington and
Montana.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
