<SLUG> BC-CVN-GORE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE, ROB REINER PROMOTE HEALTH CARE PLAN
 &HT;    By KEN FOSKETT
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND, Ohio _ As Vice President Gore continued his way
toward Hollywood for the Democratic National Convention, some of
Hollywood made its way to him here in the Buckeye state.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Rob Reiner, who says he now works full-time on
children's health issues in California, joined Gore on Sunday at a
children's hospital here to promote Gore's prescription for
extending health coverage to the uninsured, which Gore introduced
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gore told local Ohio media outlets that this week's
convention would be ``full of surprises'' and provide an
opportunity to showcase him as a leader ``fighting for working
families.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to concentrate on substance instead of balloons
and confetti,'' Gore said. ``The convention will be an opportunity
to introduce myself for who I am, not as a vice president who
stands on stage without saying much.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said his acceptance speech Thursday would focus on specific
policy initiatives such as middle class tax cuts and protecting
social security.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to take the risk of going into specifics,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by doctors and sick children at the Rainbow Babies
and Children's Hospital, Gore made no additional pledges regarding
his children's health insurance program.
</P>
<P>
   That plan would pay for children living at or below 250 percent
of the poverty level to enroll in a special Medicaid program for
uninsured children.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also made no mention of Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, in
keeping with his pre-convention strategy of striking a positive
chord. Afterwards, Reiner and other Gore aides were left to
criticize Bush's record of insuring children, noting that Texas
ranks second to last in the number of uninsured children enrolled
in the Medicaid program, also known as the Children's Health
Insurance Program (CHIP).
</P>
<P>
   In an unscripted moment, Reiner tried to goad Gore into singling
out Texas as an example of a state where Medicaid eligibility
requirements discourage people from enrolling in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would one of those states be Texas?'' Reiner asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the straight man,'' Gore responded, smiling uncomfortably.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it wasn't, you don't have to say,'' Reiner continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is, can I still not say?'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore pledged, if elected, to cut down on the red tape associated
with enrolling children in the CHIP program, saying he would
require states to enroll children first, and then determine if they
are ineligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to have a very aggressive outreach strategy that goes
into day care centers, child care facilities, all of the schools,
all the after-school programs, the pre-school programs,'' Gore
said. ``There are millions of children today who are eligible for
the health care coverage under the current program, but they are
not getting it because the barriers are so hard to get over.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett's e-mail address is kfoskett(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
