<HEADER>
A0366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-DUNHAM-PROFILE-ART-NY     08-13 1237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUNHAM-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DANCE ICON SEES A LOVELY NOW IN THE MIRROR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Katherine Dunham is getting ready for a photo shoot.
The radiant star of countless international dance tours and
Broadway and Hollywood musicals from the 1940s on, scrutinizes the
face staring back at her in the mirror. She combs her hair, now
short and gray, and expertly applies her makeup. A friend helps her
into a long blue-black velvet dress studded with small dark stars,
created for her by a young Haitian designer named Cyril. Books are
everywhere. The television is tuned permanently to CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Dunham talks about real estate and the royal succession in
Ghana, sipping what she refers to teasingly as ``that Old Devil
Coca-Cola,'' undiluted, sadly, by rum. The conversation is
punctuated by asides to her scampering 2-year-old goddaughter, Rose
Michele, who perplexes Dunham by calling her Madam.
</P>
<P>
   At 91 Dunham brims with more ideas and serene enthusiasm for
life than anyone around her in the bustling Manhattan apartment
where she is staying, on a sabbatical from her home in East St.
Louis, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   This week she will teach classes and participate in a public
``conversation'' Tuesday afternoon in a studio at City Center,
whose education department is holding an ambitious weeklong Dunham
Institute for dance educators, with daily public panel discussions
on Dunham dance Monday afternoon through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Dunham leads a busy life. Using a wheelchair, she participates
frequently in seminars and is at work on the next installment of
her autobiography, to be called ``The Minefield.'' She will soon be
involved in the renovation of her theater museum in East St. Louis,
where she also maintains a school.
</P>
<P>
   On June 22, her birthday, Dunham was presented with a check for
$1 million by state Rep. Wyvetter Younge, who had lobbied Illinois
legislators for the funds. The money will be used to match a $1
million capital improvement grant from the Doris Duke Foundation.
``We still don't know about operating costs for the next year,''
said Jeanelle Stovall, a longtime colleague and friend of Dunham's.
</P>
<P>
   But Dunham is pleased at this renewed attention to her work.
``It's almost for the accomplishment and furtherance of my
dreams,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a woman old enough to chide an admiring middle-aged
visitor gently about accepting age and embracing wisdom. ``I don't
like that `accept,' '' she said firmly. ``I would just let the
whole thing go. Just be there for it, centimeter by centimeter.''
</P>
<P>
   But then Dunham has confounded expectations all her life. A
black child raised in Joliet, Ill., in the 1920s, she went on to
earn a doctorate in anthropology at the University of Chicago,
become the dance director for the Negro Unit of the Federal Theater
Project in Chicago in 1938 and soon after achieve international
fame as a dancer, choreographer and stage and film performer.
</P>
<P>
   She created a technique, a rich amalgam of Afro-Caribbean dance,
ballet and modern dance, passed along at her influential school in
the New York theater district in the mid-1940s and '50s. Then she
seemed to disappear, settling in East St. Louis in 1967 to teach
dance at Southern Illinois University and establish her school and
museum in the bitterly impoverished town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was needed,'' Dunham said. ``Factories were
closing. But it still had a family life. All of a sudden I found
myself closing out my theater career and using my background in
anthropology to bring together a community, not only to be
preserved but developed.'' Her pupils have included the athletes
Florence Griffith Joyner and Jackie Joyner Kersee and the
filmmakers Reginald and Warrington Hudlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time went by when I took up my serious living in East St.
Louis,'' Dunham said. ``It's a section of my life that I will
someday maybe put on paper. People tend to take things for granted
sometimes, which they did with us. But finally that pays off.
Without knowing it, you find yourself a part of the fabric of the
place. I don't know when or how it happened. But the idea of
leaving there now is very foreign to me. I couldn't. That's home.''
</P>
<P>
   She is in New York at the suggestion of Harry Belafonte and his
wife, Julie, a former Dunham dancer. Dunham had come to lecture.
She recalled that the Belafontes said: ``Why not stay in New York
for a time? You haven't even started your life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And all of a sudden, I said, `Maybe you're right,' '' Dunham
continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wasn't it wonderful? I didn't feel like a dancer anymore. I
began looking at my life and seeing that I had been living it in
stages. And I sat down and figured where I was now. Well, there are
nine stages in yoga. I've gone through all those. I don't want to
have to prove it, but I know it's true. Ten was terrible, just
awful. And now I'm moving into 11. And it's a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you live your life that way, you don't really have much
relationship to the levels before. If I stand here and look
backwards, nostalgia sets in. And nostalgia is the deadly killer of
our dreams. Memory, good, if it serves a purpose. But stay away
from nostalgia.''
</P>
<P>
   When Dunham worried about the expense of living in New York, the
Belafontes helped find money for her year away. ``Not only that,''
Dunham said, ``but it was done in such a way that I did not have a
feeling at all that I was derelict and they were saving me.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversations with Dunham tend to range widely, scattered with
allusions to everything from genomes and Haitian political history
to witches and the plight of American children. ``Without knowing
it, we've left children out of the whole picture, and it's
beginning to give us trouble now,'' she said. She would like, she
said laughing, to set the record straight on another matter.
``Someone told me a few days ago that I was still looked upon as a
witch here,'' she said. ``Maybe by people who don't understand if
it's going to rain, you say it's going to rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on her life, unnostalgically, she talks of
discovering Haiti in the mid-1930s, when she went there to conduct
research on Haitian dance for her master's degree. She recalls her
delight, after experiencing racism as a high school student, in
seeing black senators in tail coats governing Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   She bought property in Haiti, intending that the estate, now in
disarray, would one day be a school and a retirement home for her
dancers. ``There could be a relationship between people who had
gained their freedom,'' she said of the Haitians, ``and people who
had been given their freedom, as we were in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   It was time for the photo session. She gazed warmly into the
camera, those famously lustrous eyes seeming to grow wider by the
second. ``Did you ever see photographs of elderly divas trying to
look sexy?'' she asked wryly.
</P>
<P>
   To what does she attribute her long life? Dunham was silent for
a moment. Could it be yogurt? ``Actually, I don't like yogurt very
much,'' Dunham said seriously. ``Well, you have to do two things.
One is to try really to know yourself, and that takes time and
patience. And you have to give so much, and know what people need,
to know yourself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
