u f BC-HYUNDAI-RESTRUCTURE-4     08-13 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HYUNDAI-RESTRUCTURE-445&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYUNDAI GROUP FOUNDER TO CUT HIS STAKE IN AUTO COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Hyundai Group, South Korea's largest
business group, said Sunday that its founder, Chung Ju-yung, would
sell a 6.1 percent stake in Hyundai Motor Co. by the end of the
year, ending months of defiance of government demands for
reorganization.
</P>
<P>
   The 85-year-old founder will cut his stake in Hyundai Motor to 3
percent from 9.1 percent, which is expected to raise about 216
billion won ($193.8 million), according to Kim Jae-soo, head of
Hyundai Group's corporate reorganization committee. Hyundai plans
to use the money to buy three-year corporate bonds issued by the
ailing Hyundai Engineering and Construction Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sincerely apologize for causing concerns to the people and
shareholders,'' Kim said at a news conference. ``We will faithfully
continue restructuring efforts to regain market trust.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the founder's stake sets the stage for Hyundai Motor
to be spun off from Hyundai Group, a crucial step in efforts to
reorganize the huge business group while easing cash shortages at
Hyundai Engineering and Construction, Kim said.
</P>
<P>
   The construction affiliate, South Korea's largest builder, owes
creditors 5.4 trillion won ($4.8 billion) and has had severe
difficulty in repaying its debts since May, setting off alarms that
both the group and the nation's economy were in danger of another
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   One of the characteristics of South Korean conglomerates has
been the complex network of financing and loan arrangements among
affiliates, which forced healthy companies to prop up the
struggling units of the same business group.
</P>
<P>
   The government has been trying to untangle this complicated web.
One of the most effective methods has been to sever the control
wielded by the founders of the conglomerates and allow individual
units to be run by professional managers.
</P>
<P>
   Kim added that Chung Mong-koo, the chairman of Hyundai Motor,
would be forced to step down as part of the agreement. With the
acceptance of a $167 million emergency loan from creditor banks in
May, Chung Ju-yung ordered his sons, Mong-koo and Mong-hun, to give
up their positions as the heads of several affiliates. While
Mong-hun relinquished his control of the electronics affiliates,
Mong-koo has refused to obey the order.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Motor officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Kim said Hyundai would not allow Chung Mong-koo to acquire his
father's 6.1 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   Korea Exchange Bank, one of Hyundai's main creditors, welcomed
the announcement. ``The plan announced today will fundamentally
resolve the liquidity problem at Hyundai Engineering and
Construction,'' said Kim Kyong-rim, head of Korea Exchange Bank.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hyundai said it would also sell stock and real estate worth $4.9
billion, sell all or part of Hyundai Elevator Co. and focus on core
businesses, including carmaking, shipbuilding and electronics.
</P>
<P>
   However, contrary to demands by creditor banks, the conglomerate
decided to keep several high-level executives, who have
demonstrated their loyalty to the founding family over decades,
even at the cost of incurring losses to investors. Only Hyundai's
board has the authority to oust them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem will be whether these loyal executives would be
able to discard old habits,'' said Yon Kang-heum, professor of
international finance at Yonsei University. ``With major
shareholders wielding the most power, it may take a consolidated
effort by minority shareholders to oust these executives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
