<HEADER>
A0368 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FANCIFUL-AD-COLUMN-NY     08-13 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FANCIFUL-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WACKY, FAKE WEB SITES GRAB ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  By ALLISON FASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Visitors to www.goblertoys.com can find cartoon versions of the
toy inventions of Ira Gobler like Gobler's Wobblers, Rodeo Rover
and Senor and Senorita Sandwich. The site also offers a scrapbook
of the career of Gobler, president and founder of Gobler Toys, and
links to animated commercials.
</P>
<P>
   But anyone doing research into the toy business will soon find
there is no Gobler Toys and no toymaker named Ira Gobler. Rather,
www.goblertoys.com is an example of an increasingly popular trend
in marketing: fictional or fanciful Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   The trend is meant to capitalize on the growing use of and
fascination with the Internet as well as to take advantage of the
capabilities of the Web to produce content at a low cost that
appears to be genuine. In other words, on the World Wide Web, it
can always be April Fool's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet allows you to be a little more out there in your
approach,'' said Peter Capper, vice president and account
supervisor at BVK/McDonald in Milwaukee. ``It's much more accepting
of different ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   For one client, Sun Country Airlines in Mendota Heights, Minn.,
BVK/McDonald created a campaign centered on a fanciful Web site,
www.heybill.com, which is separate from the airline's official
site, www.suncountry.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill'' refers to the president and chief executive at Sun
Country, Bill La Macchia Jr., who has appeared in quirky
television, radio and print ads for the airline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people looked at me as part of the brand,'' La Macchia
said, adding that the silly site was meant to further the airline's
goal of sponsoring ``relationship marketing'' instead of just
traditional advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Heybill.com was built to resemble a friend's home page,
featuring travel tips, a trivia game about famous people named Bill
and opportunities to negotiate with La Macchia for low ticket
prices. To put up the site, BVK/McDonald worked with Mark Net World
in Milwaukee, which is owned by BVK/McDonald and a group of private
investors.
</P>
<P>
   The fictional Web site for Gobler Toys was created by two toy
lovers who met two years ago at the International Toy Fair in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we would love to have is our own Mattel, our own
Hasbro,'' said Steve Fink, vice president for marketing at Bang
Zoom Design in Cincinnati, describing the virtual company he
concocted with Steve Casino, a toy inventor at Kiscom in Englewood,
N.J. ``But obviously, we can't do that because we don't have the
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought the next best thing,'' he added, ``is to have a
fake one.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Web surfers who check out www.rentarelative.com will
see information that appears to be about a company renting stand-in
replacements for people unable to attend family functions because
they are restricted from redeeming frequent-flier miles.
</P>
<P>
   The site presents what seems to be information about the
company's staff, employment opportunities and a detailed price
chart; for instance, if a meal is not served while a stand-in is
working, the price goes up $25.
</P>
<P>
   Sound real? As if.
</P>
<P>
   The site was created as an advertising ploy for a company called
WebMiles.com, which promotes itself as offering members ways to
earn frequent flyer miles with fewer restrictions than conventional
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Case, vice president for marketing at WebMiles.com in
Sandy, Utah, described the site as the ``creative concept by which
we're going to get the message of Web Miles across.''
</P>
<P>
   A humorous television commercial by the WebMiles.com agency,
GMO/Hill, Holliday in San Francisco, shows a laid-back young man
turning up at a reunion of a family clearly not his own: The family
is Asian-American and he is Caucasian. After the man explains he
has been sent to stand in for a cousin who could not attend because
of frequent flyer blackout dates, he spends the afternoon behaving
badly.
</P>
<P>
   Making up a Web site is ``definitely an idea that has legs,''
said Terry Rietta, a creative director at GMO/Hill, Holliday, part
of the Interpublic Group of Companies.
</P>
<P>
   To keep the spoof going, WebMiles.com sent out news releases and
e-mail announcing the formation of RentaRelative.com that only
briefly referred to WebMiles.com, calling the real company a
``strategic partner.''
</P>
<P>
   In the April issue of Esquire, published by Hearst Magazines,
Ted C. Fishman wrote an article meant to parody the abundance of
Web sites for products that seemed too good to be true. To ``take
readers for a ride,'' Fishman said, he described a company offering
free cars to people who agreed to have them plastered with ads, as
if it were real. He and Esquire then actually put up a site at
www.FreeWheelz.com, complete with impressive graphics and a section
titled ``about us.''
</P>
<P>
   But the company may not have been fantastic enough. Fishman said
he heard from advertisers who did not get the joke, asking for
information about becoming sponsors, as well as from people who
said he had been able to get a site up before they could.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Fishman sold the domain name www.FreeWheelz.com for
$25,000 to an entrepreneur who said he was starting his own
free-car ad company. Fishman said that he and Hearst split the
money.
</P>
<P>
   It seems when it comes to fictional sites, the difference
between fiction and fact can be slight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started this as a fake thing,'' said Fink of the
make-believe Gobler Toys site, ``but it could end up being very
real.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
