<HEADER>
A0369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT     08-13 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVE JOBS COMPLAINS ABOUT BOOK; NBC ADDS REALITY TV SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEVE JOBS FINDS FAULT WITH PORTRAYAL IN BOOK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steve Jobs, the co-founder and chief executive of Apple
Computer, is not a happy man at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Jobs called the chief executive of Random House,
Peter Olson, to complain about a book the Broadway Books division
is scheduled to publish in October, according to Stuart Applebaum,
a spokesman for Random House, a unit of Bertelsmann.
</P>
<P>
   The book, ``The Second Coming of Steve Jobs,'' by Alan
Deutschman, portrays Jobs as an abusive, insecure narcissist who,
through a ``reign of terror,'' turned around the once-moribund
company and reclaimed his authority.
</P>
<P>
   Deutschman, a reporter who has worked for Fortune and GQ and is
now a contributing editor at Vanity Fair, says that Jobs took
delight in humiliating Apple employees.
</P>
<P>
   The book also chronicles some of Jobs' business failures.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs, in his call to Olson, ``was concerned that we were
publishing a quote-unquote hatchet job on him,'' Applebaum said. He
added that Olson had no comment for Jobs on the observation.
</P>
<P>
   But Jobs can take some comfort because one place he will not be
reading about his temper and business problems is in the October
issue of Vanity Fair.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, which had negotiated a contract with Random House
to publish an excerpt from the book, told Deutschman last on Aug. 7
that the excerpt would not appear because there was not enough
space in the October issue.
</P>
<P>
   Deutschman said that he was surprised that Vanity Fair, which is
published by the Conde Nast unit of Advance Publications, had
canceled his excerpt so late in the production cycle; the magazine
will be sent to the printers this week, and Deutschman had already
scheduled his final phone call with the article's fact-checker.
</P>
<P>
   Deutschman said he believed that Jobs had put pressure on the
magazine, but he had no proof of that.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Tyrnauer, the editor at large who edited Deutschman's
excerpt, said there was no conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unfortunate, but for space reasons three pieces had to
be dropped from this issue,'' Tyrnauer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because this is a book excerpt and has to come out before the
book's publication date,'' he said, ``it could not hold for a later
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Jobs, through spokesmen, declined to comment on the book or the
excerpt.
</P>
<P>
   _ ALEX KUCZYNSKI
</P>
<P>
   IN REALITY SHOW DERBY, NBC HAS 2 NEW ENTRIES
</P>
<P>
   After a lengthy delay, NBC will announce this week that it has
acquired the rights to ``Chains of Love,'' a reality show that will
literally chain four men to one woman for a week.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has also acquired the rights to a hidden-camera show that
will begin as a special, but which NBC has the option of turning
into a series. In ``Sweet Revenge,'' a contestant will be offered a
chance to get back at a friend or family member for some perceived
offense by setting him or her up for some embarrassment on a hidden
camera.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has agreed to buy 16 episodes of ``Chains of Love,'' which
will likely run in five-episode segments, after one initial
special. That means NBC has bought the rights to three separate
editions of the series, which NBC is internally calling ``Dating
Game Meets Survivor.'' In the show, the woman discards the men one
at a time and picks the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Both shows come from the Dutch production company Endemol. The
deal has been formally finished for some time, an executive
associated with Endemol said. Endemol had negotiated to retain most
of the control over the shows, as it did for its first reality
series, ``Big Brother,'' which has seen some of its cast members
become controversial figures this summer. One participant was found
to be a follower of black leader Khalid Abdul Muhammad, who has
expressed anti-Semitic views in the past.
</P>
<P>
   According to the executive associated with Endemol, the
production house has sought even more control over ``Chains of
Love.'' Shirley Powell, the spokeswoman for NBC's entertainment
division, said, ``I'm assuming we'll have more control than CBS
had, especially after what's happened with `Big Brother.''' In the
event of an on-screen fiasco, the networks could be in a far more
vulnerable position than the production house.
</P>
<P>
   But Endemol's negotiating position has been strengthened by its
long list of reality formats, as many as 60, which are much in
demand at the networks. The shows are not only being looked on as
possible breakthrough hits, like ``Survivor'' has been for CBS, but
also as possible alternative programming if Hollywood unions
representing writers and actors go on strike next summer, as is
currently feared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is making contingency plans,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   _ BILL CARTER
</P>
</TEXT>
