<HEADLINE>
WOMEN ONLINE GO BEYOND FUN; KINKO'S AND FEDEX PLAN SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: two articles; bylines at bottom of each) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNET IS MORE THAN JUST FUN FOR WOMEN &QL; 
 &LR;  Women, it is clear, are not passing hour upon hour at their
computers watching the online equivalent of ``General Hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   A new survey shows that women go online for practical reasons,
like shopping, travel reservations and to seek specific
information, and tend to be loyal to a few chosen sites. Men, on
the other hand, tend to roam around, sometimes looking for
amusement.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one thing women don't want to do online: linger in
front of their monitors with a cup of Cafe Vienna,'' said Jesse
Berst, editor of ZDNet Anchor Desk, an industry newsletter. The
reason? Simply put: ``Women are more pressed for time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, ``It's a Woman's World Wide Web,'' was conducted by
Jupiter Communications with Media Metrix. Besides examining the
sexes' online behavior, it showed that for the first time, women
outnumber men online, with a 50.4 percent share of the online
population.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are interested in a more efficient experience _ getting
online and getting off,'' said Anya Sacharow, an analyst at
Jupiter. ``Men are more interested in technology for technology's
sake, and in the more random aspects of Net surfing.''
</P>
<P>
   Sacharow said the survey pointed to different priorities. Women
are ``often juggling kids, jobs and taking care of the house,'' she
said. ``Men more often than not are only responsible for
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The study found that older women use the Internet to make their
lives easier. Bolstering this notion that women go online to
simplify their lives rather than fulfill them, the study found that
many consumer product sites had disproportionate numbers of female
visitors. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KINKO'S AND FEDEX PLAN DOCUMENT SERVICE &QL; 
 &LR;  Kinkos.com, an online start-up, has announced a deal with the
Kinko's chain of copy shops and FedEx to create a service that
promises to deliver finished presentations and reports within a few
hours of receiving the data.
</P>
<P>
   Online document delivery services, so far offered only by a
small number of start-ups with names like Mimeo.com and
NowDocs.com, have struck a chord with business travelers and others
who want to transmit documents to printing shops for formatting,
proofread them on screen and have them delivered throughout the
country at designated times.
</P>
<P>
   Kinkos.com was formed March 1 as a separate company from Kinko's
Inc., the nation's largest chain of copy and document preparation
stores. Its financial backers include Kinko's and America Online.
</P>
<P>
   The three-way deal, announced last week, will use the 1,000
Kinko's stores and FedEx's delivery network.
</P>
<P>
   ``What customers need is `time definite,''' said Rick Steele,
Kinkos.com's chief executive, meaning they want to know exactly
when their documents will be delivered. With the new service,
customers can have finished documents within four hours in 20 major
markets; the companies plan to add 35 more by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, the service, called Print to Kinko's, will
be on both the FedEx and Kinkos.com Web sites. The deal with FedEx
will allow the companies to scale the operation quickly as customer
demand grows, said David Roussain, FedEx vice president for
electronic commerce.
</P>
<P>
   FedEx already operates service centers in 50 Kinko's stores; it
plans to increase that number to 150 in about nine months.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
</TEXT>
