<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0372 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AFRICAN-AMERICAN-FILM     08-13 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICAN-AMERICAN-FILMS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NURTURED BY TV, BLACK COMICS ARE BREAKING BOUNDARIES AT THE BOX
OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELVIS MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The slogan for the remake of `Shaft'' _ ``Still the man'' _
turned out to be more than an idle boast. The picture topped the
box-office charts in its first week of release, coming in at $21
million. ``Shaft'' was preceded by ``Big Momma's House,'' the
Martin Lawrence comedy, which made $25 million its first week. Both
were followed by ``Scary Movie,'' directed by Keenen Ivory Wayans,
which hosed its competition with $54 million, the biggest opening
ever for an R-rated movie. Then ``Nutty Professor II'' opened at
$42 million, the largest first-weekend take for an Eddie Murphy
movie.
</P>
<P>
   That all four topped the $15 million ceiling said by the studios
to be the limit for black-themed movies means they are no longer
just for a niche market; four times isn't just a fluke. Next up is
``The Original Kings of Comedy,'' a concert film featuring the
stand-up comics Steve Harvey, D.L. Hughley, Cedric the Entertainer
and Bernie Mac; it opens on Friday, and it will be interesting to
see if it continues the winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   This spate of black films may be the biggest sign yet of a new
era. At the same time that young white kids _ 'N Sync, Britney
Spears and Eminem _ are tearing up the pop charts by appropriating
hip-hop and soul, black-themed movies have made a run at the
audiences that are buying that music. In last year's ``Office
Space,'' by the writer-director Mike Judge, the creative force
behind ``Beavis and Butt-head'' and ``King of the Hill,'' a young,
white software engineer drives along and raps furiously to a
gangsta tune; shamefaced, he lowers the volume when he sees a black
man walking within earshot. (I noticed the sea change in 1992
during a live call-in show on MTV during the Los Angeles riot, when
Chuck D of Public Enemy took questions. Not a single call came from
a black viewer; there was no ``Fear of a Black Planet'' among MTV
viewers, many of whom probably had the album, and it made evident
the fact that rap had a large white fan base.)
</P>
<P>
   The mainstream appetite for such material has been stimulated by
television, whose young, white constituency _ the glowing red
center of the target demographic that studios are always aiming for
_ has been steadily growing. Murphy, Wayans and Lawrence fought
their way up on the small screen, where they initially caused a
stir.
</P>
<P>
   The new audience, for which hip-hop is simply a part of its
grammar, has demolished the ceiling for black movies. John
Singleton, who directed the remake of ``Shaft'' for Paramount, has
said the reason MGM didn't put it into production was because that
studio had no faith that there was an audience for it; apparently
MGM is much choosier than it was in 1971 when the original
``Shaft'' saved it from bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The financial glory of these films _ ``Scary Movie'' is the
first by a black director to make $100 million _ proves that
African-American talent has planted a flag right in the middle of
the mainstream. Will Smith's three hits (he even brought viewers
out for ``Wild, Wild West'') can no longer be shrugged off as an
aberration, an exception that proves the rule.
</P>
<P>
   The groundswell probably got going 10 years ago, when ``In
Living Color,'' the sketch comedy show of which Wayans was creator
and host, made its debut on the Fox network. ``In Living Color''
provided a forum for thoughts generally voiced by black comics only
in nightclubs. (That nightclub feel later became available when
``Def Comedy Jam,'' the all-the-way-live and raw stand-up comic
showcase, ran on HBO and provided a home for Lawrence, Cedric the
Entertainer, Hughley and Mac, among others.)
</P>
<P>
   ``In Living Color'' limned the anger that many African-Americans
felt while sitting through ``Driving Miss Daisy'' _ the throwback
foot-shuffling melodrama that was officially certified with Oscars
_ in a sketch where the chauffeur turned the tables on his
demanding charge. ``In Living Color'' had a killer instinct in
playing up a subject _ race comedy from the African-American
perspective _ and folding in shrewd and swift references that had
been given short shrift on network television.
</P>
<P>
   The show displayed its first-strike capability in pieces like
``The Wrath of Farrakhan,'' a ``Star Trek'' parody that blew up
into something much bigger: Wayans' brother Damon was Farrakhan,
the nemesis of a hammy, ineffectual Captain Kirk, played by Jim
Carrey. (``In Living Color'' was the offshoot of the 1987 black
culture film comedy ``Hollywood Shuffle,'' which was directed by
its star, Robert Townsend, and written by Townsend and Wayans. The
projects that Townsend later produced for television _ a
short-lived sketch show ``Townsend Television'' and ``The Parent
Hood'' _ were as gentle and optimistic as their star. The Wayans
brothers' output is considerably more coldblooded.)
</P>
<P>
   During the series' four-year run _ it stalled out creatively
after Wayans disagreed with Fox over the direction of the show and
left, and was canceled soon after _ it was the home of more future
movie stars than ``Saturday Night Live'' in the same period. Jamie
Foxx was a cast member, and Jennifer Lopez bounced to the bumping
segue as a Fly Girl, with moves choreographed by Rosie Perez.
Carrey, who was bypassed when he auditioned for ``Saturday Night
Live'' in the late '80s, got noticed on ``In Living Color'' and
made ``Ace Ventura, Pet Detective,'' the stealth comedy that came
from nowhere to crush its competition.
</P>
<P>
   The series often seemed like a Triple A training camp for the
Wayans family, though they proved to be up to the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Damon, with his heavy-lidded and placid face, took center stage
in sketches, playing the surly convict who tossed off overripe
malapropisms _ ``Allow me to flatulate my liquids,'' he would
snarl, pleased with himself. Or Antoine, one of the soi-disant
movie critics of the recurring ``Men on Film'' sketch, who happily
meowed the virtues of ``big sweaty mens'' in a gay parody of
thumbs-up, thumbs-down critique.
</P>
<P>
   The Wayans brothers Shawn and Marlon are the featured players in
``Scary Movie'' and co-writers of its script. (They're very canny
about the branding of their surname; the title of their WB sitcom,
``The Wayans Brothers,'' plays on the jokey nepotism by treating
the family name as if it were the most important part of their
resumes.) The frenetic and scattershot film is in the tradition of
attention-deficit comedies like ``Kentucky Fried Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The picture has moments good enough to have been sketches on
``In Living Color'' in its heyday: at a movie theater showing
``Shakespeare in Love,'' a young African-American woman (Regina
Hall) who prattles on her cell phone to her homey (``Brad Pitt's
girlfriend is a freak!'') and eats food that's as loud as she is,
is attacked first by the masked killer and finally by the theater
audience.
</P>
<P>
   The success of ``Scary Movie'' is likely to stir the inevitable
sequels and rip-offs that followed ``Scream.'' That kind of
reflexive moviemaking helped kill off the small renaissance of
black film in the 1990s, a movement that included ``Boyz N the
Hood,'' ``Straight Outta Brooklyn,'' ``South-Central'' and ``Menace
II Society.'' The same film was getting made over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Black coming-of-age movies of that period took themselves too
seriously; the melancholy note they sounded was unrelieved and
sentimental. In real life, rappers displayed a gallows humor and
short temper that those movies were never allowed to exploit. And
after all the pathos had been wrung out of the genre, it was as if
the urban experience had been all used up, because no one wanted to
see those pictures anymore.
</P>
<P>
   The plea for understanding had a callow, well-meaning
earnestness, which the Wayanses parodied in 1996's ``Don't Be a
Menace to South-Central While Drinking Your Juice in the Hood.''
(This was a better sketch idea than a film; the title does all the
work.) Black films about adult concerns, however, like ``To Sleep
With Anger'' (1990) _ in which Danny Glover uses his soothing,
honeyed voice for less than altruistic reasons _ lacked the easy
sell of the other films.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately comedy is still the genre where black movies can
score most. Even in ``Shaft,'' Samuel L. Jackson's black-avenger
oppressiveness is so self-conscious that he might as well wink at
the camera as he hauls his magnificence around. The laughs undercut
the crude vigilantism in the current remake. The scene in which
Shaft pulls a pistol on a drug dealer and beats him on the streets
is troubling, but at least he has already quit the police force.
</P>
<P>
   It's far more insidious when, while still a cop, Shaft punches a
suspect in front of a crowd and television cameras. That is meant
to be a bravura gesture, but it debases the worldliness and aplomb
that Shaft is meant to represent; he's supposed to be smarter than
the Dirty Harrys who would beat the sweat off a criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Now the comics who have moved from television to film are
starting to act like men. The maturity that Murphy is showing as an
actor means he may be ready to ease into much more serious work. In
``Bowfinger'' he was Jif, the shy and eager-to-please brother of a
megalomaniac movie star (he also played Kit, the paranoid brother,
without the makeup he used in ``Professor''), and the character was
so vulnerable it could have been painful. Jif's physical discomfort
branded him a needy loner, more pathetic than the Julius Kelp that
Jerry Lewis played in the original ``Nutty Professor'' and to whom
Jif seems a loving tribute. Murphy has grown up without losing his
enthusiasm for comedy.
</P>
<P>
   He was so poised and confident in ``48 Hrs.'' that it's easy to
forget he was only 20 when he walked away with the picture and held
his own against Nick Nolte, who made the mistake of trying to give
his underwritten character some psychological depth. Murphy was so
accomplished and appealing an entertainer that he could laugh at
his own jokes and have the audience laugh along with him.
</P>
<P>
   He has also learned from his mistakes, and some of them, like
``Harlem Nights,'' cost him dearly. The vulgar display of egotism
in that film _ its biggest laughs came at the number of times his
name appeared in the credits _ showed how isolated he had become.
Murphy's cockiness has burned away; he has the finesse of a
grown-up and isn't worried about being upstaged anymore. Once he
would look another performer in the eye only when a scene was being
stolen; he is tickled and stunned by Bronson Pinchot's effrontery
in purloining their scene together in ``Beverly Hills Cop.''
</P>
<P>
   Parts of ``Nutty Professor II'' show that Murphy is ready for a
comedy with feeling. And the audiences that grew up with him _ and
with Lawrence and the Wayanses _ could move along into that next
phase without a hint of fuss. After all, this is the same audience
that rented the ghetto stoner comedy ``Friday'' in droves and made
a movie star of Chris Tucker; they followed him from Blockbuster
and into movie theaters.
</P>
<P>
   It is obvious that these performers can attract the most
desirable mainstream audiences with less demanding fare. These kids
have matured with them, as well as the baby African-American comics
Kenan and Kel on Nickelodeon. Film grosses indicate that this crowd
feels that hip-hop culture belongs to them; it's in the air, part
of the way they express themselves. That interest transcends race
and can be translated into something bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the time is ripe for an alliance something along the lines
of First Artists, the production company that the '60s stars Paul
Newman, Barbra Streisand, Steve McQueen and Sidney Poitier created
so they could make the movies they wanted. They were so powerful
that no one could say no to them. (Sadly, First Artists fell into
chaos, with bruised egos leading to the collapse of the company.)
</P>
<P>
   The most remarkable aspect of the black film renaissance is that
the major television networks have totally missed the point. It was
television that nurtured the audience that grew up with this welt
of actors, writers and directors and trailed happily after them
into the movies. It's unbelievable that while these pictures have
made a mark at the box office, there are no television series
capitalizing on that interest.
</P>
<P>
   After all the noise last summer, when the NAACP announced a
campaign to press for more diversity on television, and the
networks vowed to make changes, the prime-time schedules still look
as white as a box of long-grain rice. The networks deserve to have
viewers fleeing their bland fare in droves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
