u f BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT     08-13 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ford Releases Data on Tires That Firestone Recalled
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor released documents showing that Bridgestone/Firestone
had received for years an unusually large number of warranty claims
on the tires that were recalled last week.
</P>
<P>
   Warranty data showed that the tires being recalled were the
subject of 15 to 65 times as many warranty claims as other
Firestone tires. The highest numbers of claims by a wide margin
were for tires produced at Bridgestone's factory in Decatur, Ill.,
in 1994 and 1995, when the factory was operated by replacement
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Venture to Offer Video-on-Demand
</P>
<P>
   Intertainer and Akamai Technologies plan to announce a
partnership Monday to deliver video-on-demand to the computers of
consumers with high-speed Internet connections. The service, which
is now available in Cincinnati and Denver, will be broadly
available by the end of the year, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Jobs Finds Fault With New Book
</P>
<P>
   ``The Second Coming of Steve Jobs,'' a book by Alan Deutschman,
portrays Steve Jobs, the co-founder and chief executive of Apple
Compute, as an abusive, insecure narcissist who, through a ``reign
of terror,'' turned around the company and reclaimed his authority.
Last week, Jobs called the chief executive of Random House, the
publisher's parent, to complain about the book, referring to it as
a ``hatchet job.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC Joins the Reality Show Fray
</P>
<P>
   After a long delay, NBC will announce this week that it has
acquired the rights to ``Chains of Love,'' a reality show that will
chain four men to one woman for a week. NBC has also acquired the
rights to a hidden-camera show called ``Sweet Revenge,'' in which a
contestant will be offered a chance to get back at a friend or
family member by setting him or her up for embarrassment on a
hidden camera.
</P>
<P>
   A Space Detour for Web Traffic
</P>
<P>
   Delivering simultaneous streams of music to thousands or even
millions of listeners over an ever more clogged Internet has become
increasingly frustrating. If the audio stream hits too many traffic
jams, listeners may find radio programs stuttering or stopping in
the middle of a song. One promising remedy involves sending the
stream up to a satellite and landing it at a network hub closer to
listeners.
</P>
<P>
   Networks' Convention Role Shrinks
</P>
<P>
   The three main broadcast networks are likely to continue to play
a role at political conventions, and the parties are likely to
continue to covet every moment on these high-visibility networks.
But the scaling back in prime time that occurred this year is
expected to only intensify the next time.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Heads to Web Without Wires
</P>
<P>
   While Internet access through high-speed lines is booming in the
United States, the business in Japan is barely sputtering. The
Japanese are heading onto the Internet in droves _ but by wireless
means. There are at 20 million to 27 million Internet users in
Japan, or one of every five people in the nation. Of that number,
nearly half are connecting to the Internet wirelessly.
</P>
<P>
   Web Entrepreneurs Stepping Aside
</P>
<P>
   Anecdotal evidence suggests that a changing of the guard is
under way in the Internet industry, as the early proponents of the
Web are stepping aside for the mainstream business people who have
migrated to the new medium. Analysts say the executive shift could
have broad implications for e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Founder to Sell Auto Stake
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai Group, South Korea's largest business group, said that
its founder would sell a 6.1 percent stake in Hyundai Motor by the
end of the year, ending months of defiance of government demands
for reorganization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
