<SLUG> BC-FLA-BEACH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW ECONOMY ECLIPSES A SLIVER OF OLD FLORIDA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Ill., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DESTIN, Fla. _ The sand dunes of Okaloosa Island, like
snowbanks, line both sides of U.S. Highway 98 between Fort Walton
and Destin, and they are so pretty that people weave off the road,
looking at them. The golden sea oats waft in the summer breeze, and
gnarled pines, blasted by hurricanes that hit or barely missed,
lean from sand so purely white that the sun flashes off it like a
mirror and hurts the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   To the south, just beyond the dunes, is the Gulf of Mexico, an
emerald green when the sun is out and a deep, deep blue on the
cloudy days. And across the spit of the sand, to the north, is a
wide bay, its water darker, a place where wading birds prowl the
shallows, spearing fish and crabs.
</P>
<P>
   But at 55 miles an hour, this three-mile stretch of protected,
mostly undeveloped federal land flashes past in an instant. In the
amount of time it takes a tourist to tune his car radio, the little
oasis is gone.
</P>
<P>
   And looking around at what has become of the rest of this part
of the Florida Panhandle on each side of that stretch of sand, part
of Eglin Air Force Base, it is enough to make some visitors wonder
if what they saw was even real.
</P>
<P>
   Concrete condominiums, as imposing as anything in Miami or Fort
Lauderdale, line the beachfront on both ends of this paradise,
blocking views of the Gulf. Tower cranes in the distance promise
more.
</P>
<P>
   Thick traffic on 98 moves like syrup on a cold day, and turning
left against the gridlock, to one of the gigantic new seafood
emporiums that look almost like amusement parks with their expanse
of neon, can be a hair-raising adventure. The real estate people
have a term for this kind of growth: ``Turning sand into money.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Walton, to the west, is ``built out,'' the locals like to
say, but to the east, at Destin and beyond, the building boom is
still raging. Destin, which had long been regarded as one of the
last little jewels of coastal old Florida, has been transformed
into a coastal city of condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been discovered,'' said Commissioner Nick Nicholson of
Okaloosa County.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't happen overnight; it just seems like it to people who
come only every few years. The Panhandle has been a prize for
developers for decades. Destin, once known as the ``World's
Luckiest Fishing Village,'' has been growing and changing for
years.
</P>
<P>
   Now the village is gone, at least the village that older people
here remember.
</P>
<P>
   The fishing is no longer so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of heartbreaking to see it turn into a concrete
jungle,'' said Dewey Destin, 47, great-great-grandson of the town's
founder, Leonard Destin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bittersweet feeling,'' said Destin, a part-owner of
Destin Seafood Market and a city councilman since 1985. ``There are
more jobs, and the properties are worth more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it has destroyed our community. It has destroyed the local
natural fishery. We now have much dirtier water. But this is what
you get when you exchange nature for economic well-being.''
</P>
<P>
   People used to saunter across 98 in their bathing suits. Now,
they wait for a break in the traffic, and run like a mean dog was
after them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had a choice, I would have restricted the development to
have low density,'' said Destin, who points out that most zoning
during the early boom years was handled by the county, not the
city. ``I would have done it much differently.''
</P>
<P>
   The population statistics show growth, but do not show the true
changes in Destin and the surrounding coast.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, the population of Okaloosa County was 88,188, according
to state statistics. By 1990, it had climbed to 143,776, and by
1999 it had climbed to almost 180,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the tourists and the part-time residents have truly altered
the landscape, real estate figures show.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, there were 194 sales of new condos in southern Okaloosa
County, which includes Destin, and in rapidly developing southern
Walton County, to the east.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, there were 937 sales of new condos, many of which will
be vacant for part or even much of the year, or leased to tourists.
</P>
<P>
   The boom shows no sign of stopping. Sales of condos and town
homes here almost doubled in just the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate developers say Destin and much of the rest of the
Florida Panhandle have become playgrounds of the new, fat economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the boom, baby boomers and e-commuters are
purchasing places as second homes or working from their homes
here,'' said Dave W. Hubbard, a broker here. ``The younger
generations are getting their money early on and coming to play on
the water. Condos are starting at $300,000 and going to $1.4
million. That's about average for a Gulf view.''
</P>
<P>
   Some residents say it had to happen sooner or later, and make no
excuses for the transformation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that we weren't going to be able to keep this beauty
secret for a long time,'' said Michael Beaubien, who owns Born to
Boogie Charter Boat Fishing. ``How could we put a fence around us
and say, `No, get out'?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Developers are not going to sit there and say, `We'll take
care of this land and leave it as a habitat for the redheaded
woodpecker,' '' Beaubien continued. ``It's just not realistic to
think that.''
</P>
<P>
   But people who loved it for what it was hate what it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Storm water runoff has affected the bay, and all the
fertilizers they put on the golf courses are killing it,'' said
Jacquelyn L. Tatjes, a secretary at Sexton's Seafood, a place where
locals and tourists have gone for years to get fresh shrimp and
crabs to boil.
</P>
<P>
   Tatjes has lived here 25 years, after fleeing the building booms
in California. Here it is, she said, all over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way a local can even go to the beach,'' she said.
``They say there's public access, but there's no parking. You can't
even see the beach anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   And the new people have no connection to the place, beyond their
time-share agreement or deed, longtime locals say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're rude. Instead of accepting our heritage of a small
town, they just want to change it,'' Tatjes said. ``They want it to
be just like where they came from. It's lost all its charm.''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the value of her property peaks, she said, she is
moving.
</P>
<P>
   Others have already left.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Bergwall is now a senior vice president at a bank in
Neosho, Mo., a small city outside Joplin. Bergwall and his family
left Destin this year, for good, after living here 10 years. ``What
I went there for disappeared,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a place to get away,'' he said, ``it isn't, anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Like some exotic animal in a cage, the undeveloped stretch of
land between Destin and Fort Walton is fenced off on the Gulf side.
But people regularly cross the fence, climb the dunes and look at
the water, and run or roll back down them.
</P>
<P>
   They commit a small disobedience, just to see what, once, this
was all like.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 1755EDT &QL; 
