<HEADER>
A0376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-MURDOCH-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      08-13 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDOCH-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDOCH DEAL COULD REVAMP NEW YORK TV 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER and GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Media analysts and network executives said over the
weekend that the sale of TV stations owned by Chris-Craft
Industries to the owner of the Fox network, News Corp., was likely
to create a host of opportunities for News Corp. _ and raise almost
as many questions.
</P>
<P>
   The questions will affect News Corp. and Viacom, which until
Friday had also been bidding to acquire the stations.
</P>
<P>
   The sale, expected to be announced this week, is valued at $85 a
share, or about $3.5 billion. It will add 10 stations owned by
Chris-Craft to News Corp. and present News Corp.'s leader, Rupert
Murdoch, with a competitive edge _ ownership of two powerful TV
stations in a number of major cities, including New York and Los
Angeles. It will also give him extended control over dissemination
of local news in New York, where he would own both Channel 5 and
Channel 9 as well as The New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, however, raises questions about how News Corp. will
deal with current Federal Communications Commission restrictions.
These include a limit on how much reach one broadcasting company
can attain and a ban on cross-ownership of newspapers and TV
stations in the same city, for which Murdoch won a waiver when only
Channel 5 was involved.
</P>
<P>
   The deal especially throws into question what may happen to UPN,
which is now owned by Viacom but will become the Paramount Network
in January.
</P>
<P>
   No network has ever succeeded without owning stations in the two
largest media markets of New York and Los Angeles. Viacom, which
also owns CBS, finds itself in the position of running a network
whose two biggest stations will be owned by a company that also
owns a rival network. And the affiliation agreement between the
Chris-Craft stations and the Paramount network expires in January.
</P>
<P>
   Some network executives are already predicting that the Viacom
president, Mel Karmazin, will simply decide that the UPN Network,
now losing between $100 million and $150 million a year, is a
property not worth keeping. Faced with some CBS cable TV assets
that had little prospect of turning a profit in the next five
years, the Eye on People channel and Tele-Noticias, Karmazin chose
to shut down both of them.
</P>
<P>
   But the UPN Network had shown recent signs of growth, having
found a hit in a weekly wrestling franchise. One media analyst said
that Karmazin, in recent private conversations, said ``UPN will be
profitable in a year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very much of a mind to keep it,'' the analyst added.
</P>
<P>
   Whether that will still be true with News Corp. owning the most
important stations broadcasting the network is far from certain.
But the analyst, who spoke on condition of anonymity, cautioned
against any facile predictions that Karmazin will quickly pull out
of UPN.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many advantages to owning two networks,'' the
analyst said. ``You could put a CBS News nightly newscast at 10
p.m. on the alternate network and amortize so much more of the
costs of an expensive news division. You can cross-promote to your
second network when your main network may have a show that has a
totally different appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   It is similar opportunities on the local level presented by dual
ownership of stations in the same city that is at the center of
News Corp.'s plans for the Chris-Craft stations. Michael J. Wolf,
who heads the media department at Booz Allen &AMP; Hamilton, said:
``There are cross-promotions that can take place, similar to the
way that companies are able to drive viewers from one cable network
to another. The same thing can work in local television markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Two stations in the same city can also achieve great economies
of scale, Wolf said, by combining news operations and advertising
sales staffs. ``This would let News Corp. get a bigger piece of an
advertiser's budget,'' Wolf said. And it could open up
possibilities in sports, he added, by allowing News Corp. to place
a team's games on two channels. For example, Channel 5 carries
Yankees games. But because that is the flagship station of the Fox
network there are many nights when Fox cannot pre-empt
entertainment programming for a game. Now it might be possible to
move some games over to Channel 9.
</P>
<P>
   Dual-ownership is certain to be most noticed in New York because
of Murdoch's ownership of The Post. Presumably he will have to gain
an additional waiver from the FCC to add Channel 9 if he intends to
retain The Post because of the continuing restriction on
cross-ownership of newspapers and stations.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox will be much more aggressive in seeking to overturn
another FCC restriction, the one that limits a broadcasting company
to owning stations that reach no more than 35 percent of the
nation's homes. Fox was already at that cap before this
acquisition. With the Chris-Craft stations, the network will be far
above the cap. Fox has already filed suit in federal court to
challenge the regulation and analysts and executives said this
weekend that Fox would surely step up its lobbying efforts in
Congress to have the limits either raised or eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the restrictions stay in place, Fox is not likely to
simply sell off stations to get down to the limit. ``You may see a
lot of station swapping take place,'' a Fox executive said. Another
network executive compared what might take place to ``a game of go
fish, where you take one card and I take another.'' The point of
the game: Match up stations and cities to create dual ownership.
</P>
<P>
   But all this presumes that owning stations will continue to be
good business, a point broadcast executives disagree on. One senior
executive with experience at two networks said that many
family-owned companies with long histories running TV stations had
recently decided to quit the business, sensing that the future was
too unpredictable. ``It's not like by adding Channel 9, you now
have two of seven stations in New York. With all the cable channels
out there, it means you have two of 100.''
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, one News Corp. acquisition, the Family Channel,
which Murdoch bought for $1.9 billion in 1997, has struggled to
find an identity and to make money.
</P>
<P>
   Still, David Londoner, a media analyst with ABN Amro, said there
was a prospect that coming digital technology would expand the
reach of local stations by multiplying their signals from one
channel to as many as four. ``More channels in big cities? You
should be able to do something with that,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
