<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0378 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-REPLACEMENTS-AZR &LR;      08-13 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPLACEMENTS-AZR </SLUG>
  
 BC-REPLACEMENTS-REVIEW-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    `REPLACEMENTS' LACKS NEW PLAY BOOK(a) 
 &HT;    (RESENDING FOR THOSE WHO MAVE HAVE MISSED THIS --)(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL MULLER(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I really liked (beginitalic)The Replacements (enditalic)the
first time I saw it - when it was called (beginitalic)The Longest
Yard(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it was (beginitalic)Major League(enditalic). Or
(beginitalic)Necessary Roughness(enditalic). Or any of a dozen
sports movies that feature a ragtag band of misfits who succeed
against all odds.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, (beginitalic)The Replacements (enditalic)lives
up to its name. It's essentially a collection of spare parts from
other movies, a cheesy knockoff without a whit of creativity.
</P>
<P>
   The film stars Keanu Reeves as a quarterback who blew the big
college game but gets called back to action after NFL players go on
strike. The movie wastes no time in trotting out every sports movie
stereotype and overused scene.
</P>
<P>
   The replacement team (the fictional Washington Sentinels),
includes the usual gang of underdogs we see in every movie: the
psycho linebacker, the overweight sumo wrestler, the wisecracking
receiver with bad hands, the oddball kicker, the gun-toting
gangster and the Bible-thumping preacher.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget the platitude-spewing coach, played by Gene
Hackman. He becomes a parody of himself about halfway through,
mostly because he's stuck reading dialogue left over from
(beginitalic)Hoosiers(enditalic).
</P>
<P>
   You have to wonder why Warner Bros. made this turkey at all,
especially since the last NFL strike was in 1987. You get the idea
the script was moldering on a shelf somewhere, right next to the
(beginitalic)Rocky VI (enditalic)screenplay. Whoops, I guess that's
a bad example.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, its anti-union message finds really great timing,
given the current actors' strike in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the story, which is simply a collection of scenes
from other sports movies. There's the initial goofy practice
sequence, the argument in the cafeteria, the contemplative moment
in the empty stadium, the bar brawl, the jail cell dance number and
big locker room speech.
</P>
<P>
   There are some laughs here and there, but they mostly dry up in
the second half, when the movie just pounds out the formula.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)The Replacements (enditalic)also features John
Madden and Pat Summerall, real-life football announcers who read
their lines with all the enthusiasm of Soviet newscasters. Madden's
performance is especially stilted, sounding much like the
mix-and-match one-liners he records for his ubiquitous football
video games.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, the movie doesn't even get its football right.
Since when does the season end on Thanksgiving? Since when do the
cheerleaders go on strike with the players? Since when do teams
carry only one quarterback?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's only a movie, but it's certainly likely to attract
football fans, who will spot the obvious flaws, such as skinny
Reeves shucking off 250-pound linebackers on his way to the end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   At the screening I attended, the film broke with about 20
minutes left in the movie. That gave the audience time to guess at
the ending.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, we all guessed right.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Muller at bill.muller(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8651.
</P>
</TEXT>
