</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PILLOW-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE REVIEW: TROUBLING IMAGES OF MAN AND APE, FROM SENEGAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BECKET, Mass. _ ``Le Coq Est Mort'' (``The Rooster Is Dead'') is
on the face of it a fairly simple piece. The 70-minute work,
performed by Company Jant-Bi on Saturday in the Ted Shawn Theater
at the Jacob's Pillow Dance Festival here, begins with a brisk
processional of men dressed in business suits and carrying attache
cases. They begin to bond, to fight and to drink together,
eventually shedding all but their trousers to regress to that
essence of primitivism or the natural world, the lolloping ape.
</P>
<P>
   The voyage of self-discovery from frantic, soulless Wall
Streeter to Noble Savage is a familiar enough theme in dance. But
there is one big difference here. The eight men are black Africans,
and the piece was created by Susanne Linke, a leading German
Expressionist choreographer who happens to be white.
</P>
<P>
   ``Le Coq Est Mort,'' set to a seamless weave of Shostakovich and
music by Etienne Schwarcz and Abdou Mama Diouf, grew out of the
participation of Linke and the dancers in collaborative workshops
in 1998. It has been criticized as cultural colonialism and racist
by European intellectuals, both black and white. Germaine Acogny,
the company's charismatic director, was herself troubled initially
by the ape scene. But it did not bother the dancers and the
townspeople of Toubab Dialaw, Senegal, where Jant-Bi is based and
where the premiere took place last year.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the piece would be quite a different matter if it were
performed by white or Asian dancers, given the inbred bigotry that
is so much a part of everyday life today in the United States and
Europe. And the impact and impressive accomplishment of this
disturbing yet strangely exhilarating piece is attributable in
large part to its casting.
</P>
<P>
   Linke and the powerful dancers, each with a face and stage
presence of his own in this putatively faceless chorus, take the
audience through an arduous journey. It begins with movement whose
plainness and repetition grow tedious and continues with
insidiously building signs of disarray, symbolized by the churning
and scuffing of the sand that covers the stage floor.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the tension of witnessing racist-seeming imagery
placed front and center, unashamedly and without defiance. Further
shocks to the system come with the sudden devastation of the
dance's last moments. Blasts of gunfire are heard. All but one of
the apes drop into the sand, mourned by a single cheeping,
increasingly frantic creature.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly and miraculously, however, his arms straighten like wings
and the sound of animal chirps, crowing, barking and growls begins
to rise from the bodies, muffled at first but growing stronger. The
sounds turn to faint singing, which also grows louder as one by one
the men rise and come forward. Their song, an anthem associated
with Senegalese wrestling matches, ends ``Le Coq Est Mort.''
</P>
<P>
   There are considerable intellectual pleasures to the piece. One
becomes fascinated by the gradual layering and melding of everyday
and modern-dance movement with African dance forms and motifs that
are revitalizing American modern dance today. As fascinating is the
transition from stiff, upright contained movement to tilting,
intricately articulated torsos and resilient bent-kneed travel. The
stage picture is extraordinarily handsome, particularly in the ways
Horst Muehlberger's quietly innovative lighting enhances small
differences of color, texture and light and shadow.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few puzzling or loose philosophical ends. One jokey
moment having to do with a first experiencing of Champagne does
seem condescending. But this is a dance that provokes thought long
after the curtain falls.
</P>
<P>
   Linke addresses man's growing alienation from his own
physicality, an effect of his striving for power. Developing the
piece, the dancers said that they found the ape movement
technically challenging and inherently beautiful rather than
demeaning.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers must be willing to loosen their grip on the constructs
of racism and the parameters of Western physicality to embrace this
journey into an unnerving unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The performers make this possible, especially the genially
implacable Abubakar Usman and the febrile, almost painfully
innocent Chrysogone Diangouaya. The fine cast was completed by Cire
Beye, Djibril Diallo, Amadou Gueye, Moustapha Gueye, Papa Sy and
Jean Tamba. Avi Kaiser was co-choreographer. Oumou Sy designed the
costumes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
