<SLUG> BC-LATIN-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
 
POP REVIEW: LATIN AMERICAN BANDS ROOTED IN THE '70s AND '80s  
 By JON PARELES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Latin Americans invent their own kind of rock,
they eagerly recycle music from afar, happy to mix and mismatch.
Sometimes they turn pop discards into trophies. Three South
American bands _ La Ley from Chile, Los Amigos Invisibles from
Venezuela and Illya Kuryaki and the Valderramas, from Argentina _
performed at Central Park Summerstage on Saturday afternoon,
latching on to 1970s and 80s styles with respect and mockery. The
concert was the lead-in to the first Latin Alternative Music
Conference, a music-business convention in New York City running
through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   La Ley, which topped the bill and ended up playing through a
downpour, was a Spanish-speaking echo of the 80s, particularly of
British and Irish bands that took themselves extremely seriously.
La Ley's songs addressed grand subjects: faith, love, destiny, the
meaning of life. In ``Eternidad,'' which opened La Ley's set, Beto
Cuevas sang, ``I'm nearing the end of an existential highway.''
</P>
<P>
   The music approached its high-minded messages with sounds that
ruled MTV in the mid- &UR; ' &LR; 80s. In rock marches that had the triumphal
tone of Simple Minds' songs, Pedro Frugone used plenty of U2's
echoing guitar effects, while Cuevas emoted with the melodrama of
Dave Gahan of Depeche Mode.
</P>
<P>
   Brief touches of surf guitar and funk hinted that La Ley, which
has been performing since the early  &UR; ' &LR; 90s, was once less pompous.
But for the most part the band presented the least encouraging side
of rock en espanol: a direct Spanish translation of an imported
style.
</P>
<P>
   Los Amigos Invisibles had a simpler imperative: to get people
dancing. Their core sound is the smooth mid- &UR; ' &LR; 70s funk that
returned in the  &UR; ' &LR; 90s as so-called acid jazz, and their songs are
built around the scrubbing, syncopated rhythm-guitar chords of Jose
Luis Pardo, Los Amigos' main songwriter. But Los Amigos also toyed
with other styles: merengue, boogaloo, hip-hop, even a techno
bassline spattered with conga drumming. Julio Briceno sang more or
less sardonic come-ons, making romantic promises while sometimes
grabbing his crotch. Listeners could enjoy the ironies, or ignore
them and keep on dancing; Los Amigos have done their funk homework.
</P>
<P>
   Illya Kuryaki and the Valderramas also love  &UR; ' &LR; 70s funk. Their
current album, ``Leche'' (Universal), has a guest appearance by
Bootsy Collins of Parliament-Funkadelic, and onstage the band also
performed a song modeled on P-Funk's 70s rivals, Earth Wind and
Fire.
</P>
<P>
   But funk is only one of the styles tossed into the band's songs.
Illya Kuryaki's music is a wild patchwork, ricocheting from hip-hop
to rock to funk to salsa to a Spanish-language revamp of Queen's
``Another One Bites the Dust,'' easily jumping from suavity to
noise. And the lyrics, rapped and sung by Emmanuel Horvilleur and
Dante Spinetta Zalazar, add a layer of surreal poetry, full of
rebelliousness, death and raunchy transfiguration; in ``Jennifer
del Estero,'' Jennifer Lopez leaves her derriere in the singer's
freezer. Illya Kuryaki is a promising sign that rock en espanol
plans to respect no boundaries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
