<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BEATING RUIZ, HOLYFIELD RAISES MORE QUESTIONS THAN ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL ARKUSH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The right hand late in the third round stunned his
opponent, who began to wobble. A visit to the canvas seemed
imminent. But at this pivotal moment in Saturday night's World
Boxing Association heavyweight championship bout against the
unheralded John Ruiz, 37-year-old Evander Holyfield could not do
what he almost surely would have done during his best years. He
could not put his opponent away.
</P>
<P>
   He could not do it the rest of the 12-round fight, either. In
fact, he almost lost it, escaping with a narrow decision before
about 8,500 fans at The Paris Las Vegas Casino Resort. Two judges
scored it 114-113, and the other judge had it 116-112. Only by
capturing the final round did Holyfield avoid defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But now that this close call is over, Holyfield may have an even
tougher time avoiding the doubts. Doubts about whether he can
regain the form that made him one of boxing's most admired
warriors.
</P>
<P>
   He was not, after all, not facing Lennox Lewis or Riddick Bowe
or Mike Tyson, fighters of supreme skill or power. He was facing
Ruiz, a 4-1 underdog, who had not beaten anyone of distinction and
who once lost to David Tua in 19 seconds. Yet, except for the
third-round flourish and a few good shots later in the fight,
Holyfield never had Ruiz in any real trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, who weighed in at 221 pounds, does not believe in
doubts. He never has. He has been counted out before, yet always
found a way to bounce back with victories against the best in his
sport. So in his postfight comments, he sounded as proud and
confident as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I attempted to reach a goal, people told me I
wouldn't make it,'' said Holyfield, who, by beating Ruiz, became
the first fighter to win the heavyweight crown four times, although
many say this one is tainted because Lewis, the former champion,
lost his WBA belt in the courts, not in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I fought Buster Douglas, everyone said I won because he
was out of shape,'' Holyfield added. ``He might have been out of
shape, but that's not my problem. I did beat him. After fighting
Bowe, I came back and won. My goal was to win again and I did.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his inability to put the 224-pound Ruiz away, Holyfield
had an answer for that, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He leads with his head,'' said Holyfield, who earned $5
million and improved his record to 37-4-1. ``I hit him with hard
punches. He is an awkward fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Awkward or not, Ruiz, who was attempting to make his own history
_ the first Latino to capture the heavyweight championship _ had a
different analysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fought my heart out and I feel like I won the fight,'' said
Ruiz, 28, of Chelsea, Mass. He lost for the first time in 12 bouts
since the Tua fight, dropping his record to 36-4. ``This was a big
setback. This is something I've been dreaming about. But that's
life. I will keep fighting on.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the fight, Holyfield said he would offer Ruiz
a rematch but hoped to ultimately face Lewis in a bid to reunify
the title. Lewis had been the undisputed champion until he was
stripped of his WBA belt by a federal judge who ruled that he had
violated a contract by refusing to fight Ruiz, then ranked as the
association's top contender. Lewis, who still owns the World Boxing
Council and International Boxing Federation titles, instead fought
Michael Grant, knocking him out in the second round on April 29 in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going anywhere. I am the WBA champion,'' said
Holyfield, who lost a unanimous decision to Lewis in their second,
and most recent, fight last November. Their first match, in March
1999, ended in a controversial draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has two belts and I have one,'' Holyfield said. ``I am very
happy to be the first four-time world heavyweight champion, but
this is just the first step.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a first step that almost went backward.
</P>
</TEXT>
