<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-CONCUBINES-ART-     08-13 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CONCUBINES-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONCUBINE VILLAGES GET ATTENTION OF CHINESE AUTHORITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Mrs. Lam is cq thruout because she would not give her first
name or her husband's.)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DONGGUAN, China _ A banner identifies the bustling warren of
streets in this southern Chinese city as the New Garden Village
Meat and Vegetable Market. And, indeed, one can find meat and
produce in many varieties _ fresh or cured, hanging from hooks or
still squawking in cages.
</P>
<P>
   At first, it looks like just another Chinese town, but not on
closer inspection.
</P>
<P>
   New Garden Village is one of China's most notorious ``concubine
villages.'' Hundreds of mainland Chinese women here live in a dozen
rows of drab, concrete high-rises, kept there as mistresses or
common-law wives of Hong Kong men. On a recent evening they prowled
the market _ incongruously clad in skin-tight black pants and
clingy tops _ buying groceries for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, a real estate agent hawked cheap apartments on the order
of glorified motel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can rent by the month,'' she said, winking at a passer-by
and the woman with him.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the ties that bind Hong Kong and the Chinese mainland,
there may be few more pervasive than sex. The link is not largely
fueled by quick thrills and anonymous encounters, though both are
readily available. Rather, it is based on a remarkably durable web
of relationships that have flowered between relatively poor Chinese
women and more affluent Hong Kong men, whose jobs require them to
spend days or weeks at a time in the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Even before Hong Kong reverted to Chinese rule in 1997, the
border between the two had become increasingly porous. Hong Kong
companies set up scores of factories in cities like Dongguan,
dispatching managers to oversee the assembly lines and truck
drivers to haul goods to and fro.
</P>
<P>
   Whether to soothe their loneliness, stroke their egos or indulge
their fantasies, many of these commuters support mistresses or de
facto second wives. Concubine villages have sprouted up across
Guangdong province.
</P>
<P>
   To some of these Lotharios, having a mistress is a totem of
success _ proof that they can afford to maintain two households.
Granted, the cost of housing in Guangdong is a fraction of that in
Hong Kong. Two-bedroom apartments in New Garden Village rent for as
little as $195 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the affordability of the practice, anthropologists say it
is deeply rooted in Chinese culture: The emperors had their
concubines, Mao was famous for his serial conquests and traders
kept spouses in every port. In Hong Kong, even when it was a
rule-bound British colony, concubines were legal until 1971.
</P>
<P>
   But now the Chinese government is starting to view wholesale
adultery as a social menace, and it is cracking down.
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Guangdong authorities sentenced a Hong Kong man to
10 months in jail for living in ``factual bigamy.'' The man, Choi
Kai-pang, had a wife in Hong Kong but lived with a mainland woman
in the border city of Shenzhen. The couple even had a phony Chinese
marriage certificate.
</P>
<P>
   Men who do not pretend to be married to their mistresses are
only slightly less at risk. Guangdong recently changed its laws to
make long-term cohabitation by unmarried couples a crime. Although
a single act of adultery is not illegal, a man who lives with a
woman to whom he is not married can be sent to a labor camp for two
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government is taking measures to prohibit this behavior
because the affairs have caused family problems and violence,''
said Paulina C.Y. Kwok, a social worker with the charity Caritas
Hong Kong, who counsels the wives of wayward men. ``They say it
goes against Chinese values.''
</P>
<P>
   Women's groups in China contend that the proliferation of
extramarital sex corrodes the Chinese family. Though the problem is
most acute in freewheeling southern China, mass migration and
economic dislocation have made infidelity a problem across the
country. The children who result from these liaisons also make
Beijing's family-planning policies less effective, prompting some
legal experts to call for marriage laws that mandate cohabitation
with one's spouse.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The changes will not come soon enough for Mrs. Lam, a Hong Kong
woman who says her 26-year marriage has been devastated by her
husband's philandering on the mainland. She declined to give her
full name to avoid embarrassment. Four years ago, the couple moved
to a village in Guangdong to start a fish-breeding farm. Her
husband visited karaoke bars, where he met young women from rural
China who worked as prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   When Mrs. Lam returned to Hong Kong for a lengthy medical
procedure in 1997, her husband secretly took a mistress, she said.
He rented a cozy apartment for the woman in a neighboring town and
lent her his wife's clothes. In addition to rent, her husband paid
the woman several thousand dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``These mainland women have beautiful skin and pretty faces,''
Mrs. Lam said, her face creased with sorrow and bitterness. ``They
know how to please another woman's husband. They do it for economic
stability.''
</P>
<P>
   To save her marriage, Mrs. Lam, 48, demanded that her husband
move back to Hong Kong. But recently she discovered that he had
taken up with yet another woman. She contends that the morals of
Guangdong have corrupted her husband, making him believe that
mistresses are the social norm.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in some ways, the concubine village here seems less a
red-light district than a starter community. Women wheel babies,
stopping to browse for kitchen utensils. Children scamper around a
leafy park.
</P>
<P>
   But there are reminders that New Garden Village is no Mayberry.
Next to the kitchen shop is a beauty salon, where little hair was
being cut. Instead, three heavily made-up young women loitered on a
divan, waiting for customers.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   One Hong Kong factory manager who has commuted to China since
1993 predicts the new laws will not curb the problem. For one
thing, the police will arrest a man on charges of bigamy or illegal
cohabitation only if a complaint is lodged against him here. Hong
Kong and China are separate legal jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   A Hong Kong woman who wants to haul her husband into a Chinese
court must also make sure that the state can prove he is living
with a mistress _ not easy to do in the rent-by-the-month world of
concubine villages.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many in Hong Kong are sure to welcome the crackdown. The
territory has watched nervously as its men have sired a generation
of illegitimate children _ 520,000 by one estimate _ with one foot
in the mainland and one in Hong Kong. Last year, a local court
briefly granted those children residency in Hong Kong; the ruling
was overturned by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If men are in danger of going to prison, they may control
their impulses,'' said Kwok, the social worker.
</P>
<P>
   But she added that laws alone would not solve the problem.
China, she said, must improve the status of women, particularly the
young, penniless ones who pour in from the hinterland. ``If these
women can get real jobs, if their status in society improves, they
won't get into this business to begin with,'' Kwok said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
