<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0390 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-DEMS-HILLARY-BOS &LR;      08-13 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-HILLARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LEGACY ALSO A HOPE FOR HILLARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Legacy.
</P>
<P>
   That's the big theme of this opening night of the Democratic
National Convention _ not just a fond look back at Bill Clinton's
eight years as president, but also a longing look ahead at Hillary
Rodham Clinton's possible six years or more as senator.
</P>
<P>
   At the festivities' outset, Hillary is being presented as no
less a star than Bill, Al, or Joe. She headed a star-studded,
soft-money-raising concert on Saturday, another fund-raiser at Sony
Studios Sunday night, and Monday night _ the capper _ she will
speak from the podium for 15 minutes in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's supporters hope that all these events will boost
her own political prospects _ and perpetuate the Clinton name as a
force in American politics.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly she could use a boost.
</P>
<P>
   After more than a year of constant campaigning, Mrs. Clinton,
one of the most famous women in the world, is barely holding her
own against her opponent, Representative Rick Lazio, who was
unknown outside Long Island a few months ago and who, even now,
casts only the vaguest impression.
</P>
<P>
   Of two statewide polls released last week, one puts her ahead by
two points and the other puts him ahead by seven. Both results fall
within the statistical margins of error.
</P>
<P>
   The poll in which she trails, issued by John Zogby, shows her
support slipping in most demographic categories _ upstate and
suburbs, among the middle-aged and seniors, the middle-income and
poor, white people, men, even union members.
</P>
<P>
   In the survey that puts her in the lead, by the Quinnipiac
College Polling Institute, she hasn't lost ground, but she hasn't
gained any, either.
</P>
<P>
   Most political analysts agree that she is doing just about
everything she can _ campaigning nearly every day, touching base in
every one of New York's 62 counties, spending extensive time
upstate, returning to her safety zones in the big cities now and
then to keep her base fired up.
</P>
<P>
   Her speeches have become less mannered. Huge crowds greet her
everywhere, most of them enthusiastically. She has made the
obligatory late-night talk show appearances _ with David Letterman
and, just last Friday, Jay Leno _ and come off relaxed and even
funny.
</P>
<P>
   Still, her polling numbers haven't nudged. At no point has a
poll shown her support rising above the magical 50 percent _ not
even when Rudolph W. Giuliani, the formidable mayor of New York
City, dropped out of the race and the obscure Lazio took his place.
</P>
<P>
   The final Clinton vs. Giuliani poll showed the two tied, at
45-45. The first Clinton vs. Lazio poll put her ahead, 47-32. In
other words, even then, her numbers hardly rose a blip; only the
undecideds surged. Then, after a week _ enough time for people to
get an initial impression of Lazio _ the numbers went back to where
they were.
</P>
<P>
   The underlying fact seems to be this: Many people like the first
lady a lot, many can't stand her, and the electorate is pretty
evenly divided between these two groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race is Hillary vs. Hillary,'' Zogby said over the
weekend. ``Her opponent could be _ well, not X, but X with a face,
and the numbers would be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Her supporters hope that Monday night's speech will highlight
two of Mrs. Clinton's strongest points _ her stature in the
Democratic Party and her identification as an advocate of its major
social and economic causes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is clearly a big deal at this convention, while Lazio was
a little man who wasn't even officially at the Republican
convention,'' said Maurice Carroll, head of the Quinnipiac poll.
``This is a plus for her.''
</P>
<P>
   But she has to play the scene carefully. Many of the first
lady's critics suspect she is using the Senate race as a stepping
stone to regain the White House, this time in her own name. She has
laughingly denied this accusation. Still, she must know that she
needs to come off as a leader but not The Leader.
</P>
<P>
   If her recent campaign speeches are any indication, her address
Monday night will play up the differences between Democrats and
Republicans generally _ in the presidential election, in
congressional contests nationwide, and, perhaps only by
implication, her own race.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, her campaigners have known that she could
win if the election were decided on the issues _ and that she could
lose if it came down to personalities. This became particularly
true after the departure of Giuliani, who had his own knack for
rubbing people the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of New York voters, though more conservatice than
several years ago, are still Democratic, by a 5-3 margin. President
Clinton won every county here in the 1996 election. On the
high-profile issues _ education, health care, gun control, abortion
_ most state voters are closer to the Clintons and the Democrats
than to Lazio or George W. Bush and the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   This is why Lazio has tried to make the race about Mrs. Clinton
_ and why, Monday night, Mrs. Clinton will take a chunk of free TV
time to make it about the issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
