<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0393 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT     08-13 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A ROOKIE'S GOOD INTENTIONS GONE AWRY 
</HEADLINE>
  By   IRA BERKOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The passerby sees the headlights of a parked automobile and
opens the door to turn them off when he is arrested for car theft.
A guy goes to light the cigarette of a woman and as she bends
forward her hair catches fire. You volunteer to hammer a nail into
the wall for a friend and the plaster collapses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sir,'' Samuel Johnson once said, ``the road to hell is paved
with good intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Jack Golden. Poor Jack Golden. Put another brick on that
road, Jack.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you've already heard about Jack Golden _ Good Samaritan,
Team Player, Alleged Schnook.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you saw some of the headlines in Saturday's newspapers
that followed Jack Golden and the final play of the Giants football
game against Jacksonville: ``Good Start Turns Awful for Giants,''
``For Golden, Giant Gaffe,'' and ``Jints Chill Out on Golden
Goof.'' And maybe somewhere else there was: ``Golden Opportunity
Fizzles.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Golden, a 23-year-old rookie linebacker fresh out of
Oklahoma State, is trying to realize a dream and stick with the Big
Blue. He understands that he must impress the coaches, primarily
the head coach, Jim Fassel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Fassel talked all week about needing to play smart,''
Golden said, after Friday night's preseason game in Jacksonville,
``and as soon as I came to the sidelines I looked in his eyes and I
said, `I messed up.' I was trying to be smart and wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Return with us now to that fateful moment: Giants are leading,
13-9, with seven seconds left in the last quarter. While this game
doesn't count in the standing, it still would be a morale booster
for the Giants to beat a Super Bowl contender. So in what may be
the final play of the game, cornerback Fred Lewis, Golden's fellow
rookie on the Giants, intercepts a pass a foot or so in front of
the goal line. He starts to run with the ball instead of taking a
step back and dropping to one knee in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it would give the Jaguars 2 points for a safety, but so
what, the Giants would still win, 13-11. By running around _ he did
step back into the end zone, but only to run crossfield _ he was
jeopardizing a fumble, a Jags recovery, and potential touchdown
that would send our heroes to Loserville.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, in the heat of battle, in the searing split seconds
of battle, Lewis doesn't compute all this. But guess who does? You
got it: Golden. Golden ventures what any far-thinking, well-meaning
citizen in shoulder pads and face mask would. He tackles Lewis!
Lewis, not expecting friendly fire, fumbles. Guess who recovers the
ball in the end zone? No, not Golden, but Brandon Christenson, who
does not wear a white jersey, but a teal one. Giants lose, 16-13.
</P>
<P>
   ``Holy smokes!'' Fassel said after the game, among other
exclamations. And when asked to explain what occurred on that play,
he said, ``Lord only knows why. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Too facile. What he should have said was, ``Golden made an
outstanding play, a smart play. Einstein-ian even. Ball just took a
bad bounce.''
</P>
<P>
   You're supposed to know the rules, and Golden obviously did.
While the result wasn't what a Giant partisan wishes for, it is
still a pleasure to see brains exercised with brawn _ though, yes,
in this case an eager rookie upon contact demonstrated a little too
much brawn.
</P>
<P>
   From little league on up, an athlete is instructed to consider
what he would do if the ball is hit to him, or the football spirals
his way, or if he snares a squirming basketball. Yet too often we
see the reverse in players who should know better, but don't.
</P>
<P>
   Like Benny Agbayani's blunder Saturday night _ catching a fly
ball in left field in the fourth inning and, thinking there were
three outs instead of two, giving the ball to a boy in the stands.
Meanwhile, two runs scored for San Francisco, giving the Giants a
2-1 lead. The Mets finally won, 3-2. Agbayani said he had misread
the scorebaord. In the future, the Mets might want to equip him
with a cell phone to be in touch with the dugout after every pitch.
</P>
<P>
   I've also seen a Knicks' player try to save a ball going out of
bounds under his own basket and throw it to the other team for a
score. We've seen a star college player call timeout in the crucial
final seconds of a game, in which his team was out of timeouts,
thus garnering a technical foul and giving significant free throws
to the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it is true, as noted elsewhere, that the best laid
plans do go awry. Like the man in Los Angeles who boarded a plane
thinking he was going to Oakland, Calif., and wound up in Auckland,
New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   Or the saga of Jim Marshall, a defensive end for the Vikings,
who scooped up a fumble against the 49ers in 1964 and raced 66
yards to the end zone. On the sideline, Fran Tarkenton, the
Vikings' quarterback, ran nearly the whole distance yelling and
waving to Marshall. The crowd was screaming so loud Marshall
couldn't quite catch Tarkenton's words. He thought it was simply to
cheer him on. What Tarkenton was hollering was, ``Go back, you fool
you, go back!'' Jim had run the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the reverse _ unplanned good fortune: Christopher
Columbus spotting land and shouting, ``India! India! At last,
India!'' And a man named Crawford Long coming upon the idea for
surgical anesthesia after hurting himself and feeling no pain while
stoned on ether at a party. Of somewhat less historical
significance, I've seen a guy throw a bad pass that bounced off a
teammate's head and into his basket.
</P>
<P>
   Some, now, have wondered if Golden's tackle would sink the
Giants into despair. More likely, it makes the Giants a better
team, a smarter team. Is there not a man on the squad who won't be
thinking before every snap what options he has? Rather than be Jack
Golden, they'd rather not be Fred Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   A Yiddish proverb goes, ``Better to lose with a wise man than
win with a fool.'' Because, goes the belief, the next time _
everything equal _ the wise man will win.
</P>
<P>
   For the Giants, it may indeed prove to be the Golden rule. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
