<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0395 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-MCNEELY14-COX     08-13 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-MCNEELY14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TEXAS DEMOCRATS IN L.A. NOT HUGE PLAYERS
 &HT;    By DAVE McNEELY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It is not by accident that the Texas Democrats are
housed in a hotel at the Los Angeles airport, a 45-minute drive
from the convention center where the Democrats will pick Al Gore
and Joe Lieberman as their presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
   It is not so much that the other Democrats don't like Texans,
though expect the state's record under Gov. George W. Bush to take
a pounding.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that when it comes to the votes that count in the
electoral college, Texas hasn't been worth much to Democratic
presidential candidates in recent years. The last one to win the
state was Jimmy Carter in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest role the Texas Democrats seem to have had in recent
years is to supply converts to the Republican Party such as Sen.
Phil Gramm, Lt. Gov. Rick Perry and Comptroller Carole Keeton
Rylander.
</P>
<P>
   A principal reason has been that for the four presidential
elections from 1980 through 1992, a Republican Texan named George
Bush was on the ballot either for vice president or president.
Since under federal campaign finance laws, presidential campaigns
get only so much money to spend nationally on the general election
campaign, they're not eager to spend much in states they know
they'll lose.
</P>
<P>
   So, with the exception of 1988, when Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas
was the vice-presidential nominee, Texas has been pretty much
ignored by the Democratic presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
   And after Bill Clinton in 1992 became the first Democrat to win
the presidency without winning Texas, he didn't even try in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That lack of spending by the presidential campaign has
contributed to the rapid erosion of once-solid Democratic strength
down the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   And so, the Texans, who once could boast the likes of Lyndon
Johnson and Bentsen, get star treatment and be housed near the
convention site, are now many miles from the convention center and
TV anchor booths.
</P>
<P>
   That said, there are still 231 delegates and 32 alternates from
Texas. Every Texas Democrat in Congress _ all 17 of them _ are
so-called superdelegates, as are three state senators and 22 state
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   There are no Democratic statewide elected officials here, since
there no longer are any. But former state Comptroller John Sharp
will be here, as will former Land Commissioner Garry Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   Since there's no nomination battle to fight over, the Democrats
here will party _ something they're good at.
</P>
<P>
   The Texans are already angling for tickets to some of the bigger
star-studded shindigs, like the one co-sponsored by George
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   They'll also have duty that should be a little easier.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Democrats, even though their sessions will end around
the cocktail hour because they're angling for East Coast prime-time
TV from the West Coast, will also get their get their breakfast
marching orders at the more civil time of 9 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Dave McNeely writes for The Austin American-Statesman. His
e-mail address is dmcneely(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
