<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0396 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DEM-TV-MEDIA-ART-NYT &LR;      08-13 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-TV-MEDIA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORKS MAY CUT CONVENTION COVERAGE FURTHER IN 2004 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT 9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: Story is also being filed in ``p'' category.) 
 By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a muggy night in Philadelphia, Rick Kaplan sat in the CNN
control booth in an advanced state of bliss. His floor
correspondents were killing themselves to get good material. The
Texas delegates, bowing their heads in prayer during a speech by a
gay congressman, made for a nifty TV moment. And a marquee speech
by Sen. John McCain proved to be just this side of cryptic,
excellent late-evening fodder for Jeff Greenfield and the other
analysts on the skybox anchor desk.
</P>
<P>
   Facing a wall of 100 television screens, Kaplan, CNN's president
of U.S. operations and producer of the convention coverage, could
not contain his joy. ``There's so much news here!'' he exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   It was the declaration of a man totally in his element, a
representative of a news organization that was clear about its
mission at the conventions: to be everywhere, to see everything, to
throw the equivalent, in the words of another CNN executive, of ``a
political cocktail party.''
</P>
<P>
   The shindigs may be going full blast at all-news cable networks
like CNN, a unit of Time Warner; Fox News Channel, a unit of News
Corp.; and C-Span. But on the broadcast network side of television,
the parties are ever more modest affairs. In fact, turn on ABC, NBC
and CBS this week and take a look at how they cover the Democratic
convention, because you may never see the like on these networks
again.
</P>
<P>
   All three are likely to continue to play a role, and the
political parties are likely to continue to covet every moment on
these highest of high-visibility networks. But the widespread
expectation is that the scaling back in prime time that occurred
this year will only intensify the next time, perhaps limiting the
big three to broadcasting the acceptance speeches of the
presidential and vice presidential nominees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prime time is a different landscape than it was a decade
ago,'' said Al Ortiz, executive producer of the ``CBS Evening
News.'' ``I can't imagine that four years from now the networks are
going to want to spend millions of dollars to come to these places
and do the same thing. They said this four years ago, and yet it's
a big story that we did cut back on a little bit, and I think that
in four years, there will be a further reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, there has been talk in political circles of reducing
the four-day conventions by a day or two, but the networks seem
poised to make the decision themselves. ``Under the current format
it's Monday and Tuesday that are at risk clearly for both
parties,'' said Paul Friedman, executive vice president of ABC
News, referring to the first two convention nights. Noting how
meticulously the parties try to pack these evenings with stars,
like retired Gen. Colin L. Powell and McCain in Philadelphia and
President Clinton in Los Angeles, he added, ``If we have two
totally packaged events there will be less coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   If ABC, NBC and CBS once had similar styles of convention
coverage, blocking out the same sections of prime time and relying
on the same type of programming, the 2000 conventions are
demonstrating the separate paths the three networks are taking. ABC
News remains the most traditional, providing prime-time exposure on
each of the four nights and following up on ``Nightline.'' NBC has
made the most radical departure, drastically reducing its coverage
on the flagship broadcast network and making liberal use of its
brand-name stars on MSNBC, the joint venture of Microsoft and NBC,
which itself is a unit of General Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Lack, the president of NBC News, said the networks have
merely been responding to changes in the nature of the conventions
and the political process. ``The broadcasting platform serves more
as a public service, when the nominee, say, makes that acceptance
speech,'' he said. ``But we don't have much of an obligation to go
through the party's celebration. On the cable platform, you have a
different situation: The 24-hour format is geared toward covering
the news of the day. And they cover the story, no matter what.''
</P>
<P>
   The networks, too, are relying ever more heavily on their Web
operations. Lack said that MSNBC.com was recording about 2 million
users a day during the Republican convention, ``a little bit of a
bump'' over normal usage.
</P>
<P>
   The tension, though, between the commercial demands of prime
time and the networks' civic obligations was evident in
Philadelphia. At CBS, the way that convention coverage was inserted
on the first and second nights into the 10 p.m. editions of ``48
Hours'' and ``60 Minutes II'' was criticized both inside and
outside the organization. And top news personnel, from Andrew
Heyward, the president of CBS News, to Jeff Zucker, executive
producer of NBC's convention coverage, spoke publicly of their
frustrations with the plastic in which the conventions are being
wrapped.
</P>
<P>
   The grumbling, if anything, has created something of a divide in
television news. Cable networks like CNN say they would be just as
happy if the broadcast networks would scale back and just stop
complaining about the lack of news at the conventions, a practice
that Kaplan believes turns off viewers. Indeed, ratings were down
for CNN and the broadcast networks from coverage of the 1996
Republican convention in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview the morning after McCain's speech, Kaplan said:
``I mean, tell me: It's a waste of time to cover a Republican
convention, and it's not a waste of time to put on a failed rerun
of a failed show?'' He was referring to NBC's decision to show a
rerun of its low-rated drama ``First Watch,'' consigning coverage
of the first night of the Republican convention to its cable
partner MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journalists ought not to be against covering news,'' he
continued. ``They shouldn't be embarrassed about it. Instead,
they're here to tear the story down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 1837EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0110 </DOCNO>
