</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE ACTIVITY INCREASES IN CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   By CRAIG S. SMITH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANGHAI, China _ Police activity has been increasing in several
parts of China as the country undergoes a tightening of social
controls ahead of the Oct. 1 National Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
   While the summer sweep of discos and karaoke bars and the
detention of people voicing political dissent happen every year,
the crackdown appears unusually harsh this year.
</P>
<P>
   It coincides with the annual gathering of Communist Party
leaders in the northern seaside resort of Beidaihe, where growing
social discontent and the economic challenges of China's planned
entry into the World Trade Organization are expected to be high on
the agenda.
</P>
<P>
   China is climbing out of an economic slump in which its overall
economic growth rate dipped by close to 7 percent last year.
Several regions of the country went into a deep recession, leading
to scattered unrest in heavily industrialized regions. Now a severe
drought has increased disquiet among much of the country's rural
population.
</P>
<P>
   China's entry into the trade organization, expected later this
year, will increase economic pressure on the bottom rung of the
country's population as it struggles to compete with multinational
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Following other reports of a crackdown on dissent in recent
days, the police detained a reporter in central China after he
talked to an American journalist about unrest among local farmers,
a human rights group said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong-based Information Center for Human Rights and
Democracy said that a Shaanxi province television reporter, Ma
Xiaoming, was picked up by the police after he met a journalist
from an unspecified news organization to talk about farmers trying
to sue the government. Ma was later released.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers in the province have complained of exorbitant taxes and
beatings by the local authorities. And the residents of eight poor
Shaanxi villages are trying to free their lawyer, who was jailed
last year after he went to Beijing to appeal to the central
government on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing the police apparently continued to hold a poet and
editor, Bei Ling, after they seized hundreds of copies of an
independent literary journal he had edited, The Associated Press
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Bei disappeared Friday after telling friends he planned to hold
a discussion forum that afternoon to review the August issue of his
quarterly journal, Tendency, which includes a photograph of the
exiled Chinese dissident Wang Dan and a poem by a dissident
literary critic, Liu Xiaobo.
</P>
<P>
   And in Shanghai, police officers shut down several discos and
bars for minor infractions in what the police described as a
national campaign to clean up China's night life. Several
establishments crowded with foreigners and Chinese have been raided
by vanloads of uniformed police officers for no clear reason, and
some have been told not to reopen until after Oct. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 1839EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-AR     08-13 0971
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-POLITICS-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: AMONG THE FIGHTING FACTIONS, THE GIVE-AND-TAKE OF
DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ The ``Hang Suharto!'' protesters were out
in the streets, as always. But so was a small rally demanding clean
air, another involving a local land dispute and another promoting
breast-feeding.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the streets of Jakarta were mostly quiet as
Parliament met last week _ an indication, perhaps, that despite its
daunting problems and continuing disarray, there is hope in
Indonesia for a more ordered and cohesive future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over yet,'' cautioned a local journalist. But with
another week to go, this has been the first major political event
since Suharto was driven from office 2{ years ago that has not been
riven by chaos and bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost surreal,'' said a diplomat who has in the past
watched Jakarta burning and residents fleeing. ``The popular vote
is out there on the streets. The popular vote is give this
government a chance. People are speaking by not speaking.''
</P>
<P>
   Clean air and breast-feeding are the kinds of issues that have
been drowned in the past by tidal waves of political rage.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that everything here is calm. The politically
critical Parliament session has been as tumultuous and passionate
in its way as the street demonstrations of the past. The session
was to focus on updating the country's patchwork 1945 constitution,
but in fact there is little evidence that the people's business is
being addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're watching a power struggle in Parliament,'' said Dennis
Heffernan, a director of Van Zorge, Heffernan and Associates, a
political consulting firm. ``It's very primitive from an issue
standpoint, but it's being done without gunpowder or even
fisticuffs. And if that ain't a giant step toward democracy ...''
</P>
<P>
   One thing that has changed is that the opposition now has a
voice inside government, he said. ``The streets are quiet because
the politicians in the halls of power have some constituency, some
basis among average people in this country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for the first time in half a century, the Indonesian
people voted in a free election, choosing candidates for Parliament
who had not been vetted by the party in power. But they were
elected to an institution that had little experience in democratic
give-and-take.
</P>
<P>
   The battle inside Parliament now involves raw ambition as
emerging power blocs jostle for dominance in a nation that is
working out new alignments on every front after 32 years of one-man
rule by Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   The session is a sort of D-Day in a concerted multiparty attack
on President Abdurrahman Wahid, a compromise leader with few
political defenses. The parliamentary coalition of opposing parties
that chose him as president 10 months ago has mostly turned against
him, and he finds himself racing back and forth along the cliff top
batting down their attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The dirty little secret of the battle is that despite loud talk
of impeachment, few of his opponents actually want to depose him.
His most prominent challengers _ Amien Rais, who leads an Islamic
coalition, and Akbar Tandjung, who leads Suharto's former ruling
party _ realize that they could not at this time hold a government
together, political experts said.
</P>
<P>
   So Wahid, who remains personally popular, is still the most
acceptable figure among the warring parties. And although
Indonesians inside and outside Parliament have become exasperated
by his erratic and often incompetent administration, he commands
respect for his tolerant and democratic vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, the vehemence we're seeing in Parliament is
fabricated,'' said Wimar Witoelar, a leading political commentator.
``The game these people are playing is toward positioning for the
next election. They are feeling things out and sounding out the
other guy and seeing how it will play in 2004. Are they going to be
Moslems or nationalists or pragmatists? They will play any game as
long as they can come out of it in a better political position. If
you play the tapes from what they said last year and this year, it
even becomes funny.''
</P>
<P>
   In the tumult, most of the substance has been drained from the
parliamentary session. With every issue now so politicized and with
the session preoccupied by infighting, most political experts now
say any constitutional changes are likely to be postponed.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, personal ambitions aside, the session has become a
forum for working out the dynamics of an infant democracy. It is a
struggle for dominance between the executive and legislative
branches, which in the past were both under the unquestioned
control of Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have never had a system of checks and balances before,''
the diplomat said. By ganging up on Wahid, the disparate parties
have sought to assert the dominance of Parliament over the once
all-powerful presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, they jeered Wahid at a special session they called
to demand an explanation for his unpopular dismissal of two of his
cabinet ministers. He stubbornly refused to explain himself,
asserting the constitutional division of power.
</P>
<P>
   Last week they forced him to hand over day-to-day government
administration to Vice President Megawati Sukarnoputri. Having done
so, Wahid shifted immediately into his familiar mode of bob and
weave, insisting that it was only duties _ not power _ that he had
given the vice president.
</P>
<P>
   So Parliament is now demanding the right to codify the
arrangement in law, and the president is resisting.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The political nature of the standoff is underscored by the fact
that nobody expects Megawati to be a better administrator than
Wahid. Passive and seemingly uninterested in politics or
administration, Megawati has been a notably absent figure as vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say the trouble with Mega is knowing what she wants,''
a presidential confidant said acidly, using her popular nickname.
``And I suspect she doesn't know herself.''
</P>
<P>
   She has taken little action on the major assignment Wahid gave
her last year, to try to bring peace to a secessionist movement in
remote Irian Jaya and to the Maluku Islands, where religious
fighting has taken more than 3,000 lives. In addition, people close
to the president say that in the past, she has declined the kind of
arrangement that has now been announced.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement has been pushed in Parliament by her opponents
as well as his, apparently as a sort of Trojan horse in the hope
that she can be manipulated, some experts said.
</P>
<P>
   But recently she has come to demand a bigger role, apparently in
part at least for personal reasons.
</P>
<P>
   According to a number of people active in politics, she has
become irritated by what she sees as the president's dismissive
attitude toward her. And she was reportedly angered in April when
the president fired Laksamana Sukardi, a cabinet minister who is
one of her closest advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the straw that broke Mega's back,'' Witoelar said.
``Without that incident, maybe Mega would still be content to be a
sort of passive partner. But she either got very angry or somebody
reminded her to be very angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that she has gotten what she demanded, one cabinet minister
said, the burden is on Megawati to show that she can govern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her problem is to shed the image of a housewife, of
uncertainty, of incompetence,'' he said. ``I would probably give
her the proverbial 100 days, see how she does.''
</P>
<P>
   The new partnership at the top could be made to work, he said,
both because Megawati has surrounded herself with a strong circle
of managers and because Wahid could still appoint a sort of chief
of staff to report to both of them.
</P>
<P>
   But unless the coming week explodes in some unexpected way
either on the streets or inside the Parliament building, the most
important event will come after the legislature adjourns.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Wahid has said, he will appoint a new cabinet and
particularly a new team to manage the flagging economy.
</P>
<P>
   The feuding and the unwieldy cabinet in place now are the
products of the political deals he cut last October to win office.
With the coalition fractured, experts said, he will have more
leeway this time to select his ministers on the basis of merit.
</P>
<P>
   It is this new government lineup _ much more than the political
excitement of the moment _ that may determine the success or
failure of Wahid's struggling government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
