<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0407 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-DEM-PLATFORM-ART-NYT &LR;      08-13 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-PLATFORM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATIC PLATFORM DOES NOT DISTANCE GORE FROM CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Democratic National Convention has been
carefully scripted to help Vice President Al Gore declare his
independence from President Clinton. But one important moment will
wrap Gore more tightly than ever in Clinton's legacy: the passage
of the Democratic platform.
</P>
<P>
   Far from stamping a distinctive Gore imprint on the Democratic
Party, the document the delegates will approve on Tuesday warmly
embraces the centrist policies of the Clinton administration and
lavishly credits them for the prosperity of the last seven years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1992, Bill Clinton and Al Gore were elected to turn the
American economy around,'' the platform declares in its opening
pages. ``Today, the success of these new ideas is clear.''
</P>
<P>
   From those opening lines through most of its 35,000 words, the
platform articulates a ``new Democrat'' agenda that cuts a middle
path between welfare-state liberalism and laissez-faire
Republicanism, advocating active but smaller government, fiscal
discipline, free trade and tough crime policies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton first imposed those positions on the party in 1992 over
the objections of liberals, and Gore's aides fought back efforts _
albeit weak ones _ by progressives again this year to pull the 2000
platform leftward on health care, defense spending and trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the rhetoric and the positions are where the party set
off in '92,'' said Thomas Mann, a senior fellow with the Brookings
Institution, a nonpartisan policy organization. ``Everything is
designed to say: `We are continuing with the policies and the
progress of the Clinton years, even though we are separating
ourselves from the man.'''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Democratic platform represents continuity, the
platform adopted by the Republicans in Philadelphia makes more of a
break, in tone if not always in substance, with Republican
platforms of the recent past.
</P>
<P>
   Much like Clinton in 1992, Gov. George W. Bush has tried to use
the 2000 platform to capture a broader swath of moderate swing
voters. While the platform remains fundamentally conservative,
strongly opposing abortion, gay rights and gun control while
calling for tax cuts, smaller government and more military
spending, the hard-edged proposals from 1996 are gone. The platform
would no longer deny citizenship for the American-born children of
illegal immigrants, abolish the federal department of education and
end federal financing of the arts. Instead it calls for more
inclusive attitudes toward immigrants, a strong federal role in
making schools more effective and the preservation of the biggest
of big government programs, Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In their broad efforts to reach toward the center, the
Republican and Democratic platforms can sound strikingly similar at
times. Both call for holding schools more accountable for student
performance, stricter control of the nation's borders, expanding
global trade, strengthening the military and maintaining the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But in the details, the two platforms sharply diverge on most
issues, providing clear indications of how Gore and Bush
administrations would differ.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Democrats offer modest, targeted tax cuts to help
middle-class families, while the Republicans call for an
across-the-board income-tax cut to stimulate the economy.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Democrats call for increased funds for public schools,
while the Republicans support taxpayer-financed vouchers to help
parents pay for private schools.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Democrats would keep the Social Security system as it is,
bolstering it with general tax revenues. The Republicans call for
allowing taxpayers to invest part of their payroll taxes in the
financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Democrats propose extending Medicaid, the government
health care program for low-income people, to more children, while
the Republicans advocate tax breaks to help people buy private
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Democrats call for developing the technology for a limited
system to protect the nation from ballistic missile attacks, while
the Republicans support moving full-speed ahead with an ambitious,
space-based system.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Democrats endorse civil rights protections for homosexuals
and support laws intended to expand the rights of unions to
organize workers. The Republicans oppose gay rights and support
laws intended to reduce the ability of unions to organize.
</P>
<P>
   For all those clear disagreements, the platforms are alike in
that they closely reflect the styles, broad visions and campaign
agendas of the two candidates. Writing a platform usually tests a
candidate's ability to manage the factions within his party, and
both Bush and Gore successfully enforced a high degree of unity on
their platform committees.
</P>
<P>
   (In contrast, Bob Dole claimed in 1996 that he had not bothered
to read the Republican platform, presumably because its staunchly
conservative tone clashed with his attempts to present a moderate
face.)
</P>
<P>
   But for both candidates, tamping down open dissent from their
parties' most militant wings meant accepting language that
sometimes went beyond their own positions.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, the major fight was over trade. Over the objections of
labor unions, the platform endorses the policy of ``fast track,''
which would allow presidents to negotiate certain treaties without
congressional approval. But at the behest of unions, the platform
also calls for negotiating labor and environmental standards into
all trade accords.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, adopting softer positions on issues like education and
immigration meant accepting language flatly opposing abortion in
all situations, even though he would personally allow it in cases
or rape, incest or danger to the life of the woman.
</P>
<P>
   Tonally, both platforms also reflect the stump styles of the two
candidates. The Republican platform is heavily salted with the kind
of optimistic, inclusive-sounding phrases that flavor Bush's
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We approach these challenges with compassionate conservatism,
a concept that is as old as the pioneers heading West in wagon
trains, in which everyone had responsibility to follow the rules,
but no one would be left behind,'' the platform says.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic document mirrors Gore's knife-edged efforts to
cast Bush as a risk to the nation's peace and prosperity. Thus, the
platform asserts, the Republicans ``eschew fiscal discipline and
offer up nothing less than fiscal disaster.'' Bush's Social
Security plan would ``take the `security' out of Social Security.''
And the Republican proposal for a space-based missile defense
system ``would plunge us into a new arms race.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as it attacks the Republicans, the Democratic platform
manages to echo the Republicans' words. ``If America is to secure
prosperity, peace and security for all, we cannot afford to go
back,'' it says. ``We must move forward together and we must not
leave anyone behind.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0409 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-SCENE14-COX     08-13 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-SCENE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PROTESTERS PREPARE AS CONVENTION APPROACHES
 &HT;    770&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JILL VEJNOSKA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the eve of the Democratic National Convention,
activists gathered at their MacArthur Park headquarters _ nicknamed
the Convergence Center _ for lessons on to cope with tear gas and
pepper spray and how to behave when confronted by police.
</P>
<P>
   Their printed schedule for the week includes marches to protest
police brutality and sweatshop conditions, as well as a beach party
to protest what's essentially another beach party.
</P>
<P>
   There's a legal team, on-site medical services and a makeshift
kitchen to feed hungry volunteers. There's even a ``Bike Library''
where people can borrow _ what else? _ bikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are firmly committed to non-violence,'' Brian Montes said
Sunday morning, clutching a 24-page booklet entitled ``Direct
Action at the DNC.'' ``Direct action means music and dance and
poetry, and other creative actions to get our ideas out.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, some 2,000 activists launched the first major
protest of the convention, gathering at a downtown square to speak
out against the death penalty and police brutality and in support
of Mumia Abu-Jamal, on death row for killing a Philadelphia police
officer.
</P>
<P>
   At Pershing Square, some activists distributed leaflets for
protests scheduled later in the week while others waved picket
signs opposing the death penalty. One sign read, ``Not one more
lynching'' and was emblazoned with a picture of Abu-Jamal, who was
convicted of killing an officer in 1981. Supporters contend he was
framed by racist police.
</P>
<P>
   By supporting the death penalty, Al Gore and George W. Bush have
continued to ``march the retarded, the young and quite possibly the
innocent to their deaths,'' actor and activist Ed Asner told the
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Convergence Center, a former swap meet building, is Ground Zero
for the latest round in what has been the real Y2K surprise: The
re-emergence and refinement of street demonstrations during major
political and governmental gatherings. Starting with the frequently
violent protests in Seattle during the World Trade Organization
meetings and continuing through the two major parties' conventions
this summer, plenty of people have turned out to challenge the
notion that these are the best of times.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton-Gore administration has been selling out the
environment as much as the Bush administration before them,'' said
Andy Paik, 35, who'd come down from Seattle to stay in the
apartment of someone he'd met at a World Bank protest in Washington
and was pinning letters on a large felt banner protesting the
cutting of ancient forests.
</P>
<P>
   Directly behind Paik, large puppets depicting everyone from
vice-president Al Gore to the ``Indonesian Military'' were propped
against a wall. Outside, a police helicopter circled noisily over
MacArthur Park, where some 30 activists practiced waving their
puppets or banners (``Books in the `Hood'' read one) for an
upcoming rally.
</P>
<P>
   Planning for the Convergence Center began several months ago as
a way to organize disparate groups of activists during the
convention and advise them on everything from non-violent protest
tactics to whom to call in cases of arrest or how to support
suspected police misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   A poster inside the center lists the umbrella group's
``demands'' of the U.S. government (amnesty for undocumented
immigrants, an end to ``the racist death penalty,'' etc.), while
the booklet includes a set of participant guidelines (no violence,
weapons or drugs) and a schedule of events (like Sunday night's
beach party outside the Democrats' high-priced fund-raiser on Santa
Monica Pier.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet as the helicopter and handful of police at the nearby subway
stop attest, the center has also become a focus of authorities
hoping to stem trouble before it starts outside the convention. On
Friday, all the protesters won a victory when a federal judge
issued a temporary restraining order preventing police from seizing
materials that protesters use to characterize politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Like puppets. Goofy as it may seem, police raided a so-called
``puppet factory'' in Philadelphia during the Republican
Convention. Here, the tension level is high enough that puppets and
caches of paint have been stashed around the city, one organizer
said Sunday in MacArthur Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``So if our space gets raided,'' said David Solmit, a
36-year-old carpenter who says he'll be doing ``puppet first aid''
during marches and rallies, ``we still have puppets.''
</P>
<P>
   Why puppets, you ask? For poetic reasons _ ``It's much more
clear what we're doing when you SEE Al Gore represented as a
corporate puppet,'' Montes explained _ and for pragmatic ones. TV
loves filming protesters waving big, colorful puppets, several
organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, with many of the 15,000 accredited media having arrived
here this past weekend, well in advance of Monday's convention
kickoff, the feel downtown has been of a party waiting to happen.
Close to the Staples Center, the convention site, an Italian
restaurant got lots of attention for a blackboard of specials that
included convention T-shirts and buttons served along with one's
plate of spaghetti or lasagna. Meanwhile, Los Angeles newspaper
reporters took to interviewing out-of-town reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't get much better at Saturday night's official media
party, held at L.A.'s Department of Water and Power Plaza (at a
cost of $1.5 million), and which seemed to feature as many
delegates and other convention types as anyone. If the best-known
faces were onstage, where Patti LaBelle performed, it may have been
because the Los Angeles Times was having its own party for media
bigwigs and stars who have played journalists in movies or on TV
(Albert Brooks of ``Broadcast News,'' for example).
</P>
<P>
   But that's nothing. Sunday night's big party was to be thrown by
the cast of television's ``The West Wing.'' How exclusive was it?
Even the National Journal, which finds out everything going on here
for its ``Convention Daily'' newspaper, couldn't find out what time
it was supposed to start.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska's e-mail address is jvejnoska(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
