<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Monday, Aug. 14. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The N.Y. Times News Service
night supervisor is Lynn Hoogenboom; phone: 888-346-9867 or
212-556-1927.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-DELEGATES (Undated) _ A poll of Democratic delegates: who
they are and what they believe. How they compare with Republican
delegates, who were polled before the Republican National
Convention. By Adam Clymer and Michael R. Kagay.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-PLATFORM (Los Angeles) _ Far from stamping a distinctive
Gore imprint on the Democratic Party, the platform the delegates
will approve on Tuesday warmly embraces the centrist policies of
the Clinton administration and lavishly credits them for the
prosperity of the last seven years. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN (Moscow) _ Since becoming president of Russia,
Vladimir Putin has capitalized on a voter mandate and high poll
ratings to begin putting Russia back in order after a decade of
wild economic and political swings. But along the way, he is
breaking a lot of china, indulging some of the anti-democratic
instincts, his critics say, that came with his KGB training. By
Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-AIDS-TEACHERS (Bazra-Nattis, Ivory Coast) _ Six teachers
a week in this nation of 15 million people die of AIDS, a 1998
government study found, and officials believe the number has only
gone up since then. The elite status afforded by their education
makes teachers, nearly all of them men, particularly susceptible
when, young and single, they enter remote villages for their first
teaching jobs: young village women compete for their attention. The
result is multiple sexual relationships, made riskier because the
men are unlikely to use condoms. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARELESS-COUNTY (Rushville, Ill.) _ Welfare has completely
disappeared from Schuyler County, Ill. For more than a year, there
have been no new cases, no old cases, no one on the rolls. This
results not just from a strong economy, but also from hard work by
local welfare officials, who give lots of personal attention to
each case _ and have many lessons to teach the rest of the country.
By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ U.S. officials are talking about
the possibility of reviving the Palestinian-Israeli talks, saying
the time is short, that Egypt appears ready to be helpful and that
they see some signs of willingness on both sides. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Detroit) _ The Ford Motor Co. released documents
Sunday showing that Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. had begun receiving
by 1997 numerous complaints of injuries and property damage
involving certain Firestone tires that were not recalled until last
Wednesday. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
</TEXT>
