<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0420 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SC-LOTTERY0814-COX     08-13 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-LOTTERY0814-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lottery foes bucking odds in S. Carolina
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ South Carolina has been rid of video poker since July,
and several groups are trying to make sure a state lottery doesn't
take its place.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Democrat Jim Hodges won the governorship largely
on a promise to support a Georgia-style lottery for education.
Voters in November will decide whether to make that lottery a
reality. Polls have shown lottery support running about 60 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This week, anti-lottery groups will crank up their side of the
argument.
</P>
<P>
   Hodges' lottery organization opened shop Aug. 1 when members of
his Pro-Education Lottery Coalition met in Columbia. Proponents
estimate a state lottery could raise $150 million annually for
education. South Carolina residents spend an estimated $110 million
a year in Georgia's lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans, if they can defeat it, can label it as a failure
of Jim Hodges' administration,'' said College of Charleston
political science professor Bill Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Tuesday in Charleston, the Bipartisan Lottery
Opposition Committee (BLOC) will open a series of six statewide
meetings designed to focus on lottery problems. Opponents are
facing an uphill battle. Polling during the last 11 years has shown
South Carolina lottery support ranging between 65 percent and 74
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised by that,'' said South Carolina Secretary of
State Jim Miles, co-chairman of BLOC. ``Most people feel that since
we have a bad education system that all of a sudden we'll have a
great education system if we have a lottery. I'm not so sure. The
facts will show there's a big cost to get the lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   Miles' group will focus on pathological gamblers, economic
impacts and alternative funding for education.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, state lawmakers had planned for voters also to
decide whether to keep a controversial video poker industry that
annually took an estimated $2.8 billion in bets.
</P>
<P>
   But the state Supreme Court ruled that proposed vote was
unconstitutional, triggering legislation that killed video gaming
July 1.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves the state's gambling debate focused on a lottery
modeled after Georgia's games, which gross about $2 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery will be South Carolina's top statewide election
issue. Neither U.S. Senate seat is up, the next governor's race is
in 2002, and Republican George W. Bush is far outpolling Democrat
Al Gore in the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lottery detractors are buoyed by last year's vote in Alabama,
where voters for years had told pollsters they would support a
state-sponsored game.
</P>
<P>
   But after an aggressive television campaign by anti-lottery
forces that portrayed the games as immoral and potentially corrupt,
Alabama voters overwhelmingly rejected the proposal, which had put
Democrat Don Siegelman in the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Before Labor Day, South Carolina lottery opponents expect to run
ads negatively depicting the games.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina churches that mobilized to defeat video poker now
are ready to tackle the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of that organization is still in place,'' said Joe Mack,
director of Christian Life Concerns for the South Carolina Baptist
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Geddings, Hodges' former campaign manager and one-time
chief of staff, has been the primary spokesman for the lottery. One
challenge, he said, is to demonstrate to churches that it is ``not
inconsistent to be a practicing Christian and still support a
lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, churches played a key role in defeating the lottery
referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the South Carolina Baptist Convention have
consulted with their Alabama counterparts to learn how they
orchestrated their successful anti-lottery campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly one of every five people in South Carolina belong to the
Southern Baptist Convention. The United Methodist Church, as it did
in Alabama, also is working to defeat the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Mack said lotteries disproportionately drain money from
low-income players. ``This is not some benign PTA raffle that
happens once a month. It's much more aggressive than that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
