<SLUG> BC-DEM-PLAYBOY-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYBOY'S FOUNDER HAS HISTORY OF GIVING TO LIBERALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By most measures, Hugh Hefner and his daughter, Christie, are
hardly the largest donors to the Democratic Party. But this week,
as a controversy swirled around the use of the Playboy Mansion for
a Hispanic fund-raiser, they became for a moment among the most
visible.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, the Playboy Enterprises founder, Hugh
Hefner, and the company's chief executive, Christie Hefner, have
given about $95,000 to Democratic candidates and committees, with a
large portion of their donations going to female candidates and to
liberals _ and at least $8,000 going to the Clinton and Gore
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   What is striking about the Hefners' contributions is how
personal, consistent and targeted they are, reflecting mainly the
Hefners' socially liberal ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Their publishing empire, which had sales of $348 million last
year, has no political action committee, nor does it make the
large, unregulated soft-dollar donations that many corporations do
to gain political access in Washington. In fact, few Playboy
executives besides the Hefners give much money, and when they do,
it is not always to Democrats _ Libertarian candidates, too, have
received money from Playboy employees.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Hefners' brand of quiet and personal giving drew
attention when the the Democratic National Committee pressured Rep.
Loretta Sanchez of California to move a fund-raiser for Hispanic
candidates from the Playboy Mansion, fearing it would project the
wrong image for a party trying to distance itself from President
Clinton's personal scandals.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, feisty, Hispanic and female, is exactly the kind of
candidate the Hefners support _ in principle and with dollars. Hugh
Hefner has given Sanchez $3,000, starting with a $1,000 donation
when Sanchez was the underdog in her tight and tough first race, in
which she unseated incumbent conservative Robert Dornan.
</P>
<P>
   As givers, the father and daughter are about equal _ Hugh Hefner
has given Democratic candidates around $43,000 since 1992 and
Christie Hefner has given them around $51,000.
</P>
<P>
   But what is most consistent is the pattern of their giving,
especially from Christie Hefner, whose Democratic donations have
largely gone to female candidates and committees. Christie Hefner
is a major donor to Emily's List ($11,500), which raises money for
female Democrats, and has also given to Voters for Choice/Friends
of Family Planning ($7,000), Woman Unite 2000 ($2,500) and PAC for
Change ($1,000).
</P>
<P>
   Female Democratic candidates for Congress who have received
contributions from Christie Hefner include Hillary Clinton, Patty
Murray, Susan Hynes, Dottie Lamm, Carol Moseley-Braun, Barbara
Boxer, Mary Boyle, Elaine Baxter, Lana Pollack, Lynn Yaekel, Dianne
Feinstein and Liz Holtzman. Male Democrats who have received
contributions from Christie Hefner include Charles Schumer, Bob
Kerrey, Paul Tsongas, John Dingell, Mark Udall, Charles Robb,
Harris Wofford and Terry Sanford.
</P>
<P>
   Hugh Hefner has a more mainstream approach to giving, primarily
making large contributions to leading Democratic Committees _
$20,000 in 1998 and $5,000 in 1996 to the Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee, $5,000 this year and $5,000 in 1998 to the
Democratic National Committee, and $5,000 to Leadership 98, Vice
President Al Gore's leadership PAC, along with $1,000 to Gore 2000
in 1999.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Except for Sanchez, who received four-figure donations from Hugh
Hefner on three occasions, he has not given directly to candidates
other than Gore and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He has, however, allowed the Playboy Mansion to be used for
numerous political fund-raisers, for people including Harold
Washington, the late mayor of Chicago; Tom Bradley, former mayor of
Los Angeles; Jerry Brown, former governor of California; and
presidential aspirants John Anderson and Eugene McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Harshbarger, president of Common Cause, a nonprofit
advocacy group, said the Hefners were an example of ideologically
motivated donors who were being ``tainted unfairly'' by the Sanchez
episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people who give do so because they believe in the cause
or they believe in the candidate,'' said Harshbarger, ``but they
get tainted in the same way as people who are giving for less noble
reasons of gaining access and influence. It's a corrupt system and
it taints everyone in it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
