<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-TECH14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STUDY: INTERNET POLITICS NOT READY FOR PRIME TIME
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Internet sites are scaling back their presence at
the Democratic National Convention amid charges, reflected in a new
Harvard-sponsored study, that their coverage is not ready for prime
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first online convention (held by the Republicans) failed
to live up to the hype that preceded it,'' Michael Cornfield, an
expert on the Internet and politics and a professor at George
Washington University in the nation's capital, said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Alley effort in the GOP media tent yielded such
meager results among online viewers that Pseudo.com, a key player
in Philadelphia, withdrew completely from covering the Democratic
National Convention, which opens here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The receding tide in the political dot-com world was also
evident in the sharp drop in hyperlinks. Eight of the 19 media Web
sites Cornfield studied offered a direct link to the Republicans.
In Los Angeles, only one such site, USAToday.com, linked to the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Cornfield, who watched the entire GOP convention proceedings
solely online at the behest of the Shorenstein Center at Harvard's
John F. Kennedy School of Politics, said the poor results should
not be seen as surprising, ``because the convention was not an
exciting news event.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Moreover, he added, ``technical difficulties plagued
convention innovation, the online audience paid only modest
attention and the Republican Party made little effort to
incorporate the Internet in their media strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   PC Data Online, a firm that meters the choices of 120,000 home
Internet users across the country, found a 14 percent dip in online
traffic to the four most popular news sites during the convention
week when compared with the previous week.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of traffic, the top four are MSNBC.com, CNN.com,
NYTimes.com and WashingtonPost.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clear implication of (the) data is that there was a drop
in online news attention during the Republican convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornfield's findings were sharply criticized Sunday by Gerald
Levin, chief executive of Time Warner and a panelist on a
Shorenstein Center on ``The Impact of Information Technology on
American Democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost everything in that report is mistaken,'' Levin said,
noting that he had read an advance copy that had been sent to him
via e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a very early stage in a new medium,'' he added. When
dedicated people want to provide 24-hour coverage even though
nothing is happening, we ought to regard that as a breakthrough.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin likened the Internet political experience to having
watched, ``as a youngster, the 1948 national political conventions,
the first ones to be televised.''
</P>
<P>
   Two networks, NBC and DuMont, covered both events, which were
held in Philadelphia, with one camera apiece, feeding their signal
by coaxial cable to several cities from Boston to Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   This year, America Online, which plans to merge with Levin's
Time Warner, was one of two Web sites that bought skyboxes from the
Republicans. AOL's Philadelphia neighbor, pseudopolitics.com _
Pseudo.com's corporate child _ allowed visitors to choose their own
viewing angles from its 12 cameras.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.shorensteincenter.org
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass' email address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
