A0428 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      08-13 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIA REV UP AS DEMOCRATS GET READY TO SHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Maybe it was the sunshine and palm trees. Maybe it
was the prospect of celebrity-stuffed parties in the Hollywood
Hills. Or maybe there just seemed a bit more news to fuss over in
the lead-up to the Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, the truffle-hounds of the networks, cable
channels and World Wide Web sites appeared more invigorated Sunday
than they had two weeks ago on the eve of the Republican gathering
in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, it's the Democrats' time to party,'' CNN's Bill Press
enthused.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, the vice presidential
nominee, made the same rounds of Sunday talk shows that his
Republican counterpart, Dick Cheney, had made two weeks ago. This
time, it seemed like a battle of the research departments, as each
program tried to dig up examples of how Lieberman had differed on
issues with Vice President Al Gore. School vouchers. Privatizing
Social Security. Bashing Hollywood. ``You've got a great research
team,'' Lieberman said to NBC's Tim Russert at one point.
</P>
<P>
   The Fox News lead-in to its interview said that Lieberman was
``making waves as the first Jewish vice presidential candidate''
and would be ``taking off the gloves.'' And as the senator answered
Tony Snow's questions, the words ``letting loose'' were emblazoned
on the screen below him.
</P>
<P>
   Really? This was letting loose? Maybe in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The genial Lieberman answered pretty much the same questions in
pretty much the same way he had all day (although his answers did
get more detailed and focused as the day wore on, perhaps a tribute
to the Democrats' own research team).
</P>
<P>
   Several of the Web sites and Sunday news shows provided reports
from Saturday's night's celebrity bash in Brentwood, at which stars
like Shirley MacLaine, Cher, Melissa Etheridge and Paul Anka paid
tribute to Bill and Hillary Clinton. ``You ignite in others things
we have not resolved in ourselves,'' MacLaine was quoted as telling
the first couple in one report.
</P>
<P>
   No translation was provided.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for Inside.com, Michael Cieply said that by convention's
end, so many entertainers will have appeared that ``you might just
forget how dull politicians really are.''
</P>
<P>
   Several commentators made their lead-in to the convention a look
at recent movies and television series about politicians. On CBS,
the ``Sunday Morning'' television critic, John Leonard, played a
clip from TNT's ``Running Mates'' in which Tom Selleck, as a
presidential nominee who has just embraced campaign finance reform,
is serenaded at the convention podium with chants of ``America's
not for sale!''
</P>
<P>
   Cut back to Leonard: ``And I am the Shah of Iran,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It took Cokie Roberts of ABC's ``This Week'' to point out that
the Democratic convention was opening during a full moon, an
observation that caused her fellow commentators to erupt in
giggles. Sam Donaldson was still chuckling several minutes later.
``Cokie,'' he said, ``you're wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Journal, on its convention Web page, peered into
the world of limousine liberals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting it to be like the Oscars, the Olympics, the
Super Bowl and the World Cup all rolled into one for a week,'' said
Jim Baron of Rely Transportation. However, many celebrities and
tycoons, he said, were opting for less conspicuous town cars,
fearing limousines might attract protesters. Indeed, A-List
Limousine was offering, for a slight extra charge, an armed guard
with each limousine.
</P>
<P>
   How many people will actually watch the Democratic convention on
television? Fox asked visitors to its Web site. As of Sunday
afternoon, 25.8 percent said they would watch, 65.7 percent saying
they would not and the rest weren't sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a scientific poll,'' cautioned Fox. No kidding.
But still, here was a group of people who had already taken the
trouble to log onto a political Web site and then to vote on this
question, and even they didn't intend to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if it were more like the fractious Reform Party
convention, which resulted last week in two presidential
candidates, the conservative pundit Pat Buchanan and a physicist,
John Hagelin, each claiming the true crown.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan appeared on ``Meet the Press'' Sunday and said that,
despite appearances, the party was really pretty united behind him,
considering. ``It's casting off the old shell and growing a new
one,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   We've had the New Deal, the New Frontier and the New Covenant,
so why not the New Shell?
</P>
<P>
   In a story on the Democratic Party's official campaign Web site,
the chairman of the Democrats' convention committee, Terry
MacAuliffe, went surfing and promised free lessons to all of the
15,000 media representatives covering the convention. The lessons
would be offered through the Paskowitz Surfing School of Santa
Monica whose owner, Izzy Paskowitz, said he could teach anyone,
even a journalist, to stand up on a surf board.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
