<SLUG> BC-OLY-RAIL-SERVICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYDNEY'S NEXT HURDLE: GET TRAINS IN SHAPE FOR OLYMPIC GAMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN SHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Ron Christie, the man with the job of making
the Olympic trains run on time, says there are ``no quick fixes''
for Sydney's rail network, which is plagued by problems as it
prepares to double its traffic during the Games, which start Sept.
15.
</P>
<P>
   But Premier Bob Carr, whose New South Wales state government is
organizing and underwriting the 2000 Olympics, hopes to quickly
improve the performance of the 800-mile, 300-station train system.
It is expected to have to handle 34 million passenger trips during
the Games, which run through Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   More than 400 trains carrying half a million people are
scheduled to run each day to and from the main venue, Olympic Park,
where 15 sports arenas are clustered around the main 110,000-seat
stadium seven miles from downtown. About 3,500 buses will also
carry Olympic spectators, most on highway lanes dedicated to Games
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Christie, the city's coordinator-general for rail, said there
were ``contingency plans to minimize disruptions,'' but added, ``it
would be naive to suggest there will be no rail incidents during
the Games.''
</P>
<P>
   Five weeks from the start of the biggest Games in Olympic
history, Sydney's rail lines are wracked with delays, derailments,
errors and incompetence. Rookie drivers making mistakes, signal
failures, lagging maintenance, and divided management are being
blamed for the wave of accidents, equipment failures and shabby
service.
</P>
<P>
   There have been 30 derailments this year and 60 drivers
suspended from duty for errors, including 33 instances of driving
through red lights. The suburban accidents so far have been at low
speed, resulting only in minor injuries and damage.
</P>
<P>
   At peak times on some of the busiest routes, only 75 percent of
trains have been on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been tremendous rail problems,'' Carr said. ``I
don't defend the performance.'' He called the service
``inexcusable, lamentable, embarrassing, indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors from the International Olympic Committee, including a
committee vice president, Anita de Frantz of the United States, had
given Sydney high marks earlier for its overall preparations. They
appeared to approve rail plans on the basis of a new track and
station costing $100 million (U.S.) that was built to link Olympic
Park with the suburban network serving this sprawling city of four
million.
</P>
<P>
   Carr said he was confident of having solutions in time. ``We are
working to fix the problems,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm optimistic that we will be able to move people to and from
the Olympic venues,'' Carr told interviewers this week. ``Our
trains and buses successfully handled huge crowds at recent
football games, concerts and millennium events _ we delivered then
and we will again.''
</P>
<P>
   To try to get the system back on track in time for the Olympics,
Carr last month appointed Christie as the coordinator-general for
rail with wide powers, a blank check and an annual pay raise of
$50,000 (American) to $200,000. Impatient with his transport
minister and railway officials, Carr slashed red tape and cut legal
corners to give Christie complete rail responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Christie, a veteran railroad manager, has much to coordinate.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Carr's government decided to divide rail
authority, believing administrative reforms would increase
efficiency. Services, maintenance and track were doled out to
separate departments. It proved to be the wrong way to run a
railroad.
</P>
<P>
   Christie has the urgent task of putting the system back on the
rails, getting such organizations as State Rail, City Rail, Rail
Services Australia, Rail Access Corp. and Department of Transport
to work together.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no quick fix to some of the reliability issues,'' he
said recently. He has a six-point plan to reduce accidents and run
on time _ and less than five weeks to make it work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
