<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SHOW SIGNS OF LIFE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's funny, in that bizarre kind of way, how the
emotion of a long baseball season can ebb and flow from a measly
nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   Despair on Sunday morning was replaced by hope again Sunday
evening. The Los Angeles Dodgers aren't fixed, but they still are
involved in a playoff race, regardless of what else is going on
internally.
</P>
<P>
   That was clear after they salvaged the finale of a three-game
series with Atlanta as right-hander Darren Dreifort won his
career-high sixth straight and Shawn Green homered and drove in
three in the Dodgers' 7-2 win at Turner Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers ended their season series by beating the Braves
twice in nine games, and they lost the first two games of this
series. But the Dodgers pulled to within 4 games of San Francisco
in the National League West, thanks to the drubbing the Giants are
getting in New York. The Mets have won three straight from the
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed that for our mental state more than anything,''
Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros said. ``We lost six of seven, so
a win was important.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield hit his league-leading 37th homer in the seventh
inning, the second highest total in Los Angeles history. Mike
Piazza hit 40 in 1997. Todd Hundley also homered and leadoff man
Tom Goodwin made a diving catch, drove in two runs and reached base
three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Goodwin had a good day, the offense geared up a little bit,
and that's our formula,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``You
look at (the scoreboard), but you're more concerned about playing
good ball, and we played a pretty good ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the All-Star break, Dreifort has been nearly perfect,
winning six straight starts to improve to 10-7. He's 6-0 with a
2.33 ERA after the break and hasn't allowed an earned run in three
of those starts.
</P>
<P>
   But Dreifort wasn't at his best against the Braves, though he
limited them to one unearned run and nine hits in five innings. The
lone run he allowed came after third baseman Adrian Beltre booted a
ball in the bottom of the first, but Dreifort also was aided by
some strong defense, including a pair of double plays.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones' sharp grounder back to the mound turned into a
double play that ended a first-inning rally, and a line drive to
shortstop Alex Cora, who flipped to Beltre at third for a double
play, ended the Braves' fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big defense,'' Dreifort said. ``We made clutch defensive plays
at clutch times and (Hundley) did a hell of a job back there mixing
pitches and mixing location. It was clutch hitting, clutch defense
and the bullpen comes in and gives you four quality innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Atlanta pitching coach Leo Mazzone, ``Dreifort had a
horseshoe up his (butt).''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers move on to open a three-game series at Florida
today, then return home for three games with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than looking to make up all the ground immediately,
the feeling is to chip away and be in position come September when
the schedule should, in theory, favor the Dodgers. They play 19 of
their final 28 games at home. Their last 22 games are against the
National League West, including six against Arizona and three
against San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   It was only nine days ago the Dodgers could have pulled within
1games of first place had they beaten Milwaukee, but instead they
lost in 10 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be three games out with a month left is really not a big
deal,'' Dodgers second baseman Mark Grudzielanek said. ``That's
what we should look at. You try to look at the bright side. We're
not playing well, but before that we won 10 of 13. You have to try
and hover when you're not playing well, and right now we're playing
terrible. But we're still in contention.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet there's also Dodgers' home record. They're a solid 32-29 on
the road _ the only club in the division above .500 _ but they're
28-27 at home. The Dodgers also have a solid 17-12 mark within
their division.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can gain a game a week in the next three weeks, then
we're back in,'' said Green, who hit his 22nd homer in the ninth
inning. ``That's the way you have to look at it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
