<SLUG> BC-CVN-BAXTER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    L.A., WHERE THE UNUSUAL MEETS THE STRANGE
 &HT;    By TOM BAXTER
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There wasn't much of an official nature going on
over the weekend at the Beverly Hills hotel where Georgia's
delegation is staying for the Democratic National Convention. But
the scene in the lobby reflected a little of the zany quality of
the larger event.
</P>
<P>
   As the Georgia delegates began to drift in, they found
themselves rubbing shoulders with the spiffily groomed Nation of
Islam security men who guard the Rev. Louis Farrakhan, who was in
town to promote his Million Family March.
</P>
<P>
   It was an amiable enough mingling, although Farrakhan's presence
in the same hotel where Jimmy Carter is staying did pose problems
for the former president's Secret Service detachment, which had
Carter's room moved to another floor (Farrakhan, reportedly, had
already booked the presidential suite).
</P>
<P>
   Different groups bump into each other in the hotel lobbies of
every major city, but this location guarantees as wide a range of
conceivable juxtapositions as any city you can think of.
</P>
<P>
   That makes this an exciting place for Democrats, who have been
buffeted by the progress of George W. Bush's campaign this summer,
to gather. It also presents a challenge for a party striving to
present a coherent message to the American people this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans held their convention in an orderly,
traditionally Democratic city, where the streets are compatible
with riot control tactics, and where nothing else threatened to
overshadow their presence.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats have pitched their tent in America's vast City of
Dreams, where one's importance is normally measured by last
weekend's box office returns, and small disturbances have been
known to metastasize into sprawling riots.
</P>
<P>
   Someone once defined the movie term ``high concept'' as an idea
so simple and direct it can be shouted across a parking lot, such
as ``Star-crossed lovers on a sinking ship.'' Vice President Al
Gore will fill in some of the dialogue in his acceptance speech
Thursday night, but the rest of the convention is supposed to be
devoted to presenting that high concept on which his candidacy
stands.
</P>
<P>
   How to be simple and direct, however, in a city where
message-crafting is a major industry?
</P>
<P>
   The expected campaign posters line the street near the Staples
Center, where the convention begins tonight. On closer inspection,
however, the candidate turns out to be Tom Selleck, and the poster,
really an ad for his new movie.
</P>
<P>
   One of the hottest party tickets was for Sunday night's party
thrown by the cast of the television show ``West Wing''_imaginary
politicians, in other words, standing on the hors d'oeuvres line
with politicians who sometimes act.
</P>
<P>
   A mural with the portraits of Franklin and Eleanor Roosevelt,
Martin Luther King, Bobby Kennedy and Cesar Chavez rises
majestically on the side of the Figueroa Hotel overlooking the
center.
</P>
<P>
   Look again, however, and you notice this quintet of liberal
heroes is arranged around the logo of Apple Computers, with its new
slogan, ``Think Different.''
</P>
<P>
   To be as appealing as a star, and yet somehow come off as
genuine to average Americans; to give imagination free play,
without ignoring the hard realities of an election campaign in
which he lags behind_that's the challenge facing Gore and his party
here this week.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter's e-mail address is tbaxter(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
