<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON WILL FINISH SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Wanting to put the focus on the Los Angeles Dodgers'
playoff race instead of the status of their manager, Dodgers
general manager Kevin Malone said Sunday no changes in the on-field
staff will take place during the season.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said evaluation of everyone, including manager Davey
Johnson and his staff, wouldn't take place until after the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``From ownership to management, we're not making any changes
(during the season),'' Malone said via telephone. ``We want to put
an end to wherever the speculation came from. This is the team
we're going with. It's a very talented team. We want Davey to
succeed. We want to make sure we stay focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers president and chief operating officer Bob Graziano
called Johnson after Sunday's game with the Atlanta Braves to tell
Johnson to stop wondering about his status because nothing was
going to happen during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him he's our manager, he's going to be our manager
through this pennant race,'' Graziano said. ``He shouldn't worry
about anything but trying to win. There's nothing more that
(managing general partner and CEO) Bob Daly would like to see,
nothing more I would like to see, nothing more Kevin would like to
see than Davey having unquestionable success.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Johnson's job remains in jeopardy. If the Dodgers don't
make the playoffs, he'll likely be fired, sources continue to
state.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has come under heavy scrutiny since the Dodgers' front
office questioned his on-field strategy and philosophy last month.
But Malone said the front office has never said Johnson's job was
on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Malone said all attention and effort belongs on how the
Dodgers play the rest of the season, especially since the playoffs
are within reach. Malone also said the Dodgers, who are 4 games
behind San Francisco in the National League West, had time to make
a run at the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is pulling away from it,'' Malone said. ``There is a
sense of urgency, but we're in a position to make a run and win
this thing. At the end of the season, everyone will be
re-evaluated. We can't say what's going to happen at the end of the
year. We'll evaluate everybody, like every organization does.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be no concern for Davey or the coaching staff. We
want Davey to succeed. We think we can win with this group of
players. We think they're talented. It's a nonissue. We want this
team to succeed. (Johnson's status) has never been an issue with
ownership or management.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Elster's future: Dodgers shortstop Kevin Elster isn't playing
much these days, having started twice this month because of Alex
Cora's emergence. But Elster, 36, who didn't play last season, said
he's unsure whether this will be the last couple months of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know if I want to play,'' Elster said. ``It
depends on the situation. Next year, I'm not going to go to spring
training without a guaranteed contract. But I would certainly like
to play again.''
</P>
<P>
   Elster came to spring training as a nonroster player and won the
starting job from Cora. But Cora has garnered much of the playing
time for the last two months. Elster is batting .222 with 12 homers
and 29 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   A club source said Elster wouldn't be offered a guaranteed
contract with the Dodgers after the season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Support, please: Today against Florida, right-hander Kevin
Brown makes his 60th start since joining the Dodgers before the
1999 season. He's 28-13 but doesn't get much run support. The
Dodgers have been shut out in five of the games, scored one run
three times and scored two runs twice.
</P>
</TEXT>
