<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0433 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-PGA0814-COX     08-13 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA0814-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods overshadows PGA competition, unlovable course
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Maybe the PGA of America should spot Tiger
Woods a three-stroke lead when he steps to the first tee in
Thursday's first round of the 82nd PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe Jim Awtrey, the PGA's chief executive operating
officer, should spend the week as Tiger's personal chauffeur.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the PGA brass owe the world's No. 1 player a huge
favor or two for deflecting some of the heat from a return this
week to controversial Valhalla Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Make no mistake, if we didn't have the Woods machine rolling
into town with a chance for a third straight major and hogging most
of the attention, the PGA would be receiving even harsher flak _
from players and media _ for selecting Valhalla to host another
championship after millennium majors at super-venues Pebble Beach
and St. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   Woods pumped new life into the PGA Championship last year at
storied Medinah, when he beat Sergio Garcia by a shot, to spend the
year as defending champion. And now, as the 2000 PGA commences,
Woods is again the dominant story, pushing the quality (or lack of
it) of the venue to secondary status.
</P>
<P>
   When Awtrey was in Atlanta last week to oversee the
one-year-to-go push for the 2001 PGA at the Atlanta Athletic Club,
he hardly ever mentioned Valhalla without putting Tiger in the same
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   It will be much the same for the next few days as Woods tries to
become the first player in 47 years to win three majors in the same
year. Ben Hogan was the last to accomplish it, in 1953, when he
missed qualifying for the PGA (everybody had to do so back then) to
compete in the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   With the Woods story in place, the PGA can focus on its more
positive things, such as:
</P>
<P>
   The strongest field in major championship history (since the
rankings were established) with 93 of the top 100 players
participating _ including the top 75. Even Jumbo Ozaki, who
normally needs a typhoon to be pushed out of Japan, is on the
property.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing story of Ernie (Avis) Els, who is trying not
become the first to player to finish second in all of the year's
four majors. He was second to Vijay Singh at the Masters and a very
distant runner-up to Woods at the U.S. Open and British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you feel like this is your last chance (at a major in
2000),'' Els said, ``you give it all you have.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unfortunate that the PGA has been so stubborn with
Valhalla, trying to force-feed a major venue on both players and
fans. In much of the 1990s the tournament usually has been a
stellar experience when the venues have been special. Clearly, the
PGA usually runs a quality event.
</P>
<P>
   The so-so years were at the questionable sites _ 1996 at
Valhalla, when Mark Brooks defeated Kenny
(I-don't-need-to-hit-any-range-balls) Perry in a sudden-death
playoff; and in 1998, when Singh won at Sahalee Country Club near
Seattle, a course so tight that drivers were often holstered.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere else the PGA has visited recently, when famous venues
were utilized, the tournament has flourished.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the PGA usually has gotten what it's paid for.
</P>
<P>
   While still clearly the fourth ranked of the four majors, mostly
great stories unfolded in:
</P>
<P>
   1993, when Paul Azinger won a sudden-death playoff against Greg
Norman at Inverness.
</P>
<P>
   1994, when Nick Price won his second straight major, blitzing
the field at Southern Hills.
</P>
<P>
   1995, when Steve Elkington beat Colin Montgomerie in a
sudden-death playoff at Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when Davis Love III took his first major under a
rainbow at Winged Foot, outplaying buddy Justin Leonard, then the
reigning British Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, when Woods held off the charging Garcia, Europe's most
dominant young player, in a Sunday duel at Medinah.
</P>
<P>
   All the indicators are there for low scoring at Valhalla _ not
just for Woods _ and that goes against the par-is-a-good-score
theme commanded by traditional major venues. Although Valhalla's
Bermuda rough is very thick from recent rain, the greens are also
receptive. A winning score in the 280 range seems likely at a
course where all the par-5s are reachable for the majority of the
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a better golf course now (than in 1996),'' Valhalla
superintendent Mark Wilson contends. ``People (want to) compare us
to Pebble Beach and Augusta. My line is this: We're in better shape
at 14 years old than they were.''
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY. . .
</P>
<P>
   Tom Lehman had arthroscopic knee surgery last Monday after being
forced to withdraw from the International, but is expected to play
in the PGA . . .Doug Tewell, the PGA Seniors champion, and club pro
Rick Hartmann withdrew from the field and were replaced by Skip
Kendall and Paul Stankowski. . .David Duval still expects to play
despite recent back problems. . .Mike Gill of Columbus is the
Georgia Section's representative in the tournament and one of 25
club pros participating.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
