<SLUG> BC-DEM-SCRIPT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS AIM FOR ISSUE-ORIENTED, `ANTI-FLUFF' CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER MARKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ From the sea of see-through iMac computers on the
convention floor to a center-stage program of prominent officials
engaged in issue ``dialogues'' with ordinary people, the Democratic
National Convention that opens Monday is intended to be, in look
and feel, a brainier and meatier antidote to the Republicans'
feel-good Philadelphia spectacle.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, meeting in the Staples Center through Thursday,
say that the Republicans were so consumed with banishing the
divisive demons of gatherings past that they missed the opportunity
to give American voters a comprehensive sense of what they stood
for in 2000 _ or of who their standard-bearer truly was.
</P>
<P>
   ``They spent a lot more time battling their 1996 convention than
they did battling the Democrats,'' said Joe Andrew, national
chairman of the Democratic National Committee. ``Ultimately what
people saw was the surface image. We are going to focus on issues,
because we know the issue landscape is home turf for us.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, viewers will not only be getting a refresher course
on the accomplishments of the Clinton-Gore administration: The
opening day is being devoted to discussions of the economy and the
needs of working families. But viewers will also hear enough talk
of weighty policy matters to fill a social-studies textbook. Health
care is to be a constant thread, introduced in several panel
discussions and reinforced in addresses by the week's major
speakers. The other big issues include education, retirement
security and fighting crime.
</P>
<P>
   Even the sleek computers, made by Apple and supplied to each
delegation on the floor, are intended subtly to reinforce the idea
of the Democrats as the party of the future, and Vice President Al
Gore as the candidate of innovation. (Computers were few and far
between on the floor of the First Union Center in Philadelphia.)
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a message in and of itself: `Think Different,''' Andrew
said, invoking the theme of the Apple computer advertising
campaign. ``We think outside the box.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats promise a convention less rehearsed than that of
their rivals. The party is not well known for sticking to the
script anyway, as demonstrated over the weekend by the tussle over
the plans by Rep. Loretta Sanchez of California to stage a benefit
at the Playboy Mansion, and by Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr.'s tepid
expression of support for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in other ways both symbolic and substantive, the Democrats
are taking pains to turn the Staples Center into a palace devoted
to the art of rebuttal.
</P>
<P>
   The physical layout of the hall itself is an answer to the
Republicans' goal of a four-day variety show: While the
Philadelphia rostrum was modeled on an Oscar telecast, complete
with wide steps leading directly to the stage, the Democrats have
installed a more traditional-looking podium, with a 12-foot
retractable wall between the speakers and the delegates.
</P>
<P>
   The approach to selling the message is different, too. In
Philadelphia, the Republicans came up with a slogan: ``Renewing
America's Purpose. Together,'' that was used as the gathering's
overarching theme. The Democrats, by contrast, chose not to adopt a
slogan, using instead the blandly generic ``America 2000'' as a
kind of campaign trademark. In fact, the party talks so much about
how it wants to differentiate itself from the Republican convention
that the motto could have been, ``Not the Republican National
Convention.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican convention made no mistakes, but it wasn't
successful because it didn't leave people with anything,'' said
Sen. Charles E. Schumer, D-N.Y. ``I think what we're trying to do
is focus on some issues, not abstract issues, that make people's
lives better. I think that is going to be our theme, and that
theirs was sort of all fluff.''
</P>
<P>
   To make this the convention of anti-fluff, the Democrats are
putting bright party lights like Schumer, as well as celebrities
like the actor Jimmy Smits, in major supporting roles at the
convention. They will be moderators of talk-show-style panels early
each day in the proceedings, which are to be gaveled to order at 5
p.m. ET, to accommodate prime time on the East Coast. The panels,
called ``American Dialogues,'' will feature ordinary Americans
talking about the issues that affect their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's panel, on Wednesday, will examine crime and victims'
rights, and among his ``guests'' will be the parents of Matthew
Shepard, the young gay man murdered in Wyoming in October 1998.
``The challenge of our convention is going to be to stick to the
message,'' the senator said. ``If it doesn't seem meaty in
comparison, we've sure flunked.''
</P>
<P>
   The message discipline may not reach the levels it did at the
Republican convention, where copies of media talking points nine
pages long were placed daily on the seats of every delegate. In Los
Angeles, the emphasis will be on a reiteration of Gore's positions
on issues that have tested well: Across the board, for instance,
candidates, officials and Gore surrogates will be talking about the
vice president's advocacy of adding a prescription drug plan to
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats actually may find obstacles to the delivery of
their message on television from a surprising source: their own
speakers. Addresses on the initial nights by President Clinton,
Hillary Rodham Clinton and Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman could be major
media events unto themselves, and thus could distract attention
from Gore in a way that Gov. George W. Bush largely did not have to
deal with in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Burstein, executive producer of special events for ABC
News, said that those speakers had the potential to be riveting.
``The fact that you're going to have the president and the first
lady speaking, in light of his comments the other day, it's
certainly going to be compelling television,'' he said, referring
to Clinton's talk in Illinois on Thursday about his adulterous
affair. Gail Evans, executive vice president of CNN, added that
Lieberman's nomination as the first Jew on a national ticket is
great talk-show fodder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful for discussion because everyone's got an
opinion about it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Democratic officials believe they have developed a
strategy that ensures that they get their message out even if the
national press and the political pundits are not cooperative. They
say they have committed vast resources to the creation of their own
Democratic News Service. It will deliver news feeds via satellite
to more than 500 local television stations around the country, as
well as provide sound bites for radio and content for Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew, for one, is convinced that this dimension of the
convention may be the most important. ``Our money is being spent
more on that than on the show,'' he said. And as for those Imacs,
Andrew said they were part of that mission too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we have computers on the floor is not so the podium
can communicate with the delegates,'' he added, ``it's for us to be
able to track the officials in each delegation so we can send the
message back home, `Here's what's happening in your Indiana
delegation.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
