</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-695&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. IS CONSIDERING REVIVING MIDEAST PEACE TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House has calculated that the effective
deadline for a final Middle East peace settlement during the
Clinton presidency is the end of September, a senior administration
official said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is prepared to reconvene a summit meeting _
intense, but shorter than last month's Camp David talks _ but only
if he is assured that the Israelis and Palestinians are ready to
settle all outstanding issues, including Jerusalem, the senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow time frame was dictated, the official said, by the
start of the Jewish religious holidays, which stretch from late
September into much of October, and by the return from a long
recess of the Israeli Parliament, at the end of October.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to move quickly has intensified, the official said,
because the administration has concluded that the Israeli
government of Prime Minister Ehud Barak will not be able to survive
long after Parliament reconvenes.
</P>
<P>
   Recently published opinion polls in Israel suggest that Barak's
popularity has dropped precipitously. If he is still in dire
straits when Parliament returns, the rightist opposition party
Likud is likely to succeed in maneuvering for new elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a huge window of time that is available,'' the
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat has threatened to declare a
Palestinian state on Sept. 13, the deadline set by both sides for a
final peace agreement, if there is no such accord by then.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat did not get much support for such a unilateral move
during a recent trip to Europe and Russia, the senior
administration official said. Arafat is expected to continue to
seek support for statehood when he visits leaders of Pakistan,
China and India.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has sent messages to both sides, but is not in the same
intense mode as at Camp David, the official said. There has also
been a ``wide array'' of contacts between senior Israeli and
Palestinian officials, but no direct contact between Barak and
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Camp David talks ended, ``the Egyptians have made it
clear to us that they are prepared to be helpful'' in persuading
Arafat to make tough decisions, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   One indication of this, according to another administration
official, was the cool reception that the Egyptian leader, Hosni
Mubarak, gave to Arafat's idea of an Arab summit meeting on
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the Camp David talks, the Egyptian leader
infuriated senior White House aides with his outspoken statements
discouraging Arafat from making a compromise on Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   In public, however, Mubarak has continued to sound a stern note
of noncompromise, saying in an interview published over the weekend
that no Arab or Muslim state could relinquish the traditional claim
to Jerusalem and its holy sites.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak was briefed extensively about the Camp David talks by a
U.S. emissary, Edward Walker, the assistant secretary for Near East
affairs, who has been touring Arab capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Walker, who participated only briefly at Camp David, has
instructions to tell Arab leaders the broad outlines of what went
on there and to urge them to help Arafat to compromise, U.S.
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat returned to his headquarters in Gaza on Saturday to
contemplate the results of visits to Europe and Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
   France, currently in the chair of the European Union, encouraged
Arafat to continue to talk to his ``partner,'' Barak, the official
said. This was in contrast, he said, to the message that Arafat
received from the French when he was negotiating with the previous
Israeli government under Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, whom
Paris considered more of an obstacle to Middle East peace.
</P>
<P>
   In the Arab capitals, Arafat garnered support for his refusal to
compromise on the question of sovereignty of East Jerusalem. But
there was no broad endorsement for an Arab summit meeting that
would develop into a platform for Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The White House is sending Dennis Ross, its senior Middle East
negotiator, to Israel late this week. He is expected to travel in
the region.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The administration insists that Camp David created a new
dynamic, because issues that had never been dissected before _
especially the future status of Jerusalem _ were broached in a
serious manner.
</P>
<P>
   Jerusalem remained the hardest hurdle, with the most intractable
problems concerning sovereignty over the Temple Mount, known to
Muslims as Haram, and the status of the Old City and the
immediately adjoining areas, the senior administration official
said.
</P>
<P>
   At Camp David, the administration suggested that the
Palestinians have sovereignty over the Muslim and Christian
quarters and the Israelis over the Jewish and the Armenian quarters
of the Old City. Another proposal revolved around the Palestinians
having sovereignty over several of the neighborhoods surrounding
the Old City and having administrative autonomy within the walls.
</P>
<P>
   A third notion was to defer the Jerusalem problem for some
years.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the Israelis nor the Palestinians showed much enthusiasm
for deferring the issue while completing a peace agreement on
territory, security and the fate of Palestinian refugees, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Barak's declared objectives has been to secure an accord
that would enable him to announce that it was a final agreement
ending all Palestinian claims on Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has argued that East Jerusalem must be the sovereign
capital of the new Palestinian state. ``I wouldn't dismiss the
possibility of getting the agreement on everything,'' the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   The official stressed that the administration remains willing to
do all it can, but only the two sides can actually reach agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
