<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0441 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-TEXAS-0814-COX     08-13 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-TEXAS-0814-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MISSING MAN IS NOTICED AT TEXAS DEMOCRATS CONVENE IN LOS ANGELES
 &HT;    ATTN TEXAS PAPERS
 &HT;    By KEN HERMAN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Everybody who is anybody among Texas Democrats is
in Los Angeles this week for the Democratic National Convention _
except the man who may be their gubernatorial candidate in two
years.
</P>
<P>
   Laredo oilman Tony Sanchez, seen by some Democrats as the man to
lead them out of the political wilderness, would be out of place
here as his party nominates Al Gore for president. Sanchez is a
high-dollar backer of Republican presidential nominee George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   For Texas Democrats, it's a political conundrum that makes
Sanchez the most interesting no-show. And some top Democrats _ the
same ones who generally have little nice to say about Democrats
backing Bush _ went to work Sunday defending Sanchez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know him and he is an outstanding man,'' said Texas
Democratic Chairwoman Molly Beth Malcolm. ``He has been a Democrat
all his life. He is friends with George Bush. A lot of people have
friendships.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the friendship and the big money Sanchez has raised for
and given to Bush, Malcolm is among the Democrats who are very
interested in seeing Sanchez atop the 2002 ticket as the party
attempts its comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, potential statewide candidates (something the
Democrats are short on) hang around at national political
conventions to curry favor among delegates.
</P>
<P>
   Former Comptroller John Sharp, moving toward a potential re-run
for lieutenant governor in 2002, will host a Wednesday night
dessert-and-champagne reception for the delegation. Sharp, who lost
to
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rick Perry in the 1998 race for lieutenant governor,
would have an increased chance of winning in 2002 if the Democrats
have a Hispanic atop the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Sanchez, who has declined to say whether he will run for
governor, had little to say recently when asked if he planned to
show up in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``No politics,'' he said during last week during a meeting of
University of Texas System Board of Regents, on which he serves as
a Bush appointee. ``I'm not going to comment on any politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the week, Sanchez's staff in Laredo said he had no
plans to attend the national convention. His absence helps
Democrats avoid an uncomfortable question: Can their 2002
gubernatorial candidate be a Bush
</P>
<P>
   appointee who personally gave $106,000 to Bush's gubernatorial
races and has raised more than $100,000 for Bush's presidential
race?
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Mario Gallegos of Houston, who has traveled around
the nation to bad-mouth Bush's record at home, is willing to
overlook Sanchez's support of the governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can support somebody like Tony Sanchez,'' said
Gallegos, a longtime friend who said a Sanchez gubernatorial
candidacy would invigorate Hispanic voters and benefit all
Democratic candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of folks that have given George Bush money,
especially in Texas, that are Democrats,'' said Gallegos, adopting
a forgiving tone not reflected by Texas delegates walking around
the convention floor
</P>
<P>
   wearing buttons inviting passers-by to ``Ask about my
governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime party activist Ed Martin chose his words carefully
Sunday as he sat in his hotel lobby and pondered the possibility of
a Democratic gubernatorial nominee with close ties to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people think (Sanchez) would bring a lot of
ability, a lot of resources, and certainly would bring a lot to a
Democratic ticket,'' Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   But are Texas Democrats ready to nominate a man who has become a
key cog in the Bush campaign?
</P>
<P>
   ``That matter will be dealt with if and when he decides when he
is running,'' said Martin. ``We will deal with that in 2002.''
</P>
<P>
   While they are understanding of Sanchez's support of Bush, some
in the Texas delegation are not as easy-going about the team of
Texas Democrats who back Bush and will hold daily briefings in Los
Angeles to make their point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what I've said all along. It takes Democrats to help
George Bush get anything he wants to get done,'' Malcolm said of
the Bush Democrats, including House Appropriations Chairman Rob
Junell of San Angelo and
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ken Armbrister of Victoria.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Austin American-Statesman writer Sharon Jayson contributed to
this report. You may contact Ken Herman at kherman(at)statesman.com
or 445-1718.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
