<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0446 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HOLYFIELD-FOLLOW0814-     08-13 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLYFIELD-FOLLOW0814-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Last round won crown for Holyfield
 &HT;    By Mike Tierney
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Evander Holyfield can hear them now.
</P>
<P>
   He's getting old. His skills are eroding. He better bow out
sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   And he smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``That sets up other (fighters) to say, `I can beat Evander.'
Then I bust them up.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, Holyfield knows that he won over no converts with a plodding
decision, unanimous though seat-squirming tight, Saturday night
over John Ruiz to assume the vacant WBA heavyweight title.
</P>
<P>
   But he also knows that unorthodox boxers often give him fits.
Case in point: Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   Chillin' in the 26th-floor penthouse suite at his Vegas digs
early Sunday morning, Holyfield said, ``I knew this guy was going
to fight hungry and bulldog me. I didn't want to get in a slinging
contest with this guy because he leads with his head.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield countered with elbows and other body parts _
unintentionally, he says; underhandedly, says the Ruiz camp.
WWF-like throwdowns resulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't give me room to do anything,'' Holyfield said.
</P>
<P>
   It took Holyfield until the last round to figure out that he
could hold out his glove and grab Ruiz's head as the younger boxer
bore in.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield likes to say that styles make a fight. And if the
style is difficult to decipher, it spells trouble. Ruiz was Rubik's
cube.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if he would throw a right hand or a left hand.
It was another Vaughn Bean,'' he said of the supposed fall guy who
extended him for all 12 rounds at the Georgia Dome two years ago.
``You never knew what he was going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why Holyfield might handle a one-trick pony like Mike
Tyson with greater ease than John Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Holyfield believes the fight's 11-week postponement
because of his pulled stomach muscle was a blessing. Without it, he
fears he might have been totally in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped me,'' he said. ``It gave me the opportunity to see
some things (on film). I saw that that boy was going to try and
trick me.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I would have fought him the first time, he would have tore
me up.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Holyfield entered the final round even with Ruiz on
two of three judges' cards. If the pair had not awarded the third
round to Holyfield 10-8, he would have trailed.
</P>
<P>
   A booming left hook that felled Ruiz was ruled a slip by the
referee, but Holyfield still may have broken Ruiz's nose during a
dominant last three minutes to keep the goal of undisputed champion
within his sights.
</P>
<P>
   The next key fight is not his own. WBC/IBF designee Lennox Lewis
takes on David Tua in November, with Holyfield waiting for the
winner. First, though, he likely must wade through a WBA title
defense against whoever is promoted to No. 1 contender.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Holyfield will have turned 38, an age at which most
fighters have moved on to less strenuous pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   No matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep taking care of my body,'' he said, vowing
even to work out regularly in Sydney while he attends the Summer
Olympics on Coca-Cola's dime. ``I'm still learning things. Going to
start shadow boxing again in front of the mirror.''
</P>
<P>
   He also will work on his mind, continuing to shoo away thoughts
than anytime he steps into the ring could be the last time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do that anymore,'' he said. ``That only hinders you
from being the very best.''
</P>
<P>
   Against Ruiz, Holyfield was far from his very best. At this
stage, just being better than the other guy is all that counts.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
