<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 20:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0448 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-CAR-GLEN-PARK-TEX     08-13 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-GLEN-PARK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK OUTDUELS MARTIN FOR FIRST WINSTON CUP VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. _ Steve Park and his team spent 76 races and
parts of four years attempting to solve NASCAR's toughest riddle.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying to decipher what it takes to win in Winston
Cup,'' Park said Sunday afternoon. ``It just takes a perfect day, a
perfect car, you've got to drive perfectly and have perfect pit
stops. And if you're lacking one thing, you're not going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Lacking for nothing at Watkins Glen International, Park scored
his breakthrough Cup victory on a day when everything clicked for
the native New Yorker before his home-state fans. Park used a
picture-perfect pit stop to take the lead for the first time from
road-racing ace Mark Martin on Lap 31 of the scheduled 90.
Fittingly, Park was forced to fend off Martin _ a three-time winner
here _ over the final 10 laps en route to victory in the Global
Crossing at The Glen.
</P>
<P>
   The race also saw an unceremonious end to three-time Cup
champion Jeff Gordon's six-race winning streak on road courses,
following heavy contact with the car driven by Tony Stewart and the
Armco guard-rail barrier between turns 3 and 4 on Lap 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to race our guts out to win it, and beat a guy (Martin)
who's known for winning a lot of races on road courses,'' said
Park, whom Martin admittedly tried to lure into a lapse during the
waning laps around the 2.45-mile, 11-turn layout. ``We definitely
weren't a favorite. We had to come from 18th. We had to pass cars
and we had to race to get it. We had to be one of the best to win,
and that just makes it even more rewarding to know we didn't beat
them with fuel mileage or have it be a fluke.''
</P>
<P>
   Park truly earned his first Cup victory, leading a race-high 54
of 90 laps on a track where qualifying had been rained out twice,
and practice was squeezed in between showers both Friday and
Saturday. Until Sunday, the furthest back a winner had started in
the 17-race Cup history at The Glen was 13th, by Rusty Wallace in
1989 and Geoffrey Bodine in 1996. And Park's margin of victory over
Martin, 0.384 seconds, eclipsed the former record of 0.440 seconds
between native New Yorker Bodine and runner-up Terry Labonte in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Park, whose car is owned by seven-time Cup champion Dale
Earnhardt, posted his fifth top-10 finish of the season and first
top-10 in four races at WGI. His previous best Cup finish here was
12th in 1999. But Park, a 32-year-old resident of East Northport,
N.Y., has enjoyed a career full of success at this track in
NASCAR's Featherlite Modified, Busch North, Craftsman Truck and
Busch Grand National series.
</P>
<P>
   Park's familiarity with the track paid off against Martin and
his Roush Racing teammate, Jeff Burton, as that threesome dominated
the parade over the final 40 laps. Burton tried to muscle Park out
of the lead with a fender on a restart at Lap 71, but Park held his
ground. Martin worked his way past Burton on Lap 79, and had 10
laps to reel Park in. With five laps remaining, Martin was within
three car-lengths of Park and the No. 1 Pennzoil Chevrolet Monte
Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to try to pass him anywhere I could,'' said
Martin, the winner here in 1993, '94 and '95 and driver of the No.
6 Valvoline Ford Taurus. ``When we really turned it up and put the
pressure on him, he withstood the pressure and never made a slip. I
never got alongside of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, meanwhile, was compelled to almost apologize for his
career-best road-course third-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Mark got by me, he just left me,'' said Burton, driver of
the No. 88 Exide Batteries Ford. ``I guess I was holding him up.
When he drove away from me so fast, my heart sank because I thought
I cost him a win. But I knew it would be hard for anybody to beat
Steve because his car sat real flat on the track. It didn't roll
much. When he got in the gas, it hooked up and turned real well.''
</P>
<P>
   In becoming the 13th different winner in 21 events this year,
Park averaged 91.336 mph in a race that took 2 hours, 24 minutes
and 51 seconds to complete.
</P>
<P>
   After taking the checkered flag, Park saluted his fans by
driving to the middle of the frontstretch and climbing onto the
roof of his yellow-and-black car. The celebration will continue all
week at Dale Earnhardt Inc. in Mooresville, N.C., where Park's team
flag will be flown in front of the sprawling race shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an honor,'' Park said. ``And Dale is going to buy lunch
for everybody this week. That's another perk we have for winning.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
