<SLUG> BC-DEM-DELEGATES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELEGATES MORE LIBERAL THAN THEIR FELLOW DEMOCRATS, POLL SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM CLYMER With MARJORIE CONNELLY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Democratic delegates arriving here to nominate
Vice President Al Gore for president think of themselves as
moderates, but their views on issues from affirmative action to an
activist federal government are more liberal than those of the
public or even Democratic voters generally, a New York Times/CBS
News Poll shows.
</P>
<P>
   On one issue, the death penalty, a random sample of 1,042 of the
4,339 delegates was decisively more liberal than Gore himself,
though 56 percent said they were moderates. Asked to choose between
the death penalty and life in prison without parole, only 20
percent of the delegates preferred executions, compared to 46
percent of Democrats generally and 51 percent of the public. Gore
supports capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth R. Moore, a 72-year-old delegate from Sun Lake, Ariz.,
explained that attitude. He said: ``I've gone 180 degrees on the
death penalty. I used to favor it. But with the questionable
executions recently, particularly with the mentally retarded, I
Just can't support the death penalty without standards that require
absolute proof and an adequate defense. Without that, there is no
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   The ideological distance between the Democratic delegates and
their rank and file was similar to the gap displayed two weeks ago
in Philadelphia, where Republican delegates were strikingly more
conservative than ordinary Republicans or ordinary Americans _ and
such gaps have been found at past conventions.
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty is an example of Democratic delegates being
distant from public attitudes. Occasionally, though, they were
closer than Republicans were. For example, 63 percent of Democratic
delegates and 64 percent of the American public, agreed with the
statement: ``We must protect the environment even if it means jobs
in your community are lost because of it.'' Only 32 percent of
Republican delegates did.
</P>
<P>
   Donna I. King, a delegate from Norwalk, Conn., explained her
view Sunday: ``Now is the right time to focus on the environment.
The economy is strong, unemployment is low. Address this issue in
the best of times, and focus on inspection, regulation and
enforcement.''
</P>
<P>
   One distinct difference between the Democratic and Republican
delegates was their confidence about the election. Only 51 percent
of the Democrats said Gore was the favorite in their state, and in
fact just 27 percent called him a big favorite. Among Republicans,
68 percent said Gov. George W. Bush of Texas was a favorite in
their state and 44 percent said that he had a big edge. The
Democratic poll had a margin of sampling error of plus or minus 3
percentage points; the survey of Republicans had plus or minus 2.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the interviewing of the delegates was conducted in
July, with no more than a few dozen interviews conducted after the
selection of Sen. Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut as Gore's running
mate. That selection plainly made some delegates more hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   Rosemary Trump, a labor organizer from Murrysville, Pa., who had
called the Pennsylvania race a ``toss-up,'' said the Lieberman
choice ``will have a big impact.'' She said, ``It's going to be a
close election here in Pennsylvania, but this will energize those
of us who feel empowered by this choice to work even harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen W. Long, a lawyer from Crestwood, Ky., had also called
his state a toss-up. He said: ``Lieberman being a moderate helps
him here in Kentucky. I don't think the Jewish factor will be a
problem at all here. His stances on taxes and education exemplify
what Gore has been standing for and also strengthen Gore's
personality as a `straight shooter.'''
</P>
<P>
   The surveys also showed major differences of sex, race and
income in the two groups of delegates. Forty-eight percent of the
Democrats are women, compared to 35 percent of the Republicans.
Nineteen percent of the Democratic delegates, like 19 percent of
Democratic voters, are black; 4 percent of Republican delegates and
2 percent of Republican voters are.
</P>
<P>
   While only 19 percent of all voters said their family incomes
exceeded $75,000 last year, 57 percent of the Democratic delegates
and 67 percent of the Republican delegates did. And 17 percent of
Republican delegates, compared to 6 percent of Democrats, would not
answer the question. Almost twice as many Republicans, 23 percent
to 12 percent for Democrats, called themselves millionaires.
Thirty-one percent of Democratic delegates said they belonged to a
labor union; only 4 percent of Republicans did. The median age of
Democratic delegates was 51; for Republicans it was 53.
</P>
<P>
   There was also one major similarity on issues. Sixty-four
percent of the public, with insignificant differences between
Republicans and Democrats, said they thought the large unregulated
contributions from companies, unions and rich people known as soft
money should be banned. Neither set of delegates was in step with
those attitudes. Republican delegates wanted them permitted, by 65
to 24 percent; Democratic delegates were split, with 44 percent
wanting them allowed and 47 percent calling for a ban.
</P>
<P>
   But more often one party or the other proved out of step with
its own voters or the public. On affirmative action for minorities,
83 percent of Democratic delegates said they favored it, compared
to just 51 percent of the public generally and 29 percent of
Republican delegates. Deborah Goldberg, a Democratic delegate from
Farmington, Mich., explained, ``As long as there is discrimination,
there should be affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic delegates strongly opposed tuition vouchers for
private or religious schools, by 86 percent to 10 percent. Ordinary
Democrats were opposed, too, but only by 54 percent to 16 percent,
and the public was about evenly split, with 47 percent in favor and
46 percent against. But Republican delegates, who favored them by
71 percent to 20 percent, were almost as far out of step with the
public uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic delegates were much closer to public attitudes than
Republican delegates on questions of increasing safety and
environmental regulation of business and requiring trigger locks on
handguns. But while 73 percent of Democratic delegates said the
government should do more to solve national problems, only 33
percent of the public did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
