<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME PROGRESS IN PHONE STRIKE, BUT AGREEMENT PROVES ELUSIVE
</HEADLINE>
  By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A quick end to the strike by more than 86,000 employees of
Verizon Communications, the nation's largest telecommunications
employer, appeared out of the grasp of negotiators Sunday after
unions rejected parts of the company's latest proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon made a new contract offer at 1 a.m. Sunday that did not
overcome the unions' objections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is old wine in new bottles,'' said Robert Master, a
spokesman for the Communications Workers of America, which
represents the majority of the striking workers.
</P>
<P>
   The communications workers' union and the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, which represent Verizon
employees in 12 Eastern states and Washington, D.C., are still at
odds with the company on issues like mandatory overtime, stress
levels and the movement of work resulting from Bell Atlantic's $72
billion acquisition of GTE, which formed Verizon.
</P>
<P>
   Still, progress was made in establishing a framework for a
contract for several dozen employees of Verizon's wireless unit.
And both sides agree that perhaps the main stumbling block to an
agreement was overcome last week in an understanding that would
allow unions to organize more easily at Verizon Wireless.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the strike illustrates an effort by organized labor
to find its footing in the high-technology industries that are
reshaping the economy. Instead of wages and benefits, the main
objectives of the strike involve an effort to gain a union foothold
in new areas and secure concessions for a work force weary of long
hours and the concern that mergers might translate into fewer jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Optimism over Verizon's concession in the wireless area gave way
over the weekend to feelings among negotiators that a fast
resolution to the strike, which is entering its ninth day, has
become more remote.
</P>
<P>
   The main remaining difference between the two sides concerns the
movement of work resulting from the Bell Atlantic-GTE merger.
</P>
<P>
   The unions are seeking to limit the movement of jobs or tasks by
agreeing on a flat percentage of Verizon's work force of 260,000
employees that would be subject to such movement, similar to the
half a percentage point agreed upon with Bell Atlantic after it
bought Nynex in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon, though, wants a more flexible agreement that would
limit movement of work by measuring it in net additions or
subtractions within a given region.
</P>
<P>
   In one part of Verizon's offer, the company proposed limiting
the number of employees who could transfer from stressful jobs at
call centers to other parts of the company. The unions said this
proposal would actually make matters worse.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the union reiterated concern over Verizon's move to
expand in the high-speed Internet access business by acquiring
NorthPoint Communications. Verizon told the unions about 300
union-represented jobs would be shifted into the NorthPoint
operation, but details involving the outsourcing of related tasks
remained blurry, a person close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Although an overall agreement is within reach, both sides
acknowledged that little progress was made over the weekend. If the
walkout drags on, the communications workers' union said it would
start using its $400 million strike fund on the 15th day of the
strike.
</P>
<P>
   The fund would pay its members $200 a week. If the strike were
to last a month, the amount each member would receive rises to $300
a week.
</P>
<P>
   Verizon said it had 90,000 repair requests Sunday, up from about
80,000 during most days last week, although the company attributed
the increase to rainstorms that knocked out service in parts of
several Eastern states. Meanwhile, the number of pickets thinned to
about 750 Sunday, down from the thousands at Verizon sites each day
last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
