<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FROM THE PAPER OF MONDAY, AUGUST 14 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Monday. Days and dates refer to the original article's transmission
by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be adjusted by
NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-ITALY-HEIR-NYT (moved Monday, August 7)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, August 7
about Prince Emanuele Filiberto di Sa-voia, the exiled heir to the
Italian throne, who is campaigning for the right to visit his
homeland, misstated the relationship of two members of the Savoy
dynasty. Mafalda was the daughter, not the sister, of King Vittorio
Emanuele III.
</P>
<P>
   BC-POLO-APPAREL-NYT (moved Thursday, August 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, August
10 about a dispute between Polo Ralph Lauren and Jordache misstated
the settlement date of a legal battle between Jordache and a rival
jeans maker, Guess. It was 1990, not 1980.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CLIBURN-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT (moved Sunday, August 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, August 6
about Van Cliburn's piano performance at Tanglewood with the Boston
Symphony Orchestra misstated the year in which he won the
Tchaikovsky Competition in Moscow. It was 1958, not 1968.
</P>
<P>
   BC-ART-COLONY-CLOSE-NYT (moved Sunday, August 6)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, August 6
about the Institute on the Arts and Civic Dialogue, a performing
program at Harvard founded by the playwright Anna Deavere Smith,
referred imprecisely to its end. It has closed, at least for now,
because its three-year grant will expire this year, not because its
offerings did not rally audiences.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYT (moved Wednesday, August 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service Circuits article sent on
Wednesday, August 9 about purchasing a computer to take to college
misstated the model number of an I.B.M. laptop being offered for
sale to freshmen at the University of North Carolina. It is the
ThinkPad A20M, not the 820M.
</P>
