<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0455 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-FLORIDA0814-COX     08-13 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FLORIDA0814-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gators hope to get back on track
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ The record shows that Florida did play for
the SEC football championship last December. Still, it was not a
very pleasant offseason here in Gator Country.
</P>
<P>
   For coach Steve Spurrier, 1999 provided way too many ``firsts''
in his successful decade as the head ball coach in Gainesville:
</P>
<P>
   Florida ended the season with consecutive losses to No. 1
Florida State, Alabama in the SEC championship game, and Michigan
State in the Citrus Bowl. That marked the first time Spurrier had
lost three straight games at Florida.
</P>
<P>
   With a 9-4 record, Florida failed to win 10 games in a season
for the first time since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Florida failed to finish in the final Associated Press top 10
for the first time since 1990, Spurrier's first year as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Florida lost twice (Alabama, Florida State) last season at home
in Ben Hill Griffin Stadium, a.k.a., the Swamp. That was a first.
Florida had lost only a total of twice at home in the previous nine
seasons (Florida State 1993, Auburn 1994).
</P>
<P>
   Around the SEC, the whispers began. Had Florida, which won five
SEC championships from 1991-96, merely hit a bump in the road? Or,
after going three straight years without a conference title, were
the Gators beginning to lose their bite?
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier put his players and his coaching staff on notice not
long after the season ended. Florida would get back on top in the
SEC, he told them, and everyone in the room would be held
accountable for doing their part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh it was clear,'' defensive coordinator Jon Hoke said. ``As
always, he said `it starts with me.' But everybody knew what he
meant. We were all going to be held accountable and that's the way
it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   So it was no coincidence that Florida went out last February and
signed what is arguably the best recruiting class in Spurrier's 11
years in Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   ``In retrospect, we probably got out of last season what we
deserved and it probably helped us in recruiting,'' said Spurrier,
who has won 102 games in 10 seasons at Florida. ``I think some of
those freshmen thought the mighty Gators weren't so mighty anymore
and they could step right in and play.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Spurrier now believes Florida was lulled into a
false-sense of security last season by its 23-21 win over Tennessee
in Gainesville. In that game, Florida won despite committing five
turnovers and having two touchdowns called back for penalties.
Those kind of mistakes would plague Florida the entire season. The
Gators had 15 penalties against Florida State and kept two Seminole
drives alive by simply lining up offsides.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Spurrier says he won't do as much yelling this
season. He'll just have another player ready to go if the first guy
keeps messing up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to make sure the players play the way they
are coached,'' Spurrier said. ``It's no disgrace to lose a game if
a guy just outplays you. But to lose with all those mental errors,
that's embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He got our attention in the spring, that's for sure,'' said
quarterback Jesse Palmer. ``There is no excuse for all the mistakes
we made last season.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida will be better in 2000 because the defense will be
better. A year ago the Gators were inconsistent on defense, showing
flashes of greatness (Tennessee) followed by inexplicable lapses
(Alabama twiships when they have a big-time tailback (i.e. Errict
Rhett, Fred Taylor) to control the ball in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier concedes the Gators haven't been as talented as 1995
and 1996, when they played for the national championship. But just
hang on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it will be this year, but we'll get there,''
Spurrier said. ``I believe we'll get it back to where it used to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
