u p BC-DEM-SHADOW-CONVENTION     08-13 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-SHADOW-CONVENTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHADOW CONVENTION' ADDS A BIT OF STAR POWER TO ITS POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  By   BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Let's get serious! That's what Arianna Huffington
_pundit, gadfly, author, party-giver, intellectual and, yes, enigma
_ &UR;  &LR; proclaimed as her ``Shadow Convention'' opened Sunday night at
Patriotic Hall on Figueroa Street, not far from that other
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We created this because of the vacuum created by the
Democratic and Republican conventions _ &UR;  &LR; they've drained all the
politics out of the conventions and turned them into floor shows
and charades!'' Huffington exclaimed. ``Look at what's happening
Wednesday night at the Democratic convention. The theme is the Vice
President as the principled fighter of special interests. Give me a
break. The convention has lost any grounding in reality.''
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, Huffington, who was born in Greece, educated in
England and spent several years with her millionaire former
husband, Michael Huffington, in Houston and Washington, perfectly
embodies her new hometown, Los Angeles. The 50-year-old author, and
sometime Republican, had hardly fit into the stuffy Georgetown
social strictures in Washington &UR; .  &LR;  Like many in Los Angeles, she's
constantly re-inventing herself.
</P>
<P>
   On one level the ``Shadow Convention'' seems very serious. There
are sessions on drugs, poverty and, what she termed, ``the
corruption of money in politics.'' One session will deal with gun
violence and communities poisoned by pesticides _ issues that,
Huffington said, are being avoided by the Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've cleaned up the streets of the homeless, they're
holding the convention in the poverty capital of the U.S. but not
talking about the poor. They're holding an invitation-only golf
tournament at the Riviera Country Club,'' she said, referring to a
glitzy and hugely-expensive golf club in the Pacific Palisades.
``They give nothing but lip service to the real problems we're
facing.''
</P>
<P>
   At another level, though, the convention's agenda is marked by
some silliness, intentional or not.
</P>
<P>
   Not only will Bill Maher, host of ``Politically Incorrect,''
where Huffington frequently appears, play an important role, but
pundits like Christopher Hitchens (The Nation, Vanity Fair) &UR; ,  &LR; 
Robert Scheer (The Los Angeles Times) &UR; ,  &LR;  Jonathan Alter (Newsweek)
and Norman Orenstein (The American Enterprise Institute) will
weigh-in with their Really Important Thoughts. What convention or
media gathering is possible without hearing from these savants? At
the finale of the Democratic convention journalists will be joined
by _ who else? _ Roseanne.
</P>
<P>
   Because the convention is in Los Angeles, Huffington seemed
fully aware that a bit of glitz (her pal, Warren Beatty, may show
up) as well as shallowness are necessary to lure crowds and,
especially, newspaper and television coverage. She said happily
that, during the Republican convention in Philadelphia, newspapers
like The Boston Globe and The Philadelphia Inquirer wrote about her
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see the shadow conventions as part of building a movement
that will force the two parties to change, in the same way that the
civil rights movement forced change within the Government.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course the civil rights movement did not include Roseanne.
Or, for that matter, Arianna Huffington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0459 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-13 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BILL'S THIRD ACCEPTANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ My Fellow Democrats:
</P>
<P>
   After that rousing eight-minute demonstration, I accept your
love. I accept your appreciation for triangulating you out of the
Carter-Mondale-Dukakis wilderness and back into the White House for
eight glorious years. And were it not for that damnable two-term
amendment the Republicans put through to get even with FDR, tonight
I would be saying, ``I accept your renomination!''
</P>
<P>
   That's how I'd like to start my valedictory speech. And then
there are a few other things I wish I could say.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrition business, I'd like to tell Bush and Cheney
where to get off with all their barbs about ``restoring honor and
dignity'' and other code words condemning my private life. But that
line of attack from me would play into their hands.
</P>
<P>
   So I'll choke back my feelings and pretend to be grateful to Joe
Lieberman for calling me to moral account on the Senate floor.
That'll get a big hand; We can't let the Pat Robertson crowd
out-God us. And at least Joe voted right on acquittal.
</P>
<P>
   I showed the other day how I can smother my detractors with
gratitude. My best line to my pastor in Illinois: ``If I hadn't
been knocked down the way I was, and forced to come to grips with
what I'd done and the consequences of it in such an awful way, I
might not ever have had to really deal with it 100 percent.'' Thank
you, Ken Starr and Henry Hyde, for forcing me to deal with it.
Beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   And the convention will tear the place apart if I thank the
two-thirds of the American people for sticking by me in my toughest
time. My personal purging process is not a subject Al wants me to
touch on at a convention that is supposed to be all about him, but
I know what's best for me. And what's best for me is best for him
because this election is about me.
</P>
<P>
   I won't let on about that, of course; I have to say every
election is about the future. But I'll look back, bragging on the
good times, claiming my tax increase in '93 was responsible for all
the prosperity and surpluses today. I'll blame the Democrats' loss
of the House on that unpopular party-line vote, even though
everybody in the hall who lost will know the reason was our
health-care fiasco.
</P>
<P>
   My theme will be the tried-and-true ``You Never Had It So
Good,'' backed up with a pile of facts and figures _ 22 million
jobs! Crime down! Stock market up! _ followed by the fearsome
``Don't Let Them Take It Away.'' Look, maybe we had nothing to do
with prosperity, but if we were in a depression, who would be
getting the blame?
</P>
<P>
   Looking into my own soul, I confess I'm torn. The good part of
me wants Al Gore to win because it would validate my eight years
and show the American people saying, ``We want to give Bill Clinton
a third term.'' On the other hand, the bad boy in me wants him to
lose, to show the Democrats how much they needed me personally to
drag them in and keep them in.
</P>
<P>
   Even more conflicted are my feelings about Hillary's New York
bid. I want her to win because I owe her for all that forgiving and
because she's a backup for my validation in case Al can't make it
without me. But my bad side says if she loses, she'll realize who
the only winner is in this family. Plus which, she wouldn't be able
to get on her high horse and have all that fun in the Washington I
brought her to.
</P>
<P>
   No _ get thee behind me, Satan _ I want Hillary to beat that
pushover unknown, really I do. For six years, ever since her
health-bill fiasco, we've been assuring everybody she hasn't been
affecting presidential policy, especially about the Palestinians.
But the new line is that the opposite was true, that she was deeply
involved in all sorts of big decisions. Look, whichever she wants _
strictly first lady or co-president _ I can teach it either way.
</P>
<P>
   So I'll stand up there for my Third Acceptance and wow 'em by
taking full credit for everything good that's happened in eight
great years. Let Al play Mr. Nice Guy if he likes; I'll be that old
lovable rogue who can make a centrist waffle look like red meat.
I'll make the Democrats miss my charm. I'll scare the viewers with
the prospect of Bush, backward economics and back-alley abortions,
and I'll stupefy my enemies with great globs of gratitude.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton fatigue? Not when I'm finished. Tonight is the first
night of Clinton nostalgia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
