<HEADER>
A0462 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JOHNSON-2TAKES-NY     08-13 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JOHNSON-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLAYER WHO SOARS WITH THE MOUTH THAT ROARS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., N.Y., W.Va., Calif.)   By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The offense of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers hit a
small lull last week during a dreary preseason game against Miami.
Suddenly, wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson, always the life of the
party or the huddle, saw something that would perk things up.
Dolphins cornerback Jerry Wilson, barely 5 feet 10 inches, was
guarding, all by himself, the 6-4 Johnson. The best defensive backs
in the game, some built like small forwards, have a difficult time
matching up with Johnson's combination of power and size.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson did not know it yet, but he was in big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Inside Johnson's head an alarm went off, and his heart began
racing. Johnson trotted back to the huddle and looked at
quarterback Shaun King, who speaks softly compared to Johnson, who
is a 15-piece orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my goodness, Jerry Wilson is on me,'' Johnson told King.
``Get me the ball. Let's move the chains.''
</P>
<P>
   The next few plays could not have been more predictable. Johnson
beat Wilson rather easily _ several times, in fact. But Wilson
should not feel bad. Johnson, over the course of his four-year
career with the Jets, bruised the egos of many cornerbacks. That is
why the Buccaneers reached deep into their wallets _ and their
draft-day goody bag _ to pay Johnson $56 million over the next
eight years. The team traded away two first-round picks to get him.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was an expensive acquisition, but one Tampa Bay needed,
because its passing offense last season _ when the Bucs went to the
National Football Conference championship game _ was ranked next to
last in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keyshawn gives us some identity on offense,'' said Warren
Sapp, a team leader and one of the best defensive linemen in
football. ``We should put some points on the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson did not leave New York quietly. He accused Jets Coach Al
Groh of engineering the trade, and absolved Bill Parcells, the
team's chief of football operations. Johnson recently tossed one
more grenade at Groh when he said in an interview: ``No, I don't
like Al Groh. I did like him. I don't now. The way he handled the
situation. There was a lack of communication on his part and he
displayed poor judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson gives Tampa Bay something the team has not had in years,
maybe ever _ a wideout who blasts off like a rocket every time he
leaves the line of scrimmage and can single-handedly change a game.
With the addition of Johnson, and with awesome talent like Sapp and
the Pro Bowl fullback Mike Alstott, along with one of the best
young coaches in the game in Tony Dungy, the Buccaneers are favored
by many to reach the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But Tampa Bay did not sign Johnson simply for his talent. The
Buccaneers also liked Johnson's attitude. And when it comes to
attitude, Johnson's mouth runneth over. His brashness and
rambunctious nature make him so very good. Away from the field,
they make him so very quotable. He is the player who soars with the
mouth that roars.
</P>
<P>
   The latter was never more apparent when Johnson sat down for an
interview over the weekend, and the main topic was his former team,
the Jets, a subject that still gets his blood pumping all these
months later. Some of Johnson's comments will certainly rile his
old pals, as he went on at length about:
</P>
<P>
   -- Wayne Chrebet. Their relationship became strained after
Johnson called Chrebet a ``team mascot'' in his book. A Jets player
said that the real rub between the two stemmed from Johnson's
belief that Chrebet receives extensive attention in the news media
because he is white.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a secret,'' Johnson said. He later added: ``The
better question to ask is: Are there other people who can do what
he does? Yeah. I can get a dozen of them right now, from Jackson
State, from Morgan State, from Grambling, from Southern, from
Howard.'' Johnson used traditionally black colleges as his example.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could really care less if he is black or white,'' Johnson
said. ``The only thing that I have a problem with is when people
try to compare us when there is no comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also said that another reason for Chrebet's popularity
was his status as a local player from Hofstra University in
Hempstead, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A Jets spokesman said Sunday that Chrebet was not available for
comment because it was an off-day for the players. When asked
earlier this month what training camp has been like without
Johnson, Chrebet said, ``Quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   -- Bill Parcells. Johnson believes that if Parcells were still
on the sideline, Johnson, too, would be in New York, because
Parcells would have broken the Jets' tradition of not tearing up an
existing contract with more than a year remaining on it for a new
one. Johnson had two more years left on his deal before he was
traded.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Johnson said, the Jets almost gave him a new deal at
the beginning of his third season. Parcells, according to Johnson,
proposed that Johnson give back a certain amount of money and, in
exchange, the Jets would chop two years off his contract, allowing
Johnson to become a free agent more quickly. The league's
management council rejected the proposal. Parcells has declined to
talk specifically about Johnson's contract.
</P>
<P>
   When Bill Belichick replaced Parcells as coach _ albeit for a
brief period _ he, too, was willing to break with Jets' tradition
and work out a new deal, according to Johnson. Belichick proposed
giving Johnson what amounted to a one-year contract worth $5
million, the receiver said, as a temporary solution until a longer
deal could be reached. But Belichick later resigned from the Jets
and headed for New England. Belichick had no comment on Johnson's
remarks.
</P>
<P>
   -- The spying game. Johnson is the first to speak publicly about
something Jets players have whispered about for years. Johnson said
the team installed an elaborate hidden camera system in the locker
room and weight rooms to spy on the players. Johnson said that he
once, jokingly, made an obscene gesture toward a camera he had
located.
</P>
<P>
   A team spokesman said the organization had no comment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   -- Team focus. Johnson said that some players were too concerned
about things other than winning. ``Some of those guys I just could
not deal with,'' Johnson said, making it clear he was not speaking
of the entire team. ``There were too many guys worried if they had
a commercial.'' Johnson also said a significant number of Jets
players had little interaction off the field.
</P>
<P>
   --Quarterback Ray Lucas. By drafting the rookie Chad Pennington,
the Jets basically signaled the end of the Lucas era. ``If I was
Ray, I would curse out the organization and then play somewhere
else,'' Johnson said, ``because there is no loyalty there.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson maintained that the Jets purposely steered away
potential national news media interviews, as well as lucrative
endorsement deals, as a way to keep his ego in check. Johnson said
that when GQ Magazine once called to schedule an interview, the
team said Johnson was not interested, without first asking Johnson.
A team spokesman said the Jets had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jets executives may not be saying much publicly about Johnson,
but clearly they are tired of hearing him reliving the old days. A
team official said he wished Johnson would ``simply be quiet about
us.'' Johnson said a Jets official he declined to identify relayed
a message on behalf of the team to pipe down.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Johnson, he is being asked by news media
representatives to talk about the Jets, not vice versa. ``Maybe the
Jets should stop worrying about me,'' Johnson said. ``They have
enough to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Johnson's harsh words, which can be both painful and
truthful, overshadow his substance. In many ways, he is an ideal
National Football League player. Johnson is a Pro Bowler, with 31
career touchdowns and more than 4,000 career yards. He owns a
restaurant in Beverly Hills, Calif., his name does not show up on
the police blotter, and his work ethic is renowned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do everything I'm supposed to,'' he said. ``I do not get
into trouble. I work my butt off. That's all I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the high-profile nature of the trade, Johnson may
have a bigger national following than ever before. When President
Clinton visited the Buccaneers training camp recently, one of his
first questions to team officials was ``Where's Keyshawn?''
</P>
<P>
   He is easy to find. He's the one catching all the passes _ and
talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
