<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH DEFENDS CHENEY'S $20 MILLION RETIREMENT PACKAGE AS STANDARD
PRACTICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas)   By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gov. George W. Bush over the weekend defended the
generous retirement package that his running mate, Dick Cheney,
received from his former employer as a standard practice for a
company executive.
</P>
<P>
   But senior Democrats on Sunday derided Bush, the Republican
presidential nominee, for standing behind the settlement when the
Republican-led Congress has resisted increasing the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   After accepting Bush's offer to join him as the
vice-presidential candidate, Cheney resigned as chairman and chief
executive of the Halliburton Co., a Dallas-based energy services
company. Halliburton awarded him a financial settlement worth an
estimated $20 million after five years of service during which he
received about $12.5 million in pay and stock options now worth $39
million.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Los Angeles Times that was published
Sunday, Bush said he was aware that Cheney would receive a
retirement package, as any successful chief executive would. Bush
said: ``I think what you ought to do is ask, `Does the board of
directors know what they are doing? Are they expert? And let the
experts make the decision as to what's fair.'''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for Vice President Al Gore, said the
size of the retirement package and Bush's approval reflects the
close relationship between the Republican Party and big business
that working families might find troublesome.
</P>
<P>
   Dirk Vande Beek, communications director for Cheney, said
critics were making too much of the matter, ``especially when no
one complained about the $200 million compensation package Bob
Rubin got after leaving Goldman-Sachs.''
</P>
<P>
   Juleanna Glover, press secretary for Cheney, said Halliburton
planned to disclose details of the retirement package on Wednesday.
Details of the package Robert E. Rubin received after leaving the
firm he headed to become chairman of President Clinton's National
Economic Council in 1992 could not be independently confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
