<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-CONVENTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVENING DEMOCRATS TO PRESS `ISSUES, NOT IMAGES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN AND SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hoping to boost Vice President Al Gore's chances
of winning the White House in November, Democrats convene to bid
goodbye to President Clinton and to make the case for his
understudy.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the first time the Democratic party has held a
convention in Los Angeles since 1960, when the party nominee was
John F. Kennedy and the talk was of the politics of the ``New
Frontier.''
</P>
<P>
   The weeks's events, organizers say, will focus not so much on
new frontiers but on the familiar, core issues the party believes
will bolster Gore's campaign in the fall election. Among them are
prescription drug coverage for senior citizens, Medicare, Social
Security and the right of patients to sue their health insurance
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our convention, unlike the other party's, will be driven by
issues and not images,'' said Tad Devine, a senior strategist to
the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The message for voters, Devine said, is how far the nation has
travelled over the last eight years and how much is at stake come
November. ``If we make the wrong choice and go down the wrong road,
this nation will suffer,'' Devine said.
</P>
<P>
   As Texas Governor George W. Bush retired to his ranch for a
week's vacation, the Republican nominee's campaign said it was
ready for the Democratic onslaught.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to try to claim credit for our nation's
prosperity and cast blame for those things they didn't get done,''
said Dan Bartlett, a Bush spokesman. ``Governor Bush believes you
had your chance, you didn't lead, we will.''
</P>
<P>
   At the convention, delegates will formally nominate Gore on
Wednesday, and vote to ratify the nomination on Thursday, just
prior to Gore's acceptance speech. Gore's running mate, Connecticut
Senator Joseph I. Lieberman, will address the convention Wednesday,
but will not be formally nominated or voted upon until the next
night.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, however, the spotlight will be on Clinton, the man
who has occupied the Oval Office for the last eight years and hopes
to see his partner in public policy assume the mantle of
commander-in-chief.
</P>
<P>
   Since he arrived here Friday for a round of fund-raising and
golf, Clinton has been giving periodic previews of his speech. For
example, at a star-studded tribute to the president that raised
money for his wife, Hillary, he told the crowd why they should
support Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He understands how to keep this magical prosperity going and
how to spread it to the people that, I regret to say, are still
left behind,'' Clinton told Cher, Diana Ross and a plethora of
A-list celebrities Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want somebody in the White House that understands the
future, because it's really unfolding fast,'' he said. Added
Clinton: ``The best is still out there, and the problems are still
out there, and the challenges are still out there.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday, Clinton attended a brunch hosted by Barbra Streisand
that raised $10 million for his presidential library. It couldn't
be determined if he continued his pitch for Gore, as only the
high-rolling donors behind closed doors could hear what he said.
</P>
<P>
   Amid intense speculation that Clinton's presence could be a
distraction from Gorea at a crucial time for his candidacy, the
vice president assured the Ohio News Network in Cleveland Sunday
that everything would work out fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The convention will be an opportunity for me to introduce
myself for who I am, not as a vice president who stands on stage
without saying too much,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a lot of surprises at the convention,'' he
said. ``We're going to concentrate on substance instead of the
balloons and the confetti.''
</P>
<P>
   As he accepts his party's nomination, Gore said, he will talk
about a middle-class tax cut and Social Security. Aides say he will
also pledge to continue his town-hall meetings with voters across
the country if elected.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show Bush with an edge over Gore at the start of the
convention. But campaign chairman William Daley said he hopes Gore
will draw even by the end of a week of intense media focus.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a year and a half of relentless campaigning by Gore,
Daley said voters are only beginning to take in the election
activity. ``Most people don't pay attention to this stuff,'' Daley
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore has to convey to the American people that as the next
president of the United States, his history qualifies him to be
that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to history, Daley noted that former Vice President
George Bush was in a quandary similar to Gore's in 1988 despite
serving under President Reagan for two terms. ``Most people didn't
know who George Bush was,'' he said. ``He had to introduce himself
in '88 and talk about his history in the war, his heroism, and what
he did in all those offices.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic officials have mocked Gov. Bush's Republican
convention in Philadelphia where blacks, Latinos and women filled
the stage, even as the party advocated policies which Democrats
hold to be at odds with the needs of those groups.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Democratic organizers will make heavy use of
imagery, too. Their roster of speakers include members of almost
every Democratic interest group, from the National Education
Association to the AFL-CIO to National Abortion and Reproductive
Rights Action League. But Devine said the difference is that the
speakers are linked to Gore and Lieberman's plans to fight for
working families.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Cleveland Sunday, Gore hosted a policy-heavy
group chat about children's health care, taking pains not to
criticize his opponent, for his record on health care for children
in his home state of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Gore didn't need to bring up the issue. He had actor-director
Rob Reiner on hand, and Reiner blasted Bush for failing to insure
all eligible children and for presenting the Republican party as
wide-open to diversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to get this off my chest,'' Reiner told parents,
health care workers and ill children at the Rainbow Babies and
Children's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other side talks about being the party of diversity and
the party of inclusion. How do they figure this, unless they define
diversity as two guys at the head of the ticket who are from
different oil companies?''
</P>
<P>
   Reiner was referring to the fact that both Bush and his
running-mate, Dick Cheney, worked for energy companies. Cheney, the
New York Times reported Saturday, received a $20 million retirement
package from his Wyoming company when he resigned to run for vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president outlined his plan to expand the Childrens
Health Insurance Program (CHIP), which pays for health care for
children in poor families. Two million children are insured under
CHIP currently. Gore's proposal, at an estimated cost of $42
billion over ten years, would make another 1 million children
eligible for assistance. There are now 11 million uninsured
children in America, and some of them are already eligible for
CHIP, but states are not reaching out to them, Gore aides said.
</P>
<P>
   States have a great deal of latitude in administering the
program, and some states maker it harder for families to get the
help, Gore said. The states must pay for part of the program.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has enrolled more than 12 percent of eligible children in
the CHIP program, said Bartlett of the Bush campaign. The state got
a late start, since its legislature meets only every other year.
The federal CHIP legislation passed in summer 1997; the Texas
legislature couldn't address it until January of 1999, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Ann Scales and Anne E. Kornblut of the Globe Staff contributed to
this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
