<HEADLINE>
OFF THE WALL: WE DOTH PROTEST NOT ENOUGH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In shrink talk, it's called ``anticipatory
anxiety.''
</P>
<P>
   And according to Dr. Robert R. Butterworth, it's natural that
everyone around here feel this as the demonic Democratic National
Convention begins today in and around Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``With widespread reports of anarchists coming to disrupt the
convention and memories still fresh from the past Lakers
celebrations that turned into a mini-riot, it's no wonder that
people are leaving town, downtown shops are boarding up windows,
army surplus stores report sales of gas masks . . . people are
jumpy,'' the L.A.-based media savvy doc said in a press release
just in case anyone cared about his opinions.
</P>
<P>
   So just how do you equate an Al Gore coronation to a Shaq and
Kobe victory dance?
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if thousands of desperate political nuts are gonna
be partying outside Staples, watching the big video screen as Gore
accepts the nomination _ hey, what happened to Bill Bradley? _ and
then start torchin' police cars.
</P>
<P>
   Protesters? They're harmless. An L.A. form of protest is the
Doo-Dah Parade.
</P>
<P>
   True, with Jerry West gone, Lakers fans have every right to feel
``anticipatory anxiety.'' But as for the rest of the city, try
calling it anticipatory apathy. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Mitch Kupchak should already get exec of the year for swaying
Kendall Gill to stay in Jersey with that insulting $2.25 mil slot
offer. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ From a list of the ``50 Most Annoying Things Ever'' in the
September issue of Stuff For Men mag, ``Kobe, the rapper'' made No.
39 and ``Phil Jackson and all his damn rings'' slid in at No. 30. .
. .
</P>
<P>
   __ Los Angeles magazine, page 48: There's a snapshot of PhilJax
and his main squeeze at a Playboy Mansion shindig, for those who
need a visual aid. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ If Alvin Gentry was the answer, where has he been hiding all
this time? . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Keanu Reeves, who not even Gene Hackman could rescue in ``The
Replacements,'' was escorted away from Comiskey Park the other day
for scalping tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Then security figured out the fledgling method actor was just
doing research for the role he'll attempt to play in his next
moving picture, ``Hardball.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ By the way, hang onto that $8.50 you're thinking of spending
on ``The Replacements'' and use it on Denzel Washington's
``Remember the Titans,'' which comes out in late September. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ That's the same D'zel who has been asked if he's interested
in buying into the CBA. Better to ask Spike Lee, who not only has
game, but more disposable income. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ The last five NFL teams that changed the design of their
uniforms have made the playoffs in the first year of their new
look. Which gives an edge to the New York Giants and New England
Patriots, and assures the Rams won't collapse. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ If it matters, don't let Morris Engleberg handle your
personal matters. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ An Olympic Summer Game without Karch Kiraly? Impossible. . .
.
</P>
<P>
   __ And today in Morgantown, W.Va., they're renaming a street
after Jerry West, one that runs through through the college town
and leads to the University of West Virginia basketball arena.
</P>
<P>
   The road reportedly is actually paved. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
