<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0473 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-PROTEST-ART-NYT &LR;      08-13 0443
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-PROTEST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON EVE OF CONVENTION, PROTESTERS DEMAND NEW TRIAL FOR ABU-JAMAL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Tenn., Md.)   (ART ADV: Photos NYT16, NYT17 and NYT18 are being sent to NYT
photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DON TERRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ More than 3,500 protesters, ranging from gay
rights to animal rights activists, marched through Los Angeles
Sunday, the eve of the Democratic National Convention, demanding
the end of capital punishment and a new trial for a death row
inmate, the convicted murderer Mumia Abu-Jamal.
</P>
<P>
   After two hours of music, poetry and speeches at a rally
downtown condemning the death penalty and ``corporate greed,'' the
demonstrators marched for about a mile under a blazing sun along
downtown streets, lined with police officers guarding stores and
office buildings, to the heavily guarded Staples Center, the site
of the convention and the home of the city's basketball and hockey
teams. Once at the Staples Center, there was more music, poetry and
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Abu-Jamal, a former radio journalist, has been on Pennsylvania's
death row since his 1982 conviction for killing a Philadelphia
police officer. Jamal's supporters around the world say he deserves
a new trial. His detractors say he is a ``cold-blooded cop
killer,'' who turned a young bride into a widow.
</P>
<P>
   His case has become an international cause, and for many
protesters he has become the face of death row.
</P>
<P>
   The rally at the downtown square took on aspects of a festival
and a funeral. Speaker after speaker reminded the crowd that time
was running out for Abu-Jamal.
</P>
<P>
   The actor Ed Asner, a longtime foe of capital punishment, said:
``We must fight the establishment, and we must fight the press.
This fight is for the nation's soul. Mumia must not die.''
</P>
<P>
   Scores of police officers quietly stood by on the edge of the
square named in honor of the World War I general, John J.
``Blackjack'' Pershing. Dozens of officers on motorcycles were
stationed on nearby streets, and Joe R. Hicks, executive director
of the city's Human Relations Commission, and his staff wandered
through the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Pam Africa, a leader of the effort to win Abu-Jamal a new trial,
came to Los Angeles from Philadelphia, where she also organized a
similar demonstration in that city during the Republican
convention. ``We're here to educate people,'' she said. ``A lot of
people just vote blindly. We want people to know that when it comes
to capital punishment, there is no difference between the Democrats
and the Republicans. They're both killers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
