u s BC-BOX-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-13 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Holyfield feat more like Hollywood farce
</P>
<P>
   By JOHN P. LOPEZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   There were days when a heavyweight fight meant something, when a
nation collectively stood up and gasped with anticipation and awe
at the spectacle of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Many of us remember those days, because they weren't so long
ago. Maybe we sat on lawn chairs on the front porch with our dads,
a freshly popped bag of popcorn between us, nervously staring at
the radio as voices from Zaire gave us unforgettable blow-by-blow
accounts of the Muhammad Ali-George Foreman ``Rumble in the
Jungle.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we staked out seats at a nearby theater for closed-circuit
broadcasts of Ali-Leon Spinks, marveling at the larger-than-life
figures before us when the great one took an unprecedented third
world title.
</P>
<P>
   They were special moments in sports. They were exciting,
thrilling days when heavyweights were kings. But they're gone now,
and probably, they're gone forever.
</P>
<P>
   Most of us couldn't have cared less Saturday night when Evander
Holyfield topped Ali's record of winning the heavyweight crown on
three separate occasions by winning a fourth crown _ the WBA's
version of this alphabet-soup mess. Holyfield decisioned someone
named John Ruiz, but the fight was sluggish, lightly attended,
hardly sold on pay-per-view, and, typical for this era of boxing,
the decision was a joke.
</P>
<P>
   One judge scored Holyfield the winner 116-112, which might have
been the right score, but only if Ruiz had been ruled the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Was anyone surprised? Did anyone care?
</P>
<P>
   This is a sport that has given us maybe the greatest athlete and
most captivating sports personality of the 20th century in Ali.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent years the heavyweight division has dwindled badly
through a series of controversial decisions, overrated fighters,
bitten ears, threats to eat someone else's children, contrived
contenders, shady promoters, out-of-shape fighters, cable networks
(HBO, Showtime) shamelessly one-sided toward fighters in their
stable, over-the-hill names from the past, and daughters of the
kings _ Joe Frazier, Foreman and Ali _ staging glorified scuffles.
</P>
<P>
   The saddest part is that the fighters, those great figures of
bygone days, have been replaced by mere puppets for promoters like
Don King and Bob Arum. Holyfield included.
</P>
<P>
   The only reason Holyfield ``earned'' Saturday's WBA shot was
because King manipulated the Holyfield-Lennox Lewis contract of
last November to include Ruiz _ surprise, surprise, he's a King
fighter _ as a mandatory opponent for the Holyfield-Lewis winner.
</P>
<P>
   When Lewis, an Arum fighter, won the decision, he promptly
refused to fight Ruiz and ultimately was stripped of the WBA crown.
Holyfield, another King man, stepped in, and King ranted as only he
can about the beauty of Holyfield's earning another shot at the
crown.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a farce, much like the entire division and much of
the sport has become. The window into boxing's crumbling world
never became more clear than in Saturday's undercard, which was
supposed to feature hard-hitting welterweight James Page against a
quality contender.
</P>
<P>
   But when Page signed with rap music mogul James Prince, King
became so outraged he scratched other big names and forced Page to
fight the virtually unknown Andrew ``Six Heads'' Lewis. Don't ask.
</P>
<P>
   Everything legitimate about the sport is gone. When the public
showed an enormous amount of sense by not buying into the Holyfield
hype, King spent the majority of the final week before fight night
pumping Christy ``The Coal Miner's Daughter'' Martin, who also was
featured on the undercard.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't sell, either.
</P>
<P>
   Where once there was Frazier, Foreman, Ali captivating the
masses, now there are people known as ``Butterbean'' drawing only
casual interest.
</P>
<P>
   The championships are splintered, the contenders are either
has-beens or never-will-bes, and the rankings and matches are
manipulated by promoters.
</P>
<P>
   Quick, name just two of the WBC's top-10 heavyweight contenders
outside of Holyfield and Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Did you forget Kirk Johnson, Wladimir Klitschko, Oleg Maskaeve
and Henry Akinwande? No one can blame you.
</P>
<P>
   The heavyweight division has become a pathetic charade. It's
sad, and there are only two ways the sport will become legitimate
again.
</P>
<P>
   As much trouble as players associations can cause in team
sports, boxing needs some sort of athletes' organization that could
sort through the farce and demand honest matches and true
champions. It won't happen as long as the likes of King and Arum
run the show.
</P>
<P>
   The other chance at getting back the sport is ours. Don't buy
into the farce.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, few fight fans did. Maybe there's still hope.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
