u p BC-CLINTON-REAGAN-NYT     08-13 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REAGAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS FROM REAGAN FOR CLINTON IN PASSING THE TORCH 
</HEADLINE>
  By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When you watch President Clinton at the Democratic
convention, it may look like he is stealing President Ronald
Reagan's script from 1988. As Reagan did then, Clinton plans to
officially bless his No. 2 on Monday evening. And as Reagan did
then, Clinton is expected to implore Americans to build on the
triumphs of the current administration.
</P>
<P>
   As was the case 12 years ago, members of the party faithful are
a bit edgy about their ticket and grouse that their new standard
bearer is not nearly as dynamic as the man he wants to replace.
While Reagan savored a 54 percent job approval rating in the New
York Times/CBS News Poll on the eve of his party's convention in
1988 _ impressive for a lame duck _ Clinton's stands even higher at
61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the apparent similarities, the two presidents could
not have handled their valedictory appearances any differently.
While Bill and Hillary Rodham Clinton have been roundly accused of
hogging the spotlight from his vice president, Reagan drew plaudits
for how he choreographed the passing of power in his party.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton popped up in Los Angeles on Friday for
fund-raising events and appearances that drowned out the attention
_ and complicated fund-raising _ for Al Gore, Reagan did not arrive
in New Orleans until the Sunday before the convention eight years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan pulled off what was widely described as a sentimental,
nostalgic and certainly graceful journey. He was greeted at a rally
in New Orleans to shouts of ``Four More Years! Four More Years!''
Delegates wiped tears from their eyes as the president at the
convention hailed the party for lighting ``a prairie fire'' that he
said transformed the nation. He promised never to bid a final
goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the gossip among delegates, lobbyists and
hangers-on here was whether Clinton would  &UR; ever  &LR; _ or even should _
say goodbye.
</P>
<P>
   Even as they acknowledge that Clinton is dominating the ramp up
to the convention, many delegates sounded wistful about his leaving
the White House. Some said they did not view Gore as alluring a
leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that if there were not term limits, Bill Clinton
would be running for president again,'' said Martha Aasen, a
delegate from Westport, Conn. ``Gore doesn't turn me on. He's
different. He's sincere. He knows the issues, but he's different.''
</P>
<P>
   She was glad, she said, that Gore was not speaking until three
days after Clinton, so there would not be back-to-back comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Short, a delegate from Detroit, took issue with those who
are eager for Clinton to leave. ``He's still the president and has
every right to be here,'' he said. ``He raises a lot of money that
other Democrats are certainly willing to take. Let's not beat the
guy up for his mistakes in the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference, of course, between the Clinton and Reagan models
is that while Vice President George Bush tried to distance himself
from Reagan on the Iran-Contra case, he did not have to worry about
being connected to anything approaching the embarrassment of
Clinton's personal scandals. So Gore is faced with the far more
confounding task of trying to take credit for the booming economy
encouraged by the current administration but not wanting to be
linked to the baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Andrew, the Democratic national chairman, said the party
studied Reagan's approach in 1988 but decided that Clinton had a
different place in his party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people would see the transfer in 1988 as being
successful; it was gracefully done,'' Andrew said. ``But there was
a very different goal. They wanted George Bush to be Ronald
Reagan.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked then if the Democratic Party did not want Al Gore to be
Bill Clinton, he demurred, saying, ``We want Al Gore to simply be
Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   It is especially striking that Clinton has been ridiculed for
pulling attention from Gore given that he has been much more
aggressive in helping his vice president than was Reagan. In fact,
Reagan's endorsement of Bush was so feeble _ almost like an
afterthought _ that he had to clarify his comments the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Robert M. Teeter, who was a top strategist for Bush, said
Clinton's transgressions are a horrible burden for the vice
president. ``We had the challenge of Bush having to establish
himself in his own right,'' he said. ``In Gore's case, it's a very
difficult strategy because the economy's in pretty good shape but
people want a change. There's real tension.''
</P>
<P>
   David Leland, the chairman of the Ohio Democratic Party, said he
understands the political need for Clinton to depart on Tuesday to
leave the stage for Gore. That doesn't mean he is happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in the same hotel as Bill Clinton and I'd love to have him
stay around,'' Leland said. ``We can go out and shoot pool, go have
steaks. Whatever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
