u p BC-REFORM-PARTY-NYT     08-13 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REFORM-PARTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER REFORM PARTY RUCKUS, STILL NO WINNER IN SIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
  LONG BEACH, Calif. _ As the presidential nominees of the two
Reform Parties left Splitsville to campaign across the rest of the
country by bus, their associates began plotting legal strategies to
seize the $12.6 million in federal campaign money that is awaiting
the real party's true nominee _ as soon as a court decides what and
who they are.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nominees' departures ended an intense week of bickering here
that left the Reform Party with two of everything, including
nominees claiming to be its presidential candidate: Pat Buchanan
and John Hagelin.
</P>
<P>
   The war, however, continues. It is not only before the campaign
money dispensers at the Federal Election Commission, and later the
courts, that the two sides have to argue their case. In as many as
half the states, the Reform Party is listed on the presidential
ballot by party, which means each side has to convince individual
state election commissions that its candidate is the legitimate
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much more to play out,'' said Russell J. Verney, a
leading party official who aligned himself with Hagelin after the
split. ``As much chaos as we've had nationally, now we're going to
have it at the state level.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the primary vote that both sides threw out as fraudulent
was any indication, it hardly matters what Buchanan or Hagelin
does, where they go or what they say.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the two men energized all of 78,000 Americans to cast
a vote during a month-long balloting period, a sign that as the
presidential election approaches, voters are not so uncomfortable
with the Republican and Democratic choices that they feel a need
for someone else altogether.
</P>
<P>
   In a political version of ``To Tell the Truth,'' lawyers for
each side are facing the rather daunting prospect of trying to make
sense of the last five days here.
</P>
<P>
   Not that either side views any of this as a life-or-death
struggle. Both candidates have vowed to press ahead through
November, no matter what happens in any legal or administrative
arena. If so, one side would likely have to assume a new party name
or affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   In that context, each candidate still has an edge. As a
self-described red-meat conservative and a fixture in American
politics for almost three decades, Buchanan has achieved something
of cult status as an ideologue who pushes all the right
isolationist, xenophobic and homophobic buttons for his new band of
supporters.
</P>
<P>
   And the more that the major party candidates, Vice President Al
Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, fight for the political
center, the more appeal Buchanan has to hard-right conservatives
left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Hagelin's edge may be that as a longtime leader of the Natural
Law Party, he has something of a reputation among fringe parties.
Aides said he would like to create a broad coalition of third
parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will continue,'' Hagelin said in his acceptance speech on
Saturday. ``Under what banner, I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates have enough money on hand for modest campaign
efforts, their aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Bay Buchanan, chief strategist for her brother, said he has
enough money now, between $1 million and $2 million, and expects to
raise enough through donations to keep him on the road four or five
days a week from Labor Day through the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can run the whole campaign on what we have now, but without
any media,'' she said, referring to radio and television
commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Roth, a spokesman for Hagelin, said he could do the same,
with the $2 million the Hagelin campaign currently has.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 2053EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-GORE-ART-NYT &LR;      08-13 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-GORE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S NO GEORGE BURNS BUT HE'S WORKING ON THE LIGHTER SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ohio, Texas, Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT13, 14 and 15 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ It was the Al and Rob show, an unlikely new comedy
duo now making occasional appearances on the campaign trail to the
White House. Starring Vice President Al Gore, a politician with a
famously wooden public demeanor, and Rob Reiner, the actor and
director known for sly satire, the team came to the Rainbow Babies
and Children's Hospital here to talk about the serious subject of
children without medical insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But as the two stood side by side in the hospital atrium,
swapping turns with the microphone in a discussion with doctors and
parents, the topic was at times overtaken by two other objectives
of the Gore campaign: making Gore more likable, and finding ways to
attack George W. Bush without turning voters off.
</P>
<P>
   Reiner agreeably took on both challenges Sunday, introducing
Gore as ``a good man,'' and then, almost beseechingly, assuring the
audience that Gore did indeed possess a sense of humor. ``He's a
fun man,'' he said. ``We have laughs together.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, as Gore plowed into a long description of how some states
have thrown up bureaucratic barriers to enrolling children in
government-financed health care, Reiner cut in with deadpan timing.
``Would one of those states be Texas?'' he asked, all mock
innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it isn't, you don't have to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Embracing the straight man role, Gore replied, ``If it is, can I
still not say?''
</P>
<P>
   For Gore's aides, the repartee was a welcome surprise, a moment
to get in a subtle jab at Bush while showing their candidate as a
man who, if not exactly George Burns, is at least capable of adding
a human touch to policy jargon.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months Gore's friends have repeatedly expressed
frustration at his inability to project a certain lightness of
being that seems to come so easily for Bush. One of those friends
is Reiner, who, when asked to explain Bush's lead in the polls,
offered the explanation: ``People like him.''
</P>
<P>
   During a private lunch with Gore, the two watched film footage
of Gore shot by Spike Jonze, the director of the movie ``Being John
Malkovich.''
</P>
<P>
   The footage, paid for by the Democratic National Committee, is
said to show a more appealing side to Gore, and Reiner, the
director of ``This Is Spinal Tap'' and ``The American President,''
gave it a gushing review. The public, he said, needs to see this
kind of footage, perhaps even this week at the Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a great sense of humor,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the campaign's quest to soften Gore's image, Gore has
markedly toned down his criticism of Bush. ``I pledged not to make
any negative personal attacks and I won't,'' Gore said in one of
several local television interviews Sunday. The same cannot be said
of Gore's press aides and surrogates like Reiner, who did not
disappoint. He launched into passionate attacks on Bush that were
oddly reminiscent of the diatribes he once delivered against
Richard Nixon, back when Reiner played Archie Bunker's liberal
son-in-law in the 1970s sitcom ``All in the Family.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The other side talks about being the party of diversity and
the party of inclusion,'' he said. ``How do they figure this? This
is what I want to know. Unless they define diversity as two guys at
the head of the ticket that are from two different oil companies.
If that's how they define diversity then I guess they are
diverse.''
</P>
<P>
   He was even more animated when Gore's aides had him meet with
reporters. Waving his arms, talking a mile a minute, bobbing about
like an agitated bear, Reiner called Bush ``a hypocrite of
staggering proportions.'' He chided Bush for having ``the
audacity'' to call himself a champion of children when it is Gore
who has proposed spending $42 billion to provide health care to
another million uninsured children and $115 billion to expand
schools and improve teacher pay.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Reiner and Gore advisers said, Bush has resisted
efforts to expand government health care programs to hundreds of
thousands of poor children in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   At one moment, though, Reiner's impassioned advocacy seemed to
get the better of him. Reiner asserted that Gore was one of the
three most qualified men to run for president ``in our lifetimes.''
The other two, he said, were Lyndon B. Johnson and Nixon,
presidents perhaps best known to history for leading the nation
through the twin traumas of Vietnam and Watergate. ``Al Gore, of
those three, is the most qualified,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When reporters burst into laughter at the unlikely comparison of
Gore to Nixon, Reiner tried hard to backpedal. ``Don't just print
the Nixon part,'' he begged, far, far too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
