<HEADER>
A0480 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-YOUNG-APPRECIATION-SF     08-13 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-APPRECIATION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LORETTA YOUNG: A GIANT FROM SILENT FILM TO TV 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICK LaSALLE  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Loretta Young's career was so significant and went on for so
long that she's a little like the mythic animal _ so big that the
description varies, depending on whether the describer saw the head
or the tail.
</P>
<P>
   Young, who died Saturday at age 87, is remembered as the great
lady of early television by people in their 50s and as the gracious
leading actress of 1940s films by those who are older. Yet, in the
end, when the histories are written, Loretta Young will be best
remembered as one of the screen's great early stars. The filmed
record of her young beauty _ and her many fine performances, during
the Great Depression, as a struggling working woman _ guarantee her
immortality.
</P>
<P>
   For many it's hard to think of Young as an early star, and yet
she began in silent films. By her own count, she played 98 leads
over the course of some 60 years onscreen, and more than half of
those leads came to her before age 25. Her early films remained
unseen until fairly recently, but their availability, on video and
cable, has borne out film historian David Shipman's contention that
Young was at her best in her apprentice years.
</P>
<P>
   Young's development, from film to film, is fascinating to trace.
``When I started all you had to be is photographable and do what
the director told you,'' Young told The Chronicle in 1998. In her
first talkie, ``The Squall'' (1929), Young was only 16 playing a
girl of about 19, and her presence was merely decorative. A year
later,  &LR; In ``Road to Paradise'' (1930), she played twins separated
at birth, and she was confident and appealing, though not a
striking actress. But a year later, in Frank Capra's ``Platinum
Blonde'' (1931), it was all there: the beauty, the depth of
feeling, the command of the medium.
</P>
<P>
   In these years, Young had the challenge of playing women older
than herself. In ``Platinum Blonde,'' for example, she was 18,
playing a tough city-side reporter. In ``Big Business Girl''
(1931), she was an advertising executive. In ``They Call It Sin''
(1932), she was a successful composer; in ``Grand Slam'' (1933), a
famous bridge player.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for posterity, Young worked often in this period,
churning out six or seven pictures a year. Her pictures could be
said to have come in one of two varieties. There were the Nice
Loretta movies, and there were the Naughty Loretta movies.
</P>
<P>
   The Nice Loretta movies are worth seeing. Young worked at Warner
Bros., and just about everything that studio churned out in the
early '30s had some zing: In ``Taxi'' (1932), she played the loyal
wife of cab driver James Cagney. But he's portrayed as a hard,
troubled man, and the marriage isn't easy. (``Taxi'' is the picture
in which Young strips down to a nearly transparent slip.) In ``Life
Begins'' (1932), she spends the film in a maternity ward, trying to
live through a difficult pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   The Naughty Loretta movies were even better. In ``Employee's
Entrance'' (1933), she's a married woman who gets drunk at an
office party and goes to bed with her sleazy boss (Warren William).
``Midnight Mary'' (1933), which Young herself said was one of her
best films, begins with Young on trial for murder. As the
prosecuting attorney makes his summation, she sits in court reading
Cosmopolitan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1934, Young signed with 20th Twentieth &LR;  Century Studios and
made ``Born to Be Bad,'' about a woman who moves in with her son's
foster parents and seduces the husband (Cary Grant). Unfortunately
20th Twentieth &LR;  Century, which soon merged with Fox, wasn't a good
studio for actresses. ``(Studio boss) Darryl Zanuck had no interest
in women's stories,'' Young recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Even under the Production Code, which went into effect in
mid-1934, Young could have thrived had she stayed at Warner Bros.
Instead she found herself cast in boring wife roles at Fox. ``I
finally told Daryl, I'm sick of playing Mrs. Alexander Graham Bell.
I want to play Bell.''
</P>
<P>
   Young had a resurgence in the mid-1940s. By then it seemed as if
she'd been around forever, but in 1946, when she co-starred with
Orson Welles in ``The Stranger,'' she was only 33. The next year
she played a Swedish immigrant in ``The Farmer's Daughter'' (1947),
for which she won an Academy Award, and had the title role in ``The
Bishop's Wife'' (1947).
</P>
<P>
   By the late '40s she was an angular beauty with a gentle aura,
the opposite of what she'd been in the early '30s: a gentle beauty
with an edge. She still possessed one of the show business' most
watchable faces, and at 40 years old, she made a highly successful
second career in television.
</P>
<P>
   When I think of Loretta Young I think, of course, of the soft
hair and the cheekbones. I think of the look of distress she got in
dramas, with those huge eyes welling up with tears. But I also
think of her sidelong smile and nod, her deft way with a punch
line. And then there was the voice: refined, matter-of-fact and so
clear.
</P>
<P>
   It is probable that Loretta Young is just beginning to be
appreciated. Her body of work is vast. Her early films are winning
her new audiences, and when her television work becomes available,
we'll be able, for the first time, to grasp the full breadth of
this career.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is safe to say: We've just lost a giant _ and one of
the last of them.
</P>
<P>
   (Mick LaSalle is a film critic for the San Francisco
Chronicle.) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
