<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0481 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-REUNION-KOREA-BOS &LR;      08-13 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REUNION-KOREA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`I DON'T WANT ANYTHING MORE THAN THIS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL _ Seonwoo Chun Shil has been crying all day _ tears of
anticipation over seeing her long-lost brother Tuesday for the
first time in half a century; tears of sorrow over a lifetime of
separation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no more wishes if I die right after I see my little
brother,'' said Seonwoo, 72, wiping her eyes with a wad of tissues
clenched in her fist. ``I'll be hoping to see him again. But I
don't want anything more than this.''
</P>
<P>
   Seonwoo is one of 1 million people born in North Korea who fled
south during the 1950-53 Korean War and who lost contact with their
parents, children, spouses, or siblings. She will be among the 100
South Koreans who will travel to the North Tuesday for a 72-hour
family reunion _ the most emotional and tangible sign of the
cross-border rapprochement that has blossomed since the first-ever
summit of leaders from the North and South in June.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts believe the reunions carry far more than
humanitarian significance. Such contacts may offer the best hope of
diminishing ignorance and distrust on both sides of the border,
thereby pushing diplomatic efforts toward peace and eventual
reunification.
</P>
<P>
   The governments will reopen liaison offices at the border
village of Panmunjom Monday. On Saturday, they announced a
fiber-optic cable link between the capitals.
</P>
<P>
   The nascent detente may be extending to other nations as well.
Sunday, North Korean leader Kim Jong Il was quoted as saying that
he would establish diplomatic ties with the United States as soon
as Washington removes Pyongyang from its list of states that
sponsor terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The Korean War, which claimed as many as 2 million lives, ended
with Korea divided along the 38th Parallel, the communist North
backed by China and the Soviet Union, the capitalist South defended
by US forces, 37,000 of whom remain here.
</P>
<P>
   The two Koreas never signed a peace treaty and technically
remain at war. Before the summit, both governments denounced the
other viciously and regularly, with the North sending agents and
spy submarines to infiltrate the South and provoking armed clashes
as recently as last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike German families divided by the Berlin Wall who kept in
touch through letters, phone calls, and in later years, annual
visits, Korean families on either side of the world's most heavily
fortified border have been denied any contact, making the burden of
separation worse and blocking residents of the North from learning
about life outside.
</P>
<P>
   Some southerners have paid thousands of dollars to ethnic Korean
Chinese citizens _ who are allowed to enter the North _ to locate
relatives and smuggle them into China for brief meetings. Two
thousand people managed to track down their relatives in the past
decade, but only 500 succeeded in meeting them, according to South
Korean government figures.
</P>
<P>
   Visits Tuesday of 100 northerners to Seoul and 100 southerners
to Pyongyang are only the second-ever sanctioned reunions since the
country split. In 1985, 50 people from each side were chosen by
their governments for brief meetings. This time, nearly 77,000
South Koreans applied and that number was whittled down to 400 by a
Red Cross lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The lucky 100 from the South were chosen after North Korea
verified their relatives were alive, with priority given to the
elderly and those separated from a parent, child, or spouse.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the 7.6 million southerners with relatives in the
North _ 15 percent of the southern population _ Seonwoo knows
nothing about what happened to her family and is not sure she will
recognize her 68-year-old brother, although she remembers ``the
shape of his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   She has packed photos to show him of her late husband, who was a
police officer in the southern city of Pusan, her two children, and
five grandchildren. She bought a shiny pink silk hanbok to wear,
the traditional Korean gown, and an array of gifts _ toothbrushes,
vitamins, clothes, cosmetics, underwear, stockings, watches,
jewelry, and $500 _ half the amount southerners are permitted to
give relatives in the cash-strapped North. It is all she could
afford.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I will ask him is what happened to our father.
The next thing will be if he ever got married. Does he have
children? Is he happy there? I feel so sorry for him that he might
have had a hard life there,'' Seonwoo said, her eyes watering.
``It's just destiny. We were born in the wrong time period.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Pyongyang to a privileged family (her father was a
senior executive at the Korean Tobacco Company), Seonwoo grew up
with several homes, a pleasure boat, and plenty of land. But by
1949, tensions between North and South were at a fever pitch, and
her family's friends had begun to say they could only survive if
they fled south.
</P>
<P>
   Her widowed father sent her to stay with an aunt but expected
that she would return when things calmed down. He kept his son to
help manage the family property.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pyongyang at that time had a better quality of life than
Seoul,'' Seonwoo recalled. The northern half of the country was
then thriving with industrialization, while the rural South lagged
sorely behind.
</P>
<P>
   Seonwoo, then 21, packed a bag for a 10-day respite in the
South, but the political situation deteriorated rapidly. Militants
swarmed along the de facto border and sealed the roads heading
north. Her aunt feared she would be killed or seized by soldiers
and refused to let her leave. Soon, war broke out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only when Korea was divided for good along the 38th Parallel
did I realize that was it: There was no going home for me,'' she
said. ``I cried all the time. I couldn't accept that I couldn't see
them again. Every year on their birthdays and big holidays, I would
think of them.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, she applied to be considered for the first, limited
reunions but was turned down. Discouraged by the 77,000 others who
were applying this time, she didn't even bother, and was surprised
when the Red Cross contacted her, citing her 15-year-old
application.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's 100 visitors to Seoul were chosen from the
country's elite _ artists, scientists, officials, and defectors.
Seonwoo's family suspects she was chosen because her brother may be
well-connected to the northern regime.
</P>
<P>
   Seonwoo wants to visit her father's grave, but the government
said that will be impossible. Families will be permitted to see one
another only in their hotels, with North Korean officials present,
and on organized sightseeing trips. She is disappointed that she
won't see her brother's home or sleep in the same room, but she is
grateful for any chance to see him.
</P>
<P>
   She realizes it will be hard to bond in a few days after a
lifetime apart and doubts he will be able to tell her the truth
about his life in North Korea, although ``I'll be able to guess
from his voice and facial expressions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross gave southerners instructions about presents:
nothing expensive, no television sets, nothing with English words,
no South Korean or US flags, no South Korean currency, and no
books, tapes, or videos that could be considered subversive or
insulting to the North Korean government.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she wishes she could bring her brother back with
her, Seonwoo averted her eyes, now heavy with emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel so appreciative that I even get to see him _ what can I
expect more than three days? I wish someday I could bring my little
brother to Seoul or Pusan with his whole family. Our wish is
reunification and to all live together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
