<HEADLINE>
AT CONVENTION, DEMOCRATS LEAVE NO DELEGATE UNPLUGGED 
</HEADLINE>
  By LESLIE WAYNE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Picture the scene this week on the convention floor in Los
Angeles: Democratic delegates galore with banners and balloons,
funny hats and confetti. And computers. And Palm Pilots, digital
cameras, wireless beepers, ``smart cards'' and all sorts of other
high-tech gadgets meant to showcase the party's technological
prowess and burnish its party-of-the-future image.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the major party conventions have largely faded as big
television and radio events, the Democratic Party is making a show
of having the most plugged-in national convention in history,
leaving no moment unrecorded and no delegate unconnected. In
cyberspace, that is.
</P>
<P>
   A 360-degree camera will be streaming video images on the
Democrats' Web site for the entire four-day convention. Everyone
making a podium speech will be required to participate in an online
chat immediately afterward. When the cry rings out _ ``The great
state of Tennessee casts its votes for . . .'' _ those votes will
be recorded by one of 56 Apple Imac computers scattered across the
convention floor. And each delegate is being given a card to be
used at any of the more than 100 computer kiosks scattered at the
convention and at Los Angeles hotels, to get late-breaking
information from party officials and to talk to other delegates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've basically wired the entire city of Los Angeles,'' said
Naz Nageer, director of technology for the Democratic National
Convention Committee. ``It's our `e-mersion' coverage. We're on the
frontier of something big; we are in the space of the future. We've
got technological diversity here.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Democrats _ who have a far more extensive technological
display planned than what the Republicans offered in Philadelphia _
the high-tech gadgetry serves purposes both practical and
political.
</P>
<P>
   It connects disparate delegates in the nation's most sprawling
city and is a way to communicate with them on issues ranging from
the party's daily talking points to scheduling changes and
restaurant reservations.
</P>
<P>
   But, more subtly, the gadgetry sends the message that the party
embraces technology and, by implication, the future. ``It's mainly
a demonstration,'' said Adam Clayton Powell III, vice president of
technology for the Freedom Forum, a nonprofit foundation. ``It
becomes a showcase of technology and a way to make the party look
very 21st century. It means we won't have pictures of delegates
sitting in their seats reading the newspapers. The party would
rather have them looking at their Palm Pilots.''
</P>
<P>
   And for some, this technology is also a way to keep delegates in
line. ``All this technology is not so much to solicit opinions of
delegates as it is to tell them what to do and what to say,'' said
Marion Just, research director at the Joan Shorenstein Center at
Harvard University. ``This certainly will help delegates get the
message of the day _ or of the hour _ and provides an opportunity
for the convention to speak with one voice to the media.''
</P>
<P>
   The technological display, which is being offered free by many
high-tech companies, involves gadgets both in real space and in
cyberspace. More than 100 seven-foot-high kiosks will connect
delegates and anyone else to the Internet and to special convention
Web sites. The kiosks, 12 on the convention floor and the rest at
delegate hotels, contain easy-to-use computers with touch screens
instead of mice.
</P>
<P>
   The main Web site is DNC411, a delegates-only part of the main
site (www.Dems2000.com) that is a way for delegates to get
information online at any kiosk rather than having to carry around
sheets of paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the computers reinforce the image that this is the party
of the future,'' said Michael Cornfield, research director of the
Democracy Online Project at George Washington University. ``There
really is no other purpose for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
