u s BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT &LR;      08-13 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEITER IS PICTURE-PERFECT AS METS TOP GIANTS, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Leiter spotted a photo of a pitcher a few days
ago, and he looked it over with admiration. As the pitcher released
the ball, his arm was like the minute hand on a clock at the top of
the hour. That is impressive, said Leiter, who felt his release
point was off in a sloppy outing at Houston last week.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, the Mets' left-hander, knew his mechanics would have to
be better. Sunday, they were. Leiter reached out more with his arm,
kept his fingers on top of his pitches and worked eight marvelous
innings to beat the San Francisco Giants, 2-0. He gave up only two
hits and one walk while striking out 12, improving to 13-5.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter left for a pinch-hitter in the Mets' eighth, when Robin
Ventura's double and Mike Bordick's single brought in the only runs
of the game. With Armando Benitez having pitched the last two days,
John Franco worked the ninth inning for his fourth save.
</P>
<P>
   With the victory, the Mets (69-47) moved within a game and a
half of Atlanta, the closest they have been in five weeks. The Mets
have won 16 of 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in this four-game series, which the Mets can sweep with
a victory Monday night, Leiter talked with Dave Righetti, the
Giants' pitching coach and his friend, about his Sunday opponent,
Livan Hernandez. Righetti told him how sharp Hernandez had been,
and Leiter knew that every pitch would count.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time I'm facing a guy who's quality, that kind of elevates
my concentration, and realizing that the execution of a pitch is
important,'' Leiter said. ``I even thought about that with Barry. I
really wanted to throw a fastball in at some point in one of his
at-bats, and I never did.''
</P>
<P>
   The wind was blowing in from center field, but Leiter feared
Barry Bonds could turn on a pitch and drive it down the right field
line for a homer. So Leiter changed his approach to Bonds, a
left-handed power hitter, and twice struck him out with curveballs.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter had all of his pitches working, even his changeup, which
he used against Ellis Burks to set up the groundout that ended the
seventh inning, just after Jeff Kent singled to end a stretch of 19
consecutive outs.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Valentine let Leiter hit with a man on third and
one out in the seventh _ he struck out _ and Leiter fanned the side
in the eighth. His high fastball was humming, his slider diving and
his cutter boring in on the Giants' hands.
</P>
<P>
   When Leiter was younger, he would continue to try to make a
nasty pitch when he fell behind in the count. When he struck out a
lot of hitters, he usually walked a lot, too. Sunday, Leiter said,
he mostly tried to throw strikes without worrying whether a hitter
would put it in play.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter got several outs this way, and Righetti noticed how
Ventura, the third baseman, would set up close to the line and
Bordick, the shortstop, would set up in the hole. The wild rookie
whom Righetti knew with the Yankees in the late-'80s now has
superior command of his cutter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a good, rising fastball and a pretty good slider,''
said Righetti, who was the Yankees' closer when Leiter started his
career there in 1987. ``But he never had that other pitch, that
curveball and that efficient fastball he could spot; it was all
over the place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, he's got that cutter to go along with the other fastball
that he has. He's using a pitch that right-handers have a tough
time dealing with. Even if they hit it good, they have a tough time
hitting it fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter idolized Righetti, who taught him slider grips but whose
professionalism made the most lasting impression. Leiter noticed
how Righetti would sit in the bullpen all game long, even though he
would not be called on until the end, and he said that commitment
taught him respect for the team ideal.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's outing looked like Leiter's best this year, but he did
not care to rank it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really I'm not proud anymore of whether it's a complete
domination or not, so long as we win the game,'' he said. ``I don't
want to give up five runs in my games, because after a while you
realize you're playing with fire, but a win's a win. The
organization, the GM, owner, fans _ all they care about is whether
you won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter would not have won without the offense finally getting to
Hernandez (11-9).
</P>
<P>
   The Mets left seven runners on in the first seven innings _ they
lead the National League in runners left on base, with 7.76 a game
_ but Edgardo Alfonzo walked to lead off the eighth and scored when
Ventura split the gap with a double that bounced to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really on the upward climb,'' Valentine said of Ventura,
who was slowed at midseason by a shoulder injury. ``He's been very,
very good in the dugout all year long, and very good with his
preparation, but you could tell that he's felt he could contribute
more. Now he's getting right on track.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Leiter, whose mechanics looked just fine to his mentor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing he's doing now is finishing his pitches,''
Righetti said. ``He attacks hitters better out front than he did
before. He used to land and spin off the ball. Now, he's not doing
that. He's finishing.''
</P>
<P>
   His forgettable Houston start behind him, Leiter's performance
was picturesque again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
