<HEADLINE>
TIGHT END BRINGS WIDE POSSIBILITIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JILL PAINTER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Big Sky Conference teams had plenty of trouble
defending Cal State Northridge's prolific offense last year. Now
CSUN is adding another wrinkle: the tight end.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors, who open camp today, seldom have used the
position, but CSUN coach Jeff Kearin expects that to change this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never really done anything before with a tight end,''
Kearin said. ``We've been more of a spread unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Nate Davenport _ CSUN's tight end last season _ had just six
receptions for 40 yards. He played in six games with an injured
shoulder, but he's healthy now and much improved, Kearin said.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport will compete for playing time with Mt. San Antonio
College transfer Cory DiSanti (6-foot-3, 225 pounds).
</P>
<P>
   ``(DiSanti) is more of a receiving tight end,'' Kearin said.
``We'll keep defenses guessing as to whether we're going to run the
ball or stand him up as a receiver. I'm excited about the ability
to have a tight end.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Crushing blow: Bryson Atkins _ who started at strong safety
toward the end of last season _ blew out his knee playing
basketball last summer and is out for the season.
</P>
<P>
   __ SDSU loss, CSUN gain: San Diego State transfer Jason Stone
should prove to be a big-time receiving threat. The 6-5, 220-pound
Stone played at Santa Barbara City College before receiving a full
scholarship to SDSU. Kearin said Stone wasn't one of SDSU's top
four receivers in the spring and also wanted to be closer to home.
</P>
<P>
   __ Maybe next year: Ron Givan, a strong safety CSUN signed out
of Mt. SAC, is academically ineligible. Givan was a projected
starter but is shy credits to earn his Associate of Arts degree.
Givan plans to finish in the fall and begin practicing with CSUN in
the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very disappointing because he's a great player and good
person,'' Kearin said. ``He would've been a good part of this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Out for good: Senior defensive lineman Joe Engle, a starter
last season, lost an appeal to the NCAA regarding eligibility
issues and can't play, Kearin said. Engle, a senior, went to San
Jose State and then Bakersfield College before transferring to
CSUN. Engle's collegiate football career is through.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
