<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-SECURITY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
  L.A. GET FIRST TASTE OF DEMONSTRATORS
 &HT;      By MARK HELM 
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The first skirmish in a potential week-long battle
between Los Angeles police and demonstrators ended quietly Sunday
after more than 3,500 protesters marched without incident through
the city's downtown streets under the watchful eye of riot-clad
officers.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters _ chanting for the release of Mumia Abu-Jamal, a
death-row inmate convicted of killing a Philadelphia police officer
_ walked peacefully on a designated route from Pershing Square
downtown toward the Staples Center, site of the Democratic National
Convention, which will begin Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A few protesters broke away from the crowd and ran toward
police, only to stop a few feet before them. On the sidewalks,
tourists retreated into shops when the marchers moved toward them
while some business owners pulled down steel doors over their
storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   Although this demonstration remained trouble-free, Los Angeles
officials made clear they would still take no chances in their
preparation for the arrival of an estimated 50,000 protesters. To
prevent any disruptions to the convention's official nomination of
Al Gore as its presidential candidate,, the city has erected an
armed camp around the convention site.
</P>
<P>
   Patrolled by nearly 10,000 officers from the Los Angeles Police
Department, the L.A. County Sheriff's office, California Highway
Patrol, FBI and Secret Service, the camp's perimeter _ protected by
a 13-foot high fence set in concrete blocks _ runs a mile in length
and a half-mile in width around the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the perimeter, police cars slowly cruised downtown
streets Sunday while hundreds of officers _ equipped with tear gas,
pepper spray and bean-bag projectiles _ patrolled the area on foot.
In addition, other police units in full riot gear were stationed
nearby, ready to move instantly. Police even commandeered many of
the city's closed-circuit cameras and highway sensors normally used
to traffic control to watch for suspicious activity at hundreds of
locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we don't want any trouble, we are prepared to act and to
act decisively,'' Officer Jason Lee, an LAPD spokesman, said.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators hope to draw attention to such causes as
environmental degradation, poverty, treatment of undocumented
immigrants and campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent violence, police have also cut down trees, which
could be set on fire, and removed newspaper stands, which could be
used as battering rams, and mail boxes, which could hold small
bombs.
</P>
<P>
   An example of the department's tense position occurred Saturday
morning after police received reports of a large package wrapped in
duct tape in front of the downtown Marriott Hotel. Police quickly
blocked access to the building, closing the street in front of it
for 1 1/2 hours. They refused to allow anyone to enter or leave the
hotel. Officers surrounded the building and deployed a bomb squad
with specially-trained dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the scare was diffused when police opened the box
and found it was filled with kitty litter.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their preparations, police privately admitted they
cannot prevent every act of violence in a city as spread-out as Los
Angeles, which stretches for 469 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   However, police said they felt confident that they can achieve
their two main goals: ensuring the smooth running of the convention
and stopping demonstrators from disrupting the downtown area.
</P>
<P>
   But officials said it will be nearly impossible to stop
protesters from blocking traffic or cutting off access to
businesses in the surrounding suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   They stressed that they are determined to avoid the riots of
1992, when hundreds of police waited for hours as demonstrators _
spurred by a jury's acquittal of four LAPD officers on state
charges in the Rodney G. King beating _ destroyed parts of the
city.
</P>
<P>
   Police Cmdr. Tom Lorenzen, who heads security for the
convention, has said that it will provide a chance for the
department to redeem its tarnished image. But the LAPD also is
dealing with a corruption scandal in which officers were found to
have covered up unjustified shootings, intimidated witnesses and
planted evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lee said, ``We will treat every demonstrator fairly and
according to the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Protest organizers said they feared that the police in their
desire to keep order and not to repeat the mistakes of the 1992
riots will overreact against peaceful protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The area has become a militarized zone, and they think we're
the enemy,'' said Caroline Brown, a spokeswoman for an umbrella
group of protest organizations which calls itself D2KLA.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the Los Angeles City Council voted 13 to 0 to require
city agencies to respect the rights of demonstrators during the
convention. The vote came a day after the American Civil Liberties
Union, on behalf of several protest groups, filed a lawsuit against
the LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   The suit contends that the department has selectively enforced
laws _ including issuing jaywalking citations to protest organizers
in front of their near downtown. The suit also alleges that the
police have photographed people entering the headquarters, demanded
to search the building without a warrant, confiscated protester
property, followed people leaving the building and recorded the
license plate numbers of cars parked nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spying and the harassment of political protesters is the
hallmark of a police state, and must not be tolerated here,'' ACLU
attorney Dan Tokaji said.
</P>
<P>
   Preparing for the worst, protesters have trained themselves in
how to cope with tear gas and pepper spray and how to behave when
confronted by police. ``It's not that we want trouble, but the
police have shown every sign that they're willing to use this kind
of force,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
