<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0493 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-DEM-CONVENE-NYT &LR;      08-13 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEM-CONVENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN PRAISES, AND PARTS WAYS WITH, GORE ON EVE OF CONVENTION
</HEADLINE>
  By JAMES DAO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As Democrats prepared to kick off their national
convention here on Monday, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, the party's
choice for vice president, sought to minimize his differences with
Vice President Al Gore on some of the leading issues of the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But in the process he revealed a new and potentially contentious
one, saying proposals to raise the retirement age for Social
Security and Medicare should be ``kept on the table'' for further
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on five different news shows, Lieberman acknowledged
that he had held different positions from Gore on a variety of
issues, from affirmative action to school vouchers to legal reform.
But he scoffed at assertions that his views were closer to the
Republicans than to Gore's, and he praised the vice president for
having had the confidence to select a running mate who differs with
him on important subjects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is again a mark of Al Gore's strength of leadership that he
didn't look for somebody who had 100 percent agreement with him,''
Lieberman said ``Meet the Press.'' ``We've argued, we've debated,
and I think that's what progress comes from, particularly the
willingness to look at new ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in explaining how he has come to agree with Gore on a
core issue of the campaign _ whether to allow taxpayers to invest
some of their Social Security payroll taxes in the markets _
Lieberman exposed another rift in their views. While Gore has
insisted that he would not consider raising the retirement age for
Social Security or Medicare, Lieberman said Sunday that any debate
on keeping the system solvent should include that idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should keep it on the table for the good reason that people
are living longer,'' Lieberman said, also on NBC's ``Meet the
Press.'' Later, on CNN's ``Late Edition,'' Lieberman said, ``There
is very little you take off the table if you want to be an honest
public official.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday interviews capped a remarkable week for Lieberman,
whose selection by Gore infused many Democrats with a new sense of
optimism about the race. But the ability of television interviewers
to throw Lieberman repeatedly onto the defensive Sunday, over his
differences with Gore and his past criticisms of President Clinton,
suggested a line of attack that the Republicans are likely to
pursue.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has denounced the idea of raising the retirement age for
Social Security, and the party's platform is unequivocal on the
issue. Moreover, the Gore campaign has repeatedly hammered the
Republican candidate, Gov. George W. Bush, for even considering the
notion.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday, Gore's aides sought to play down the differences,
saying that Lieberman supports Gore's broad plan to keep Social
Security solvent through 2055 by using general tax revenues instead
of raising the retirement age, cutting benefits or increasing
taxes. The current retirement age is already scheduled to rise to
67 over the next several decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Lieberman was suggesting that at some future point,
perhaps after 2055, that it might need to be considered,'' said
Doug Hattaway, a spokesman for Gore. ``But not now.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Bush, sought to exploit the
apparent conflict, saying, ``Al Gore should resolve his internal
differences with Sen. Lieberman so the American people know where
they stand on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the back-and-forth over Lieberman's views, Gore spent the
day campaigning in Ohio and Missouri, making his way west for a
Wednesday arrival in Los Angeles and a Thursday evening coronation
as the party's standard bearer.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are looking to their convention to cast Gore in a
warmer, more appealing light, hoping to close what has been a
double-digit lead for Bush in many polls. Many delegates spent the
day fanning out across this sprawling city performing good deeds,
from picking up litter on beaches to preparing meals for the poor
to planting trees.
</P>
<P>
   Though the four-day extravaganza has been carefully
choreographed to help Gore step out of President Clinton's shadow,
the president and Hillary Rodham Clinton have already been in town
for two days, raising money, visiting supporters, soaking up media
attention _ and causing some grumbling within the Gore camp.
</P>
<P>
   (Gore himself did little to build a sense of separation from the
president Sunday when he told the Associate Press that he would
continue to seek Clinton's counsel after he left the White House.)
</P>
<P>
   Asked on Fox News whether he was worried that Clinton, who is
scheduled to address the convention in prime time on Monday night,
might dominate the convention spotlight this week, William Daley,
Gore's campaign chairman, said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's totally appropriate for him to be here to thank
the Democrats, because the Democratic Party stood with him during
good times and difficult times over the last eight years,'' Daley
said. ``But after tomorrow night's speech _ which is an important
speech for the president, for the campaign, and for Democrats _
this is Al Gore's convention.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats are also counting on the convention to demonstrate
that they are every bit as unified as the Republicans. But already,
some liberals have begun warning that Gore and Lieberman's centrist
positions on important issues may have dampened enthusiasm for the
ticket among vital parts of the party's base, including union
members and black voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only option is Al Gore,'' Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr., an
Illinois Democrat, said at a forum at the University of Southern
California on Saturday. ``But if there was another campaign that
was speaking to our issues that had the possibility and
plausibility of winning, we should support that campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   In his television appearances Sunday, Lieberman repeatedly tried
to put to rest concerns that he differed significantly from Gore on
major issues. He said, for instance, that although he had voted for
a pilot program for school vouchers, he would also increase federal
spending on public schools. And he said that while he had raised
concerns about affirmative action, he did not support efforts to
ban it.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Gore had encouraged him to argue his views
vigorously _ in private. But in public, Lieberman said, a Gore
administration would be firmly united. ``When he makes a decision,
I know what the administration policy will be, his,'' Lieberman
said on Fox News.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, who was the first Democrat to chastise President
Clinton from the Senate floor about his affair with a White House
intern, praised Clinton Sunday for seeking repentance at an
Illinois church last week for his adultery. But when asked whether
he would place Clinton among the pantheon of great presidents, as
Gore has, Lieberman demurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I'm going to leave the exact words for history,''
Lieberman said on ``Meet the Press.'' ``But I think he has done
some great things as president, which makes the personal mistakes
that he made even sadder.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 2133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
