<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BUICK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIATE BIRDIES THE LAST HOLE TO TAKE THE BUICK OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND BLANC, Mich. _ For Rocco Mediate, Sunday's final hole was
the perfect time for a birdie. For Chris Perry, it was the worst
time for a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   A two-shot swing on the 18th hole gave Mediate a dramatic
one-stroke victory at the Buick Open, a triumph he will savor for
many reasons. He shot a final-round, six-under-par 66, a determined
performance under pressure. He won over a strong field that
included Tiger Woods, who settled for an 11th-place tie. And with
his fourth career victory, Mediate showed the huge crowd at Warwick
Hills Golf &AMP; Country Club that while Woods may be the world's No. 1
player, he does not corner the market on providing back-nine
excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting 20 under par for the tournament (68-64-70-66-268),
Mediate finished a stroke ahead of Perry, who shot 68 Sunday, and
three shots ahead of Hal Sutton. With the $486,000 first-place
check, Mediate soared to 16th on this year's PGA Tour money list
with more than $1.23 million in earnings, while gaining the fourth
victory of a 16-year career.
</P>
<P>
   For Woods and other top players, this weekend was a tuneup for
the year's final major, the PGA Championship, which begins Thursday
in Louisville, Ky. But for Mediate, it was confirmation that when
his game is right, he need not be intimidated by anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play where Tiger is playing,'' said Mediate, a
37-year-old player who overcame major back surgery in 1994. ``I
don't want to duck him. I'm not going to beat him for a career, but
I beat him this week. I'm not going to beat him for the next 10, 15
years. Forget it. I'm not even going to try. I think he is going to
be the best player for a long time. But I beat him this week, and
someone can beat him next week.''
</P>
<P>
   While Mediate celebrated, Woods looked forward to the PGA
Championship, where he will try to become the first player since
Ben Hogan in 1953 to win three consecutive majors. Winning this
weekend wouldn't have upset Woods, but he came to Michigan to work
on the type of shots he will need to win the PGA at Valhalla Golf &AMP;
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   After shooting a 68 Sunday, Woods felt closer to reaching his
peak. His scariest moment came at No. 13, when he felt a twinge in
his left wrist after swinging hard at a ball that was lodged
against a tree root. Woods dropped his club immediately and began
to flex his wrist, but the pain subsided quickly and he completed
his round showing no ill effects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt quite a bit,'' said Woods. ``I took out a root, but I
hit the top edge of it and moved on.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would've been nice to shoot lower scores, but I'm making
progress. I'm not getting the most of my rounds right now. But
winning next week would mean a lot. It would put a nice little cap
at the end of my year.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Mediate who capped the tournament in style Sunday. The
outcome was decided on the par-4, 435-yard 18th, with Perry holding
a one-stroke lead. After Mediate hit a superb drive, Perry drove
into the rough, and his second shot came to rest just short of the
green. Sensing an opportunity, Mediate hit an impressive 9-iron
shot that landed on the green, 15 feet from the pin. Then Perry
made a mistake, hitting a chip shot that rolled 8 and a half feet
past the pin, leaving him a difficult putt attempt for par.
</P>
<P>
   Mediate stood over the putt that would win him the tournament, a
difficult 15-footer over a ridge. He hit it smoothly and the ball
broke into the cup for birdie. The gallery roared, but Perry had a
chance to force a playoff if he made his putt, so Mediate showed no
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to do anything disrespectful, because Chris
still had to play,'' Mediate said. ``I wasn't going to pump my
fist. I don't do that. It doesn't do anything for me. We are
professionals. If he makes it, we go to a playoff.''
</P>
<P>
   A playoff was not necessary. Perry's par attempt slid past the
hole, and his knees sagged in disappointment. The huge galleries
this weekend came mainly to see Woods, but it was Mediate who left
with the biggest prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on the tour 16 years, 15 more years than I thought I
would be on tour,'' Mediate said. ``I have also won four more times
than I thought I would. I don't have the greatest swing, I don't
hit the ball better than anybody, but I hit a lot of good shots
when I wanted to today. It sure was a lot of fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
