<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0500 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-CERABINO14-COX     08-13 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CERABINO14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHAT'S WHITE, SQUARE AND BORING? HINT: NOT AL GORE
 &HT;    By FRANK CERABINO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Could it be just a coincidence?
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about the National Democratic Convention and the Los
Angeles Tofu Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Really. A tofu festival.
</P>
<P>
   I had to see it for myself. I couldn't imagine an entire
festival making a big deal about tofu _ but then again, I can't
image an entire week making a big deal about Al Gore, whose new
moniker is ``principled fighter.''
</P>
<P>
   Principled fighter? How did those two words end up around his
neck? I've always looked at him more as ... human tofu _ malleable,
tasteless, and available in firm, regular and soft.
</P>
<P>
   At various times in his political career, Gore has been soft and
firm on gun control, gay rights, tobacco company regulation,
campaign finance reform and abortion. And he has picked a running
mate who has disagreed with him on such fundamental things such as
school choice, tort reform, and the need for a missile defense
system.
</P>
<P>
   So what you get with Gore seems to depend on what else is
cooking _ just like tofu.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I was surprised the Dems didn't find a way to
reschedule the Fifth Annual L.A. Tofu Festival to another weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Why tempt the comparison?
</P>
<P>
   I got to the tofu festival in time to see a humorous
presentation of ``the story of tofu,'' which included Aaron
Takahashi, 29, inside a cardboard box that made him appear to be a
talking tofu cube.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there anything that will make this more palatable?'' a
person on stage asks.
</P>
<P>
   The tofu man answers: ``If you should happen to find a bottle of
elixir from the Kikkoman.''
</P>
<P>
   I think a similar play will go on Thursday night when Tipper
Gore tells the story of Al from the convention hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there anything that will make this more palatable?''
convention planners must have asked Tipper.
</P>
<P>
   So she's bringing some heart-warming family photos to spice
things up.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for the Democrats, most of the conventioneers stayed away
from the tofu festival, which was held close to the skid row
section of downtown Los Angeles, a place where cardboard boxes line
the sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   And these boxes aren't being used as tofu costumes, either.
</P>
<P>
   At first I thought the boxes were just trash, but then I saw
that they were actually makeshift shelters for scores of homeless
people. Seeing this would just dampen the spirits at the
convention, which features _ I swear, this is true _ a performance
by the Men's Homeless Choir.
</P>
<P>
   Eat your tiny hearts out, Republicans. The Republicans throw a
guy on stage with a sombrero and they think they're being
inclusive. But, a choir of homeless people _ now that's compassion.
(Not to mention, the only music act that can both stink and be good
at the same time.)
</P>
<P>
   Although, I can't imagine what homeless people have to sing
about. (Will harmonize for food?) The guys I saw in the cardboard
boxes Sunday didn't appear to be ready to burst into song.
</P>
<P>
   But you've got to hand it to the Democrats. They've thought of
every compassionate angle.
</P>
<P>
   Even the confetti. The Dems announced that half the confetti
dropped during the convention will be made of ``80 percent recycled
fiber.'' The balloons are biodegradable, 30 percent of the delegate
shuttle buses use alternative fuels, and energy for the convention
will be ``generated from wind, water and sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially the wind, would be my guess.
</P>
<P>
   But back to the food.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday afternoon, Gore's daughters Karenna Gore Schiff and
Kristin Gore made an appearance as volunteers at the Los Angeles
Regional Food Bank, a network of charities that feeds over 280,000
hungry people in need.
</P>
<P>
   The quest to feed the hungry, though, wasn't restricted to the
lower rungs of the economic ladder.
</P>
<P>
   Other hungry people in need of a meal at Spago, the swank
Beverly Hills eatery under the culinary wizardry of chef Wolfgang
Puck, are out of luck unless they know the right Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The Dems have taken over Spago, reserving it for one luncheon
and four dinners this week. Sunday night, the restaurant was
cooking up a special menu for House Minority Leader Richard
Gephardt and 1,200 of his closest friends. The menu included
Cantonese duck, roasted salmon with pea greens and coconut curry,
and wild mushroom ravioli.
</P>
<P>
   But no tofu.
</P>
<P>
   I may be able to go the rest of the week without eating another
bite of tofu, which was available in every form imaginable at the
tofu festival.
</P>
<P>
   But the guys who really had their fill of tofu were the
contestants in the tofu-eating contest. The idea was to be the
fastest to eat two pounds of raw tofu.
</P>
<P>
   A little bit of tofu isn't so bad. But two pounds? Yuck. That's
like choking down four days of Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Cerabino's e-mail address is
frank(underscore)cerabino(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
