<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY'S MONDAY NIGHT SPEECH IS AIMED AT WOMEN VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers  
LOS ANGELES _ First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's nationally
televised speech Monday night to the Democratic National Convention
will focus on children and families, with her supporters hoping
those topics will help her win more support from women voters in
her New York Senate race.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton's official role in her 10-minute talk is to introduce
her husband, who then will make his last speech as president to a
Democratic National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton said Sunday she will broaden her speech to focus on
education and health care, topics that pollsters say are of special
interest to women voters.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokeswoman Cathie Levine said her boss is actively
involved in writing her speech and believes ``there are real
differences between the presidential candidates, specifically on
how they deal with children and families.''
</P>
<P>
   A Quinnipiac University poll last week showed Hillary Clinton
trailing Rep. Rick Lazio, R-N.Y., her Republican opponent in the
race, 41 to 46 percent among white women.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said she plans to use her convention speech to take
some potshots at Republicans. ``The other party offers a recipe for
going back to the past,'' she told CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Andrew, chairman of the Democratic National Committee, said
Clinton's theme of the ``values of working families'' is a natural
for her because she has ``done a lifetime of fighting for women and
children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of her genetic makeup,'' Andrew said. ``We
believe she is an excellent spokesperson and one of the building
blocks of that message.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew added that Clinton's prime-time talk ``is not designed to
assist her in her race for the U.S. Senate, but I'm sure it will
have the added benefit to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Miringoff, director of the Marist College poll, said the
first lady's 10 minutes in the spotlight ``is important, but it's
not make or break it for New York.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chance for her to have a ceremonial role,'' Miringoff
said. ``I don't think the 10 minutes is going to restart her
campaign. She doesn't get a fifth chance to make a first
impression. But if she's successful, she will energize some of her
base in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after Lazio criticized her for doing nothing for New
York during her White House years, Clinton insisted that she has
been more of an active behind-the-scenes policy maker than a
traditional first lady.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want people to know that, because if someone is going to
claim I sat around eating bonbons for the last five or six years, I
think it's only fair that the truth come out,'' she said last week.
</P>
<P>
   (Judy Holland can be contacted at 213-336-1800.)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
