<HEADLINE>
IN THE CALM AFTER A RELENTLESS STORM, N.J. SURVEYS FLOOD DAMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 20,000 people of Jefferson Township in north-central New
Jersey came out into the gray windy air Sunday, shaking their heads
in disbelief. Saturday's diabolical thunderstorm _ the one that
wouldn't go away _ had finally departed, having dropped 14 inches
of rain on their lovely, lake-dotted little domain.
</P>
<P>
   It is a place where hardly anything ever happens, folks say. But
Sunday, it seemed, the town had been pixilated: 300 homes flooded,
several bridges and roads washed out, driveways running like
millraces, trees down, cars and boats drowned, two dams gone _ and
the small lakes the dams had held back vanished, too, drained into
mudflats littered with dead fish.
</P>
<P>
   Some power and phones were still out, and water pumps were
chugging away in basements and garages in Jefferson Township,
nearby Sparta and other parts of northern New Jersey. The
Musconetcong River was still cresting, and dozens of residents of
Sparta and Hackettstown were evacuated as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   But water was receding in most of the flooded areas Sunday, and
officials and residents of Jefferson Township and in surrounding
Morris, Sussex, Passaic, Bergen, Warren, Essex and Hunterdon
Counties were counting their blessings as well as their losses as
they began the cleanup.
</P>
<P>
   No one had been killed or injured, and while damage may run into
hundreds of millions of dollars _ the estimate was $7 million in
Jefferson Township alone _ many town residents were more astounded
than stricken by the deluge that had hit their middle-class,
semirural community 40 miles west of New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the water high, but never anything like this,'' said
Linda Silbert, a 25-year resident of Jefferson Township, 42 square
miles of scenic wooded hills and winding roads in Morris County
north of Lake Hopatcong. ``Everyone I've seen around town is just
in awe.''
</P>
<P>
   Properly so, said Fred Gadomski, a meteorologist with
Pennsylvania State University, who noted that the storm that struck
New Jersey on Saturday was phenomenal. Most thunderstorms dump vast
amounts of rain for a few minutes and pass on. But this one stood
dead still much of the day, dumping rain on a narrow corridor of
northern New Jersey hour after hour after hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the people in Sparta and Jefferson Township,'' Gadomski
said, ``that would have been a once-in-a-lifetime rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman and other officials flew over the flooded
areas Sunday to assess the damage and pledged aid. A spokesman for
the governor, Peter McDonough, said officials would have a
preliminary damage estimate on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Graham, his wife and two children were in their Jefferson
Township home on Shawnee Lake on Saturday when, he said, ``I heard
a deafening noise, and the house started to tremble.'' The lake and
two brooks flanking his house had risen up and engulfed his
property.
</P>
<P>
   He and his family were rescued by police boat. When they
returned, they found the waters had dug a moat around their house,
destroyed their car and washed away their sailboat, paddleboat and
rowboat, and a gardening shed full of equipment. They found the
shed 75 feet away, but the boats were gone. ``I don't know where my
boats are,'' Graham said. ``Probably at the bottom of the lake.''
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon Sunday, power had been restored to all but about
250 of the 10,000 homes that had been blacked out in northern New
Jersey on Saturday, officials of GPU Energy said. About 50 homes in
Jefferson Township were still without power, town officials said.
Phone repairs also were under way, but there was no estimate of the
number of homes and businesses without service.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Creatura, 63, said his house had ``a river going through it.
'' He explained: ``The water was coming in the front door and
sweeping out the back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
