r s BC-TEN-DILBECK-COLUMN-LA     08-13 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-DILBECK-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE THEY COME AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ Better start getting used to this.
Better stop looking for the flaws, saying it'll never happen,
wondering if the moment will pass.
</P>
<P>
   The Williams sisters, Serena and Venus, aren't exactly
attempting to conceal their ambitions, though being shy never has
been part of their amazing repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   They've already announced their desire to make the WTA into the
``Williams tennis circuit,'' threatening to turn the greatest
women's tennis tour in the world into their own little backyard
sibling rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Cue the coronation. Order double tiaras, line up the trumpeters,
arrange for the worshippers. Their time might have arrived ahead of
everyone's schedule, save for their father's. It is happening.
</P>
<P>
   They were at it again on Sunday. This time it was Serena
Williams taking home another title, outlasting Lindsay Davenport in
the final of the estyle.com Classic at Manhattan Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   That meant in the past two days, Williams had defeated the
players ranked the No. 1 (Martina Hingis) and No. 2 (Davenport) in
the world. This after having taken off the last five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Like she needs a lot of work?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can get a lot better,'' Williams said. ``I haven't even
begun. This is just a warmup.''
</P>
<P>
   Goose bumps just shot up the collective backs of every
professional women's tennis player.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to this, Venus had won the last three significant WTA
events, including Wimbledon. Serena, of course, is the defending
U.S. Open champion.
</P>
<P>
   It's getting so the only player who can beat a Williams is
another Williams.
</P>
<P>
   That seldoms happens, however, since they have this nifty way of
almost never playing in the same tournament, unless it's a Grand
Slam. But they can afford to play as much as they like and remain
sharp, having the greatest practice partners in the world _ each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like playing the best all the time,'' Serena said.
</P>
<P>
   They serve better and return harder than probably any other
player on the tour. Any rough parts to their games have been
polished by their last two years on the tour. They are great right
now and getting better.
</P>
<P>
   Strong and powerful, their finely muscled physiques are almost
intimidating in their single-strap tennis outfits. Tennis might
never have seen any players quite like them. Serena is 18, Venus 20
and they're already at another level.
</P>
<P>
   Others are trying their best, but you have to wonder if the
Willliamses are getting into their heads.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, Davenport should have won Sunday. After taking the
first set 6-4, she was serving and leading 4-3 in the second set
and lost. She was serving and leading 6-5 in the third set and
lost, then got swamped 7-1 in the tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport is too experienced a player to presume nerves were a
factor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember a match when I had so many chances,''
Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport said she played well, and really she did, except for
those uncharacteristic 13 double faults.
</P>
<P>
   But much of that credit has to go to the purple-clad Williams.
There's extra pressure to make your second serve a good one when
you know it can come back at you like something conceived at JPL.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said her feet just weren't moving right. Said that
mentally she just wasn't there. Said she just didn't play well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how I won,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That has to be scary to the rest of the tour, that Williams can
think her game a mess, play for the first time in a month, and
still beat the best players in the world not named Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The rankings are a bit of a joke, anyway. They're based on a
point system, and the Williams sisters aren't playing in enough
tournaments to be ranked first and second.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Venus is third and Serena seventh, but everyone
realizes the top two players in the world are a couple of sisters
reared on the city courts of Compton.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit the ball hard and serve very well,'' Davenport said.
``They're tough. They have a lot of similarities to their game.
Right now, Venus is more consistent. But they both have such
dangerous games.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Open is three weeks away. Serena, who predicted her
victory last year, is not backing off this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know who I think is going to win _ the lady in purple,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   If she doesn't, look for her older sister. The Williams era is
at hand. Next stop, domination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
