<HEADER>
A0510 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-ROCKLAND-COUNTY-10     08-13 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ROCKLAND-COUNTY-1055(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SMALL COUNTY WITH AN IDENTITY CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMAPO, N.Y. _ Upstate New Yorkers think of Rockland County as
downstate, while downstate New Yorkers think of it as upstate, if
they think about it at all. Many know it simply as the first rest
stop after they cross the Tappan Zee Bridge: Rockland, then New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   At just 176 square miles, Rockland is the smallest county in the
state (after the five boroughs of New York City) and one that is
often slighted because of its precarious foothold west of the
Hudson River above New Jersey. Even some of its own residents say
that Rockland is just the county you have to go through to get
somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Yet geography is only partly to blame for this identity crisis.
Although Rockland has pockets of wealth, it has never wielded the
political muscle of Nassau, or enjoyed the same cachet as
Westchester, its better-known neighbor across the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   It has never produced a governor, and its most honored native,
James A. Farley, the postmaster general under President Franklin D.
Roosevelt, moved to New York City and was buried in Westchester.
``It's another thing to be chagrined about,'' said Thomas F.X.
Casey, the Rockland County historian.
</P>
<P>
   Now an increasing number of Rockland's citizens are seeking
recognition and respect through a surge of civic activism:
protests, town meetings, even bold threats to withhold tax money
from the Metropolitan Transportation Authority if more local trains
and buses are not provided.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, many other citizens are fighting to
preserve the serene landscape and quiet charm that have long
defined their county. Like so many places in the Hudson River
Valley, Rockland seems caught between two contradictory impulses as
it tries to decide whether it is ready for a larger role in the
world and the headaches that come along with growth and visibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who preferred when Rockland was forgotten,''
said Craig H. Long, a police detective and historian for the town
of Ramapo. ``They were content and didn't seek that recognition,
because it was like a well-kept secret here. When you open up the
county, you invite more problems. Some residents feel the worst
thing that ever happened was the Tappan Zee.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockland _ the name is thought to have been inspired by the
rocky soil _ was carved out of Orange County over two centuries ago
by British colonists and thrived for a time as an outpost for
shipbuilders and manufacturers. But most of the county remained
farmland until the Tappan Zee Bridge was built in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opening of the Tappan Zee changed everything,'' said
Casey, the county historian. ``It changed Rockland from a
semirural, sleepy county to a much larger county.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two-thirds of the county is now covered with industries,
subdivisions and roads, while much of the rest has been preserved
as parks or open space. In the past fiscal year, those industries
created 3,100 new jobs, mainly in services and sales. This gave
Rockland the second-highest job-growth rate in the state, after
Putnam County.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Rockland's citizens earn a comfortable living; the
median income for a family of four is $82,400 a year, compared with
$56,200 in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Yet despite its growing affluence and visibility, Rockland
continues to be dwarfed by its neighbors. The county has 284,022
residents, compared with 7.4 million in New York City, 1.3 million
each in Nassau and Suffolk, and 905,572 in Westchester.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated Rockland residents say their concerns and issues are
routinely ignored by numbers-driven media organizations and
government agencies. ``Let me put it to you this way,'' said Paul
Adler, a real estate agent who is chairman of the county's
Democratic Party. ``One of the biggest thrills in Rockland is when
the Channel 2 weatherman mentions we're going to have rain. Unlike
Westchester or Long Island, the only time we make the news is when
there's a murder or a flood.''
</P>
<P>
   They are still seething, for instance, over being assigned an
845 area code in June while Westchester was allowed to keep the
longstanding 914 prefix. Though Rockland officials protested
loudly, the Public Service Commission in Albany decided that more
people would have been inconvenienced by the area code in
Westchester being changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the common goal was to minimize any disruptions,''
said David Flanagan, a spokesman for the commission. ``Westchester
had a greater number of businesses and cellular-phone users that
would have been disrupted.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockland loyalists saw this as yet another affront. ``I'm pretty
upset,'' said Ron Javer, a media account executive from Ramapo, who
likened it to being stuck away in a corner all over again. ``Where
is 845?'' he asked. ``Montana?''
</P>
<P>
   Such complaints are nothing new, of course, in a sprawling state
where 62 counties compete for the same resources. And for all its
grumbling, Rockland actually fares better than many other counties
because it is viewed as a swing district in state elections.
Albany's political leaders actively court its voters _ 70,912
enrolled Democrats and 40,900 enrolled Republicans _ because they
are known to stray across party lines.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Thomas Morahan, a Rockland Republican who is running
for re-election this fall, said Gov. George Pataki and other
Republican leaders had been helpful in supporting county projects.
He pointed to $840,000 in state funds this year for refurbishing
downtown areas in the villages of Suffern, Spring Valley and
Haverstraw. ``While we don't get as much as Westchester, we're not
totally abandoned here,'' he said. ``We are not the poor cousin.''
</P>
<P>
   State and county officials say it is nearly impossible to
pinpoint Rockland's total portion of the state budget, because it
receives money under various programs and grants. But federal money
is tracked more easily, and many county leaders contend that they
have been shortchanged in that.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan S. Karben, a Democratic county legislator from Ramapo, said
his research found that Rockland received only 1 percent of the
federal dollars spent annually in New York even though it had 1.5
percent of the state's population.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a need for a much more aggressive style of
leadership,'' he said. ``I think a new generation of leaders are
going to demand that Rockland get better. I'm not content with
crumbs.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One long-running skirmish has been over what county leaders see
as a chronic shortage of bus and train service. After years of
complaints, Rockland legislators passed a resolution in May that
sought state approval to drop out of the MTA, which coordinates
public transportation for New York City and seven downstate
counties.
</P>
<P>
   C. Scott Vanderhoef, the county executive, said that Rockland
contributed $33.6 million in taxes to the authority in 1998 but
received only $11.7 million worth of service and capital
improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pay attention to enormous numbers,'' said Vanderhoef.
``For them, this is a small issue; for us, it's big. If you're
doing bottom-line stuff, Rockland has to fight harder and yell
louder.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Boylan, the MTA's deputy executive director, said
Rockland's size had not been a factor in decisions. The MTA has
continued to improve its services, he said, including pledging $41
million over the next five years to expand and refurbish train
service west of the Hudson in Rockland and Orange.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the MTA has contributed $53 million to New Jersey
Transit for a train station in Secaucus that will be used as a
transfer point by Rockland residents commuting to New York City.
``There are periods when member counties may get more than they put
in, and some periods when they may put in more,'' he said. ``When
they put in money, it's for the benefit of the mobility of the
entire region.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockland's citizens have not always defended their local
interests so vigorously, and they say their county has suffered for
that. First, the Tappan Zee Bridge ushered in traffic and
pollution. Then industries created environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Environmental Protection Agency has designated four
Superfund sites in Rockland (compared with two in Westchester and
15 in Nassau) over the last two decades. While one of the Rockland
sites has been fully cleaned, the others remain hazardous. At the
newest site in Hillburn, Hudson Technologies spilled 7,500 pounds
of freon last year that made its way into the drinking-water
supply. Four wells had to be closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm at ground zero again,'' said Geoff Welch, a
musician who moved to Ramapo in 1981 to escape the pollution and
crowds of New York City, only to spend his free time researching
Rockland's environmental issues. ``That's why I'm standing my
ground and fighting. I could move further out, but the same thing
would happen all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   Welch and many others have banded together to preserve their way
of life from the dual threats of development and the ambitions of
fellow Rockland citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In the villages of South Nyack and Nyack, many residents are
fighting a proposed expansion of the Tappan Zee Bridge in their
back yard. But elsewhere in the county, others say it would help
alleviate congestion. A state task force appointed by Pataki has
advocated replacing the aging structure with a wider, $4 billion
bridge and rail system to accommodate the growing traffic.
</P>
<P>
   In Ramapo, a dozen community groups are trying to block
construction of two power plants that they say would drain their
water supply and ruin their view of Torne Mountain, a spot
immortalized by the Hudson River School painters. Yet at the same
time, two other power plants proposed for the town of Haverstraw
have received a different welcome. Many residents there say the
plants will generate more jobs and income from taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Such contradictory impulses have divided Rockland's citizens and
perplexed outsiders who do not know what to make of the mixed
signals. Does the county want growth and more transportation links
to New York City? Or does it really want to hold onto the last
vestiges of a rural life that once thrived here? There seems to be
no consensus.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, Welch and his neighbors in Ramapo showed
off a billboard warning: ``Stop the power plants. Once it's up,
it's over.'' But several of the neighbors hastened to add that they
were not trying to stop economic growth, just the problems that
come along with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``People zip by on the highway and they don't realize the
history and the wildlife in this county,'' said Welch as he pointed
with pride to the craggy peak of Torne Mountain rising above
low-lying buildings. ``We have a lot of work to do to bring it to
their attention and give it the respect it deserves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
