r a BC-DNC-MEDIA-LADN     08-13 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-MEDIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL WRITERS RIP INTO L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HARRISON SHEPPARD 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ On the eve of the Democratic National Convention,
the barbs sharpened as political writers _ with nothing else to do
_ turned their attention to the event's host city.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't until I left and came back that I realized every
cliche about this place is true,'' former White House press
secretary Dee Dee Myers, an Angeleno herself who worked for former
Mayor Tom Bradley, wrote in Sunday's Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weather is great. The culture is superficial. The roads
are as clogged as the bookstores are empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically, this town is more of a cash cow than a think
tank, and, truth be told, it's easier to find people who can wax
knowledgeable about Brad (Pitt) and Jennifer (Aniston)'s wedding
than about the pros and cons of privatizing Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles, it seems, is the city that the rest of the nation
loves to hate.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's jealousy, but nearly every out-of-town writer who
traveled to Los Angeles this week for the Democratic National
Convention has delighted in repeating every stereotype ever
circulated about ``La-La Land.''
</P>
<P>
   We're superficial. We're all wannabe actors. We're politically
apathetic. Not that they're completely untrue, but it hurts when
others say it.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a sampling:
</P>
<P>
   From The Associated Press: ``As L.A. events go, a political
convention doesn't rate all that high on the local excitement
meter. `It's not the Lakers, you know?' notes one native.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is in town. A man who might be next is on his
way. And everyone who's anyone in the Democratic Party is crawling
the city. But at Venice Beach, the hubbub barely rates a blip on
the radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's surfing to be done. A handball tournament in progress.
Tanning to get to.
</P>
<P>
   `We just don't care,' aspiring actress J. Lynn Hoffman says as
she drags her surfboard into the waves.''
</P>
<P>
   From APBnews.com, a Web site about public safety issues: ``The
Democrats are coming to the City of Angels, and so are the hookers.
Police have noticed an increase of about 50 percent in the number
of prostitutes offering their wares on two major local streets,
Sunset Boulevard and Santa Monica Boulevard.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the broadcast media, Sunday was a day of preparations,
more Los Angeles psychoanalysis and navel gazing.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimate policy wonks tuned to C-SPAN, which has been
highlighting Los Angeles issues in its own unique style _ hearing
directly from the source, rather than through a reporter's filter.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, last week, Richard Close, chairman of the San Fernando
Valley secession movement got half an hour to explain why Valley
cityhood would be better for the Valley and Los Angeles. County
Supervisor Gloria Molina was on C-SPAN to discuss Latino issues.
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday, Los Angeles Daily News Managing Editor Ron Kaye
answered questions from across the country about Los Angeles and
national politics.
</P>
<P>
   One caller from Sarasota, Fla., a former Angeleno, described Los
Angeles as a ``city that hasn't found itself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it does find itself. but I found it's easier to get
directions on how to locate places in Poland than it is in Los
Angeles,'' the caller said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaye agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They blew it,'' he said about the city's political leadership.
``They let it sprawl. Freeways stopped being built by the early
'60s. The congestion on surface streets during most of the day is
nearly impossible. There's no public transportation system that's
effective despite billions and billions of federal dollars that
have really been squandered in the subway to nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he added: ``I couldn't think of ever giving it up or
leaving. There's something worth fighting about in L.A., and I
think a lot of people share that now.''
</P>
<P>
   In the ultimate media navel-gazing, C-SPAN turned its camera on
itself, interviewing its own convention director, Gary Ellenwood,
and broadcasting the location of every camera inside Staples
Center.
</P>
<P>
   C-SPAN is serving as the pool camera inside Staples Center,
sending its video feeds to the other broadcast networks, rather
than having thousands of cameras outnumber delegates in the hall.
</P>
<P>
   So it must have been unnerving to viewers when, in the middle of
the report about the network's own cameras, the screen went black.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just lost our signal,'' said in-studio host Susan Swain,
maintaining her composure. ``How 'bout that? Right in the middle of
showing off, we lost our signal. ... Isn't that ironic?''
</P>
<P>
   The signal came back in less than a minute, however _ to the
relief of the crew.
</P>
<P>
   Said Ellenwood: ``I hope it's not a shade of things to come.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
</TEXT>
