<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fisher pushing Titans to take final step
</P>
<P>
   By JOHN McCLAIN
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ When Tennessee entertains St. Louis in a
preseason rematch of Super Bowl XXXIV tonight at Adelphia Coliseum,
it will be the Titans' first appearance on Monday Night Football
since Nov. 21, 1994, when Jeff Fisher made his debut as interim
coach of the Houston Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher has come a long way since he was elevated from defensive
coordinator to head coach in place of the fired Jack Pardee. His
coaching career began with a 1-5 record and $300,000 salary.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, the Titans finished 13-3 and reached the Super
Bowl for the first time in franchise history, losing 23-16 to the
Rams. Owner Bud Adams rewarded Fisher with a new $10-million
contract.
</P>
<P>
   In his sixth full season with the franchise, Fisher is trying to
push the team into taking one step more than last season, when
receiver Kevin Dyson came within one yard of forcing the first
overtime in Super Bowl history. The next step would be a Super Bowl
XXXV victory at Tampa, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a better team right now than we were at this time last
season, but the book's closed on last season,'' Fisher said last
week at the Titans' training camp. ``If we start thinking about
Tampa, we're selling ourselves short. This is a step-by-step
process that builds from week to week.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming off a landmark season in which the Titans set a franchise
record for victories, defeated AFC Central champion Jacksonville
three times, made the playoffs as a wild-card entry and went
farther than any team in the 40-year history of the franchise, they
are favored to repeat as AFC champion in many preseason forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher insists with a straight face that the Jaguars should be
favored because they are the defending AFC Central champions and
posted a conference-best 14-2 record. Asked if carrying the
favorite's tag with Indianapolis and Jacksonville, both of whom
were eliminated from the playoffs by Tennessee, provides extra
incentive to his players, Fisher said, ``The way the Super Bowl
ended was a motivating factor to come back and work even harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we lost, we wished the season could start the next
day. (Running back) Eddie (George) was quoted as saying he'd pass
up the Pro Bowl if he could start working immediately on next
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Next season has arrived. Because of changes in the coaching
staff and on the roster, this isn't the same team that provided so
many thrills making the playoffs for the first time since 1993. The
coaches and players believe this can be a better team.
</P>
<P>
   ``That '93 team was real good, but we were hurt by guys having
their own agendas,'' said offensive tackle Brad Hopkins, who was a
rookie on that 12-4 team that lost in the second round. ``We don't
have any prima donnas on this team. That type of attitude helped us
get this far, and it can help us get farther.''
</P>
<P>
   Gone from last season's team are offensive coordinator Les
Steckel, quarterbacks coach Bart Andrus, linebackers coach O'Neill
Gilbert, offensive tackle Jon Runyan, outside linebacker Joe
Bowden, middle linebacker Barron Wortham, cornerback Steve Jackson,
defensive tackle Josh Evans, free safety Anthony Dorsett and tight
end Jackie Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Fisher has brought in offensive coordinator Mike Heimerdinger,
receiver Carl Pickens, middle linebacker Randall Godfrey, offensive
tackle Fred Miller, outside linebacker Keith Bulluck and defensive
tackle Robaire Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally getting to the Super Bowl speaks volumes about where
we are as a team,'' Hopkins said. ``Coming so close at the end has
made us even hungrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've got to be more consistent and win more
convincingly, leaving no doubt who the best team is. We've got to
be unbeatable at home and steal a few wins on the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Titans moved into Adelphia Coliseum and Baptist
Sports Park, a state-of-the-art stadium and practice facility. They
were 8-0 at home and 9-1 in the AFC Central. The only division team
to defeat them was Baltimore (41-14).
</P>
<P>
   The players and coaches are excited about the addition of
Heimerdinger, the former Rice assistant who left Denver, where he
won two Super Bowl rings as the receivers coach.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fisher's philosophy of controlling the ball by
utilizing George as much as possible won't change, Heimerdinger has
added some wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants me to throw the ball down the field more,''
quarterback Steve McNair said. ``The receivers are more disciplined
in their routes. They'll be in the same place at the right time. It
helps me to know where everybody's going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   If injury-prone receiver Yancey Thigpen recovers from ankle
surgery and manages to stay healthy for the first time since
signing with the Titans, he would form a dangerous threesome with
Pickens and Dyson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Yancey's healthy, we could be unstoppable,'' McNair said.
</P>
<P>
   This season, opponents will have extra motivation to prepare for
the Titans. They get down to serious business Sept. 3 when the
Titans visit Buffalo. It will be a Sunday night rematch of the
Music City Miracle, the wild-card playoff game in Nashville that
featured one of the most incredible finishes in league history.
</P>
<P>
   On a trick play with time running out, Dyson scored the winning
touchdown on a kickoff return.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Titans are hoping they don't have to rely on
gadget plays to win any games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had confident teams in the past, but that confidence turned
out to be unfounded until last season,'' said guard Bruce Matthews,
who is playing in his 18th season. ``In the past, we earned a label
by our performances in the playoffs, and last year, we got rid of
that label.''
</P>
<P>
   For those fans unfamiliar with NFL history, when the Titans were
the Oilers, they were known as the biggest playoff chokers in
history.
</P>
<P>
   No one is sure how good the Titans will be this season. They
finished 13-3 after three consecutive 8-8 records. Backup
quarterback Neil O'Donnell won't make a prediction about their
record, but he believes the Titans have an excellent chance to win
Super Bowl XXXV.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell turned down an offer from Tampa Bay, another team
favored to reach the Super Bowl, to remain with Tennessee. With the
Buccaneers, he would have earned $2.5 million more in base salary
over two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came here to win a championship more than anything,''
O'Donnell said. ``When you look back, and it's all said and done,
you want to say you played for a championship team. I have two AFC
championship rings. I don't have a Super Bowl ring.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
