 ufvj 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; BYLINE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By Anne Barnard
</P>
<P>
   &LR; GLOBE STAFF
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Roark performed sur-L gery on hundreds of patients in L
Ohio, Michigan, and Canada before supervisors learned his medical
de- gree was bogus.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen applicants for a gastro- enterology fellowship at the
Uni- versity of Pittsburgh falsely L claimed they had published
re-L search papers.
</P>
<P>
   The chief financial officer of L UMass Memorial Health Care was
demoted to vice president last L month when his bachelor's and L
master's degrees were exposed as fictional.
</P>
<P>
   Falsified credentials have be-L come a nagging problem for the L
health care industry, helping to L spur a whole new cadre of back-
ground-checking firms in recent L years to stem the tide.
</P>
<P>
   Although executive search L  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  firms say
resume fibs are at epi- demic levels across professions, the
problem is particularly worrisome in the health care industry,
where lapses in integrity can not only em- barrass a company but
also endan- ger a patient. Roark, for example, has been sued by a
man who says his botched surgery left him with no feeling in one
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Now, UMass Memorial's will-L ingness to keep Michael Greene on
as vice president has some critics calling for more serious
attention to the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Massachusetts, two areas in which we are national leaders,
edu- cation and medicine, are also two areas where qualifications
and per- sonal integrity are paramount,'' L said Nancy Achin
Sullivan, execu- tive director of the state Board of Registration
in Medicine. ``I think we should expect better.''
</P>
<P>
   While Greene never pretended  &UR; &AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP;&AMP; &LR;  to be a
doctor _ a more severe of- fense in most people's books _ some feel
UMass Memorial set a bad ex- ample by deciding to demote him, not
fire him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am stunned. It is incompre- hensible to me,'' said Peter
George, a headhunter for Management Re- cruiters International who
said he has located 12 new hires for Mass- achusetts General
Hospital in the past year. ``They should demote L him to
unemployed.''
</P>
<P>
   But UMass Memorial trustees and executives have essentially L
pleaded ``no harm, no foul.'' Al-L though Greene's falsified resume
is regrettable, they say, he has been good for the institution.
Greene de- clined to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   The brilliant outsider who lacks the right pedigree but bluffs a
way into success is almost as much an American icon as the Horatio
Alger hero who rises from humble origins by following the rules.
Resume-L bluffing is often viewed as a victim-H less crime,
something ``everybody does,'' job recruiters say.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, claiming false credentials or omitting negatives from a
re-L sume can have real, harmful conse- quences, say physicians,
headhunt- ers, and educators. The harm, they say, ranges from the
physical, such as subjecting patients to treatment by phony
doctors, to the intangible, such as devaluing the sacrifices of
people who honestly earn degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said the Massachusetts medical board disciplined 17
doc- tors between 1995 and 1999 for em- bellishing credentials _
nothing L nearly as extreme as faking a medi- cal degree _ or
failing to disclose disciplinary actions or malpractice lawsuits
against them. The doctors were fined between $2,500 and L $5,000 as
part of the board's mis- sion of ``protecting the public,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with non-physician em-L ployees, teaching hospitals,
includ- ing UMass Memorial, which is af- filiated with the
University of L Massachusetts Medical School, L have a special
responsibility to up- hold academic integrity, Sullivan L said.
</P>
<P>
   Witt/Kieffer, a national execu- tive search firm that
specializes in health care and has Brigham and Women's Hospital
among its cli-L ents, automatically rejects candi-L dates,
physicians or not, who are found to have falsified a resume,
spokeswoman Susan Nalepa said.
</P>
<P>
   Health systems have a ``sacred trust'' to provide care, she
said, and the leader of the system must be ``regarded as having
very high per- sonal integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Recruiter and vice president L Emanuel D. Berger said applicants
should be straightforward: ``Most executive search consultants are
L willing to look at an unusual candi- date, perhaps without a
degree, if they have other qualifications.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene built his 20-year career partly on claims he had a
bachelor's  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  degree from the University of L
Massachusetts and a master's of L business administration from L
Northeastern University, schools L he attended but from which he
did not graduate.
</P>
<P>
   The fiction helped get him a L two-year stint as top
administrator at Cambridge City Hospital in the 1980s and a
succession of jobs at University of Massachusetts Medi- cal Center,
which he helped shep- herd through a merger with private Memorial
Health Care. Questioned by his bosses last month after the
Worcester Telegram &AMP; Gazette L raised questions, Greene offered L
his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of accepting it, chief ex- ecutive officer Dr. Arthur
Russo L said Greene was a brilliant adminis- trator who had made a
youthful L mistake, and demoted him to vice president.
</P>
<P>
   John O'Brien, who worked un- der Greene at the Cambridge hos-
pital and is now its CEO, declined to pass judgment on the UMass
deci- sion. ``Every (health care) system has to make a decision
like that on their own,'' he said, adding that L Greene was a
``hard-driving, re-L sults-oriented'' administrator.
</P>
<P>
   That is beside the point, said L Barmak Nessirian, an analyst
with the American Association of Colle- giate Registrars and
Admissions L Officers, which represents 9,300 L higher education
administrators in the United States and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have all the sympathy in the world with people who feel that
L their performance in itself explains their qualificaton,'' he
said. ``It may be that there are plenty of positions that currently
require a degree L that should not. But the college de- gree
represents a significant com- mitment of resources in terms of cost
and in terms of academic ef- fort. People shouldn't simply decide
that ... they can essentially award it to themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, Harvard L Medical School fired a middle man-
ager who was found to have exag- gerated educational credentials L
and prior work experience, said L Don Gibbons, director of communi-
cations. He said the school checks references but does not
routinely verify the college degrees of appli- cants for
non-medical positions.
</P>
<P>
   The physician who finally L caught Roark _ by carrying out a
routine check with an American L Medical Association database when
he applied for a job _ said most phy- sicians would be perturbed if
they had to work under a hospital execu- tive with a faked record.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to think you've affiliated yourself with an
organiza- tion that's not as assiduous as they might be in checking
one's creden- tials or qualifications,'' said Dr. Lin- da Nash,
chief of medicine at L Ingham Regional Medical Center in Lansing,
Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Her experience with Roark has prompted her to lobby for tighter
credential-checking requirements L for hospitals. She is not alone:
L James B. Stewart's 1999 book L  &UR; -------------------- &LR;  ``Blind
Eye'' criticized doctors for failing to police their own in the L
case of Michael Swango, the physi- cian accused of killing patients
in a series of hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Roark practiced medicine for 10 years, although he never
attended medical school and was dropped L from two residency
programs for inadequate performance. In 1998, he was sentenced to
six to 14 years in prison by a judge who compared his conduct to
sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   Even criminal background L checks have their limitations. Hen-
ry M. Jiminian, a 33-year-old cleri- cal worker at Massachusetts
Gen- eral Hospital, was arraigned last L week on charges of killing
a man in New York eight years ago. The L charges hadn't been filed
in 1995, when he was hired, and the hospi- tal's routine criminal
background L check wouldn't have caught an out- of-state offense.
</P>
<P>
   Companies afraid they could be sued for hiring people with false
L credentials have fueled the growth of an entire industry of
credential- checking firms, Nessirian said. L Thousands of
falsifiers are caught each month through calls to regis- trars'
offices, according to a five- year-old study.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Connors, of Risk Manage- ment Advisors in Stoneham, said
his firm does about 4,500 credential checks a year, half in the
health L care industry, and finds significant misinformation in
about one-fourth of the cases.
</P>
<P>
   If an applicant lies about cre- dentials, he said, ``how can you
be- lieve them when they come to you with information that's
critical to the health of the company?''
</P>
<P>
   Local credential-checking firms have plenty of stories to tell
about bogus health care applicants.
</P>
<P>
   According to Paul Byron, senior vice president of LCF Associates
in Braintree, which charges $500 to $5,000 per search, one
applicant for a senior position claimed he had L been blinded in a
boating accident for 12 years and regained his sight through
surgery. In fact, Byron L said, he'd been in jail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufauthor &LR;
</P>
