u a BC-BLUES-STREET-NYT &LR;      08-13 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLUES-STREET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BLUESMAN AT THE CROSSROADS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., S.C.)   By JOHN W. FOUNTAIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The blues flow with his fingers. Pressing skin to
steel strings and wood, the fingers make the city night wail with
the music of the bluesman and his Manhattan blues band.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Eugene Linen. He is both man and band, with a
curious ensemble of guitar, harmonica and recorded backup band
rolled into one, and powered by a car battery. Linen plays at a
cozy spot most summer nights, just off Broadway. He plays the
washboard to boot.
</P>
<P>
   Born in South Carolina, Linen, a chubby-cheeked 63-year-old with
neatly trimmed salt-and-pepper beard, is not anyone blues
enthusiasts would know. He is no less a bluesman. Sometimes a
bricklayer by day, a ``one-man blues band'' by night. His stage is
a slice of curb on the east side of Seventh Avenue, between 49th
and 50th streets, and halfway between the subway music circuit and
the Manhattan club scene.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of musicians like Linen play on the streets on New
York. There is something that gets Linen's juices jangling,
something that has led him each summer over the last four years to
make the nightly drive from Harlem to star in his own Midtown
sideshow. Is it the $20 bill here, the $10 there, or just the
jingle of spare change that patrons dump into Linen's tin can?
</P>
<P>
   Or something else?
</P>
<P>
   When he connects and the licks fall like rain, when his fingers
and the frets are in harmony, and the blues and the man are one, he
sways.
</P>
<P>
   On a mild Thursday night, the bluesman sits in the glare, on a
self-constructed, uncomplicated stage.
</P>
<P>
   It is late. The crowd on the street is a little thin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hardly anybody is out tonight,'' says Linen. ``But you can
never tell, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   The melody rises in the wind at the edge of Times Square, a
bluesy soundtrack to a life's story.
</P>
<P>
   But there are gaps in this life's song. Missing verses and
dissonant chords, between the past and present, places and faces
that a man omits when telling his life to a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   But within his seasons of picking potatoes on Southern
plantations and his days of gambling before becoming a gospel
preacher lies the story of who he is, and the reason he plays the
blues.
</P>
<P>
   The conversation turns to the past.
</P>
<P>
   It was hours before the red sun rose on the white man's
plantation on Wadmalaw Island, S.C. Half asleep, the little boy
ambled toward the field, holding his mother's hand. He was the
fourth of eight children. With his family, he plucked potatoes
until long after sundown.
</P>
<P>
   He was in the fourth grade when full-time work in the fields
beckoned, and he had not yet learned to read. At 13, work made him
a man. Back then, pubescent boys without a whisker suddenly
matriculated to manhood. At week's end, he handed his earnings to
his mother, Annie Linen, a God-fearing Methodist.
</P>
<P>
   By age 14, Linen had joined the migrant worker circuit with his
older siblings, who worked and sent their money back home, his
youngest brother, Leroy Linen, remembered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since I was a kid, they were traveling to and fro, trying
to provide for the family,'' Leroy Linen said. ``Jobs were not as
plentiful, so there was a great need.'' Especially after their
father, Ernest Linen, died in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, Linen moved to New York to work in
construction, the beginning of the trip that led to the music.
</P>
<P>
   It's 10:20 p.m. The music is loud enough to draw attention, low
enough to keep the police from calling it a disturbance.
</P>
<P>
   Linen plays a range of blues, from the Mississippi Delta-born
slow and mournful twang to spicy soul-stirrers reminiscent of
gospel music, along with finger-snapping melodies. He might play
John Lee Hooker. Or B.B. King. Sometimes even a little rock 'n'
roll. But even when Linen is playing to a track of ``Johnny B.
Goode,'' his rendition is slower, less fluid, less like rock, more
like blues.
</P>
<P>
   His playing is not always clean. Sometimes his fingers seem
sticky, sluggish. Sometimes the notes buzz, until Linen warms up
like a car engine on a cold winter morning. Then Sally cries, and
sometimes she talks. At other times, she sings.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, their music has fallen on the ears of neighbors:
the Federal Express deliveryman who stops by occasionally. The
officers who know him as a regular and nod as they walk by. The
roving street vendors with their cases of sunglasses and fake $10
Rolexes, who pause as they pass, if only to steal a peek into his
tin can.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years I've been hearing him,'' says Peter Petrucci, 26, a
manager at the Sweet Factory candy store across the street. ``The
tourists enjoy it. He's pretty good. Sometimes it's good for
business. It makes people happy and they want to buy candy.''
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, Linen's listeners drift in from the crowds that flow up
and down Seventh Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Linen started playing the guitar at 18. How he learned to play
is one story. How he learned to read is another.
</P>
<P>
   He was about 19, and at a Salvation Army center, staring at a
Bible. A woman assumed he was reading and gave him the Bible to
keep. That night, Linen placed it under his pillow. A few hours
later, he says, the Lord roused him from bed and told him to read.
</P>
<P>
   But through the years, whenever Linen had trouble with words,
his friends showed him the light. He committed each word to memory.
He did the same with the lessons he found on the pages of the
guitar and harmonica books.
</P>
<P>
   He says he first played the streets of New York about four years
ago with a friend. Linen eventually took up the solo act.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting now in a coffee shop on a gentrified corner of Harlem,
he laughs and his eyes become slits as he recalls the way his
relatives jump and scream, ``big Gene, big Gene,'' whenever they
see him coming. But the laughter and words disappear inside his
paper cup when his thoughts shift to his divorce, to the life he
has since made with a woman he calls his fiancee, and to his days
as a fire-and-brimstone preacher. It is not clear why he rarely
ever plays gospel anymore, or why he has not been home to South
Carolina in a few years. Half his siblings are dead now, and so is
his mother, who died in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   He looks forward to going to Wadmalaw again soon, to driving up
the road that leads to the house of his youngest brother, Leroy, a
magistrate for the last 20 years who has a street named in his
honor _ ``Judge Linen Lane,'' the bluesman says with pride.
</P>
<P>
   Leroy Linen wishes his brother would come home for good. ``I
always wanted him to be able to come home and enjoy some of the
fruits of his labor,'' he says. ``I always ask him, `When you
coming home?' '' But he never answers. ``It appears he's in love
with the bright lights of the big city.''
</P>
<P>
   Out on Seventh Avenue, an older woman approaches from the south.
``All right now, all right now,'' she says. The woman slows, then
passes by, sashaying, caught up in the rhythm. She turns and walks
back, drops a fistful of coins into Linen's can. ``All right now,''
she says again, smiling, feeling the connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, brother,'' she says, smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Linen peeks up from his straw hat, his face spreading in a
smile. ``OK,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The blues flow with his fingers. And Linen starts to sway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
