<SLUG> BC-REAL-LIFE-COMEDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METROPOLITAN DIARY 
</HEADLINE>
   By ENID NEMY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A weekly column featuring readers' reports on life in the Big
Apple.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   I was sitting in the front of one of those new double-length
79th Street crosstown buses heading west when a young woman got on
and sat in the first seat behind the driver. Her cell phone rang.
She answered and then looked to the back of the bus and waved.
Seated across from her, I was privy to the conversation, and this
is what transpired.
</P>
<P>
   The man she had waved at, obviously a friend who knew her
number, was calling her from the far rear of the bus. After
exchanging pleasantries, she explained that she was sitting in the
front because she was going to Park Avenue, and as there was no
stop there, she was getting off at Lexington. Leaving by the front
door was closer for her.
</P>
<P>
   He was also getting off at Lexington, but since he was going to
the Lexington Avenue subway, the back exit was closer for him.
Neither one considered moving seats. As they approached Lexington,
they said their cell-phone goodbyes: The young woman signed off
with ``Next time we're on a bus together, give me a call.''
</P>
<P>
   They both got off and went their separate ways. They had saved a
few steps and missed any personal contact.
</P>
<P>
   _ ANGELA OSBORNE
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn friends define ``nanosecond'' as the amount of time
that lapses between traffic lights turning green and someone
honking his horn.
</P>
<P>
   I had a recent example of that as I was driving down Franklin
Street. The traffic light at the next intersection turned amber and
I slowly came to a stop. There was a single car waiting at the
cross street _ no cars in front or behind. But like Pavlov's dog,
as soon as the light turned green, the driver honked his horn, then
quickly made a left turn and drove away. I wonder if he even
realized what he had done.
</P>
<P>
   _ FRED J. HOWARD
</P>
<P>
   CLASSIFIED INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   To discover a place in which to reside
</P>
<P>
   may require decoding a classified.
</P>
<P>
   An EIK with a nu, lge Kelvinator,
</P>
