</P>
<P>
   for nothing's quite clear excepting the price.
</P>
<P>
   _ A.H. BLOCK
</P>
<P>
   A month before prom time, Bee Johnson spotted a freshwater pearl
necklace, bracelet and earrings that she thought would be a perfect
gift for her 17-year-old granddaughter, Claire Johnson. The letter
she received, after the traditional thanks, went on to say:
</P>
<P>
   ``Today I had the incredible surprise of finding out that I was
going to get to eat breakfast with Dennis Hastert, the speaker of
the House. I was just wondering what jewelry I should wear, when
your package came. It couldn't have been better timing! I'm not
getting too dressed up, though; I knew you wouldn't approve of me
getting all dressed up for a Republican!!''
</P>
<P>
   The advice offered on the sign seen by Diana Binder in the
window of Schatzie's Prime Meats on Madison Avenue might be worth
considering:
</P>
<P>
   Invest in our stocks:
</P>
<P>
   Chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   Veal stock
</P>
<P>
   Beef stock
</P>
<P>
   Lamb stock.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   It was a bright and cool day when I saw a small elderly woman,
somewhat shabby but neat, leaning on a late-model Cadillac, holding
a paper coffee cup. She looked very much like my long-departed
mother and I couldn't help but smile at her. She returned the
smile. My eyes began to fill with impending tears. I dug into my
pocket and gathered about $2 worth of quarters saved for street
telephone use, walked up to her and emptied the coins in her
container.
</P>
<P>
   To my horror _ and hers _ the container was filled with coffee.
She had a few words for me that I know my mother would never have
used. I stood motionless as she opened the car door and drove away,
leaving the spilled container and the coins at my feet. Beware of
bearing unwanted gifts.
</P>
<P>
   _ PAUL GREGORY
</P>
<P>
   GOSSIP
</P>
<P>
   a fragment
</P>
<P>
   becomes a tale
</P>
<P>
   a minnow
</P>
<P>
   grown into a whale.
</P>
<P>
   _ MYRTLE E. CAVALLO
</P>
<P>
   Dear Diary:
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those very hot days and the Long Island Rail Road
car, still at Pennsylvania Station, was sweltering.
</P>
<P>
   Cadets from the Police Academy, still dressed in their uniforms
and with duffel and garment bags scattered about, were in the car
where I was sitting. They were all basically slumped over,
overheated and exhausted, holding water bottles and barely speaking
to one another.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the train doors were closing, a young, attractive woman
got on. Her hair was pulled up with beautiful ornaments, and she
was wearing a flowered minidress and high-heeled sandals. The heat
seemed not to have affected her.
</P>
<P>
   Her face lit up as she spotted the young men. ``Oh, wow!'' she
exclaimed. ``Are you guys cadets from the Police Academy?''
</P>
<P>
   The young man who replied didn't move a muscle. ``No, we just
like wearing polyester,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ SUSAN OSTERER
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Gunzenhauser is 5 feet 1 inch tall and accustomed to
sitting behind taller people at the theater. She had a center
orchestra aisle seat for a recent performance of ``Copenhagen,''
and true to her luck, the man in front of her was about 6 feet 3
inches with a large head and broad back. She spent the first act
weaving back and forth in an effort to keep up with the action.
</P>
<P>
   At intermission, the man turned to her and asked if she was
having difficulty seeing. When she said she was, the woman he was
with turned around and said, ``I know your problem,'' and insisted
that Gunzenhauser change seats with her. The second act was enjoyed
without stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a born and bred New Yorker currently living in Newtown,
Pa.,'' she said. ``I keep telling my new Pennsylvania friends that
beautiful things do happen in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Anne Kabak Schwalb was in a cab recently when the Pakistani
driver started talking to her. Education was very important to him,
he said. He had an advanced degree, as did his wife and three
children, and he was very proud of them.
</P>
<P>
   He asked Schwalb her occupation and she told him she was a
volunteer tutor for needy children. When she reached her
destination, he not only refused her tip but even handed her an
extra dollar and told her to buy something for the children she
tutored. The next time she took her students on an outing, she gave
each of them money for a video game and made sure they knew about
the driver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
