<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PIERSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAROLD PIERSON, DANCER AND ACTOR, DIES AT 66
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., N.Y.)  By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harold Pierson, a dancer, actor and educator, died on Aug. 1 in
Manhattan. He was 66 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, said Joan Myers Brown, the founder
and artistic director of the Philadelphia Dance Company.
</P>
<P>
   Pierson was the former artistic director of the Philadelphia
company, also known as Philadanco; he was a choreographer and
teacher for the troupe.
</P>
<P>
   He directed and helped write the video script for ``On the
Shoulders of Our Ancestors,'' a multimedia work presented by
Philadanco in June at the Joyce Theater in Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   Pierson trained in dance with Robert Joffrey and Valentina
Pereyaslavec and in acting with Louis Gossett Jr. and Sanford
Meisner.
</P>
<P>
   He played a quiet but important role in the development of many
black modern-dance choreographers' careers from the 1950s on,
performing with the companies of Alvin Ailey, Syvilla Fort,
Geoffrey Holder, Louis Johnson, Matt Mattox, Donald McKayle and
Olatunji. He danced in the premiere of McKayle's classic ``Rainbow
'Round My Shoulder'' in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Pierson also performed in the Broadway and touring casts of
musicals, including ``Golden Boy,'' ``Sweet Charity,'' ``Cry, the
Beloved Country'' and ``Purlie.''
</P>
<P>
   He was the artistic director for the Black Dance America
Festival presented by the Brooklyn Academy of Music in 1983. He
also held a visiting professorship at Howard University in the
College of Fine Arts and Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Pierson is survived by his sisters, Dorothy Johnson and Agnes
Hamilton, both of St. Albans, Queens, and his brother, Benjamin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 2216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0524 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-AR     08-13 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SHOOTING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN WHO AMBUSHED POLICE IN BROOKLYN SEEMED HEADED FOR VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT11 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By C.J. CHIVERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The man who ignited a fierce gun battle with police
in Brooklyn on Saturday _ a shootout that left four officers
wounded and led to his own death _ lived a reclusive life, sulking
in his parents' home, according to police authorities and some of
his neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Alalouf kept a shabby room in his parent's basement. He
took Xanax, a prescription drug used to calm anxiety. He was known
to swear loudly at his several large dogs. And he stockpiled enough
weapons for a platoon.
</P>
<P>
   Alalouf, 47, also managed to remain so secretive and anti-social
that some of his neighbors in the Gravesend section of Brooklyn did
not realize he still lived among them, until the gunfire rang out
Saturday afternoon and heavily armed police officers began to be
evacuated in ambulances while helicopters thumped overhead.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the most violent police gun battles of the last
decade, ending only after four officers had been shot and Alalouf
was dead. And apparently, the police said, it was planned _ the
final act of a man who had lived for years as something of a hermit
but who chose to draw the police into a shootout for an extremely
public end.
</P>
<P>
   Milton John, the father of one of the injured officers, called
it ``suicide by cop.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the authorities said, the day before Alalouf opened
fire on a police Emergency Service Unit, he broke from his
seclusion and made a rare trip out of his house. He went to a gun
shop.
</P>
<P>
   Alalouf hardly needed any more weapons. A search of his home
after the police killed him turned up a literal armory of pistols,
rifles and shotguns in his basement and a stack of samurai swords
in a first-floor closet. He also had Bowie knives and daggers, the
police said, and boxes on boxes of small-arms ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   But the authorities said that on Friday, Alalouf bought two new
guns: a pump-action shotgun, mounted on a pistol grip, and a Ruger
Mini-14, a compact assault rifle. He also bought ammunition: 15
buckshot shells for the shotgun, and 120 rounds for the Mini-14.
</P>
<P>
   And then he went home and began to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said Alalouf had shown signs of bad intentions
earlier. He had recently asked his mother to buy him gas cans, duct
tape and propane, and said he wanted to burn the house down. She
refused to help him.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, Alalouf, dressed in surplus military
fatigues, frightened his parents from their home, telling them he
would kill the first police officer he saw. His parents hurried to
the 61st Precinct station house and alerted the police.
</P>
<P>
   When the first members of a police Emergency Service Unit
approached the house, he opened fire through the window, striking
Officer Gregory John in the shoulder and knocking him to the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   William H. Allee Jr., the chief of detectives, said the rest of
the unit overwhelmed Alalouf with a heavy volume of gunfire.
Alalouf then fled and found refuge in a yard two houses away. The
police, unaware that he had gone, remained positioned outside
Alalouf's home. Several hours later, they stormed the house and
found it empty. But they soon converged on his hiding place. A
second exchange ensued, and Alalouf ran into a second house and out
the back door, where the officers opened fire again, killing him.
</P>
<P>
   Three other officers struck in the final exchange were Jose
Guerra, 34, ined who remained in an intensive care unit last night;
Joseph Ocasio, 43, who along with Officer John, remained
hospitalized in stable condition, and James McGrath, 33, who was
treated and released.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police officers that subdued him did a wonderful job under
tremendous stress,'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said. ``To have
executed this without the loss of innocent human life is
remarkable.''
</P>
<P>
   At home, Alalouf kept many of his neighbors on edge.
</P>
<P>
   One woman said he fashioned a peephole in his fence through
which he sometimes peered out. Another man, Boris Kaminyar, said he
took care to avoid his strange neighbor four years ago, when
Alalouf threw old shoes and feces into his back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the details of Alalouf's life remain sketchy. The city's
Department of Corrections said that he worked as a prison guard at
an adolescent unit on Rikers Island from June 1982 to November
1984, and had been the subject of two complaints alleging that he
had used excessive force. But the complaints were ruled minor
incidents, a law enforcement official said, and neither the inmates
nor him were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said that Alalouf had no known criminal record.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
