<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0526 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-CVN-CLINTON14-2NDLD-C     08-13 1293
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CLINTON14-2NDLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON MUST EMBRACE GORE _ BUT NOT TOO CLOSELY
 &HT;    Eds: Inserts grafs 5-7 with Clinton comments Sunday.
 &HT;    780&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS and JILL VEJNOSKA
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Two years after enmeshing his fellow Democrats in
a scandal that shook the nation, President Clinton is poised to
deliver a triumphant valedictory address Monday night to a party
reborn.
</P>
<P>
   When he speaks to the Democratic National Convention in Los
Angeles, however, Clinton must do more than burnish an imperfect
legacy by touting his role presiding over eight years of peace and
prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   He must somehow make Americans believe it couldn't have happened
without Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has to tell them that the last eight years have been the
greatest achievement since sliced bread, and that Al Gore was an
integral part of that success,'' said political scientist Gary
Segura of Claremont Graduate University, Claremont, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hinted Sunday night that his speech would not be devoid
of partisan overtones.
</P>
<P>
   At a gathering sponsored by four Jewish interest groups at the
Sony Pictures studio in Culver City, Clinton said he ``wanted to
say a few words about the peace process in the Middle East.''
</P>
<P>
   He then quickly added: ``You'll hear enough election rhetoric
elsewhere'' _ and, then, leaning into the podium and grinning,
added, ``and maybe a little from me tomorrow night.''
</P>
<P>
   For months now, at political fund-raisers, campaign speeches and
press conferences, Clinton has labored to give Gore his due,
portraying the vice president as a man of integrity and a full
partner in the policies behind the administration's successes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made an absolutely incalculable contribution to
whatever good we've accomplished in the White House,'' Clinton said
at a Democratic fund-raiser in Washington in June.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond lip service, helping Gore has always been a complicated
trick for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The closer Gore stands to the charismatic Clinton, for one
thing, the more vice-presidential he looks.
</P>
<P>
   That's one reason Gore won't be seen at all with Clinton in Los
Angeles. The two will meet instead at a rally Tuesday in Michigan,
where Clinton will charge his No. 2 with the mission of keeping the
keys to the White House in Democratic hands.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard also for Gore to cozy up to Clinton's coattails
without smudging his own attire.
</P>
<P>
   It was two years ago this week that Clinton went before the
nation to confess that he had an ``inappropriate'' relationship
with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky, after publicly
denying it for eight tumultuous months.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton survived a bid to remove him from office. But
Republicans want Gore to pay the price for standing by his boss and
calling Clinton ``a man I believe will be regarded in the history
books as one of our greatest presidents'' on the night the House
voted impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our generation has a chance to reclaim some essential values,
to show we have grown up before we grow old,'' presidential nominee
George W. Bush told the GOP convention. ``But when the moment for
leadership came, this administration did not teach our children, it
disillusioned them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some pundits have suggested that Clinton owes it to Gore to make
clear in his speech that his personal conduct had nothing to do
with his vice president.
</P>
<P>
   But there's nothing in Clinton's past to suggest that he would
turn a celebration of the life and times of the man from Hope into
yet another public confessional, and White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart dismissed such speculation as ``hot air.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is his valedictory speech, his swan song,'' said
government professor Phil Klinkner of Hamilton College in Clinton,
N.Y. ``For him to bring up something that is clearly the low point
of his political career, the low point of his personal life, it's
probably not something he would want to dwell on.''
</P>
<P>
   The odds that Clinton will raise the topic Monday were
diminished by the president's extraordinary confessional last week
before a ministers conference in suburban Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm now in the second year of a process of trying to totally
rebuild my life from a terrible mistake I made,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   And in a bid to distance Gore from the scandal, Clinton said
that his vice president ``doesn't get enough credit for what we did
together that is good, and surely, no fair-minded person would
blame him for any mistake that I made.''
</P>
<P>
   Since arriving in Los Angeles on Friday, Clinton has taken
further steps to accommodate Gore. Amid concerns that his packed
pre-convention schedule would overshadow Gore's campaign message,
the president canceled a round of televised interviews Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his events, including high-dollar fund-raisers with some
of Hollywood's biggest stars, have been closed to the press
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   What Clinton has been stressing in recent speeches is his role
in turning the country around and the importance of avoiding a
U-turn toward the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1992, the country was in trouble,'' Clinton told supporters
at a fund-raising dinner for the U.S. Senate campaign of First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton in McLean, Va., last Wednesday night. ``I
mean, our backs were against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gets much public credit for the longest and largest
economic expansion in the country's history, even though it began
in March 1991, nearly two years before he took office.
</P>
<P>
   On his watch, though, the economy has generated 22 million new
jobs. Over the past year alone the economy has grown a blistering 6
percent, after adjusting for moderate inflation of just above 2
percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton gets some credit, as well, for the dramatic turnaround
in the federal budget, which was $290 billion in the red in 1992
and is on track to be $211 billion in the black this year. Surely
Clinton will make the case Monday that he has led the charge on
policies that have helped take the budget from record deficit to a
record surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, though, has no plans to step into the shadows. He has
set aside the entire month of September for high-profile battles
with the Republican-led Congress over next year's budget, as well
as banner Democratic issues such as the quest for a so-called
patient's bill of rights, a minimum wage hike and increased gun
controls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have a very healthy debate in the month of
September, where the president tries to get these things
accomplished,'' said Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   In his convention speech, he's sure to attack GOP tax cut
proposals _ which the White House projects would amount to nearly
$2 trillion over the coming decade _ saying the changes would risk
throwing the nation back into a cycle of deficits. Under ``the Gore
plan,'' Clinton will likely point out, the country could pay off
its $3.2 trillion worth of publicly held debt by the year 2012.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton isn't likely to leave Los Angeles, though, without
employing his considerable rhetorical gifts to cast his own legacy
in the most favorable light possible. Nor is he likely to resist
taking a jab at those who scoffed at his prospects eight years ago,
when as the governor of Arkansas he appeared at the Democratic
National Convention to embark on his own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other side kind of referred to me as a governor of a small
Southern state, and I was so naive I thought it was a compliment,''
Clinton told the NAACP last month. ``You know what,'' he asked, ``I
still do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Deans's e-mail address is bobdeans(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska's e-mail address is jvejnoska(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
