<SLUG> BC-TEN-TENNIS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS SHOWS NERVE NOT SERVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ It wasn't a tennis display Serena
Williams will brag about or want to duplicate, but for all her
double faults and unforced errors, she proved something important
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   When the going gets tough and her famous serve doesn't get
going, Williams still can find a way to win. She battled her way
through three intense and enthralling sets to beat Lindsay
Davenport 4-6, 6-4, 7-6 (1) in the estyle.com Classic final at
Manhattan Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Williams defended her title with wins over the world's two
top-ranked players in less than 24 hours and improved her chances
at repeating her U.S. Open championship in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't serving well and I still came through with a win,''
said the fifth-seeded Williams, who beat Martina Hingis in
Saturday's semifinal. ``Usually when my serve is that bad, I don't
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams correctly assessed the flaws in her game. She got her
first serve in just 44 percent of the time and committed 36
unforced errors, but she showed the constitution of a champion when
it mattered most.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-5 in the third set, Williams could have put enormous
pressure on Davenport by holding serve but instead hit long on the
last two points of the game and trailed 6-5 with Davenport to
serve. But Williams didn't fold. She smashed two winners to start
the game, then watched as Davenport first double-faulted, then hit
a backhand into the net on break point.
</P>
<P>
   The frazzled Davenport didn't recover in the tiebreaker and
dropped 11 of the match's final 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're up a break at 6-5 in the third set, it's your
match,'' Davenport said. ``I thought I played well, except for a
couple points.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, never the type to admit to any self-doubt, said she
remained confident despite facing defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 5-6, I was thinking, `I have to break, or this is the end,
it's gone, it's done,' and I didn't want that,'' Williams said. ``I
knew I wasn't serving all that well, so I just tried to go for my
shots, and it worked.''
</P>
<P>
   If Williams is unhappy with her serving, Davenport should be
despondent. Usually one of the tour's most consistent servers, she
had nine aces to Williams' eight but also had 13 double faults.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport seemed to serve her worst at the worst times. She went
up a break early in the second set and had three chances togo up
4-2 but double-faulted twice, and Williams put the set back on
serve at 3-3.
</P>
<P>
   It stayed that way until Williams, leading 5-4, broke Davenport
to win the second set, a game typical of Davenport's problem. She
struggled to get her first serve in consistently. When she
didn't,Williams was right there to pounce on her second serve with
sharp returns.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, meanwhile, worked to showcase other nonserve aspects
of her game. She charged the net more and converted on 18 of 19
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been a one-dimensional player,'' Williams said.
``If one thing isn't working for me, I can always go to plan B or
C, or even D.''
</P>
</TEXT>
