<HEADER>
A0528 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HUNGARIAN-GRANDPRIX-N     08-13 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HUNGARIAN-GRANDPRIX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAKKINEN PULLS A FAST ONE IN THE FIRST CORNER
</HEADLINE>
  By BRAD SPURGEON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST, Hungary _ With his two biggest rivals preoccupied by a
war of nerves, Mika Hakkinen came from behind for the second race
in a row to get through the first corner first at the start of
Sunday's Hungarian Grand Prix. And on the narrow, dusty and twisty
Hungaroring, where it is next to impossible to pass, that is half
the job of winning.
</P>
<P>
   The other half is keeping the car on the track during the
grueling 77 laps of the 2.4-mile circuit. That is exactly what
Hakkinen did to win in 1 hour 45 minutes 33.869 seconds for an
average speed of 108.096 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Schumacher, in a Ferrari, finished second, 7.9 seconds
behind, with David Coulthard, Hakkinen's McLaren teammate, another
half a second behind.
</P>
<P>
   But Hakkinen, a 31-year-old from Finland, did far more than
steal the show from Schumacher and Coulthard. For the first time
this season, Hakkinen took the lead in the Formula One drivers
standings from Schumacher and set himself on course to join Juan
Manuel Fangio as the only drivers to win the title three years in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Hakkinen, who started the race two points behind Schumacher and
tied with Coulthard, now leads the championship with 64 points.
Schumacher is in second with 62 points, and Coulthard is third with
58. But Hakkinen would not say he was now the favorite to win the
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the way through the season people talk about who is going
to win, or who is going to lose, or who has lost motivation, or who
has motivation,'' said Hakkinen, who trailed by 24 points four
races ago. ``I've been keeping my own head all the time and
concentrating on my work and going to the races and trying to win.
I'm not going to think about who is going to win and who is going
to lose. That will be decided at the end of the year when we count
the points.''
</P>
<P>
   The first- and third-place finishes by the McLaren cars carried
the team past Ferrari in the constructors series, 112-111.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hakkinen's third victory this year and his second in a
row in Hungary, which, because of the vast number of Finnish
spectators who fly down for the race, is considered to be the
closest thing to a home race for Hakkinen.
</P>
<P>
   Hakkinen got off to a perfect start from third place on the
grid, taking advantage of the cleaner side of the track _ on the
racing line _ while Coulthard started from second, on the dusty
side.
</P>
<P>
   Hakkinen pulled up beside Schumacher, who was on the pole, and
squeezed between Schumacher and the edge of the track before the
first corner. Schumacher braked late and the two were lined up for
a collision, but Schumacher let Hakkinen through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had again a fantastic start,'' Hakkinen said. ``It was very
close with Michael in the first corner, but that's what racing
should be. And we came around the corner in one piece.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher said he ``was perhaps a bit too careful'' at the
start.
</P>
<P>
   Tension was high on the starting grid; Schumacher was knocked
out of the last two races in tussles at the first corner. In
Germany, Coulthard, who started on the pole, swerved in front of
him. That move was a repayment by Coulthard for a similar move
Schumacher pulled on him at the start of the French Grand Prix in
July.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, Hakkinen sped past the two of them from fourth place
but later lost the lead and finished second. In Austria, Schumacher
was also knocked off the track at the first corner, by Ricardo
Zonta.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's race was tightest after the second pit stops, when
Coulthard, on Lap 51, returned to the track after his stop just
behind Schumacher, who had already had his stop. For the last 25
laps, Coulthard, in the faster car, pressured Schumacher while less
than a second behind him, trying to force him into an error.
</P>
<P>
   But Schumacher held his nerve.
</P>
<P>
   ``On this sort of circuit you can take it fairly easy,'' he
said. ``You don't have to push to the limit because of the guy
behind you. That's all I was doing, just trying to concentrate and
not push to the limit or the tires would wear out near the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The Finnish fans went wild with cheers and horn honking as
Hakkinen climbed the victory podium. He waved his arms like an
orchestra conductor as the Finnish national anthem played.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
