<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0530 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-1S     08-13 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CONVENTION-RDP-1ST-LEDE-WRIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    CLINTON WILL TRY TO IGNITE A GORE COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 (EDS: Fixes reference to GOP convention in 3rd graph) (For use by clients of the New York Times News Service)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
LOS ANGELES _ President Clinton, hoping to ignite a comeback
victory for political heir Al Gore, will launch the Democratic
National Convention Monday night with the claim that he and Gore
transformed the ``terrible economic mess'' they inherited from
Republicans in 1992 into unprecedented promise and prosperity.
<P>
   Clinton's speech, expected to last as long as an hour, is his
last chance to speak to the Democratic Party faithful as president.
He plans to fly back to Washington on Tuesday after stopping in
Michigan to meet Gore and symbolically pass the torch to his
designated political heir.
</P>
<P>
   As Democrats flocked to this summer-hot convention city Sunday
on the eve of their first convention here since 1960, more than
3,000 protesters choked part of downtown Los Angeles to dramatize
opposition to environmental degradation, poverty and the ill
effects of world trade. Riot-equipped police flanked protesters as
they neared the Staples Center, site of the Democratic convention
that opens Monday. Some protesters voiced support for Mumia
Abu-Jamal, on death row in Pennsylvania for killing a Philadelphia
police officer.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to Democratic activists in beachfront Malibu, Clinton
acknowledged the uphill battle facing Gore, who lags Republican
presidential nominee George W. Bush in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can turn around these polls,'' Clinton told. ``But it's not
the work of a day. It's going to take every day between now and
November.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest nationwide survey showed Gore edging closer to Bush
after Gore chose Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., as his running
mate. Lieberman is the first Jewish American chosen for a national
party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   An NBC-Wall Street Journal poll released Sunday showed Bush
leading Gore by 3 percentage points, 44 percent to 41 percent. The
survey had a margin of error of 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The results offered good news to Gore who has trailed Bush by as
much as 14 percentage points in some recent surveys and by 6
percentage points in a comparable NBC News-Wall Street Journal
survey conducted before Bush's GOP convention in Philadelphia
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Chairman Joe Andrew welcomed signs of Gore gaining
``momentum,'' adding: ``We're in a position where just a decent
convention puts us where we want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   White House chief of staff John Podesta and White House press
secretary Joe Lockhart said Clinton would use his valedictory
address as a symbolic farewell to his supporters before stepping
aside to let Gore seize the political limelight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's his moment to get off the stage and let someone else get
on the stage and do the job,'' Podesta said.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton leaves the convention, ``politically, the
president will be in the background,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential aides said Clinton hoped to debunk the claims
that Bush made in a well-received GOP convention address in
Philadelphia on Aug. 3 that the Clinton-Gore team had needlessly
``squandered'' opportunities offered by the longest economic
recovery in American history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Republicans may have had a little amnesia about where
things stood in 1992,'' Podesta said, adding that Clinton ``will be
happy to remind people about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said Clinton will remind the nation that it has been
the Clinton-Gore ``partnership'' and Democrats in Congress who have
been ``reversing a terrible economic mess in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, who _ like Podesta _ has been working with Clinton on
the speech, said the president would reject Bush's claim that
Clinton and Gore had taken ``an eight-year vacation'' once elected
and that ``everything that happened over the last eight years had
happened by accident.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart emphasized, however, that Clinton had no plans to
apologize during his address for the sexual dalliance with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky. Clinton was impeached by the
House for obstruction of justice in the aftermath of the affair.
The president was acquitted by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton revived discussion of the sensitive personal issue in an
appearance last week before 4,500 ministers in Chicago en route to
Los Angeles. Clinton, saying that he was still ``trying to totally
rebuild my life from a terrible mistake I made,'' sought to exempt
Gore from criticism leveled at him, saying, ``Surely no fair-minded
person would blame him for any mistake I made.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will leave a rich monetary legacy to his party. He has
raised $100 million for various party entities this year, according
to Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, campaigning Sunday in Cleveland, promised sick children
and their families that he will make expanded federal health
coverage to all children ``a centerpiece'' of his battle with Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's morally wrong in this period of prosperity ... to have
families go through what's been described here,'' Gore told the
families, after hearing their heart rending stories at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would be willing to risk criticism as being a
``policy wonk'' in order to load down his address with specific
policy proposals including details of $500 billion in tax breaks to
advance his social priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said he would offer America `a positive speech'' that did
not criticize Bush but would underscore ``some of the policy
differences'' he has with the two-term governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In separate comments Sunday, both Gore and Lieberman continued
to subtly distance their ticket from Clinton's shadow. Gore told
reporters in Cleveland that he would ``uphold the oath'' that he
hopes to take as president on Jan. 20, 2001, adding that he had
given his ``whole heart'' to ``every job I have ever had'' and that
he had ``done it according to the highest values and I will
continue to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said that if elected, he might consult with Clinton ``if
there's a subject where he can contribute advice of course _ along
with President Carter'' but ``I don't anticipate that being a
regular occurrence.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, the Democratic vice presidential candidate who was
the first Democratic senator to publicly criticize Clinton's
behavior in September 1998, reminded viewers on NBC News' ``Meet
the Press'' on Sunday that he had favored censuring Clinton for his
personal misbehavior until the day the Senate impeachment trial
ended.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also ducked an invitation to echo Gore's declaration
that Clinton was ``one of our greatest presidents'' that the vice
president made at a pep rally style gathering on the White House
lawn following the House impeachment vote in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   As Lieberman put it: ``History will judge... I'm going to leave
the exact words for history.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said it was ``fine'' with him if Gore had selected him
to join the Democratic ticket in a bid to neutralize GOP criticism
of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans seem to be campaigning mostly against a guy
who's not on the ballot this year, not on his record because the
record is so great but because of his personal mistakes that he
made,'' Lieberman said. ``That's not fair to Al Gore. Nobody who
knows Al Gore can rightly associate him at all with that
behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent the day with Sen. John McCain in Arizona before
returning to his Texas ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at
stewarthearstdc.com)
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
