<HEADLINE>
WINNER HASN'T STOPPED IMPROVING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; MANHATTAN BEACH, Calif. _ The scary news for the players on the
women's tennis tour is not that Serena Williams defended her title
at the estyle.com Classic on Sunday, nor that she beat two of the
world's top players in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The real scary part is that she thinks she can be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can do a lot better,'' Williams said. ``I'm just warming up,
basically. I haven't even started hitting my serve really well.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Williams' confidence comes off as cockiness, but tennis
followers seem to have reached a consensus that Williams is
correct. Her serve, while one of the biggest in the world, is
inconsistent, and she often talks about needing to improve
mentally.
</P>
<P>
   Even the players _ including Lindsay Davenport, who lost to
Williams on Sunday _ agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have great serves, but Venus is probably just a little
more consistent right now,'' Davenport said of the Williams
sisters. ``I had a million chances (against Serena) and I probably
should have won, but the last time I played Venus, she didn't give
me anything.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Quotable: With the U.S. Open approaching and Serena Williams
never lacking for confidence, reporters tried to get her to
guarantee victory at the Grand Slam event.
</P>
<P>
   Williams declined, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guys know my prediction, I don't need to say it,''
Williams said. ``You know who it is. The lady in purple.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams wore a purple dress all week, and yes, everybody
already knew who it was.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hot stuff: The court temperature approached 100 degrees
during the singles final, but it didn't seem to be a problem for
either player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt great,'' Davenport said. ``No injuries, so that's a
good sign going into the Open.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Some consolation: Belgium's Dominique Van Roost, who
controversially lost a second-round singles match, teamed with
countrywoman Els Callens to win the doubles title Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Van Roost and Callens defeated American Kimberly Po and
Anne-Gaelle Sidot of France 6-2, 7-5. Van Roost had protested
earlier in the week when the chair umpire overruled two points late
in her loss to France's Sandrine Testud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
