<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSE RACING: UPBEAT PLANS FOR INDUSTRY AT JOCKEY CLUB ROUNDTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
  By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ It would have been much more
pleasurable to spend a rare sunny morning here in a rocking chair
along Broadway poring over The Daily Racing Form. But an important
part of the Saratoga meet for breeders, owners and racetrack
executives is the Jockey Club roundtable, which takes place
annually and is often a gloomy affair conducted at a comatose pace
in a darkened hotel ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   Yet an upbeat business mood prevailed on Sunday as the
thoroughbred racing industry, with a more or less league office in
place, crisply set out an agenda for horse racing. Like all league
meetings, there was good news: a new televised series of races for
2-year-olds that will not only provide purses of $2.9 million and
potential bonus money of $1.3 million to their owners but also
introduce next year's Triple Crown stars over seven heats to racing
fans.
</P>
<P>
   There was troubling news: substantive recommendations to
strengthen drug testing to weed out cheaters, which one owner,
Stuart S. Janney III, said should be addressed in the open so the
public, as well as trainers, jockeys and owners, know without doubt
that a horse running is doing so honestly. Janney, the owner of the
1998 Travers Stakes winner Coronado's Quest, acknowledged that lax
regulation, new performance-enhancing drugs and unscrupulous
veterinarians and trainers had contributed to a lack of confidence
in racing's integrity in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in recent weeks, Bob Baffert had a horse in California
test positive for morphine _ though Baffert, a veteran Triple Crown
trainer, contends that the small amount could have come from any
incidental contact. But Janney, who headed a task force on the
subject of drugs, called for more vigilance, with measures like
camera surveillance of competitors on race day, to ensure ``that
cheaters do not win our greatest races, that undeserving horses are
not crowned champions and that all our effort and hard work to
enhance our sport is not destroyed by compromising our standards
and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps best of all for the racing enthusiasts who wagered a
record $14.4 billion in 1999 on horse races in North America was
that there was plenty of talk about new technology and marketing
plans to make Internet delivery part of winning new fans and
helping existing ones.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most promising initiatives is perhaps one of the most
puzzling. The National Thoroughbred Racing Association, which has
finally consolidated some amount of power, hired IBM Global
Services, which has studied the industry for the past year, to come
up with initiatives to update technologies and advance access to
the sport. Though the consultants initially determined that
thoroughbred racing still does not have enough fans, they saw
enough potential to want to finance future projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to negotiate a long-term contract that we
believe would be a win-win situation,'' said Rob Law, a senior
consultant for IBM.
</P>
<P>
   There remain many obstacles for horse racing to return as a
major player in the crowded sports landscape. The conglomerates of
Churchill Downs Inc. and the MI Entertainment Corp., which is led
by the industrialist Frank Stronach, are battling to acquire
racetracks. Smaller, independent track operators have felt squeezed
out. The Internet Gambling Prohibition Act was narrowly defeated
recently in Congress. It needs approval if simulcast betting and
account wagering _ the staples of wagering revenue _ are to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   But as recent developments and the roundtable discussion
demonstrated, the industry is moving, if not always in harmony, in
a productive direction. The Breeders' Cup Championship, now in its
17th year and by far the most successful venture in horse racing in
modern times, has consolidated with the NTRA, and the two entities
will probably merge within three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made sense to have the championship of our sport under the
umbrella of the league office,'' explained D.G. Van Clief Jr.,
president of the Breeders' Cup, which brings the best horses from
around the world together for a day of competition. ``It means more
money and focus on building up the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Less intramural skirmishing also means that more energy can be
put into arranging a natural marriage between a sport with true
interactive capabilities and a population already doing plenty of
commerce by computer and on the Internet. Skilled handicapping of
horses leads to financial rewards for selecting winners, which are
delivered as horses gallop around an oval to the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   As the drug testing discussion illustrates, the industry has
done well at keeping the performance on the racetrack at a high
standard. Now, it's time for the business plans to do the same. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 2233EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
