<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0219 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0534 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-DEMS-LIZ-HNS &LR;      08-13 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-LIZ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARPENTER: THE DEMOCRAT'S GRANDE DAME &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Liz Carpenter, self-described ``artifact'' and
``rooting-tooting Democrat,'' arrived here over the weekend to help
spread the gospel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you're going to vote Democratic,'' she said, ambushing
an unsuspecting couple whose stroll around the hotel pool had
brought them within challenging range of one of Texas' most
colorful and outspoken partisans.
</P>
<P>
   First as a news reporter, then as a White House insider and now
as an author and elder stateswoman, Carpenter has been attending
political conventions for more than half a century.
</P>
<P>
   Scooting around on an electric cart, wearing a red jacket and
brandishing a cane festooned with red, white and blue streamers,
the white-haired Austinite still offers a commanding presence.
</P>
<P>
   And although an ailing leg has physically slowed her at 79, her
enthusiasm remains as strong as ever for her party and her
delegate's role at this week's Democratic National Convention. It
is matched only by her disdain for the enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 21 before I saw my first Republican, and it was a
terrifying experience. They still scare me,'' she quipped.
</P>
<P>
   And she was unapologetic for breaking ranks with most of her
fellow Texans and opposing Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican
presidential nominee who is expected to overwhelmingly carry Texas
over Democrat Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter said Bush was ``very likable,'' but she ridiculed his
campaign theme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think compassionate conservative is about as inconsistent as
virgin hooker,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The sixth generation Texan, who first came to national
prominence as Lady Bird Johnson's press secretary during President
Johnson's administration, will be one of the oldest delegates at
the Democratic meeting, which begins today.
</P>
<P>
   She looks forward to nominating Gore and running-mate Joseph
Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter grew up in an era when Republicans were virtually
nonexistent in Texas. And although the state's political landscape
has changed drastically during her lifetime, she hasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only trouble with Republicans is they just don't like
people,`` she said, echoing the late, legendary Democrat, Sam
Rayburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just happen to believe that government's role in a democracy
can contribute to how civilized our society is, and I think the
Democratic Party has that more in mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter, who was a Washington-based reporter, attended her
first national political conventions in 1948, when the Democrats,
the Republicans and the Progressive Party all gathered in
Philadelphia. They chose the same city, she said, to accommodate a
new invention called television.
</P>
<P>
   She also recalled that Rayburn, the longtime speaker of the U.S.
House who also presided over the Democratic National Convention
that year, was ``dive-bombed'' during one of the Democratic
sessions by pigeons, who were apparently confused by TV lights.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter continued covering conventions as a reporter through
1960, when Democrats, meeting in Los Angeles, nominated the John F.
Kennedy-Lyndon B. Johnson ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter's fourth book, ``Start With a Laugh: An Insider's
Guide to Roasts, Toasts, Eulogies and Other Speeches,'' will be out
Sept. 1, on her 80th birthday. The book draws from her extensive
political experiences, including speechwriting for Lady Bird
Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter was a delegate to a Democratic convention for the
first time in 1972, when George McGovern was nominated. She was a
Bill Clinton delegate at the 1992 and 1996 conventions. This year,
her daughter, Christy Carpenter, also is a Democratic delegate _
from California.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter readily points out that the face of the Democratic
Party has undergone major changes in her lifetime, in large part
because of civil rights legislation enacted during the Johnson
administration.
</P>
<P>
   What was once a party dominated by white men who discriminated
against blacks and Hispanics is now much more diverse, and
Carpenter feels right at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of heart, and we have a record of caring'' for
the underprivileged, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter is a strong supporter of abortion rights and the Equal
Rights Amendment, and she doesn't think very highly of former
Democrats who became Republicans when the GOP began to grow in
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any use for people who leave the Democratic
Party,'' she said. ``I love the Democratic Party. That's who I am,
and I know who I am.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
