<HEADLINE>
FORD SAYS FIRESTONE KNEW OF FLAW IN TIRES BY 1997 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing)   (12:01 a.m. ET EMBARGO for electronic media.)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Ford Motor Co. released documents Sunday showing that
in 1997 Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. began receiving numerous
complaints of injuries and property damage involving certain
Firestone tires that were not recalled until last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the recalled tires have rates of injury and personal
damage claims up to 100 times greater than those for tires not
recalled, Ford disclosed Sunday. Many of those claims were sent to
Bridgestone by vehicle owners from 1997 to 1999, but the tire maker
did not tell Ford, whose new automobiles, particularly Ford
Explorer sport utility vehicles, are equipped with two-thirds of
the recalled tires.
</P>
<P>
   The automaker said it learned of the high rate of claims only a
week ago, when it performed its own computer analysis of
Bridgestone's data. Bridgestone had resisted Ford's disclosure of
the information, said a person briefed on the automaker's work on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said that Bridgestone's factory in Decatur, Ill., had been
the main source of the problem tires, and that the factory had
experienced its biggest quality problems from 1994 to 1996. Those
were the years when the factory was operated mainly by replacement
workers because of a labor dispute between Bridgestone and its
union, although Ford made no mention of that fact Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone officials did not dispute Ford's data but said that
the problem had not caught their attention until Ford began
reviewing Bridgestone's files two weeks ago. The overall rate of
complaints on tires from all Bridgestone factories had not been
unusually high, and Bridgestone did not conduct the detailed review
of tire quality by factory that Ford undertook, said Bob Wyant,
Bridgestone's vice president of quality assurance.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Karbowiak, a Bridgestone spokeswoman, said that there was
no evidence that the labor dispute had affected quality in Decatur.
She was also quick to point out during a conference call with
reporters Sunday afternoon that Ford itself had given the Decatur
factory a quality award.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies' mutual sniping was the clearest sign yet of
strain in one of corporate America's oldest relationships.
Firestone, which was bought by Bridgestone in 1988, has been
supplying tires to Ford since 1906, when Henry Ford was still
designing the first Model T.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Bridgestone had presented a mostly united front since
last Wednesday's recall of 6.5 million Firestone tires, which in
addition to being sold on new Ford vehicles were sold as
replacement tires for several manufacturers' sport utility vehicles
and pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Ford dealers have been flooded with customers seeking
replacement tires, including replacements for Firestone tires not
covered by the recall, while buyers have been leery of buying new
Ford Explorers equipped with Firestone tires.
</P>
<P>
   Ford released the data Sunday partly in the hope of reassuring
customers that Firestone tires not covered by the recall were safe,
notably Wilderness AT tires made at factories other than the one in
Decatur. But the data is unlikely to appease plaintiff lawyers and
safety groups, who scheduled a press conference for Monday in
Washington to call for Bridgestone to expand the recall to include
far more Wilderness brand tires.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Hoar, the founder of Safetyforum.com, a consulting firm
that is coordinating many of the lawsuits against Bridgestone and
Ford, said Ford was trying to put all the blame on Bridgestone to
draw attention from what he described as design defects in the Ford
Explorer's suspension that put strain on the tires. Ford officials
have repeatedly denied this.
</P>
<P>
   The automaker has recalled Explorers in four foreign countries,
equipped with a larger size of Wilderness tires than those recalled
in the United States. Ford said the overseas recall reflected
driving conditions seldom found in the United States, so a broader
recall was unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   People who have been briefed on Ford's work on the tire problem
said the automaker had been deeply disturbed to learn two weeks ago
that Bridgestone had done little work to analyze the reliability of
its tires in the United States despite growing complaints and a
federal investigation that began in May.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Vines, a Ford spokesman, took pains on Sunday to mention
that Ford had used very sophisticated programs and equipment to
analyze the Bridgestone data, including a Cray supercomputer. But
another person briefed on Ford's work said that the company's
analysis was ``not rocket science'' and represented standard
practice for automakers that try to identify quality problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ford faxed a 12-page summary of the data to reporters Sunday
afternoon and then held a conference call during which its
officials discussed the material. Ford initially scheduled the call
only for its own executives, but Karbowiak and Wyant decided to
participate as well. They were mostly silent as Vines explained how
Ford had asked for and received Firestone's data on injury and
property damage claims, and quickly discovered problems.
</P>
<P>
   Vines said Ford officials obtained the data on July 28 and spent
eight days entering it into Ford's computers. Within several days,
Ford had concluded that there was a problem with all Firestone ATX
and ATX II tires of the P235/75R15 size, and with Firestone
Wilderness AT tires of the same size that were produced in Decatur
only. Firestone and Ford then decided on a recall.
</P>
<P>
   The federal investigation that began in May includes 300
complaints about Firestone tires, involving 46 deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford data released Sunday showed that there had been just
one to six tread-separation claims per million Wilderness AT tires
from factories other than Decatur. Wilderness tires from other
factories are being used to replace the Decatur-made Wilderness
tires that are being recalled and various ATX tires being recalled.
</P>
<P>
   For Wilderness AT tires from Decatur, the rate of injury and
property damage claims was more than 50 per million tires produced
in 1996 and close to that level for tires produced in 1997. While
there have been few claims for Decatur-made Wilderness tires
produced since 1998, these have not been on the road long enough
for many claims to have been received, Vines said.
</P>
<P>
   The claims rate was far higher for ATX tires, all of which are
being recalled in the P235/75R15 size regardless of where they were
produced. For factories other than the Decatur plant, the rate
approached 100 claims per million tires for tires produced from
1993 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   At the Decatur plant itself, the claims rate soared to between
350 and 650 claims per million ATX tires produced in 1994, 1995 and
1996.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thomas F. Dasse, a Phoenix lawyer handling several lawsuits
against Bridgestone, said in an interview on Friday that his
litigation depended partly on testimony from former Bridgestone
employees who had worked at the Decatur factory until 1996 and who
had described quality problems there.
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Post reported Sunday that some of the lawsuits
against Bridgestone included testimony from former workers in
Decatur who described manually piercing blisters in the rubber of
flawed tires and sending them to a warehouse for sale, instead of
scrapping them.
</P>
<P>
   Karbowiak described these comments as the views of ``disgruntled
workers,'' and said that Bridgestone disagreed with them. She said
Bridgestone believed that all of the replacement workers had
performed their jobs as well as the union workers had before them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly believe there is no connection based on what we
know of our training and operating procedures,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Decatur factory makes tires of various sizes for other
automakers, and Ford has not analyzed the claims rates for these
tires. Wyant said that Bridgestone did not believe these tires had
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The United Steelworkers of America went on strike against
Bridgestone in Decatur in July 1994. After 10 months, the union
ordered its workers to return to their jobs without a contract, but
the company only hired them when job openings occurred, while
continuing to operate the factory with replacement workers.
</P>
<P>
   The company and the union did not reach an agreement until
November 1996, when the remaining union workers went back to their
jobs with the exception of those who had committed acts during the
strike that the company deemed unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The claims rate for Wilderness tires made in Decatur began to
fall in 1997 and it is now virtually equal to the claims rate for
Wilderness tires made elsewhere, Ford's Vines said. But Bridgestone
is recalling all Wilderness tires made in Decatur since 1996 as a
precaution.
</P>
</TEXT>
