<P>
   (NYT12) DONGGUAN, China -- Aug. 13, 2000 -- CHINA-CONCUBINES-1
-- A banner forms a gateway to the New Garden Village Meat and
Vegetable Market in Dongguan, China. At first, it looks like just
another Chinese town, but not on closer inspection. New Garden
Village is one of China's most notorious ``concubine villages.''
Hundreds of mainland Chinese women here live in a dozen rows of
drab, concrete high-rises, kept there as mistresses or common-law
wives of Hong Kong men. (Mark Landler/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 2000 -- NY-POLICE-SHOOTING -- A
deranged man who wounded four police officers from two Brooklyn
houses late Saturday in a fierce standoff, was once a jail guard
who aspired to become a police officer, according to authorities.
Afterwards, police found an arsenal in his basement along with a
dead dog and cat and dozens of samurai swords, Bowie knives, and
hundreds of rounds of ammunition. A day earlier, the crazed gunman,
identified as Albert Alalouf, warned his parents ``that he would
shoot the police if they came to his house.'' (William C. Lopez/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 13, 2000 -- DEM-CLINTON -- The
Democratic National Convention that opens in Los Angeles Monday
could give Vice President Al Gore his best chance to emerge from
President Bill Clinton's shadow, and present himself as a man of
stature even as he trails Republican George W. Bush in the polls.
At the Sony Pictures Studio in Los Angeles, Calif., Clinton and his
wife Hillary attended a Jewish Democratic Council rally, Sunday.
(Keith Meyers/The New York Times)
</P>
