<P>
   (NYT5) LOS ANGELES -- Aug. 13, 2000 -- DEM-CHAIRMAN-PROFILE --
Joe Andrew, 40, the chairman of the Democratic National Committee,
who will bring the gavel down to start his party's convention in
Los Angeles on Monday. As a child in a Republican family, Andrew's
escape, passion, entertainment and probably his rebellion were
Democratic politics inspired by Robert F. Kennedy. At age 12, his
idea of fun was to go to the mall and slap bumper stickers for
local Democratic candidates on the cars of unsuspecting shoppers.
(Jim Wilson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 2000 -- DUNHAM-PROFILE -- Katherine
Dunham, the radiant star of countless international dance tours and
Broadway and Hollywood musicals from the 1940s. At 91 Dunham brims
with more ideas and serene enthusiasm for life than anyone around
her in the bustling Manhattan apartment where she is staying, on a
sabbatical from her home in East St. Louis, Ill. Dunham who
participates frequently in seminars is currently at work on the
next installment of her autobiography, to be called ``The
Minefield.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 2000 -- TOMCLANCY-MEDIA -- On August
3, Robert Gottlieb, one of the most powerful agents in the book
business and the head of the William Morris agency's New York
literary group, received a letter from Tom Clancy, his old friend
and biggest client. His message: He was ending their 15 years of
business together. From now on, his book deals would be handled by
Michael Ovitz. Gottlieb during a tribute to the late writer Joseph
Heller in New York last June. (Carol Halebian/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CARTERET , N.J. -- Aug. 13, 2000 -- MUSIC-SATELLITES --
Receiving radio signals over the Internet has just become much
easier with the use of satellites. IBeam Broadcasting Corporation
is using a satellite to send music while avoiding interference on
the ground and will provide a constant stream of music. Listeners
will receive music at a network hub that is close to them. Two
Internet distribution companies, InterPacket and iBeam, use the
Williams Communications Vyvx Services satellite stations located in
Carteret, N.J. (Dith Pran/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Aug. 13, 2000 -- E-COMMERCE-COLUMN --
Christine Harmel, 32, is the chief executive of Interactive
Resource, a firm in Manhattan that matches Web site developers with
clients. Since 1995, Harmel has watched the Internet industry
transform itself from a stomping ground for young workaholics to a
group of burned out veterans wanting to leave the industry. Harmel
has begun searching for a home away from the nation's technology
hotbeds in order to sell her business and leave the industry.
Harmel in her office in Manhattan. (Ruby Washington/The New York
Times)
</P>
