<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0654 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USC-LADN-(SLANG)     08-13 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OHALETE BACK IN SAFETY PICTURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ For USC's entire training camp, senior Ife
Ohalete has nearly been a forgotten man, relegated to practicing
with the second team after starting last season at free safety.
</P>
<P>
   Even during Saturday's scrimmage, converted tailback Frank
Strong played with the first unit while Ohalete remained with the
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   But after recording six tackles in the scrimmage, Ohalete has
resurfaced and is a starter once again, despite Strong's attempt to
win the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been concentrating and his experience and knowledge are
invaluable, and he's been really steady,'' secondary-coach Dennis
Thurman said.
</P>
<P>
   With Ohalete back as a starter, there are a few positions left
where a player could come out of nowhere to win the top job.
</P>
<P>
   Strong still is expected to play this season. The Trojans will
rotate players at nearly every secondary spot.
</P>
<P>
   Another player who keeps raising his stock is freshman strong
safety Matt Grootegoed, who has solidified his grip on the No. 2
strong safety spot during the scrimmage and could be challenging
for a starting spot soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matt really made a move,'' Thurman said. ``The lights came on
and he performed. He reminds me of Daylon McCutcheon, Brian Kelly
and Antuan Simmons when they were freshmen.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Scrimmage stars: After viewing a tape of Saturday's
scrimmage, coach Paul Hackett said defensive end Matt Childers and
Grootegoed stood out. He also was pleased with the running backs
and cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   As for quarterback Carson Palmer, Hackett was mostly positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carson looked good. He was a little bit off on one pass but
otherwise pretty good,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Penalty problems? The Trojans had 12 penalties in Saturday's
84-play scrimmage, but more troublesome for Hackett were the six
false starts, which was reminiscent of last season.
</P>
<P>
   __ Stevenson returns: After being bothered by a sore hamstring
all week, sophomore wide receiver Steve Stevenson finally practiced
Sunday. He will have his first contact workout today.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, tight end Gregg Guenther of Taft, who caught a
touchdown pass in the scrimmage, has a sore back and will miss a
couple of days of practice.
</P>
<P>
   __ Kicking change: Last week, Hackett said he would narrow the
kicking battle from three to two before choosing a starter. But
Sunday he said he would continue to let junior David Newbury,
senior David Bell and freshman John Wall of Birmingham High battle
through at least midweek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, David Newbury has the edge,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett wants to give all three kickers as much as experience as
possible before making any decisions.
</P>
<P>
   One place there is not a kicking problem is at punter: Junior
Mike MacGillivray averaged 53 yards in five attempts Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-13-00 2310EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
