These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business section
plans to move for Monday, Aug. 14, on the New York Times wire. For
questions, please call Dominick Calicchio at 415-777-6055 or the
business desk at 415-536-5172. For business stories running in main
news, call the news desk at 415-777-7074.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; TECH21 (COLUMN) _ &LR;  Little did I know, when I observed in last
week's column that there's a disagreement about computers'
contribution to our power problems, that I was wandering into a
nasty little debate involving not only technical and methodological
issues, but also political and even philosophical ones.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the debate is the contention that computers and
peripherals today consume about 13 percent of the nation's
available power, including 8 percent specifically for Internet use.
I first noticed these numbers in an Associated Press report from an
``energy summit'' held in Redwood City in June, but it turns out
they've been cited in just about every major publication in the
country over the last year.  &UR; COLUMN BY HENRY &LR; 
 &UR; NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; BIOSCOPE (COLUMN) _  &LR; As visiting lawmakers filed off the bus at
Alza Corp. in Mountain View, Calif., last week, they walked past a
sign that read: ``Welcome to 10 percent of the U.S. Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   The sign was a bit exaggerated. Several no-shows brought the
delegation down to three dozen lawmakers, all Democrats, who raced
through the region to gawk at the New Economy on their way to their
party's convention in Los Angeles.  &UR; COLUMN BY TOM ABATE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; EDOVERVIEW _  &LR;  (Opening story of a 10-story package about
Technology and Education. Other nine stories, by various authors,
will be CHEAT, HOMEWORK, PARENTS, LAPTOPS, DESKTOPS, APPLY,
SCHOLARS, SOFTWARE, DISTANCE.)
</P>
<P>
   The specifics keep changing, but the promise hasn't: For two
decades, technology has been touted as a panacea for America's
troubled educational system.
</P>
<P>
   First, the idea was that learning keyboarding, word processing
and Logo programming would prepare kids for jobs in the information
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Then came ``kill and drill'' software titles that tried to
inspire enthusiasm about arithmetic and spelling exercises by
adding goofy characters and funny noises. In the 1990s, with the
popularization of CD-ROMs, electronic encyclopedias and multimedia
were added to the mix.  &UR; OPENING STORY BY HENRY NORR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CHEAT _ &LR;  Call it high-tech cheating.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since graphical calculators started popping up in the
classroom, quick studies have found ways to program them with
complex formulas, hard-to-remember vocabulary words and other hints
to gain an edge during tests.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca, who asked that her last name not be used, said she and
her high school classmates in Los Angeles cheated all the time
using TI-85 calculators, especially in chemistry and calculus about
five years ago. Eventually, proctors for the Advanced Placement
tests got wise and started walking down the aisles, checking to
make sure all the students cleared their calculator's memory.  &UR; BY
TODD WALLACK &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; HOMEWORK _ &LR;  Curtis Santee, a 10th-grader from San Francisco,
prefers to do schoolwork from the comfort of home rather than going
to the library. So when doing a report about Algeria recently, he
logged on to his family's computer and, faster than a lesson on the
Dewey Decimal System, found information about the North African
country's gross domestic product and cultures in an online
encyclopedia.  &UR; BY VERNE KOPYTOFF &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; PARENTS _  &LR;  At the tender age of 10, Jake Schlackman enjoys his
role as his family's computer tutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you get to be the boss, for once,'' Jake said.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to computers, kids are often in charge, as
technophobic parents struggle to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Often it's a blessing when a child like Jake can teach his dad
how to use Adobe Photoshop, or fix his grandmother's iMac so she
can access the Internet.  &UR; BY DAN FOST &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; LAPTOPS _ &LR;  For the high school or college-bound student, portable
computers do double duty. They travel readily between home and
school, as well as save space in crowded dorm rooms. (Imagine
toting a desktop home for Christmas break.)
</P>
<P>
   They cost a little more than the equivalent power in a desktop
model, but the benefits are legion. How else can one hang out in
the neighborhood coffee shop writing papers while kibitzing with
friends? It's a lifestyle thing.  &UR; BY BECKY WARING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; DESKTOPS _ &LR;  A home computer has become an absolute necessity for
school-age children. Fortunately, prices have fallen so far that
most families should be able to afford one. Whether for homework,
Web cruising, e-mail or game-playing, the computer will likely
become the focal point of many home activities. Here's how to
choose one with the right features and the right price.  &UR; BY BECKY &LR; 
 &UR; WARING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; APPLY _  &LR;  Kids today have it so easy.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a college graduate of practically any age, you
probably had to choose between typing college application forms and
filling them out in pen. The first option was a disaster _ the
form's tiny blanks were impossible to aim at, and after 15 tries
your application would be so heavy with Wite-Out, it would require
extra postage. As for using pen, if your handwriting wasn't neat,
you were doomed.  &UR; BY CARRIE KIRBY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SCHOLARS _ &LR;  If you care to do research on the North American loon,
you could land a $3,000 education grant.
</P>
<P>
   If birds aren't your thing, the makers of Calgon bath and body
lotions have up to $2,500 in scholarship money ready for students
who can stomach answering fragrant queries like this one in 450
words or less:
</P>
<P>
   ``Calgon flavors like Sparkling Raspberries, In the Rain and
Moon Petal Musk are truly inspired! Which teacher inspired you most
and how?''  &UR; BY BENNY EVANGELISTA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SOFTWARE _ &LR;  OK, so I went about the SATs all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what I learned after experimenting with some of
the software titles designed to help raise scores on the dreaded
Scholastic Achievement Test _ one of the rights of passage for most
college-bound students.
</P>
<P>
   Way back in 1989 when I took the SATs, my math and English
teachers stressed memorizing endless geometry formulas and
vocabulary lists. In other words, they advocated doing every
problem and analogy the long _ or right _ way.  &UR; BY KELLY ZITO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; DISTANCE _ &LR;  For college student Jaxon Louie, taking an online
course has several advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go to school ... without leaving home,'' said the
University of California at Berkeley student. ``I remember waking
up one minute before a class session, turning on the computer and
in a matter of moments I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, there are no crowded classrooms and ``you won't
get bored because you could be doing other things at the same time
_ like watch TV,'' Louie said.  &UR; BY BENNY EVANGELISTA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
