<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAPTOPS-CHOICES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 LAPTOP COMPUTERS SUIT THE NEEDS OF MOST STUDENTS  &HT;     By BECKY WARING 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For the high school or college-bound student,
portable computers do double duty. They travel readily between home
and school, as well as save space in crowded dorm rooms. (Imagine
toting a desktop home for Christmas break.)
</P>
<P>
   They cost a little more than the equivalent power in a desktop
model, but the benefits are legion. How else can one hang out in
the neighborhood coffee shop writing papers while kibitzing with
friends? It's a lifestyle thing.
</P>
<P>
   To help your scholar choose the right portable, we've listed the
most important features to look for below. We've also divided the
portable landscape into four categories and chosen a representative
machine for each. For the cost conscious, there's our budget saver
choice; for the kid who has everything, there's the full-featured
model that rivals desktop functionality; and for those who take
things everywhere, an ultralight model. Finally, we've also made a
selection for Mac users.
</P>
<P>
   Note that your total computer budget should also include a
printer, padded carrying case, and possibly a scanner. These can be
had for an extra $250 or so. Inexpensive inkjet printers are just
fine for schoolwork.
</P>
<P>
   Features to Look For:
</P>
<P>
   -- Display. Portable displays have come a long way recently.
Almost all are now bright active-matrix varieties, with full 24-bit
color. A few under-$1,000 portables still have passive-matrix DSTN
screens _ steer clear of these. For most student use, a 12.1-inch
800x600 SVGA screen is fine. If the portable will be the student's
only machine and will be used heavily, consider a 14.1-inch
``desktop replacement'' size screen. These are much more expensive
but worth it if you've got the bucks.
</P>
<P>
   -- Processor/RAM. If all your scholar will be doing is word
processing, Web surfing and e-mail, there's no need to spring for
the latest processor. The processor and screen are the two most
costly components of any portable. Consider Intel's Celeron line,
or the AMD K6-2 as lower-cost alternatives to the Pentium III. And
if you do decide on a PIII, don't get the very fastest version. A
650-MHz model costs hundreds more than a 500 MHz, for little
appreciable improvement in most tasks. As for RAM, get at least 64
MB. All our choices have that much RAM, although 96 MB is even
better. Serious Web research benefits greatly from added RAM.
</P>
<P>
   -- Storage. All our choices have at least a 6-GB hard disk.
Multimedia files like pictures and music take up a lot of space and
are staples of student life. All the portables except the Sony also
have a built-in CD-ROM or DVD drive. The Sony is an ultralight,
where you have to buy an external CD or DVD drive. Only the Apple
iBook lacks a floppy, which is an $89 option. Consider buying an
external CD recorder if your student wants to make audio and
picture CDs or backup the hard disk.
</P>
<P>
   -- Expansion. All the PC models have the requisite USB, serial,
parallel and external VGA monitor ports, as well as PC card slots
and 56K modems. Other useful connections to look for are Ethernet
ports for networking at school (a built-in port saves filling up a
PC Card slot) and an IEEE 1394 (FireWire) port for connecting
digital camcorders.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, some portables have special connectors for docking
stations, which let you plug into peripherals such as printers,
monitors, external drives, full-size keyboards and mice more easily
(using just one plug instead of many).
</P>
<P>
   -- Battery life. Battery life on most portables is pretty poor,
typically one to three hours. The iBook is the standout here, with
four to six hours of life. We recommend getting an extra battery
for long sessions in the coffee shop or park. (The library, on the
other hand, should have plugs!)
</P>
<P>
   -- Software/operating system. For home/student use, definitely
go with Windows 98, rather than Windows 2000 Professional. It's
easier to use, and has more support for popular applications and
games. Do look for free upgrades to this summer's Windows ME
(Millennium Edition), however. Also look for Microsoft Word (best
for exchanging files with others) and valuable extras such as virus
protection software, encyclopedias and photo editing software.
</P>
<P>
   -- Warranty and technical support. Pretty much all vendors offer
a one-year basic warranty. Also look into extended warranties for
portables, which are very prone to problems. Just be forewarned
that if the screen gets broken because it was shoved into a
backpack, it's not covered.
</P>
<P>
   For tech support, look for 24-hour, seven-days a week, toll-free
access. Compaq shines here. Sony and Apple have skimpy 90-day
rules, although you can buy more with extended warranties. Also
look for good Web-based support sites, which all three companies
have.
</P>
<P>
   The Budget Saver:
</P>
<P>
   -- Compaq Presario 1200-XL118. Compaq's Presario line is
especially designed for home and school, and sports a full range of
models from $1,000 on up. We looked at nearly a dozen other vendors
but ended up choosing two Compaqs to fill the budget and desktop
replacement slots.
</P>
<P>
   The 1200-XL is just $1,199 but is stacked with features that
will appeal directly to most students. The screen is not the
biggest, nor the processor the fastest, but it's got a full
complement of ports and slots for expansion (including USB) and has
a built-in floppy drive, CD-ROM drive and 56K modem. It also
bundles Microsoft's Works 2000 suite, with Word and the Encarta
encyclopedia, two educational essentials.
</P>
<P>
   On the fun side, it's got 3-D video acceleration for game
playing and MPEG video playback capabilities, as well as great
audio features. It sports JBL Pro Audio speakers with Bass Reflex
and special audio CD player function keys and a volume control
button.
</P>
<P>
   There are also special Internet buttons that take you directly
to common Web functions like search.
</P>
<P>
   The Desktop Replacement:
</P>
<P>
   -- Compaq Presario 1800. The Presario 1800 we looked at on
Compaq's build-to-order Web site weighs no more than the 1200-XL
but packs in the power. It's got all the above features, plus a
14.1-inch screen, big enough to watch movies on, and a DVD drive to
play them.
</P>
<P>
   It's also got a superfast 600 MHz Pentium III processor and a
video out port so you can connect it to a TV monitor for showing
those DVDs. Integrated Ethernet lets students hook up to the
network outlets in classrooms and dorms, and a docking port
connector adds versatility. When you buy on the Web site, you also
get a Compaq inkjet printer for $1 and a coupon for a free upgrade
to Windows ME when it ships.
</P>
<P>
   The Ultralight:
</P>
<P>
   -- Sony PCG-Z505JE VAIO SuperSlim Pro. Sony's VAIO line combines
light weight (3.75 pounds), super multimedia features and
expandability. While it may be a little on the expensive side, if
you want an ultralight, it's a great choice with features that will
appeal to students.
</P>
<P>
   It's got a Memory Stick port for data exchange with certain
digital cameras and MP3 players, an IEEE 1394 port for connecting
DV camcorders, as well as a full suite of photo and movie editing
tools. It comes with an external USB floppy drive _ add a DVD drive
and you've got a real multimedia workhorse. A port replicator is
also included for easy desktop connections.
</P>
<P>
   The Mac Alternative:
</P>
<P>
   -- Apple iBook. Whether you choose blueberry or tangerine, the
iBook tastes great. It's designed with students in mind and has a
rugged case that can withstand backpack abuse.
</P>
<P>
   It also has a crisp 12.1-inch screen and a nice $1,599 price tag
(for $1,799 you can also get the 366 MHz Graphite Special Edition
model). The iBook has built-in Ethernet and an AirPort wireless
networking slot covering the connectivity bases. It lacks a
built-in floppy, like all of Apple's recent Macs, but you can
attach one to the USB port. All in all, it's a top-notch student
machine.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Becky Waring at  &LR; becky(AT)waring.org &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
