<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0661 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CHEAT-TECHTRICKS-SFCH     08-13 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEAT-TECHTRICKS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH-SAVVY STUDENTS NO LONGER NEED CHEAT SHEETS TO TRICK TEACHERS  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Call it high-tech cheating.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since graphical calculators started popping up in the
classroom, quick studies have found ways to program them with
complex formulas, hard-to-remember vocabulary words and other hints
to gain an edge during tests.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca, who asked that her last name not be used, said she and
her high school classmates in Los Angeles cheated all the time
using TI-85 calculators, especially in chemistry and calculus about
five years ago. Eventually, proctors for the Advanced Placement
tests got wise and started walking down the aisles, checking to
make sure all the students cleared their calculator's memory.
</P>
<P>
   But the students found a new trick: They programmed the gadgets
to display ``memory cleared'' when they pressed a button right next
to the actual key for erasing programs. ``The proctors never knew
the difference,'' said Rebecca, who now lives in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Experts easily cite other examples of how students are
increasingly employing their computers and other electronics to
gain an unfair edge. Some students use laser printers and tiny
fonts to squeeze more data onto crib sheets. Others swap answers by
sending short text messages with pagers and cell phones. Some
students have been caught hacking into school computers to change
their grades. And countless more have copied term papers and essays
posted online.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just too easy,'' said Don McCabe, a Rutgers University
management professor who has studied cheating for the past decade.
In a survey last fall, nearly 10 percent of college students
confessed to stealing papers from the Internet. ``There's no
question that the level of cheating is disturbingly high.''
</P>
<P>
   Other examples of high-tech cheating:
</P>
<P>
   - Thirty engineering students at Northeastern University were
caught earlier this year exploiting a bug in the school's computer
program that allowed them to copy each others' homework
assignments, which were stored online.
</P>
<P>
   -- University of California at Berkeley professors caught 150
students plagiarizing papers in two classes after the students were
told to upload the papers to a Web site run by Plagiarism.org, an
Oakland company that scans the Internet and a database of
previously uploaded papers to check for duplicates.
</P>
<P>
   -- Berkeley High School refused to graduate 29 seniors this year
after discovering they paid a classmate to break into a school
computer and raise their grades.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-eight students at Dartmouth College were charged with
copying the answers to a homework assignment that were posted
online, although the case was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, cheaters have long predated computers. And, although
there has been a rise in cheating since the '60s, McCabe says there
is little hard research to show a meteoric rise. McCabe suspects
that the same people who peered over their neighbors' exams years
ago or scribbled answers on their shoes are now using calculators
and online term-paper mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question it's attracted new people, but it's not a
wild increase,'' McCabe said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Zuidema, an administrator at UC Berkeley, said he has
seen no indications of an increase in cheating during the past few
years, though more people are getting caught copying information
from the Internet. Four years ago, the school even caught a student
trying to break into the school's computer system to change his
grades.
</P>
<P>
   Some stories are even more outlandish. McCabe, for instance,
loves to talk about the time a campus security guard spotted a van
slowly circling a high school in New Jersey. The first few times
seemed odd. Finally, when it came around a fourth time, the guard
stopped the van and checked inside.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from an anxious driver, he spotted someone seated at a
desk, text books fanned out in front of him. As it turned out, the
man was frantically figuring out the answers to an exam and
radioing them to a student inside the building. (One student had
sneaked out just after the test began to slip him a copy of the
exam.)
</P>
<P>
   Most examples of cheating are far more mundane. Students
routinely plug keywords for their homework assignments into an
Internet search engine, find some relevant text, then copy and
paste.
</P>
<P>
   Some go further, though, and grab entire essays. Dozens of sites
with names like Cheater.com, Net Essays and BigNerds.com provide
ready access to thousands of papers, often for free.
</P>
<P>
   The founder of Schoolsucks.com says 10,000 people a day visit
his site, which offers 4,500 free papers in 120 languages,
including Yiddish and Swahili. The 4-year-old Web site features the
word ``Homework'' with a red slash across it and an ``A+'' at the
bottom of a wrinkled sheet of notepaper.
</P>
<P>
   Founder Kenny Sahr brags that teachers are his best marketing
tool. He says instructors routinely warn students to steer clear of
the site, prompting the students to hop online to find out what all
the fuss is about.
</P>
<P>
   But even Sahr, 28, says ``it's stupid to plagiarize'' papers
from the site because many are poorly written. None of the papers
are graded, so some students aren't sure what they are downloading.
Plus, many teachers know about the site anyway, Sahr adds.
</P>
<P>
   McCabe, though, says it is common for younger students to grab
papers, even of relatively low quality, rather than spend time
doing homework. In focus groups, he said, kids say it is easy to
find information online and the ``teachers are clueless.''
</P>
<P>
   But McCabe said college students say it is harder to fool
professors because they demand higher quality and generally know
their particular field well.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not deterring cheaters from trying. John Barrie, a
recent UC Berkeley graduate who helped start Plagiarism.org a
little more than a year ago, said 15 percent of the college papers
uploaded into his system set off alarms _ meaning a similar paper
is already online or has been uploaded before. Barrie suspects that
most professors who don't use the software and often rely on
teaching assistants to check papers usually don't catch the
plagiarism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is a lot worse than anyone knows,'' he said.
``Students have been getting away with it in a bold-faced way.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrie says instructors at 125 campuses now use the tool, but
few use it campuswide. (UC Berkeley hopes to make it available to
every department starting this fall.)
</P>
<P>
   And both McCabe and Barrie say relatively few teachers bother to
go through the trouble of trying to catch cheaters or go through
the cumbersome disciplinary process to prove them guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, Barrie argues, if a prestigious college uses the service
campuswide and finds thousands of plagiarists, what would it mean
for the school's reputation?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they really want to turn over the rock?'' he asked. ``There
is not a lot of incentive for certain universities to do anything
about the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
