<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTS-PRODIGIES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 KIDS' KNOWLEDGE OF TECHNOLOGY CAN BE HUMBLING FOR THEIR PARENTS  &HT;     By DAN FOST 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ At the tender age of 10, Jake Schlackman enjoys
his role as his family's computer tutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You feel like you get to be the boss, for once,'' Jake said.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to computers, kids are often in charge, as
technophobic parents struggle to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   Often it's a blessing when a child like Jake can teach his dad
how to use Adobe Photoshop, or fix his grandmother's iMac so she
can access the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also a challenge for many parents who came of age in a
generation that didn't have computers and still want to take an
active role in their children's education.
</P>
<P>
   Have no fear. There are resources available. Librarians are
often willing to teach the basics of Net navigating. And teachers
can show parents the computer lab and discuss what kind of
instruction the kids are getting.
</P>
<P>
   Ambitious parents can even take classes at community colleges,
which offer affordable instruction in the basics of computers.
</P>
<P>
   And, echoing a common theme, one expert suggests the best
teacher of all.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all else fails, you go find a 17-year-old. They know it
all,'' said Warren Buckleitner, editor of Children's Software
Revue, a bimonthly magazine ( &LR; www.childrenssoftware.com &LR; ) published
in Flemington, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the experts say, when your child is more technically
adept than you are, don't fear it _ embrace it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell parents this is your biggest opportunity to let your
kids be the teacher,'' said Robin Raskin, editor in chief of
FamilyPC magazine. ``When you're going on vacation, let the wired
kid plan it. Have the wired kid research buying the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Anne Bubnic, who runs Custom Computers for Kids, a consultant
service in Novato, suggests volunteering in the schools. Parents
can lend a helping hand in the computer lab and learn at the same
time.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon Robertson, who teaches computers at McAteer High School
in San Francisco, is willing to help show parents around the
computer lab, but he says most of the parents he sees are
overwhelmed by the technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``They really appreciate that their kids are learning how to use
equipment that guarantees them at least a foothold in the job
market,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents with computers at home, however, need to be involved
when their children are using the computer. Bubnic advises keeping
the computer in a central, high-traffic area of the house, so you
can keep a watchful eye on how it is used.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not necessary for a parent to know everything, but it is
necessary for a parent to understand what a child is doing at the
computer,'' Bubnic said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents may often have to step in to set limhow long a
child may be online. ``Parents say the phone rings constantly _ and
it's always calls from kids who are already talking to their child
online,'' Bubnic said. When they're playing online games, for
instance, ``They'll call each other to say, `Did I just hit you, or
did you get me?'''
</P>
<P>
   Even the most computer-illiterate parents bring something to the
table when it comes to technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``You as a parent bring a moral framework and life experience
and set of attitudes,'' Raskin said. ``With issues like Napster and
plagiarism and pornography and hate sites, you as a parent can be
really effective. Those are issues that kids will face online, and
you'd better bring your parenting skills whether you understand
technology or not. But you'd better try to understand as much of
the technology as you can.''
</P>
<P>
   Dory Schramm of Alamo is one of those parents who fear the
Internet. She tried to set up her three young sons with restricted
Internet access, but the oldest boy was able to rig the machine so
he could send instant messages and cruise the Net freely.
</P>
<P>
   Schramm gave up and let him do it, and gave her other boys
complete Net access as well. ``There's a trust thing you have to
have with your kids,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, parents who find computers intimidating need to
remain calm.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, said Stephen Gass, group president of Sesame Workshop,
which produces  &LR; www.sesamestreet.com &LR; , ``It wasn't so long ago
people were dubious about cash machines and voice mail. It will get
easier. It always does.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Dan Fost at  &LR; fostd(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
