<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0667 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DISTANCE-LEARNING-SFC     08-13 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISTANCE-LEARNING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE UNIVERSITIES TO OFFER CLASSES, DEGREE PROGRAMS VIA
THE  INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ For college student Jaxon Louie, taking an online
course has several advantages.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can go to school ... without leaving home,'' said the
University of California at Berkeley student. ``I remember waking
up one minute before a class session, turning on the computer and
in a matter of moments I was there.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, there are no crowded classrooms and ``you won't
get bored because you could be doing other things at the same time
_ like watch TV,'' Louie said.
</P>
<P>
   Louie is one of business Professor George Cluff's class of
``Space Bears,'' a dozen students enrolled in a unique 12-week
course designed to be the school's first fully online undergraduate
class.
</P>
<P>
   The business course, ``Strategic Planning for a Global
Economy,'' is taught through a Web site that features an online
lecture room, a tutorial room, links to research material and a
chat room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the first bears in cyberspace,'' said Cluff, drawing the
name from the nickname of Cal's sports teams, the Golden Bears.
``The intent is to reach students anywhere in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   They are not alone in cyberspace. The Internet is quietly but
quickly transforming distance education, with august institutions
such as Stanford University, Cornell University and Temple
University offering continuing education classes and degrees
online.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's any school anywhere where distance
learning is not on their agenda,'' said Mike Rouan, manager of
Stanford Online, which offers a master's degree in electrical
engineering.
</P>
<P>
   Distance learning itself is not new. Mail-order correspondence
schools have been around for a century, and more recently, students
have ``attended'' classes brought to them by television or CD-ROM.
But the Internet is proving to be a faster and more comprehensive
method of delivering education away from the traditional classroom.
</P>
<P>
   According to the education research firm Market Data Retrieval,
72 percent of 1,028 colleges surveyed said they offered distance
learning programs last year, 34 percent of them offering an
accredited degree. That was a jump from the year before, when only
48 percent offered distance learning programs, and only 15 percent
offered degrees.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 700,000 people took online courses last year, and
that number is expected to balloon to 2.2 million by 2002, said
Terry Hartle, senior vice president of the American Council on
Education, a trade group representing 1,800 two- and four-year
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   One example is the online program run by the University of
Maryland University College _ the biggest in the world _ where
enrollment in classes has exploded from 10,000 just two years ago
to 40,000 this year, Hartle said.
</P>
<P>
   And the University of Phoenix, which has become the largest
private university in the country, offers online bachelor's degrees
in business and information technology for its 12,000 registered
online students.
</P>
<P>
   By far, most of the online courses available are related to
business, finance, accounting or electronics, ``which are going to
trump humanities, social sciences and fine arts for the time
being,'' Hartle said.
</P>
<P>
   The courses offered online mainly cater to the needs of working
professionals who have a hard time making it to a classroom once or
twice a week, but seek some post-degree education to improve their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Students are taking the courses whenever it suits them,''
Hartle said. ``If they want to take the course at three in the
morning dressed in their bathrobes, it's up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford Online, part of the Engineering School's Center for
Professional Development, is an outgrowth of curriculum offered by
the Stanford Instructional Television Network for the past 31
years. Geared toward Silicon Valley professionals who already have
bachelor's degrees, the school has delivered continuing education
classes through closed-circuit television and videotape.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Internet, class lectures on subjects like computer
programming or accounting can be streamed live and archived for
later viewing, giving students a ``hybrid'' clicks-and-mortar
classroom experience, Rouan said.
</P>
<P>
   On the Stanford Online Web site, a demonstration of a virtual
class shows video from a professor's lecture on molecular biology
streamed on one side of the screen, with slides from the
accompanying PowerPoint presentation on the other. Other links call
up the course description, class assignments, grades and chat rooms
to contact other students.
</P>
<P>
   Some regular students are using the online courses to review
lectures they attended in person or to be able to take two courses
scheduled at the same time. Some are even using them to forgo
sitting sleepily through an 8 a.m. class in favor of a 10 p.m.
replay.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the biggest number of hits to online courses come
between 10 p.m. and 2 a.m., Rouan said.
</P>
<P>
   Cluff's class at UC Berkeley was designed to give students the
option of staying completely online _ interacting directly with
Cluff by e-mail or chat rooms _ or combining that with
person-to-person visits with the professor. Most opted for the
face-to-face visits.
</P>
<P>
   The class was designed for 42 students, but had only 12 this
summer because of some ``administrative glitches.'' Cluff hopes to
get the full complement next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Cluff said he believes more reliance on online education
programs will become one major solution to the problem faced by the
state's university system, which won't be able to build enough
classrooms to handle a spike in enrollment expected during the next
three to five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to use existing bricks and mortar more
intelligently,'' Cluff said.
</P>
<P>
   Online education is not without controversy. Critics still
question whether students can get the same quality education
through an impersonal computer as they can with face-to-face
interaction with teachers and other students.
</P>
<P>
   Critics also say the rise in distance learning is turning
education into a commercial commodity that might distract colleges
from their traditional purpose: expanding students' minds.
</P>
<P>
   But Hartle said online education continues to grow. Some
education experts estimate distance learning will become a
$250-billion-a-year market. Web sites like HungryMinds.com,
DigitalThink.com, WebCT.com and Blackboard.com have sprung up to
position themselves as portals to online learning. And universities
such as Stanford, Carnegie Mellon and Columbia have signed deals
with UNext.com, an Illinois company that is creating a virtual
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a period of very rapid change in post-secondary
education,'' Hartle said. ``We're in the middle of a revolution,
and it's hard to tell where it's going to go. It's an era of
enormous promise and an era of enormous questions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
