<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIOSCOPE-ABATE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BIOSCOPE: PRESCRIPTION PRICES VEXING CONGRESS  &HT;     By TOM ABATE  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ As visiting lawmakers filed off the bus at Alza
Corp. in Mountain View, Calif., last week, they walked past a sign
that read: ``Welcome to 10 percent of the U.S. Congress.''
<P>
   The sign was a bit exaggerated. Several no-shows brought the
delegation down to three dozen lawmakers, all Democrats, who raced
through the region to gawk at the New Economy on their way to their
party's convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the sentiment was valid. The Alza tour, which was
organized by Rep. Anna Eshoo, D-Atherton, Calif., and Rep. Nancy
Pelosi, D-San Francisco, is arguably the largest congressional
junket to ever view the region's biotech industry.
</P>
<P>
   The visit came at a time when Congress is wrestling with how to
add prescription drug benefits to Medicare without bankrupting a
system that is already on the financial ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Prescriptions have never been covered by basic Medicare. That
puts the payment burden on seniors whose prescription bills can run
thousands of dollars a year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bipartisan desire to please the potent senior lobby,
election-year politics worked against change. Republicans wanted to
solve the problem by encouraging seniors to join Medicare HMOs.
Democrats said that wasn't a solution because HMOs are pulling out
of some locales, especially rural areas. Democrats proposed having
Medicare pay for prescriptions directly but that ran into
Republican objections to a new government-funded entitlement.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, both parties decided they'd get more mileage out of
blaming each other for failure than they could have by sharing
credit for a successful compromise.
</P>
<P>
   But when the new Congress convenes next year, the Medicare drug
issue will remain at the top of the agenda _ along with the
question of how to pay for a benefit that will cost tens of
billions of dollars. And the big fear in industry circles is that
lawmakers will be tempted to enact some form of price control to
cap the overall cost.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of this was discussed openly during the two-hour
congressional stopover at Alza. This event was a soft sell, a
chance to show off the developments pouring out of Bay Area biotech
labs, with the subtle subtext being not to kill the goose that lays
the golden egg.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn Kailian, chief executive of Cor Therapeutics, talked
about his company's new drug, Integrilin, which unclogs blocked
arteries. ``We think we've prevented 10,000 heart attacks, which
makes us pretty proud,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ajit Gil, chief executive of Inhale Therapeutics, showed off a
new device that dispenses a powdery form of insulin. If Inhale wins
government approval next year, it will provide diabetics with the
option of inhaling their daily insulin dose instead of taking
injections.
</P>
<P>
   The closest the discussion ever came to Medicare was during a
presentation by Michael Coffee, president of Elan Pharmaceuticals
in South San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Elan is beginning human trials of a drug that shows great
promise for preventing and treating Alzheimer's disease. Coffee,
together with Elan chief scientist Dale Schenk, explained how it
has taken 10 years and tens of millions of dollars just to bring
their drug to Phase I clinical trials _ where it still stands only
a 30 percent chance of getting approved to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're relying on investor confidence and the kind of
(financial) environment we have here in America,'' Coffee said in
polite political code.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, I asked Coffee to spell out his concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Price controls,'' he said without hesitation. Without the
unfettered ability to charge whatever the market will bear for hit
drugs, the industry could never afford to pay for its many
failures.
</P>
<P>
   Coffee said price controls have already undermined the drug
industries of Europe. It is an open secret in pharmaceutical
circles that every developed country, with the exception of the
United States, has some form of government price controls on drugs.
Coffee said these controls have driven firms like his _ Elan is an
Irish company _ to American shores.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be a lot of drug development in the United
Kingdom and France and Germany but now much of it takes place
here,'' said Coffee, because the free market permits a higher
potential return on investment.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the absence of price controls also means Americans
pay more for prescription drugs than, say, Europeans or Japanese.
Whenever I question industry lobbyists about this, they say that
America's free-wheeling system benefits the whole world. American
venture capitalists take the biggest risks and support the
companies that produce the most innovative drugs, in part because
they know they can get the biggest rewards here. If Congress
changes that risk-reward ratio, it risks slowing down the pace of
medical development for the entire world.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. Or perhaps medical science would quit chasing riches
and focus on public health measures that, while not as profitable
as a new patented remedy, might yield more health benefit than
costly wonder drugs.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, when Congress takes up the Medicare drug issue
next year, the cost of the program is sure to spawn debate about
prices. ``They (industry leaders) know if we provide a benefit, we
have a duty to control the costs,'' said Rep. Pete Stark,
D-Hayward, Calif., one of the ranking leaders in the House
hierarchy on health issues.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, drug industry leaders should at least thank
Americans for subsidizing drug development through their
prescription payments. I'm thinking of TV spots along the lines of
the old Chevron spiel: ``Do Americans really pay more for
prescriptions so that drug companies can be rewarded for developing
remedies for the whole world? Americans do.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Tom Abate at  &LR; abate(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
