<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0675 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SCHOLARS-GRANTS-SFCHR     08-13 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOLARS-GRANTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB-SURF YOUR WAY TO COLLEGE BY RESEARCHING GRANTS,
SCHOLARSHIPS  ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 &HT;     c.2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ If you care to do research on the North American
loon, you could land a $3,000 education grant.
</P>
<P>
   If birds aren't your thing, the makers of Calgon bath and body
lotions have up to $2,500 in scholarship money ready for students
who can stomach answering fragrant queries like this one in 450
words or less:
</P>
<P>
   ``Calgon flavors like Sparkling Raspberries, In the Rain and
Moon Petal Musk are truly inspired! Which teacher inspired you most
and how?''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the Web, it's easier than ever to find these and
thousands of well-known-to-obscure scholarships and grants to help
pay your way through college. But be prepared to spend a little
time answering questions and sifting through dozens of pages of
information.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, don't fall for scams that ask you to pay any money
to search for scholarships because the information is already there
online for free, said Tim McDonough, public affairs director for
the American Council on Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get very nervous when we find out about a service that asks
people to send in $200 or $300 to have them do a scholarship
search,'' McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   Students and parents may want to first peruse the Federal Trade
Commission's Web site on how to avoid scholarship scams,
www.ftc.gov/bcp/conline/edcams/scholarship/sixsigns.htm.
</P>
<P>
   Next, there's the U.S. Department of Education's Student
Financial Assistance Web site at
www.ed.gov/offices/OSFAP/Students/, where you can learn about a
program that provides more than $40 billion a year in grants,
loans, and work-study assistance. You can also apply online.
</P>
<P>
   Your school of choice may even have online financial aid
information. The University of California at Berkeley, for example,
is developing a Scholarship Connection Web site with online and
off-line resources. The site, at http://scholarships.berkeley.edu,
will soon have a searchable database.
</P>
<P>
   Another place to start an online scholarship search is
www.collegeispossible.org, a Web site that is part of a pro-college
campaign sponsored by the Council on Education and numerous
organizations like the National Association for Student Financial
Aid Administrators and the College Board.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site has links to five free online search services
operated by Fastweb.com, the College Board, SRN Express, College
Net and Sallie Mae.
</P>
<P>
   According to the site, 95 percent of scholarships come from the
federal or state governments or individual colleges and
universities, covering bigger portions of tuitions or educational
fees. The remaining 5 percent come from private loans and
scholarships, where the awards of $500 or less are still good
enough to pay for books or other incidental expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial college-help Web sites like San Francisco's
Embark.com also use databases like Sallie Mae's WiredScholar.com
service, which you can also access directly.
</P>
<P>
   I searched several different sites on behalf of my son, who is a
high school senior and is thinking about a career in medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites, like www.scholarships.com, require you to enter more
than two dozen fields of detailed information to help narrow the
scholarship search. These include the student's PSAT, SAT and ACT
scores, college choices, hobbies, religion, household income and
date of birth.
</P>
<P>
   McDonough said parents and students should carefully consider
whether they want to divulge such information or data like a Social
Security number.
</P>
<P>
   The searches turned up several pages worth of scholarship
possibilities that would be otherwise hard to gather from just
reading the bulletin boards outside a high school guidance
counselor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson's CollegeQuest.com, for example, dug up the $100 to
$3,000 grants from the North American Loon Fund for ``research,
management and education projects'' on that bird _ presumably a
grant for upper division or grad students, not college freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   More on the mark, CollegeQuest.com came back with information on
the California Student Aid Commission, which last year awarded
educational grants worth $1,410 to $9,422.
</P>
<P>
   Fastweb.com, which according to San Francisco online monitoring
service Media Metrix Inc. was the busiest online scholarship site
in June, returned 18 possible scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   One was from the National Society of the Sons of the American
Revolution Inc., which was giving as many as three awards worth up
$7,500 to students who submit the best 500- to 750-word essays on
``The U.S. Constitution: Does it stand the test of time?''
</P>
<P>
   And the Texas Sheep and Goat Raiser's Auxiliary and the American
Land Foundation are awarding $100 to $1,000 to junior and senior
high school students who submit the best entries in a
letter-writing contest answering the burning question, ``Should
private property rights be an issue in the 2000 election
campaign?''
</P>
<P>
   Scholarships.com turned up 56 givers, from the Northern
California Scholarship Foundation to the National Italian American
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The College Board's search program wasn't nearly as intrusive
because it didn't ask for specific personal details like name or
household income.
</P>
<P>
   But it still turned up 28 possible scholarships and grants from
sponsors such as Tylenol, Target, Prudential and the National
Association of Secondary School Principals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(at)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of SCHOLARS (104453 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
