<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTWARE-SATTEST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAT PREPARATION PROGRAMS OFFER GOOD TEST-TAKING TACTICS  

</HEADLINE>
   By KELLY ZITO  
 c.2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, so I went about the SATs all wrong.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what I learned after experimenting with some of
the software titles designed to help raise scores on the dreaded
Scholastic Achievement Test _ one of the rights of passage for most
college-bound students.
</P>
<P>
   Way back in 1989 when I took the SATs, my math and English
teachers stressed memorizing endless geometry formulas and
vocabulary lists. In other words, they advocated doing every
problem and analogy the long _ or right _ way.
</P>
<P>
   While I did relatively well (don't bother skipping ahead, I
won't tell you my score), I'll bet I would have done much better if
I had used some of the techniques outlined in some of the leading
SAT preparation software titles.
</P>
<P>
   The three products I reviewed _ the Princeton Review Inside the
SAT, ACT and PSAT (2000 edition); Kaplan SAT &AMP; PSAT (2001 edition);
and Compton's Learning Score Builder for the SAT, PSAT &AMP; ACT _
varied in graphics quality and ease of use. But all three
emphasized working around the SAT questions. That is, when unsure
of the correct answer, eliminate possible wrong answers and avoid
thinking like the test writers. (I reviewed only Windows versions
and focused on the SAT portion because it was a common denominator
among all three programs.)
</P>
<P>
   In fact, all three programs took decidedly irreverent approaches
to the SAT.
</P>
<P>
   When I loaded the discs into my computer, I envisioned screen
after screen of questions right out of the SAT test booklets.
Rather, the programs seemed to undermine the SAT process
altogether. For example, the writers at Educational Testing
Services _ the New Jersey firm that makes the SAT _ were described
alternately as ``chumps'' and ``wacky.''
</P>
<P>
   The first product I tried, The Princeton Review SAT software,
published by the Learning Co., even went so far as calling the ETS
staffers ``evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the name calling, I liked this program a lot,
particularly the ``General Strategies'' section. It provided a
great overview of the test, told users how to spot ``trap answers''
and offered some important tips, such as the fact that both math
and verbal questions are divided into three sections in order:
easy, medium and difficult (the other programs mention these
concepts as well).
</P>
<P>
   The program's ``tutors'' were live-action Gen X types with
untucked flannel shirts and backward baseball caps, the kind of
guides who would keep teenagers interested without patronizing
them.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of SOFTWARE (28582 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The main menu is an easy-to-navigate hallway, divided into
``General Strategies,'' ``Verbal,'' ``Math'' and a few others,
including the ``Counselor's Room,'' where users can peruse a
college applications road map or the average SAT scores for
hundreds of schools.
</P>
<P>
   Once inside the Verbal or Math ``rooms,'' users proceed through
various lessons. At any point, the user can click on an ``index''
button and skip questions or continue ahead within each section,
such as the ``Critical Reading'' portion.
</P>
<P>
   This lesson, which focuses a specific set of questions in the
Verbal section, emphasized that test takers shouldn't spend too
much time reading or memorizing the test's passages. It advised
users to get a general idea of what the passage is about, then move
as quickly as possible to the questions _ which include usually
only one about the passage's overall meaning.
</P>
<P>
   One of my only criticisms about this product is that Web access
_ which links to important sites on financial aid and virtual
campus tours _ was buried in the ``Counselor's Room.'' I think it
should have been one of the main doors off the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, this preparation course was well organized, the
interface was well designed and it was humorous without being
annoying.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with the next piece of software I tried, Kaplan SAT &AMP;
PSAT, published by Kaplan, the same company that runs training
centers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   This program offered many of the hints about test taking the
other programs offered. But the introduction was long, and some of
the bells and whistles were more irritating than helpful.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when you choose a wrong answer, the sound effect
was of glass breaking. After getting many of the math questions
wrong (calculus was many years ago), I was very tired of the
shattering sound.
</P>
<P>
   The animations _ such as a cartoon contrasting the successful
and unsuccessful SAT test taker _ were more stylized than those of
the Princeton Review program. But some seemed a bit childish _
aimed more at elementary rather than high school students.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the technology didn't seem as advanced. A few
times, the program wouldn't let me type in an answer where
required, and the main ``guide'' through the program was jerky or
was cut off midsentence.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to the third program I tried, Compton's Learning
Score Builder for the SAT, PSAT &AMP; ACT, also published by the
Learning Co. This program was decent but was lacking on the visual
side.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it stressed some of the tactics outlined above. In
addition, it let users fashion their own lesson plan and pace. But
the interface in this case proved very unengaging.
</P>
<P>
   The main guide through the program is a computer, with a British
accent, named Hallie. Though she sounded pleasant enough, staring
at my computer screen at another computer screen was not conducive
to learning. Also, some of the colors were so dark that I had a
difficult time making out some text.
</P>
<P>
   I liked the drills that popped up after each lesson. My favorite
part was the ``Word Rally'' vocabulary builder/video game. The user
drives a virtual car down a straight road. Word definitions pop up
on a small screen on the dashboard, and the user must honk the horn
at the correct word, which flies toward you on the road. If you
pick the right one, the word splats on your windshield.
</P>
<P>
   The concept was a little hokey and the graphics crude, but I had
fun and found myself learning some new words along the way.
</P>
<P>
   In sum, these SAT programs might help average test takers bump
up their scores without spending hundreds of dollars on an SAT prep
course. All three provided behind-the-scenes clues about how the
SATs are structured, how to save time and how to avoid common
fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   For my money, though, I thought the Princeton Review SAT
software was the best, in part because it seemed the most well
thought out and easy to use.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito &LR; (at) &LR; sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
