r f BC-APPLY-COLLEGES-SFCHRO     08-13 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLY-COLLEGES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 INTERNET EASES THE TRAUMA OF FILLING OUT COLLEGE APPLICATIONS  &HT;     By CARRIE KIRBY 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kids today have it so easy.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a college graduate of practically any age, you
probably had to choose between typing college application forms and
filling them out in pen. The first option was a disaster _ the
form's tiny blanks were impossible to aim at, and after 15 tries
your application would be so heavy with Wite-Out, it would require
extra postage. As for using pen, if your handwriting wasn't neat,
you were doomed.
</P>
<P>
   But for today's high school graduates, applying to college is as
simple as logging on to a Web site, accessing an online version of
a school's application, filling it out, adding a credit-card number
for the application fee and hitting Send.
</P>
<P>
   Fully 65 percent of schools accepted online applications in
1999, according to a survey by consulting firm Education Now and
online application service ApplyYourself. Some schools, such as the
University of California system, offer applications on their own
Web sites, while others let outside companies such as Embark.com or
CollegeLink create applications for them.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet makes it easier for students to figure out which
colleges to apply to as well. Many of the services that provide
online applications also help kids pick a school by asking them
questions and searching databases of college profiles for
institutions that match their interests, grades and budget. Some of
these Web sites help students interact with their prospective
schools by e-mailing in questions or suggesting themselves to
college recruiters.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt that the PC is an easier route to admission
than the traditional process of reading brochures, visiting the
school counselor, touring the campus and filling out paperwork. But
is it a better route?
</P>
<P>
   First of all, online search and application services stress that
they are not out to replace school counselors. In fact, San
Francisco's Embark.com has a version of its college search product
designed for counselors, called the Educational and Career
Opportunities System.
</P>
<P>
   But in California public schools, there are more than 1,000
students for each counselor, far exceeding the national standard of
250 to 1, a goal set by the American School Counselor Association.
In many schools, a college-bound senior may not have many
opportunities to meet with a counselor one-on-one. So it makes
sense for students to use the Internet to explore college choices
on their own, and come to counseling sessions prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives you an idea, from the counselor's point of view, of
what the kid is interested in,'' said Mission High School principal
Marigrace Cohen, whose school has used Embark's system for two
years.
</P>
<P>
   While online pictures and text can't substitute for a real
college visit, the Internet is making it easier for students to
learn about schools outside their geographic area. Acknowledging
that, the National Association of College and Admissions Counseling
is augmenting its real-life college fairs with online events for
the first time this year.
</P>
<P>
   Physical NACAC college fairs take place in convention centers in
36 U.S. cities, where a representative from each school sets up a
booth and speaks with prospective students. Because of travel
costs, schools usually send only one or two employees to college
fairs. But in the online version _ the first of which takes place
October 19 at  &LR; www.onlinecollegefair.com &LR;  _ high school students
will be able to chat with a college's current students and
financial aid counselors.
</P>
<P>
   Admissions counselors say applying online does not help or hurt
students' chances of getting accepted. However, some say
applications submitted online are more likely to have missing
information or errors, and essays sent via the Internet are usually
shorter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Proofreading is key,'' said Paul Marthers, director of
admissions at Ohio's Oberlin College. ``Don't hit the Send command
until you are sure you have finished the application and filled it
out correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   And much like paper applications that get lost in the mail,
electronic forms sometimes get lost somewhere in the pipeline, some
counselors report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tell our kids, if you're doing online applications, follow
up with a paper application,'' said Mission High principal Cohen.
However, not all colleges agree with that advice; some instruct
students not to send duplicate applications.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for caution is that many of the companies that
create and run online applications are money-losing dot-coms
fighting for market share in a highly competitive business. If one
or more close their doors, who knows what would happen to the
college applications filed through them?
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, electronic college applications have become as
popular as paper ones with students. A poll conducted by education
market research firm Art &AMP; Science and sponsored by Embark showed
that 43 percent of students preferred applying online, while 44
percent preferred using paper.
</P>
<P>
   The survey also found that 35 percent of the graduates in the
class of 2000 submitted at least one online application. The
telephone survey found that almost all prospective college students
had access to the Internet either at home, at school or _ most
commonly _ both places.
</P>
<P>
   However, just having Internet access does not automatically make
it possible to apply online. Most services require a credit-card
number, something many of her students did not have access to,
Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   Online applications are bound to become more common, since many
colleges encourage the practice. In fact, at least two schools,
West Virginia Wesleyan College and the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology's Sloan School of Management, now accept only online
applications. Schools expect to save on data-entry costs and they
hope to process applications more quickly when the entire procedure
is computerized.
</P>
<P>
   So those coveted acceptance letters might arrive a little
sooner. Since going electronic, the University of California at
Berkeley is sending out letters two days earlier. But don't expect
today's teens to be impressed with gains like that: For a
generation raised on automated teller machines, one-hour photo
developing and online instant messaging, anything short of instant
acceptance won't be fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carrie Kirby at  &LR; ckirby(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
