u p BC-CVN-CARTER14-COX     08-13 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CVN-CARTER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONVENTION FILM TO HONOR CARTER
 &HT;    By MELANIE EVERSLEY
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The big news tonight at the Democratic National
Convention will be President Clinton's farewell speech.
</P>
<P>
   But another Democratic chief executive, former president Jimmy
Carter, will also have a moment in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   A five minute-film will pay tribute to Carter.
</P>
<P>
   The former president said he has been told the tribute will
focus largely on his work during his presidency from 1976 to 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reports say it's very good,'' Carter said, smiling during
an interview in his hotel room Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   The genesis of Monday night's film, Carter explained, came about
earlier this year when he, former President Gerald Ford and Henry
Kissinger visited the White House to pore over the details of
granting permanent normal trade relations status to China.
</P>
<P>
   Gore pulled Carter aside and asked him if he would consider
speaking at the Democratic convention, Carter recalled. Carter said
that he did not want to get involved in the typical convention
competition jostling for prime speaking time.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the film tribute to Ford during the Republican
National Convention in Philadelphia two weeks ago, Gore thought a
film tribute would be another way to recognize Carter's work yet
still respect Carter's desire to stay away from the political
limelight.
</P>
<P>
   During the interview, Carter applauded Gore's selection of Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., as his running mate. He said Gore has
been wise to separate himself from the moral shortcomings of the
Clinton White House, and he admires the fact that Lieberman was
among the first Democratic critics of Clinton's affair with White
House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, there are parallels for this ticket and what
Carter has experienced. When the former president took office, a
previously sheltered American public seemed enthralled and curious
about a president who was not only a Southern Baptist, but a devout
one as well.
</P>
<P>
   Carter remembered reporters asking him if he was a born-again
Christian and he replied yes, explaining his faith was ``like
breathing'' for him. ``The members of the press thought it was a
radical and mysterious and cult thing,'' Carter recalled with a
laugh.
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, the public has devoted similar attention and
curiosity to Lieberman's devotion to his Judaism. Carter said he
feels this is a positive sign that the American public continues to
become more tolerant of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Tolerance also is a key word of a different kind when it comes
to the Gore-Lieberman ticket in Carter's mind. It has been no
secret that Carter and the Clinton White House have shared a
strained relationship. Published reports have indicated that the
White House has not been happy when Carter has stepped in to help
alleviate tensions around the world, although Carter has said he
has always kept the White House informed of his doings.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday night's tribute, Carter said, also serves as a
welcome sign that he will enjoy a good relationship if Al Gore
makes it all the way to the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm looking forward to,'' Carter said with a warm
smile. ``In this administration, Al Gore is the one who has been my
friend. I'm not criticizing anyone else. Whenever I have had access
to the White House, it has been through al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Some convention attendees considered the tribute a just dessert
for Carter, who has logged success after success in steering
political negotiations with world leaders, but whose presidency has
been subject to criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Lewis, D-Ga., who is a delegate at the convention,
said Sunday that Democrats were happy to have a chance to recognize
Carter for his human rights work, which has included overseeing
potentially troubled elections around the world. Carter and his
wife, Rosalynn, are also active with Habitat for Humanity, a
national, non-profit organization that constructs housing for the
poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's fitting and appropriate that this party pays
tribute to Jimmy Carter. He is a man who tried to do his best to
bring integrity to government,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since he left the White House, he's been looking to help
people home and abroad,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   The tribute also is a sign that someone still recognizes the
record and work of Southern Democrats, said Tom Eisenhauer,
communications director for Rep. Martin Frost, D-Texas, who also is
chair of the House Democratic Caucus. Pundits seem to forget people
such as Sen. Zell Miller, D-Ga., Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., Carter
and others, Eisenhauer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a reminder of the Democrats' strength in the South,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
