<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0679 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-TECH21-NORR-SFCHRON &LR;      08-13 2233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH21-NORR-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSERVATION IS QUESTION OF VALUES _ COLUMN HEATS UP DEBATE  &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRY NORR  
 c.2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Little did I know, when I observed in last week's column that
there's a disagreement about computers' contribution to our power
problems, that I was wandering into a nasty little debate involving
not only technical and methodological issues, but also political
and even philosophical ones.
<P>
   The crux of the debate is the contention that computers and
peripherals today consume about 13 percent of the nation's
available power, including 8 percent specifically for Internet use.
I first noticed these numbers in an Associated Press report from an
``energy summit'' held in Redwood City, Calif., in June, but it
turns out they've been cited in just about every major publication
in the country over the last year.
</P>
<P>
   It also turns out that the ultimate source, direct or indirect,
for these estimates is a 1999 study called ``The Internet Begins
with Coal,'' written by Mark P. Mills and published by the Greening
Earth Society of Arlington, Va. The figures entered mainstream
discussion through an article by Mills and Peter W. Huber that
appeared in the May 31, 1999, issue of Forbes Magazine under the
title ``Dig more coal _ the PCs are coming.''
</P>
<P>
   What the self-styled ``capitalist tool'' didn't bother to tell
its readers is that Mills, who worked in the White House Science
Office during the Reagan years and now runs a Washington, D.C.,
consulting company, is tightly tied to the energy industry.
According to his biography on the Greening Earth society's Web site
( &LR; www.greeningearthsociety.org &LR; ), he has worked with more than 80
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Forbes mention the Greening Earth Society, much less
explain what it &LR;   &LR; is. In fact, it's a nonprofit organization
created by the Western Fuels Association Inc., a cooperative that
mines and buys coal and supplies it to rural electric cooperatives
and municipal utilities ( &LR; www.westernfuels.org &LR; ).
</P>
<P>
   According to the greening group's executive director, Chris
Paynter, Western Fuels set it up in 1998 to defend carbon dioxide
against the EPA's efforts to regulate it as a pollutant and, more
broadly, to promote the virtues of fossil fuels, ``one of the
Creator's greatest gifts to humankind.'' (In addition to its main
Web site,  &LR; www.greeningearthsociety.org &LR; , the group also runs
 &LR; www.fossilfuels.org &LR; .)
</P>
<P>
   In the society's view, ``Nature is growing stronger, bigger,
greener and more resilient as a result of what we humans are doing
to promote our own growth'' _ including in particular our
increasing consumption of fossil fuels and the resulting increases
in atmospheric concentrations of carbon dioxide. The group doesn't
deny the greenhouse effect _ it argues that it's a good thing,
because, ``Our use of fossil fuels is helping give plants the extra
CO2 they need to grow more lush and green worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does all this relate to Mills' study of high technology
and power consumption?
</P>
<P>
   Judging not only by the Forbes article but also by other
writings of his posted online, it appears that he is trying to
polish up the somewhat tattered image of the industry he works for
(he admits it's ``widely thought to be in senescent decline'') by
linking it with the wonders of high technology. He even argues in
Forbes _ without providing any supporting evidence _ that it takes
a pound of coal to ``create, package, store and move 2 megabytes of
data.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, none of this proves his numbers are wrong, but
there's plenty of evidence that they are. His calculations start
from the contention that a ``typical PC and its peripherals require
about 1,000 watts of power.'' That figure caught my eye
immediately, because it's six or seven times higher than the
numbers I got last week from the EPA and Dell.
</P>
<P>
   That's only one of many places where Mills' assumptions about
electrical consumption differ dramatically from other sources.
Jonathan Koomey, staff scientist in the Energy Analysis Department
of the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory _ a group that
conducts detailed measurements of specific devices' power
consumption, as well as macro-level analyses of electricity usage,
often on contract to the EPA _ pointed me to a critique his group
did of Mills' work and to its own recent study of ``Electricity
Used by Office Equipment and Network Equipment in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   I won't go into all the details here _ if you're interested, you
can find a dispassionate overview of the debate and links to all
the main papers at  &LR; enduse.lbl.gov/Projects/InfoTech.html &LR; . The
bottom line is that the Berkeley scientists conclude that office
equipment, including home computers and peripherals, plus network
equipment, accounted for about 74 terawatt hours (74 billion
kilowatt hours) in 1999. That's a mere 2 percent of total
electricity use in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Of those 74 terawatt hours, more than 70 percent go to power
office equipment in commercial settings (offices, basically), while
residential and industrial office machines each soak up about 12
percent, and network equipment takes 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even when you factor in the power used in the manufacture of the
equipment _ including semiconductors _ you still come out to no
more than 3.2 percent of total U.S. consumption _ less than a
quarter of Mills' widely repeated estimate.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, even in the ``New Economy'' computers are pretty
small potatoes in the larger energy picture. In that light, is it
even worth worrying about power-saving settings or shutting down at
night?
</P>
<P>
   Many readers, I'm sure, will say no. In fact, most already have,
implicitly: Field audits the Berkeley group has conducted show that
only about 25 percent of desktop computers have power management
features in use and operating properly.
</P>
<P>
   But in the aggregate the stakes aren't trivial. Even with the
limited support power management now gets from office-equipment
users, it saves 23 terawatt hours a year, the Berkeley group
estimates _ roughly a quarter of what this equipment would
otherwise consume. With ``complete saturation of power management''
_ if such capabilities were built into all equipment, properly
configured and activated _ an additional 17 terawatt hours a year
could be saved.
</P>
<P>
   And shutting down all office equipment except mainframes,
minicomputers, servers and faxes would save an additional 7
terawatt hours per year. (Office-equipment power consumption in
1999 was 15 percent higher than the Berkeley group had projected
back in 1995. One reason, according to Koomey, is that monitors are
consuming more power in active use than expected, but the main
problem is that more PCs and laser printers than anticipated are
left on at might.)
</P>
<P>
   Whether such savings justify investing a few minutes to set up
power-management software and waiting for a sleeping system to wake
up is really a question of values. I've already said where I stand,
and I won't do any more preaching here.
</P>
<P>
   But I do want to address some more down-to-earth objections and
questions readers raised after last week's column.
</P>
<P>
   -- Backup. A couple of readers noted that their employers forbid
them to shut down their computers because their data is backed up
or network-management software pushes out software updates over the
network at night. In that case, no argument _ leave your PC on.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't extend to your monitor _ neither backups nor
updates require that the screen be on. And remember that displays,
on average, use twice as much power as a PC when left on. Setting
your display to sleep when idle saves most of that juice, but
hitting the off button does even more _ and it takes only a second.
</P>
<P>
   -- Confusion. This one comes from The Chronicle's own
information technology staff, which told me the main reason it
disables power management in the standard software setup here is
that users get confused when they find a black screen _ too many
assume their PC has crashed, or that someone has shut it down, and
they proceed to hit the power button, intending to start the system
back up but actually shutting it down. The result: unsaved work is
lost, and sometimes disk directories get corrupted _ a major
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Those are real concerns, but it seems to me that some concerted
user education could go a long way toward alleviating them. PC
manufacturers could also help by putting unmistakable indicators
for sleep mode on the front of their systems. Apple has set a good
example here: New Macs have LEDs that pulse slowly, like a
heartbeat, when the machine is sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   -- Power spikes. Several readers wrote in to ask about the
argument that it takes more power to restart a PC and monitor than
you save by turning them off. This one has been around for
generations, but as far as I can determine, there's nothing at all
to it. That's what both Lawrence Berkeley's Koomey and Brian
Zucker, technology evangelist at Dell, told me. Zucker said it
takes hardly any more power to start a PC up than to keep it
running.
</P>
<P>
   -- Wear and tear. The last argument against shutting down your
PC regularly is that starts and stops increase wear and tear on
your system and could thus shorten the life of key components.
There's clearly some truth to this: As Dell's Zucker put it,
``Turning on a system causes more harm than letting it run for
several hours due to the electric stress presented. Signals will
jump to voltage levels higher than normal before settling to their
normal levels when power is applied.''
</P>
<P>
   Others note a related issue: thermal expansion. When your system
starts up, internal temperatures rise, and components expand
accordingly; when it's shut down, it cools, and the same parts
contract. Repeated often enough, this process can cause failure.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, let's keep this in perspective: Modern PC
components are designed to survive thousands of starts and stops.
Odds are, the system on your desk will become obsolete, relative to
the software of the day, long before it suffers electrical or
mechanical failure.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, as I mentioned last week, I've found that leaving
Windows on too long invites a crash. If that's the case, you're
going to suffer the stop/start wear-and-tear anyway _ you might as
well get some power savings out of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Putting all these considerations together, here's my advice in
summary: Look for power-management software on your system, and
when you find it, set it to put your PC and monitor to sleep after
10 or 15 minutes of inactivity, so it won't kick in every time you
stop to chat with a colleague or get embroiled in a phone call, but
will reduce your power when you head for lunch or a meeting. If you
don't have power-management software or can't get it to work right,
just switch off your monitor when you leave your desk for long. At
the end of your work shift, shut both your PC and your monitor down
unless your employer tells you not to; in that case, just shut down
the monitor.
</P>
<P>
   It may not do a whole lot to reduce electrical consumption, but
it's the right thing to do, and it's pretty painless.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
THE LATEST FROM REDMOND: A good part of Microsoft's success stems
from its persistence in improving its products, including some that
were mediocre at best when first released. I was reminded of this
pattern last week when I installed the latest version of
Microsoft's reference and research package, Encarta Reference Suite
2001.
</P>
<P>
   When the first Encarta encyclopedia appeared in 1993, it was a
competent but undistinguished entry in a crowded field. But the new
package is, frankly, awesome. It includes new versions of not only
the encyclopedia, but also the gorgeous Encarta Interactive World
Atlas and the Encarta World English Dictionary, together with a new
thesaurus, an almanac, an expanded book of quotations, a computer
and Internet dictionary, and other goodies.
</P>
<P>
   I was especially pleased with some of the new components in this
year's version: the third edition of Encarta Africana, an excellent
resource on black history and culture, which until now hasn't had
the distribution it deserves because it was sold separately and at
a relatively high price; a new Web Center, which enables users to
search either a selected set of high-quality Web sites or the
entire Web without leaving the Encarta environment; and Researcher,
an application that makes it easy to assemble text and graphics
copied _ complete with source citations _ from Encarta, the Web or
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   The whole package goes for $74.95 before a $10 rebate, and in my
book it's well worth the money, especially for families with kids
in school.
</P>
<P>
   One caveat, though: The suite fills seven CD-ROM discs, and
every time you switch among its components _ say, from Africana to
the atlas _ you have to swap out the CD, just like in the bad old
days of floppy disks. But if your PC has a DVD-ROM drive, you can
avoid that hassle by waiting until next month, when Microsoft plans
to release a DVD version at the same price. I haven't seen that
version yet, but Microsoft says that in addition to easier
integration, it will deliver more multimedia, including full-screen
versions of video clips that only fill a window in the CD version.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Tech21 appears every Monday in The Chronicle. Send your
comments and tips to Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr &LR; (at) &LR; sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
