<SLUG> BC-EDOVERVIEW-SCHOOLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEPID RESULTS HAVEN'T STOPPED PUSH FOR TECH IN SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c.2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The specifics keep changing, but the promise hasn't: For two
decades, technology has been touted as a panacea for America's
troubled educational system.
</P>
<P>
   First, the idea was that learning keyboarding, word processing
and Logo programming would prepare kids for jobs in the information
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Then came ``kill and drill'' software titles that tried to
inspire enthusiasm about arithmetic and spelling exercises by
adding goofy characters and funny noises. In the 1990s, with the
popularization of CD-ROMs, electronic encyclopedias and multimedia
were added to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Now, overshadowing everything that came before, is the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   So far, none of these applications of technology to education
has delivered fully on its promises. Though billions have been
spent on hardware and software for classrooms and students' homes,
there is scant evidence of a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   But that hasn't stopped the industry from hyping _ or parents
and teachers from hoping. Today, almost two-thirds of American
families with at least one child between ages 2 and 17 have a
computer at home, and the figure for families is undoubtedly even
higher in the Bay Area, where one recent study found that 72
percent of all households have a computer. There are, of course,
many reasons families buy home computers, but parents continue to
cite their children's educations as the most common justification
for buying a home PC and the main use for it, according to a recent
report of the National School Boards Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Educators and policymakers have also bought the argument for
high tech, especially since the rise of the Internet. Once limited
to labs and libraries, computers are now deployed in
ever-increasing numbers in the classroom _ more than half of U.S.
classrooms now have at least one machine.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the most recent year for which the U.S. Department of
Education has complete data, the average U.S. public school had 75
computers, and 79 percent of public-school students in grades one
through eight were using them to some extent _ a percentage that,
surprisingly, exceeded that for secondary-school students and
college undergraduates. And all indications are that the
percentages have continued to increase during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
   These computers are no longer islands unto themselves, either. A
poll conducted last fall by the National Center for Education
Statistics found that virtually all public schools in the United
States are connected to the Internet, and the number of classroom
hookups has increased twentyfold since 1994. Another recent study
found that 66 percent of public-school teachers are using computers
or the Internet for instruction during class time.
</P>
<P>
   As in the past, a small but insistent chorus of critics contends
that these expenditures are misguided _ that school districts would
be better advised to spend their money on smaller classes, teacher
training and books, and that kids need parental time and attention
far more than technology at home.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, school districts that have filled their
classrooms with technology and trained their teachers how to use it
can point to compelling examples of creative teaching that clearly
would not have been possible in the pre-Internet era.
</P>
<P>
   But education researcher Peter Grunwald of San Mateo's Grunwald
Associates said the truth lies somewhere in between. Early
advocates of technology in the schools often engaged in what he
called ``technohedonism, making unsupported claims that raised
people's expectations.'' When the reality didn't live up to the
promise, he said, the inevitable result was disappointment and
skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of the problem, he said, is that administrators often
plunked hardware down in their schools without recognizing that
teachers wouldn't be able to take full advantage of it without ``a
fair amount of professional development _ teacher training and
curriculum development.''
</P>
<P>
   That remains a problem, but more school districts and other
funding sources recognize it, according to Grunwald, and they have
shifted their budgeting priorities to address it.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the explosive growth of the World Wide Web has
changed the nature of computing in schools, just like everywhere
else. The drill programs, the encyclopedias and all the rest
remain, but now they are increasingly integrated with the Web. And
thousands of sites have sprung up to offer education-related
information and services to children, parents and teachers _
everything from help with homework to locating scholarship
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   It's no secret that these online resources have created new
ethical dilemmas _ cheating has never been easier _ not to mention
new ways to waste time. But there's little doubt that they also
provide unprecedented possibilities for finding, evaluating,
utilizing and sharing information.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of all these resources, of course, still
requires hardware. The precipitous price cuts of the late 1990s
have slowed, but the performance and storage capacity of PCs (and
Macs) have continued to increase. And the cost of PC notebooks has
at last come down enough so some families can afford to consider
this option, at least for older students.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the real educational benefits of computers, there's no
question that most kids enjoy using them. According to a report in
American Demographics magazine, a recent Kaiser Family Foundation
survey asked children ages 8 to 18 to choose which media they would
prefer to bring to a desert island.
</P>
<P>
   ``A computer with Internet access'' was the first choice of 33
percent of the kids surveyed, putting it at the top of the list.
``CDs, tapes or radio'' ranked second, with 24 percent, while
television and video games were tied for the next two positions
with 13 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   ``Books or magazines'' came in fifth at 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(at)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
