<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEWORK-ONLINE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NOWADAYS, STUDENTS GO TO THE LIBRARY BY GOING ONLINE  &HT;     By VERNE KOPYTOFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Curtis Santee, a 10th-grader from San Francisco,
prefers to do schoolwork from the comfort of home rather than going
to the library. So when doing a report about Algeria recently, he
logged on to his family's computer and, faster than a lesson on the
Dewey Decimal System, found information about the North African
country's gross domestic product and cultures in an online
encyclopedia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get on the Internet every single day when I have big
projects and research papers to do,'' said Santee, who attends
Gateway High School. ``You don't have to go anywhere, you just have
to sit in your seat.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to homework in the online era.
</P>
<P>
   Students no longer need to visit libraries to search long rows
of bookshelves. Anyone with an Internet connection has access to
one of the world's largest collections of knowledge, eliminating
the excuse used by generations of students that the books they were
looking for were already checked out.
</P>
<P>
   The Web offers students help at every grade level and in nearly
every subject. Children can find online tutoring from topics as
diverse as basic math and geography, English and physics.
</P>
<P>
   Many teachers, in fact, encourage students to do research on the
Internet and even show them how to use Web search engines. At some
schools, students do as much as 90 percent of their research
online, teachers said.
</P>
<P>
   Marnie Studva, a fifth-grade teacher at Jack London Elementary
School in Antioch, Calif., praised the Internet for providing
students with timely information that is too recent to be mentioned
in some of her school's textbooks. That is particularly important
in geography, she said, because new countries are created all the
time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the maps in our books show the Soviet Union,'' Studva
complained.
</P>
<P>
   Students are generally happy to do research on the Internet
instead of from books and magazines, she said. As a consequence,
she no longer needs to photocopy as many magazine articles to hand
out in class as when she began her career eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something more exciting for children about going on a
computer and looking information up, even though it's the same as
what they could find in a book,'' Studva said.
</P>
<P>
   Older students at the Emerson School, a private institution for
grades one through eight in Palo Alto, do virtually all of their
research online. But with so much dubious information on the
Internet, teachers there tell students which Web sites are more
reliable.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the challenges is to give kids a sense of what is good
information and what sites are credible,'' said Michael Strong, the
school's director. ``We teach them about the brand names _ the
university sites are better than the sites run by the ideological
groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Many educators applaud the Internet because it allows students
to interact more while learning than with a traditional workbook.
Some Web sites offer games in which students must give correct
answers to move to higher levels.
</P>
<P>
   But like many educators, Nurje Williams, executive director of
Back on Track, a nonprofit student tutoring program in San
Francisco, had a few words of caution. She said that the Web makes
it easier for students to plagiarize and look busy when they are
really goofing off.
</P>
<P>
   ``They certainly need to be monitored,'' Williams said. ``I
don't think you can depend all the time on these blocking systems
so kids can't wander off to other sites.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
