<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPARKS EASILY ADVANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ With each game, the Los Angeles Sparks look
more like a team that could win the WNBA championship.
</P>
<P>
   They were at their best again Sunday afternoon at the Forum.
They shot 56 percent from the field and eliminated the Phoenix
Mercury from the first round of the playoffs with a 101-76 victory
in front of an excited crowd of 9,811, the second-largest of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Center Lisa Leslie played like the MVP Sparks coach Michael
Cooper claims she is, scoring a game-high 29 points on 12-of-17
shooting with eight rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am honored to coach this young lady, because she, in my
eyes, is the MVP of the league this year simply for the fact that
she's made the rest of the team so much better,'' Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Mwadi Mabika made four of the team's nine 3-pointers, Tamecka
Dixon scored 14 points and had seven assists, DeLisha Milton had 11
points, and reserve Clarisse Machanguana had 10 points.
</P>
<P>
   Next is the Western Conference finals, which begin Thursday on
the road, against either three-time defending champion Houston or
Sacramento. Houston leads the series 1-0 and hosts the Monarchs
tonight at 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and established everything that we wanted to do,''
Cooper said. ``You have to tip your hat to the Mercury. They gave
us everything they had and you have to respect them for that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks scored three consecutive 3-pointers _ one each by
Dixon, Mabika and Ukari Figgs _ to go ahead 17-12 and never looked
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted to come out aggressive,'' Mabika said. ``We
knew that they wanted to be the aggressor, but we kept our poise.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks pushed the lead to 30-16 on a Mabika outside shot
with 10:14 to play in the first half. Phoenix cut the deficit to
42-36 at the break, but midway through the second half, the Sparks
mounted another attack to put the game out of reach.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks were just 1 of 5 from the free-throw line in the
first half but made 23 of 28 in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have so many weapons, you have to pick your poison,''
Phoenix coach Cheryl Miller said. ``I thought we played well. The
first seven minutes, we were right with them. We just ran out of
gas.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercury's 36-year-old Jennifer Gillom, who promised she is
coming back next season, and Lisa Harrison scored 16 points apiece.
The Sparks limited Brandy Reed to 11 points, eight under her
average.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie injured her right knee in the first half but returned
with five minutes to play in the half.
</P>
<P>
   __ No miracle for Miracle: Merlakia Jones and rookie Helen
Darling scored 15 points each as the host Cleveland Rockers beat
the Orlando Miracle 63-54 to tie their best-of-three Eastern
Conference playoff series.
</P>
</TEXT>
