<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS SEEK SPOT FOR HARRIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Bob Toledo refers to Akil Harris as his secret
weapon. The problem is he might continue to be a secret this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, a redshirt freshman tailback, got a long look this
spring when an injury slowed starter DeShaun Foster. But even
though Harris impressed the coaches, getting him the ball won't be
so easy when he stands behind Foster and dependable senior Jermaine
Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, Harris, who ran for 4,697 yards his last two
seasons at Monrovia High, probably will return kicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to find a way to get him on the field,'' running
backs coach Kelly Skipper said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Injury report: Starting guard Oscar Cabrera is listed as day
to day after suffering a high right-ankle sprain when he tripped
during a running drill Saturday afternoon. Toledo doesn't expect
the injury to keep Cabrera out of the season-opener Sept. 2 against
Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Two other linemen who are coming off knee surgery, center Troy
Danoff and guard Brian Polak, are being limited to one practice per
day.
</P>
<P>
   __ Boys will be boys: Testosterone, the midday sun and two-a-day
practices proved combustible Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end the morning practice, a pair of redshirt freshmen _
guard Shane Lehman and defensive tackle Rodney Leisle (cq) _ got
into a wrestling match. Senior defensive end Kenyon Coleman then
asserted himself as the alpha male by jumping in, throwing Lehman
to the ground and ripping his helmet off.
</P>
<P>
   __ Most expensive scholarship: It didn't take long for the
coaches to notice the leg strength of freshman punter Chris Kluwe.
In the first two days of drills for freshmen last week, Kluwe
punted two balls over the a 60-foot screen at the end of the
practice field and onto the roof at Pauley Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Toledo said he was going to start charging me for
those,'' said Kluwe, who could supplant sophomore Nate Fikse.
</P>
<P>
   __ Recruits: Spencer Havner, a linebacker from Nevada City Grass
Valley High, has watched practice the past two days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
