<DOCNO> NYT20000813.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-13 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0710 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-KC-CROSSEDEYES-KAN &LR;      08-13 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-CROSSED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERIENCE OPENS WOMAN'S EYES TO PLIGHT OF MEXICAN STREET
CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
 EYES-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STACY DOWNS  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, MO. _ Martha Roberts thought life would change
dramatically for 15-year-old Manuel Burboa.
</P>
<P>
   After spending most of his life on the streets of Juarez,
Mexico, ostracized by his family and mocked by his peers, Manuel
was brought to the United States, where an Overland Park, Kan.,
doctor corrected his crossed eyes.
</P>
<P>
   When Manuel returned home, his life would be much better,
thought Roberts, who had spent many days with Manuel in Overland
Park as his interpreter.
</P>
<P>
   But when Roberts visited Manuel this summer, she found no
fairy-tale ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``He isn't teased anymore, but everything else is still the
same,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   What she found was Manuel sleeping in the back of an old yellow
pickup truck or on the dirt floor of the home of a family for whom
he worked.
</P>
<P>
   She saw him standing near a bridge and singing to earn a little
money.
</P>
<P>
   Saddest of all, perhaps, she found that Manuel had sold the
eyeglasses he had received after his surgery so that he could buy
food.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the most heartbreaking experience of my life,'' Roberts
said. ``I cried every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of giving up, however, she determined to do something
for Manuel and other street children in Juarez.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and others recently formed Compassion Foundation of
Kansas City, with the goal of raising money to provide shelter and
a tutor for Manuel, who cannot read or write. He has no education
beyond kindergarten. A teacher once said she could not educate
someone with his vision problems.
</P>
<P>
   Any additional money would go to adopt a school in Juarez, where
public education stops after the sixth grade and most people can't
afford to send their children to private schools, Roberts said.
Public schools usually don't have libraries, cafeterias or sports,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts first met Manuel in May, when he was in Overland Park
for his surgery.
</P>
<P>
   A group of St. Thomas Aquinas High School students had
befriended Manuel last year during a spring-break mission in
Juarez, where they painted a school and a library.
</P>
<P>
   The students told a teacher of Manuel's laughter and generosity.
One student spoke about how Manuel recycled soda bottles to pay for
food but used some of that money to buy the student a small gift.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired, the teacher helped bring Manuel to Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   A woman from Johnson County donated money to fly Manuel and his
mother, Sara Menchaca, to Kansas City. Trudi Grin, a pediatric
ophthalmologist, performed the surgery for free.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery corrected the appearance of Manuel's eyes and
improved his peripheral vision, but it could not help the sight in
his right eye.
</P>
<P>
   So Manuel was given glasses to wear to protect his good eye from
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who grew up in Colombia and Venezuela, has served as
interpreter for hundreds of people in hospitals, courtrooms and at
Johnson County Community College.
</P>
<P>
   But she was especially touched by Manuel.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts accompanied Manuel to an Overland Park store, where he
was able to get some things he needed after a Girl Scout troop
donated money. He replaced the size 2 shoes he had been wearing
with a size 6.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel also bought a bike, which had been his lifelong dream.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts saw how Manuel loved being around others, often dancing
and playing soccer.
</P>
<P>
   But she also noticed the palms of Manuel's hands were yellowed
and lined with scars. Menchaca, Manuel's mother, tearfully
confessed she put his hands on a hot stove as a way to punish him.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was so painful to me,'' Roberts said. ``He has such a
gentle spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   After the boy returned to Mexico, Roberts wondered about how his
life had changed. So she took the opportunity to accompany a TV
crew to Juarez. A 30-minute program about Manuel aired recently on
KMBC, Channel 9.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts found herself overwhelmed by Manuel's situation and by
the extreme poverty that surrounded him in Juarez, a desert city
across the border from El Paso, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel's mother lived in a one-room home of cardboard walls.
Manuel sometimes visited her when his stepfather _ who had banished
Manuel, then only 5, because of his crossed eyes _ wasn't around.
The room has no running water, and a hole dug in the ground serves
as a toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said she could only contrast her comfortable life with
Manuel's poverty. She felt helpless when she saw other children
living like Manuel.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing Manuel to live permanently in the United States wasn't
an option, Roberts said. Manuel had longed to be back in Mexico
each day he was in Overland Park, and he would miss his family,
even though he had spent most of his life apart from them.
</P>
<P>
   So plans for the Compassion Foundation for Kansas City were
born.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts plans to keep up with Manuel through Jorge Mata, an
Evangelical Presbyterian pastor in Juarez who helps street
children. Roberts said she hopes to return this fall to give Manuel
any money that is raised and form long-term plans to help him and
to adopt a school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education is magic,'' Roberts said. ``I don't see any other
way to help. We need to change this system.''
</P>
<P>
   And another pair of glasses was sent to Manuel when Roberts
visited. Before she left, Manuel promised he would not sell this
pair.
</P>
<P>
   How to help:
</P>
<P>
   Compassion Foundation for Kansas City Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Bank of Blue Valley
</P>
<P>
   P.O. Box 26128
</P>
<P>
   11935 Riley St.
</P>
<P>
   Overland Park, KS 66225-6128
</P>
</TEXT>
