To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION _ (Moved in ``p'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DEM-PLATFORM (Los Angeles) _ Far from stamping a distinctive
Gore imprint on the Democratic Party, the platform the delegates
will approve on Tuesday warmly embraces the centrist policies of
the Clinton administration and lavishly credits them for the
prosperity of the last seven years. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DEM-DELEGATES (Los Angeles) _ The Democratic delegates arriving
here to nominate Vice President Al Gore for president think of
themselves as moderates, but their views on issues from affirmative
action to an activist federal government are more liberal than
those of the public or even Democratic voters generally, a New York
Times/CBS News Poll shows. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DEM-SCRIPT (Los Angeles) _ A look at the way the Democrats plan
to control the message. From the sea of see-through IMAC computers
on the convention floor to a center-stage program of prominent
officials engaged in issue ``dialogues'' with ordinary people, the
Democratic National Convention is intended to be, in look and feel,
a brainier and meatier antidote to the Republicans' feel-good
Philadelphia spectacle. By Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DEM-PLAYBOY (Los Angeles) _ By most measures, Hugh Hefner and
his daughter, Christie, are hardly the largest donors to the
Democratic Party. But, this week, as a controversy swirled around
the use of the Playboy Mansion for a Hispanic fund-raiser, they
became, for a moment, among the most visible. By Leslie Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REAGAN (Los Angeles) _ When you watch President Clinton
at the Democratic convention, it may look like he is stealing
President Ronald Reagan's script from 1988. As Reagan did then,
Clinton plans to officially bless his No. 2 on Monday evening. And
as Reagan did then, Clinton is expected to implore Americans to
build on the triumphs of the current administration. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT6) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DEM-PARTIES (Los Angeles) _ A look at 48 hours of parties. By
Alex Kuczynski.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-MEDIA (Los Angeles) _ Surfing the net, cable and network
television. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-SPEAKERS (Los Angeles) _ Profiles of Monday speakers.
</P>
