   DEM-DIARY (Los Angeles) _ Convention diary. By Elisabeth
Bumiller and Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-CHAIRMAN-PROFILE (Washington) _ Profile of Joe Andrew,
Democratic convention chairman. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PUTIN (Moscow) _ Since becoming president of Russia,
Vladimir Putin has capitalized on a voter mandate and high poll
ratings to begin putting Russia back in order after a decade of
wild economic and political swings. But along the way, he is
breaking a lot of china, indulging some of the anti-democratic
instincts, his critics say, that came with his KGB training. By
Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-AIDS-TEACHERS (Bazra-Nattis, Ivory Coast) _ Six teachers
a week in this nation of 15 million people die of AIDS, a 1998
government study found, and officials believe the number has only
gone up since then. The elite status afforded by their education
makes teachers, nearly all of them men, particularly susceptible
when, young and single, they enter remote villages for their first
teaching jobs: young village women compete for their attention. The
result is multiple sexual relationships, made riskier because the
men are unlikely to use condoms. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ U.S. officials are talking about
the possibility of reviving the Palestinian-Israeli talks, saying
the time is short, that Egypt appears ready to be helpful and that
they see some signs of willingness on both sides. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta, Indonesia) _ The streets of Jakarta
were mostly quiet as parliament met this past week _ an indication,
perhaps, that despite its daunting problems and continuing disarray
there is hope in Indonesia for a more ordered and cohesive future.
``It's not over yet,'' cautioned a local journalist. But with
another week to go, this has been the first major political event
since former President Suharto was driven from office two and a
half years ago that has not been riven by chaos and bloodshed. By
Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-POLICE (Shanghai) _ Police activity has increased in
several parts of China as the country undergoes a tightening of
social controls ahead of the October 1st National Day holiday.
While the summer sweep of discos and karaoke bars and detentions of
people voicing political dissent is an annual event, the crackdown
appears unusually harsh this year. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-CONCUBINES (Dongguan, China) _ Of all the ties that bind
Hong Kong and the Chinese mainland, few may be more pervasive than
sex. But it is not fueled by quick thrills and anonymous
encounters. It is based on a remarkably durable web of
relationships that have flowered between relatively poor Chinese
women and more affluent Hong Kong men, whose jobs require them to
spend days or weeks at a time in the mainland. Many of these
commuters support mistresses or de facto second wives, and
concubine villages have sprouted up across Guangdong Province. But
now the Chinese government is starting to view wholesale adultery
as a social menace, and it is cracking down. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT grahics clients.
Photos [MYT12,19) have been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WELFARELESS-COUNTY (Rushville, Ill.) _ Welfare has completely
disappeared from Schuyler County, Ill. For more than a year, there
have been no new cases, no old cases, no one on the rolls. This
results not just from a strong economy, but also from hard work by
local welfare officials, who give lots of personal attention to
each case _ and have many lessons to teach the rest of the country.
By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   FLA-BEACH (Destin, Fla.) _ Destin, the Florida Panhandle village
that had long been regarded as one of the last, little jewels of
coastal old Florida, has been transformed into a coastal city of
condominiums. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Detroit) _ The Ford Motor Co. released documents
Sunday showing that Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. had begun receiving
by 1997 numerous complaints of injuries and property damage
involving certain Firestone tires that were not recalled until last
Wednesday. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE-DEVELOP (San Francisco) _ A group of key Linux software
developers and major computer manufacturers is planning to announce
Tuesday at a Silicon Valley computer conference the first effort to
compete directly with Microsoft's Office suite of applications for
the personal computer. Exclusive. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   TOMCLANCY-MEDIA (Undated) _ A look behind Tom Clancy's decision
to leave his longtime agent, Robert Gottlieb, for Mike Ovitz. Is
Gottlieb, once one of New York's most powerful book agents, losing
his clout? By David D. Kirkpatrick and Jim Rutenberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT3) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-WEB-MEDIA (Undated) _ ``The Medium Gets the Message.'' A few
years ago, the TV broadcast networks assumed their skills were
directly transferable to the Web. But they have learned the hard
way that unlike the broad mass medium of broadcast television, the
Web is a highly fragmented medium. By Saul Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MURDOCH-MEDIA (Undated) _ Media analysts and network executives
said over the weekend that the sale of TV stations owned by
Chris-Craft Industries to the owner of the Fox television network,
News Corp., is likely to create a host of opportunities for News
Corp. _ and raise almost as many questions. The questions will
affect both News Corp. and Viacom, which until last Friday had been
bidding to acquire the Chris-Craft stations itself. By Bill Carter
and Geraldine Fabrikant.
</P>
<P>
   STOSSEL-TVNEWS-MEDIA (Undated) _ Reviled in some quarters as an
ideologue and crusader, admired in others for his fresh, contrarian
approach, John Stossel is an anomaly in TV journalism. Reporters
are generally forced to keep their ideologies to themselves.
Stossel is allowed to make his views known. And that he does. An
unabashed libertarian, he has argued that greed is good for the
economy; that environmentalists are ``scaremongers'' with vastly
overblown fears of global warming and pollution; and, even, that
seat belts in school buses are a waste of money. His views have put
him under intense scrutiny in the hothouse world of environmental
and consumer politics. By Jim Rutenberg and Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   FANCIFUL-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ Visitors to www.goblertoys.com
can find cartoon versions of the toy inventions of Ira Gobler like
Gobler's Wobblers, Rodeo Rover and Senor and Senorita Sandwich. The
site also offers a scrapbook of the career of Gobler, president and
founder of Gobler Toys, and links to animated commercials. But
anyone doing research into the toy business will soon find there is
no Gobler Toys and no toy maker named Ira Gobler. Rather,
www.goblertoys.com is an example of an increasingly popular trend
in marketing: fictional or fanciful Web sites. By Allison Fass.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ECON-COLUMN (Tokyo) _ The New Economy column: In Japan this
year, the number of people with Internet access is expected to
surpass the number of Internet users in the United States. But
because most Japanese are getting their access via wireless
devices, with relatively slow connection speeds, the Japanese
experience of the Internet is vastly different from the typical
American's experience. Does this suggest yet another type of
digital divide? By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE-COLUMN (Undated) _ The E-Commerce column: A changing
of the guard is underway in the Internet industry, as the early
proponents of the Web are stepping aside for the mainstream
business people who have migrated to the new medium. By Bob
Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo [NYT1) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-SATELLITES (Undated) _ Delivering simultaneous streams of
music to thousands or millions of listeners over an increasingly
clogged Internet has become increasingly frustrating. If the audio
stream hits too many traffic jams, the listener may find his
Internet radio program stuttering or stopping halfway through a
song. One promising remedy involves sending the stream up to a
space satellite, hopping over most of the jam-ups on the ground and
landing the music stream at a network hub closer to the listener.
By Theresa Foley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphics clients. Photo
[NYT2) has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   DEM-TV-MEDIA (Undated) _ The Democratic convention television
coverage you see this week will probably be the last time you'll
ever see anything like the oldtime convention coverage on a
broadcast network. By Peter Marks.
</P>
